\chapter{6502 programming techniques}

\section{Zero page temporaries}

Zero-page consists essentially of global variables. Sometimes we need local
temporaries, and Apple II programs mostly don't use the stack for those. Rather,
some ``global'' variables are reserved for temporaries. You might see multiple
symbols equated to a single zero-page location. The names of such symbols are
used to make sense within their context.

\section{Tail calls}

Rather than a [[JSR]] immediately followed by an [[RTS]], instead a [[JMP]]
can be used to save stack space, code space, and time. This is known as a
tail call, because it is a call that happens at the tail of a function.

\section{Unconditional branches}

The 6502 doesn't have an unconditional short jump. However, if you can find
a condition that is always true, this can serve as an unconditional short
jump, which saves space and time.

\section{Stretchy branches}

6502 branches have a limit to how far they can jump. If they really need to
jump farther than that, you have to put a [[JMP]] or an unconditional branch
within reach.

\section{Shared code}

To save space, sometimes code at the end of one function is also useful to
the next function, as long as it is within reach. This can save space, at
the expense of functions being completely independent.

\section{Macros}

We use these macros to make our assembly language listings a little less verbose.
However, a restriction is that you cannot use local labels as arguments to a macro,
since macros implicitly create an anonymous local scope for themselves. Thus, they are
not good candidates for use in self-modifying code.

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{lll}
\hline
\textbf{Macro} & \textbf{Args} & \textbf{Description} \\
\hline
\multicolumn{3}{l}{\textit{Store / Move}} \\
[[STOW]]  & val, dst     & Store 16-bit immediate to memory \\
[[STOW2]] & val, dst     & Same as [[STOW]], opposite instruction order \\
[[STOB]]  & \#val, dst   & Store immediate byte to memory \\
[[MOVB]]  & src, dst     & Move byte between memory locations \\
[[MOVW]]  & src, dst     & Move 16-bit value between memory locations \\
[[LDWIY]] & ptr, \#off, dst & Load 16-bit word via indirect Y-indexed pointer \\
\hline
\multicolumn{3}{l}{\textit{Stack}} \\
[[PSHW]]  & addr         & Push 16-bit value onto stack \\
[[PULB]]  & addr         & Pull byte from stack to memory \\
[[PULW]]  & addr         & Pull 16-bit value from stack to memory \\
\hline
\multicolumn{3}{l}{\textit{Arithmetic}} \\
[[INCW]]  & addr         & Increment 16-bit value in memory \\
[[ADDA]]  & addr         & Add A to 16-bit memory (with carry propagation) \\
[[ADDAC]] & addr         & Add A + carry to 16-bit memory \\
[[ADDB]]  & addr, val    & Add 8-bit value to 16-bit memory \\
[[ADDB2]] & addr, val    & Same as [[ADDB]], swapped [[CLC]]/[[LDA]] order \\
[[ADDW]]  & a, b, c      & Add two 16-bit values, store to third \\
[[ADDWC]] & a, b, c      & Same as [[ADDW]] but without [[CLC]] (uses existing carry) \\
[[SUBB]]  & addr, val    & Subtract 8-bit value from 16-bit memory \\
[[SUBB2]] & addr, val    & Same as [[SUBB]], swapped [[SEC]]/[[LDA]] order \\
[[SUBW]]  & a, b, c      & Subtract two 16-bit values, store to third \\
[[SUBWL]] & \#val, b, c  & Subtract 16-bit memory from 16-bit literal \\
\hline
\multicolumn{3}{l}{\textit{Rotate}} \\
[[ROLW]]  & addr         & Rotate 16-bit memory left \\
[[RORW]]  & addr         & Rotate 16-bit memory right \\
[[ROL2]]  &              & Rotate accumulator left by two bits \\
\hline
\multicolumn{3}{l}{\textit{Compare and branch}} \\
[[BAEQ]]  & val, lbl     & Branch if A equals val \\
[[BANE]]  & val, lbl     & Branch if A does not equal val \\
[[BAPL]]  & val, lbl     & Branch if A minus val is positive \\
[[BAMI]]  & val, lbl     & Branch if A minus val is negative \\
[[BALT]]  & val, lbl     & Branch if A is less than val (unsigned) \\
[[BAGE]]  & val, lbl     & Branch if A is greater than or equal to val (unsigned) \\
[[BXEQ]]  & val, lbl     & Branch if X equals val \\
[[BXNE]]  & val, lbl     & Branch if X does not equal val \\
[[BYEQ]]  & val, lbl     & Branch if Y equals val \\
