@ The region [[$B800]]--[[$BBFF]] contains residual assembler source code
from the EA development environment, preserved because it fell within the
EALDR's 2-track footprint.  This is a remarkable piece of digital
archaeology: the original EA source for the VM opcode definitions.

The data is structured as length-prefixed lines (each preceded by [[$0D]]
and a length byte).  Each opcode entry consists of a description line
(a semicolon comment) followed by a definition line containing the
8-character mnemonic, a [[$D9]] field separator, and the opcode number
in decimal.  The fragment begins mid-entry at opcode~5 (opcodes 0--4
were in memory before [[$B800]] and have been overwritten by the splash
screen data).

The [[$D9]] field separator is notable: it is the same byte used as the
XOR key for encrypting the high byte of 16-bit address arguments in the
VM bytecode (see~\S\ref{sec:ealdr}).  This may not be a coincidence---the
encryption key may have been chosen from the source code format.

The EA mnemonics reveal the original naming conventions:
\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{clll}
\toprule
\thead{Op} & \thead{EA mnemonic} & \thead{Our name} & \thead{EA description} \\
\midrule
 0 & JMP  & VMGOTO  & ? \\
 1 & JSRA & VMCALL1 & ? \\
 2 & BEQ  & VMBEQ   & ? \\
 3 & LDI  & VMLDI   & ? \\
 4 & LDA  & VMLD    & ? \\
 5 & JSR  & VMCALL  & ? \\
 6 & STA  & VMST    & Store acc. absolute \\
 7 & SUB  & VMSUBI  & Subtract acc. immediate \\
 8 & JMPA & VMCALL0 & Jump to assembly \\
 9 & RTS  & VMRET   & M-code return from subroutine \\
10 & LDX  & VMLDX   & Load acc. a99. indexed by Acc. \\
11 & ASL  & VMASL   & Shift acc. left \\
12 & INC  & VMINC   & Increment absolute \\
13 & ADD  & VMADD   & Add immediate \\
14 & EOR  & VMDXR   & EOR encryption bytes \\
15 & BNE  & VMBNE   & Jump if acc. non-zero \\
16 & SBA  & VMSUB   & Subtract absolute \\
17 & COP  & VMCOPY  & Copy byte from (PTR) to (PTR2) \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

Following the opcode definitions is a fragment of documentation,
[[EALDR_SOURCE_COMMENTS]], that maps
opcodes (starting from [[5]]) to their handler labels
(e.g., [[IJMP]], [[IJSRA]], [[IBEQ]]).
The [[$E5]] bytes (high-bit [['e']]) are likely an assembler pseudo-op
(equate or entry directive). This could be a leftover table for
a VM code disassembler.

@ [[EACR]] emits a [[$0D]] line separator followed by a length byte.
[[EASEP]] emits the [[$D9]] record separator.

<<EALDR VM macros>>=
    MACRO EACR    ; line separator: $0D
        DC.B $0D
    ENDM
    MACRO EASEP   ; record separator: $D9 (high-bit 'Y')
        DC.B $D9
    ENDM
    MACRO SLEN    ; string length byte
        DC.B {1}
    ENDM
@

