@ [[EALDR_RWTS_READ_SECTOR]] reads and decodes one sector's data field
from the disk.  It searches for the [[D5 AA AD]] data prologue, then
reads the 6-and-2 encoded nibbles, decodes them through the translation
tables at [[$BD98]] and [[$BE00]], and stores 256~bytes at the address
in [[$44]]/[[$45]].  Returns with carry clear on success, carry set on
error.

The routine uses self-modifying code: the [[STA]] instructions at
[[$BC6E]], [[$BC95]], and [[$BCAD]] have their high byte patched by
[[EALDR_RWTS_READ_SECTOR]] itself (at [[$BC14]]/[[$BC17]],
[[$BC21]]/[[$BC24]], and [[$BC2C]]/[[$BC2F]]) to set up three different
destination regions within the 256-byte output page.

This is structurally identical to [[BOOT1_READ_SECTOR]] at [[$0902]],
with zero-page [[$4A]] used instead of [[$26]] for the running checksum,
[[$44]]/[[$45]] for the destination pointer (same as BOOT1), and the
slot index hardcoded to [[$60]] instead of read from [[$2B]].

<<EALDR RWTS read sector>>=
    ORG     $BC10
EALDR_RWTS_READ_SECTOR:
    SUBROUTINE EALDR_RWTS_READ_SECTOR

    ; Self-modify STA targets based on destination address ($44/$45)
    LDA     #$00
    LDY     $45             ; destination page
    STA     .sta_1+1        ; \  patch STA $xx00,Y low byte
    STY     .sta_1+2        ;  | patch STA $xx00,Y high byte
    SEC
    SBC     #$54            ; \
    BCS     .no_borrow1     ;  | subtract $54, borrow from page
    DEY                     ;  |
    SEC                     ; /
.no_borrow1:
    STA     .sta_2+1        ; \  patch second STA target
    STY     .sta_2+2        ; /
    SBC     #$57            ; \
    BCS     .no_borrow2     ;  | subtract $57, borrow from page
    DEY                     ; /
.no_borrow2:
    STA     .sta_3+1        ; \  patch third STA target
    STY     .sta_3+2        ; /

    ; Search for data prologue: D5 AA AD
    LDY     #$20            ; timeout counter
.search:
    DEY
    BEQ     EALDR_RWTS_READ_ERROR ; timeout
.wait1:
    LDA     $C0EC           ; read nibble
    BPL     .wait1
.check_d5:
    EOR     #$D5
    BNE     .search
    NOP
.wait2:
    LDA     $C0EC
    BPL     .wait2
    BANE    #$AA,.check_d5 ; not AA -> re-check for D5
    NOP
.wait3:
    LDA     $C0EC
    BPL     .wait3
    BANE    #$AD,.check_d5 ; not AD -> re-check for D5

    ; Read 86 bytes of secondary data ($AA-$FF range of page)
    LDY     #$AA
    LDA     #$00
.read_secondary:
    STA     $4A             ; running checksum
.read_secondary_wait:
    LDX     $C0EC
    BPL     .read_secondary_wait
    LDA     $BD00,X         ; decode via primary nibble table
    STA     $0200,Y         ; store in buffer
    EOR     $4A             ; update checksum
    INY
    BNE     .read_secondary ; loop $AA..$FF (86 bytes)

    ; Read and decode primary data (86 bytes -> page+$00..$55)
    LDY     #$AA
    BNE     .read_primary_start
.sta_3:
    STA     $FFFF,Y         ; self-modified: page+$AC..$FF
.read_primary_start:
    LDX     $C0EC
    BPL     .read_primary_start
    EOR     $BD00,X         ; decode nibble
    LDX     $0200,Y         ; secondary data
    EOR     EALDR_RWTS_NIBBLE_B,X ; pair-decode table
    INY
    BNE     .sta_3          ; loop $AA..$FF (86 bytes)
    PHA                     ; save last decoded value
    AND     #$FC

    ; Read and decode middle data (86 bytes -> page+$56..$AB)
    LDY     #$AA
.read_mid:
    LDX     $C0EC
    BPL     .read_mid
    EOR     $BD00,X
    LDX     $0200,Y
    EOR     EALDR_RWTS_NIBBLE_B+1,X ; offset +1 in pair-decode table
.sta_2:
    STA     $FFFF,Y         ; self-modified: page+$56..$AB
    INY
    BNE     .read_mid

    ; Read and decode final data (84 bytes -> page+$00..$53)
.wait_final1:
    LDX     $C0EC
    BPL     .wait_final1
    AND     #$FC
    LDY     #$AC
.read_final:
    EOR     $BD00,X
    LDX     $01FE,Y         ; secondary data (offset -2)
    EOR     EALDR_RWTS_NIBBLE_B+2,X ; offset +2 in pair-decode table
.sta_1:
    STA     $FFFF,Y         ; self-modified: page+$00..$55
.wait_final2:
    LDX     $C0EC
    BPL     .wait_final2
    INY
    BNE     .read_final

    ; Verify checksum byte
    AND     #$FC
    EOR     $BD00,X         ; decode final nibble
    LDX     #$60            ; slot index (hardcoded slot 6)
    TAY
    BNE     .checksum_bad   ; checksum must be zero

    ; Read epilogue byte (expect $DE)
.wait_epilogue:
    LDA     $C0EC
    BPL     .wait_epilogue
    BAEQ    #$DE,.ok
.checksum_bad:
    SEC                     ; error: carry set
    HEX     24              ; BIT $zp opcode -- hides next CLC byte
.ok:
    CLC                     ; success: carry clear
    PLA                     ; discard saved byte
    LDY     #$55
    STA     ($44),Y         ; store final byte
    RTS
@ %def EALDR_RWTS_READ_SECTOR

@ [[EALDR_RWTS_MOVE_ARM]] moves the drive head to the half-track in~A.
The target track (doubled for half-track stepping) is compared against
the current position in [[EALDR_RWTS_TRACK]].  It steps inward or
outward one half-track at a time, activating the stepper phases via
[[EALDR_RWTS_PHASE_ON]] and waiting with [[EALDR_RWTS_DELAY]] between
steps.  Zero-page [[$4A]] holds the target half-track, [[$4B]] saves
the previous position.

This is structurally identical to [[BOOT1_SEEK_TRACK]] at [[$09C8]],
using [[$4A]]/[[$4B]] instead of [[$26]]/[[$27]] and the slot index
hardcoded to [[$60]].

<<EALDR RWTS move arm>>=
    ORG     $BCD4
EALDR_RWTS_MOVE_ARM:
    SUBROUTINE EALDR_RWTS_MOVE_ARM

    ASL                     ; double for half-track addressing
    STA     $4A             ; target half-track
.compare:
    MOVB    EALDR_RWTS_TRACK,$4B ; save current position
    SEC
    SBC     $4A             ; current - target
    BEQ     EALDR_RWTS_PHASE_ON_RTS ; already there -> RTS at $BD10
    BCS     .step_out
    INC     EALDR_RWTS_TRACK ; step inward
    BCC     .do_step
.step_out:
    DEC     EALDR_RWTS_TRACK ; step outward
.do_step:
    JSR     EALDR_RWTS_PHASE_ON ; activate stepper phase
    JSR     EALDR_RWTS_DELAY ; wait for head to settle
    LDA     $4B             ; previous half-track
    AND     #$03
    ASL                     ; phase index x 2
    ORA     #$60            ; $C0x0 slot offset
    TAY
    LDA     $C080,Y         ; deactivate previous phase
    JSR     EALDR_RWTS_DELAY ; wait
    BEQ     .compare        ; always taken (delay returns Z=1)
    JSR     EALDR_RWTS_DELAY ; (unreachable)
@ %def EALDR_RWTS_MOVE_ARM

@ [[EALDR_RWTS_PHASE_ON]] activates the stepper motor phase
corresponding to the current half-track position.  The slot index
is hardcoded to [[$60]] (slot~6).

<<EALDR RWTS phase on>>=
    ORG     $BD04
EALDR_RWTS_PHASE_ON:
    SUBROUTINE EALDR_RWTS_PHASE_ON

    LDA     EALDR_RWTS_TRACK
    AND     #$03            ; phase = track mod 4
    ASL                     ; x 2 for IWM register spacing
    ORA     #$60            ; slot offset $60 (slot 6)
    TAY
    LDA     $C081,Y         ; activate phase (odd address = on)
EALDR_RWTS_PHASE_ON_RTS:
    RTS
@ %def EALDR_RWTS_PHASE_ON EALDR_RWTS_PHASE_ON_RTS

@ [[EALDR_RWTS_DELAY]] is a nested delay loop providing approximately
40$\times$256$\times$5 = 51,200 cycles, giving the drive head time to
settle after a step.  [[EALDR_RWTS_DELAY_INNER]] at [[$BD14]] is the
inner entry point used by [[EALDR_READ_DATA_TRAMPOLINE]]: entering here
skips the initial [[LDA #\$28]] and [[SEC]], running the delay with
whatever count and carry the caller has set in~A.

<<EALDR RWTS delay>>=
    ORG     $BD11
EALDR_RWTS_DELAY:
    SUBROUTINE EALDR_RWTS_DELAY

    LDA     #$28            ; outer counter = 40
    SEC
EALDR_RWTS_DELAY_INNER:                    ; $BD14
.outer:
    PHA
.inner:
    SBC     #$01
    BNE     .inner          ; inner loop: 256 iterations
    PLA
    SBC     #$01
    BNE     .outer          ; outer loop: 40 iterations
    RTS
@ %def EALDR_RWTS_DELAY EALDR_RWTS_DELAY_INNER

@ [[EALDR_RWTS_ADDR_ERROR]] is the address-field error return.

<<EALDR RWTS addr error>>=
    ORG     $BD1F
EALDR_RWTS_ADDR_ERROR:
    SEC
    RTS
@ %def EALDR_RWTS_ADDR_ERROR

@ [[EALDR_RWTS_SEARCH_ADDR]] searches for an address field prologue
([[D5 AA 96]]) and reads the four two-bit-encoded header bytes:
volume, track, sector, and checksum.  The decoded sector number is
stored in [[$39]].  Returns with carry clear on success.

This is structurally identical to [[BOOT1_FIND_SECTOR]] at [[$0A15]],
using [[$4A]]/[[$4B]] instead of [[$26]]/[[$27]] for the timeout
counter and scratch, and [[$38]]--[[$3B]] instead of
[[$2C]]--[[$2F]] for the header fields.

<<EALDR RWTS search addr>>=
    ORG     $BD21
EALDR_RWTS_SEARCH_ADDR:
    SUBROUTINE EALDR_RWTS_SEARCH_ADDR

    ; Timeout counter
    LDY     #$FC
    STY     $4A             ; outer counter (high byte)
.retry:
    INY
    BNE     .wait_d5
    INC     $4A
    BEQ     EALDR_RWTS_ADDR_ERROR ; timeout

    ; Search for D5 AA 96 address prologue
.wait_d5:
    LDA     $C0EC
    BPL     .wait_d5
.check_d5:
    BANE    #$D5,.retry
    NOP
.wait_aa:
    LDA     $C0EC
    BPL     .wait_aa
    BANE    #$AA,.check_d5 ; not AA -> re-check D5
    LDY     #$03            ; 4 header fields to read
.wait_96:
    LDA     $C0EC
    BPL     .wait_96
    BANE    #$96,.check_d5 ; not 96 -> re-check D5

    ; Read 4 encoded header bytes (volume, track, sector, checksum)
    LDA     #$00
.read_header:
    STA     $4B             ; running checksum
.wait_odd:
    LDA     $C0EC           ; \
    BPL     .wait_odd       ;  | read odd-bits byte
    ROL                     ;  |
    STA     $4A             ; /  save shifted value
.wait_even:
    LDA     $C0EC           ; \
    BPL     .wait_even      ;  | read even-bits byte
    AND     $4A             ;  | combine with odd bits
    STA     $38,Y           ;  | store at $3B,$3A,$39,$38 (Y=3..0)
    EOR     $4B             ;  | update checksum
    DEY                     ;  |
    BPL     .read_header    ; /  loop for all 4 fields

    ; Verify checksum
    TAY
    BNE     EALDR_RWTS_ADDR_ERROR ; checksum must be zero

    ; Read address epilogue: DE AA
.wait_de:
    LDA     $C0EC
    BPL     .wait_de
    BANE    #$DE,EALDR_RWTS_ADDR_ERROR
    NOP
.wait_aa2:
    LDA     $C0EC
    BPL     .wait_aa2
    BANE    #$AA,EALDR_RWTS_ADDR_ERROR
    CLC                     ; success
    RTS
@ %def EALDR_RWTS_SEARCH_ADDR

@ The region at [[$BD7D]]--[[$BD97]] is unused padding between
[[EALDR_RWTS_SEARCH_ADDR]] and the nibble translation table.  It
contains a residual [[CLC]]; [[RTS]] pair at [[$BD7D]] (dead code) and
a [[$04]] byte at [[$BD97]] that is the last entry of the secondary
nibble decode region (matching the [[$04]] at [[$0A97]] in [[BOOT1]]).

<<EALDR RWTS padding>>=
    ORG     $BD7D
EALDR_RWTS_PADDING:
    HEX     18 60           ; residual CLC; RTS (dead code)
    DS      24,$00          ; zero padding
    HEX     04              ; secondary nibble table tail byte
@ %def EALDR_RWTS_PADDING

@ The nibble translation tables at [[$BD98]]--[[$BDFF]] and
[[$BE00]]--[[$BEFF]] are used by [[EALDR_RWTS_READ_SECTOR]] to decode
the 6-and-2 encoded disk nibbles back into data bytes.  These are
byte-identical to the BOOT1 tables at [[$0A98]]--[[$0AFF]] and
[[$0B00]]--[[$0BFF]].  The primary table at [[$BD98]] maps raw disk
nibbles (high-bit set values in the range [[$96]]--[[$FF]]) to 6-bit
values.  The secondary table at [[$BE00]] provides the pair-decode
lookup.

<<EALDR RWTS nibble tables>>=
    ORG     $BD98
EALDR_RWTS_NIBBLE_A:
    ; $BD98-$BDFF: primary 6-and-2 decode table (104 bytes)
    HEX     98 99 08 0C 9C 10 14 18
    HEX     A0 A1 A2 A3 A4 A5 1C 20
    HEX     A8 A9 AA 24 28 2C 30 34
    HEX     B0 B1 38 3C 40 44 48 4C
    HEX     B8 50 54 58 5C 60 64 68
    HEX     C0 C1 C2 C3 C4 C5 C6 C7
    HEX     C8 C9 CA 6C CC 70 74 78
    HEX     D0 D1 D2 7C D4 D5 80 84
    HEX     D8 88 8C 90 94 98 9C A0
    HEX     E0 E1 E2 E3 E4 A4 A8 AC
    HEX     E8 B0 B4 B8 BC C0 C4 C8
    HEX     F0 F1 CC D0 D4 D8 DC E0
    HEX     F8 E4 E8 EC F0 F4 F8 FC
@ %def EALDR_RWTS_NIBBLE_A

@ The interleave table maps physical sector numbers to page offsets
within the target region.  This is identical to [[BOOT1_INTERLEAVE]]
at [[$0C48]].  The destination page table at [[$BF74]] is computed at
runtime by adding the base page to each interleave entry.

<<EALDR RWTS interleave table>>=
    ORG     $BF64
EALDR_RWTS_INTERLEAVE:
    HEX     0F 08 01 09 02 0A 03 0B 04 0C 05 0D 06 0E 07 00
@ %def EALDR_RWTS_INTERLEAVE
@ [[EALDR_RWTS_READ_TRACK]] reads all 16~sectors of a track into
memory.  It takes a track number in~A, seeks to it, and loops until
every sector has been read or a timeout occurs.  On entry, the track
number is saved and [[EALDR_RWTS_ERROR_FLAG]] is cleared.  If the first
attempt encounters errors, the error flag is cleared and a second
attempt is made.

The inner routine at [[$BF1F]] builds the destination page table by
adding the base page ([[$3E]]) to each entry of the interleave table at
[[$BF64]], then iterates: [[EALDR_RWTS_SEARCH_ADDR]] finds each
sector's address field, the sector number in~[[$39]] indexes the
destination page table, and [[EALDR_RWTS_READ_SECTOR]] decodes the
data.  Table entries are zeroed after successful reads; the loop ends
when all~16 are zero.  A retry counter at~[[$40]] prevents infinite
loops.

This is structurally identical to [[BOOT1_LOAD_TRACK]] at [[$0C00]],
using [[$39]] instead of [[$2D]] for the sector number and [[$BF64]]
instead of [[$0C48]] for the interleave table.

<<EALDR RWTS read track>>=
    ORG     $BF00
EALDR_RWTS_READ_TRACK:
    SUBROUTINE EALDR_RWTS_READ_TRACK

    ; First attempt: clear error flag, seek, load
    PHA
    STOB    #$00,EALDR_RWTS_ERROR_FLAG
    PLA
    JSR     .seek_and_load  ; seek + load all sectors
    LDA     EALDR_RWTS_ERROR_FLAG
    BNE     .retry
    RTS                     ; success

.retry:
    ; Second attempt on error
    STOB    #$00,EALDR_RWTS_ERROR_FLAG
    JSR     .load_sectors   ; try again (already on track)
    LDA     EALDR_RWTS_ERROR_FLAG
    RTS                     ; return with error flag in A

.seek_and_load:
    JSR     EALDR_RWTS_MOVE_ARM ; seek to track in A
    ; Fall through to .load_sectors

.load_sectors:
    ; Build destination page table: interleave[i] + base page
    LDY     #$0F
.build_table:
    LDA     EALDR_RWTS_INTERLEAVE,Y
    CLC
    ADC     $3E             ; add base page
    STA     EALDR_RWTS_DEST_PAGES,Y
    DEY
    BPL     .build_table

    LDX     #$60            ; slot index (hardcoded slot 6)
    STOB    #$60,$40 ; retry counter
.retry_sector:
    DEC     $40
    BEQ     .timeout
    JSR     EALDR_RWTS_SEARCH_ADDR ; find address field -> sector in $39
    BCS     .retry_sector   ; error -> retry

    LDY     $39             ; sector number
    LDA     EALDR_RWTS_DEST_PAGES,Y ; destination page for this sector
    BEQ     .retry_sector   ; zero = already read, skip
    STA     $45             ; destination page
    STOB    #$00,$44 ; destination = $xx00
    JSR     EALDR_RWTS_READ_SECTOR ; read and decode data field
    BCS     .retry_sector   ; error -> retry

    ; Mark sector as done
    LDY     $39
    LDA     #$00
    STA     EALDR_RWTS_DEST_PAGES,Y ; zero = done

    ; Check if all sectors read
    LDY     #$0F
.check_done:
    LDA     EALDR_RWTS_DEST_PAGES,Y
    BNE     .retry_sector   ; still have sectors to read
    DEY
    BPL     .check_done
    RTS                     ; all 16 sectors read

.timeout:
    INC     EALDR_RWTS_ERROR_FLAG ; signal error
    RTS
@ %def EALDR_RWTS_READ_TRACK


<<EALDR RWTS dest pages>>=
    ORG     $BF74
EALDR_RWTS_DEST_PAGES:
    DS      16,$00          ; filled at runtime by EALDR_RWTS_READ_TRACK
@ %def EALDR_RWTS_DEST_PAGES

@ The remainder of the EALDR RWTS area ([[$BF84]]--[[$BFFF]]) is unused
padding filled with an alternating [[$FF $00]] pattern, except for the
final byte at [[$BFFF]] which is [[$0F]].

<<EALDR RWTS tail padding>>=
    ORG     $BF84
EALDR_RWTS_TAIL_PADDING:
    HEX     FF 00 FF 00 FF 00 FF 00 FF 00 FF 00 FF 00 FF 00
    HEX     FF 00 FF 00 FF 00 FF 00 FF 00 FF 00 FF 00 FF 00
    HEX     FF 00 FF 00 FF 00 FF 00 FF 00 FF 00 FF 00 FF 00
    HEX     FF 00 FF 00 FF 00 FF 00 FF 00 FF 00 FF 00 FF 00
    HEX     FF 00 FF 00 FF 00 FF 00 FF 00 FF 00 FF 00 FF 00
    HEX     FF 00 FF 00 FF 00 FF 00 FF 00 FF 00 FF 00 FF 00
    HEX     FF 00 FF 00 FF 00 FF 00 FF 00 FF 00 FF 00 FF 00
    HEX     FF 00 FF 00 FF 00 FF 00 FF 00 FF 0F
@ %def EALDR_RWTS_TAIL_PADDING


<<EALDR track pages>>=
    ORG     $A9F3
EALDR_TRACK_PAGES:
    HEX     08 10 20 30 00
    HEX     40 50 60 70 80 86 00
    HEX     08 10 20 30 00

EALDR_TRACKS:
    HEX     03 04 21 22 00
    HEX     07 08 09 0A 0B 0C 00
    HEX     0D 0E 0F 10 00
@ %def EALDR_TRACK_PAGES EALDR_TRACKS

@ The address field search routine [[EALDR_FIND_SECTOR]] at [[$AA15]]
scans the disk for a [[D5 AA]] prologue, used by the sector loader to
locate sectors.

<<EALDR sector search>>=
    ORG     $AA15
EALDR_FIND_SECTOR:
    ; Sector search routine: $AA15-$AA34 (32 bytes)
    HEX     A0 FC 84 26 C8 D0 04 E6 26 F0 F3 AD EC C0 10 FB
    HEX     C9 D5 D0 F0 EA AD EC C0 10 FB C9 AA D0 F2 A0 03
@ %def EALDR_FIND_SECTOR
@

\chapter{Startup}

When EALDR finishes, it transfers control to [[$0800]] via [[CALL0 0800]].

\section{Memory map at entry}

The VM program loads three groups of tracks using the track tables at
[[EALDR_TRACK_PAGES]]/[[EALDR_TRACKS]].  Each track is 16~sectors of 256~bytes, placed
into memory by the sector loader using the custom interleave table
(see~\S\ref{sec:boot1}).  The base page [[XX]] for each track determines the
starting address, [[$XX00]].

\subsection{Group 1 (conditional, skipped in this image)}

Loaded only when the flag byte at [[$A805]] is nonzero (it is~0 in
this disk image, so Group~1 is skipped).  Group~3 overwrites the same
region anyway.

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{ccl}
\toprule
\thead{Track} & \thead{Base page} & \thead{Memory range} \\
\midrule
\$03 & \$08 & \$0800--\$17FF \\
\$04 & \$10 & \$1000--\$1FFF \\
\$21 & \$20 & \$2000--\$2FFF \\
\$22 & \$30 & \$3000--\$3FFF \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

\subsection{Group 2: game data (\$4000--\$95FF)}

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{ccll}
\toprule
\thead{Track} & \thead{Base page} & \thead{Memory range} & \thead{Notes} \\
\midrule
