\$0800--\$0FFF & Track \$0D & \\
\$1000--\$1FFF & Track \$0E & \\
\$2000--\$2FFF & Track \$0F & \\
\$3000--\$3FFF & Track \$10 & \\
\$4000--\$67FF & Tracks \$07--\$09 & DXR-decrypted (even bytes) \\
\$6800--\$6FFF & Track \$09 & Not decrypted \\
\$7000--\$7FFF & Track \$0A & Not decrypted \\
\$8000--\$85FF & Track \$0B & Not decrypted \\
\$8600--\$95FF & Track \$0C & Not decrypted \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

Entry point: [[$0800]].

\section{Runtime memory map}

During [[GAME_INIT]], [[RELOCATE_HIRES_STAGING]] copies data from the
hi-res page area into its runtime addresses:
\$2000--\$32FF~$\to$~\$9600--\$A8FF and
\$3300--\$3FFF~$\to$~\$B300--\$BFFF.
The source area (\$2000--\$3FFF) is then cleared, freeing the hi-res
page for graphics.  After this relocation the full memory map is:

\begin{center}
\ra{1.15}
\begin{tabular}{lrl}
\toprule
\thead{Address range} & \thead{Size} & \thead{Contents} \\
\midrule
\$0500--\$07FF &    768 & Resident routines (from EALDR \$A300--\$A5FF) \\
\$0800--\$1FFF &  6\,144 & Main program code \\
\$2000--\$3FFF &  8\,192 & Hi-res graphics page 1 (cleared by game\_init) \\
\$4000--\$4008 &      9 & Character record header (record 0) \\
\$4009--\$423F &    567 & Location / character records (62 $\times$ 9 bytes + 9-byte sentinel) \\
\$4240--\$451D &    734 & Location name strings \\
\$451E--\$4C7F &  1\,890 & Location event lists (3-byte entries per location) \\
\$4C80--\$547F &  2\,048 & Mob data records (128 $\times$ 16 bytes) \\
\$5480--\$59C8 &  1\,353 & Character / mob name strings \\
\$59C9--\$5AFF &    311 & Residual debug text (unused) \\
\$5B00--\$5FFF &  1\,280 & Game state, display setup, UI tables \\
\$6000--\$7FFF &  8\,192 & Main program code (continued) \\
\$80A4--\$83A4 &    769 & Tune table and tune bytecode \\
\$83A5--\$92A4 &  3\,840 & Custom font data (120 chars $\times$ 32 bytes) \\
\$92A8--\$97A4 &  1\,277 & HRCG library (Hi-Res Character Generator) \\
\$97A5--\$9AA4 &    768 & Standard font data (96 chars $\times$ 8 bytes) \\
\$9AA5--\$B2FF &  6\,235 & \emph{Unused / not mapped} \\
\$B300--\$B5FF &    768 & Disk I/O: VM interpreter and bytecode \\
\$B600--\$BFFF &  2\,560 & DOS 3.3 RWTS (unmodified, relocated) \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

The main program code occupies two non-contiguous regions
(\$0800--\$1FFF and \$6000--\$7FFF) with game data tables and the hi-res
framebuffer in between.

\section{Extracting [[main.bin]]}

The following script reads the disk image, applies the EALDR loading
sequence, and writes a flat binary covering [[$0500]]--[[$95FF]]
(37\,120 bytes).

<<extract_main.py>>=
<<extract main imports>>
<<extract main constants>>
<<extract main read track>>
<<extract main funny inc>>
<<extract main dxr>>
<<extract main entry>>
@

<<extract main imports>>=
import sys
@

<<extract main constants>>=
DSK_FILE = "Ali Baba and the Forty Thieves (4am and san inc crack).dsk"
EALDR_FILE = "ealdr.bin"
OUTPUT_FILE = "main.bin"

BASE_ADDR = 0x0500
END_ADDR = 0x9600
SIZE = END_ADDR - BASE_ADDR  # $9100 = 37120

# DOS 3.3 physical-to-logical skew (physical sector -> file sector)
DOS_SKEW = [0, 7, 14, 6, 13, 5, 12, 4, 11, 3, 10, 2, 9, 1, 8, 15]

# Custom game loader interleave: physical sector -> page offset from base
LOADER_INTERLEAVE = [0xF, 0x8, 0x1, 0x9, 0x2, 0xA, 0x3, 0xB,
                     0x4, 0xC, 0x5, 0xD, 0x6, 0xE, 0x7, 0x0]

# Track loading tables (from EALDR $A9F3 and $AA04)
GROUP2 = [(0x07, 0x40), (0x08, 0x50), (0x09, 0x60),
          (0x0A, 0x70), (0x0B, 0x80), (0x0C, 0x86)]
GROUP3 = [(0x0D, 0x08), (0x0E, 0x10), (0x0F, 0x20), (0x10, 0x30)]
@

<<extract main read track>>=
def read_track(dsk, track, base_page, mem):
    """Read 16 sectors of a track into mem using the custom interleave.

    Each physical sector on disk maps to a page offset via
    LOADER_INTERLEAVE, so the data lands at (base_page + offset) * 256.
    """
    for phys in range(16):
        page_offset = LOADER_INTERLEAVE[phys]
        dos_logical = DOS_SKEW[phys]
        file_pos = (track * 16 + dos_logical) * 256
        dest = (base_page + page_offset) * 256 - BASE_ADDR
        if 0 <= dest and dest + 256 <= SIZE:
            mem[dest:dest + 256] = dsk[file_pos:file_pos + 256]
@

<<extract main funny inc>>=
def funny_inc_gen(bot=2, top=3):
    """Yield the EALDR_FUNNY_INC key sequence: 1,2,3, 1,2,3,4, ..."""
    while True:
        bot += 1
        if bot == top:
            bot = 1
            top += 1
            yield 1
        else:
            yield bot
@

<<extract main dxr>>=
def dxr_decrypt(mem):
    """XOR every other byte from $4000 to $67FE with the funny_inc key."""
    keys = funny_inc_gen()
    src = 0x4000
    while True:
        key = next(keys)
        offset = src - BASE_ADDR
        if 0 <= offset < SIZE:
            mem[offset] ^= key
        src += 2
        if (src >> 8) == 0x68:  # src_hi ^ $68 == 0 -> done
            break
@


<<extract main entry>>=
def main():
    with open(DSK_FILE, "rb") as f:
        dsk = f.read()
    with open(EALDR_FILE, "rb") as f:
        ealdr = f.read()

    mem = bytearray(SIZE)

    # Group 2: tracks $07-$0C -> $4000-$95FF
    for track, base_page in GROUP2:
        read_track(dsk, track, base_page, mem)

    # Group 3: tracks $0D-$10 -> $0800-$3FFF
    for track, base_page in GROUP3:
        read_track(dsk, track, base_page, mem)

    # DXR decrypt $4000-$67FE
    dxr_decrypt(mem)

    # Copy EALDR $A300-$A5FF -> $0500-$07FF
    EALDR_SRC = 0xA300 - 0xA000  # offset in ealdr.bin
    mem_dest = 0x0500 - BASE_ADDR
    mem[mem_dest:mem_dest + 0x300] = ealdr[EALDR_SRC:EALDR_SRC + 0x300]

    with open(OUTPUT_FILE, "wb") as f:
        f.write(mem)
    print(f"Wrote {len(mem)} bytes to {OUTPUT_FILE}")
    print(f"Load in Ghidra at $0500, entry point $0800")

if __name__ == "__main__":
    main()
@



\chapter{Initialization}

@ %def INIT_WORLD

@ [[GAME_INIT]] sets up the Apple II for the game.  It runs once at startup,
before the main loop or attract screen.  The steps, in order:

\begin{enumerate}
\item Set the reset vector to [[$A56F]] via the ROM routine at [[$FB6F]].
\item Disable the blink cursor by setting [[BLINK_COL]] to [[20]].
\item Call [[RELOCATE_HIRES_STAGING]] to copy the HRCG library and disk I/O
  routines from the staging area at [[$2000--$3FFF]] to their runtime
  addresses ([[$9600+]] and [[$B300+]]), then clear the staging area to free
  the hi-res page for graphics.
\item Switch to hi-res graphics mode by setting the soft switches at
  [[$C050]] (graphics), [[$C052]] (full screen), [[$C054]] (page~1), and
  [[$C057]] (hi-res).
\item Call [[INIT_DISK_IOB]] to set up the disk I/O parameter block.
\item Call [[INIT_HRCG]] to patch and initialize the [[HRCG]] text engine.
\item Call [[SET_TEXT_WINDOW_WRAP]] to enable text window wrap mode.
\item Call [[INIT_STUB]] (a single RTS---likely a disabled hook point).
\item Call [[INIT_GAME_STATE]] to draw the game display (borders, labels,
  icons) and run the opening tune.
\item Call [[FILL_MAP]] to fill the map grid with default tiles.
\item Call [[SET_TEXT_WINDOW_BOTTOM]] to confine text output to the bottom
  three rows (the status/input area).
\item Call [[INIT_STUB2]] (another no-op hook).
\item Clear state variables to zero:
  \begin{itemize}
  \item [[LOCATION_POS]]---the last-drawn location identifier.  The main
    loop compares this against the current character's location; when they
    differ, it triggers a full map redraw.  Zeroing it here forces the first
    [[ENTER_LOCATION]] call to redraw unconditionally.
  \item [[LOCATION_STYLE]]---the current map tile style (which tile set to
    use when drawing the map).  Zeroing ensures it will be reloaded from the
    location record on the first scene entry.
  \item [[ENTITY_PTR+1]]---the high byte of the entity record pointer
    ([[$F8/$F9]]).  Zeroing signals ``no entity selected,'' preventing stale
    pointer references before the first character is processed.
  \end{itemize}
\item Call [[SELECT_INPUT_MODE]] to detect keyboard or joystick.
\item Call [[INIT_WORLD]] to initialize the game world from its data table.
\item Call [[INIT_MOB_COUNT]] to count all active mob groups.
\item Set [[CURRENT_PLAYER]] to~1.  The main loop walks the 62-entry
  record table once per round, using [[CURRENT_PLAYER]] as a 1-based
  index.  Initializing it to~1 starts the iteration at the first record.
\end{enumerate}

@ The following state variables are referenced by [[GAME_INIT]].
[[BLINK_COL]] is the cursor blink column; storing [[$14]] disables the
blink.  [[LOCATION_POS]], [[LOCATION_STYLE]], and [[CURRENT_PLAYER]] are
the three variables cleared to zero during step~13/17 (described above).
[[ENTITY_PTR]] ([[$F8/$F9]]) is the 2-byte pointer to the entity record
currently being processed.

<<defines>>=
BLINK_COL       EQU     $5AA2   ; font column  (0-19; $14 = disabled)
LOCATION_POS        EQU     $5A55   ; current location position (triggers redraw when changed)
LOCATION_STYLE      EQU     $5A56   ; current map style (from record field 5, bits 0-6)
CURRENT_PLAYER      EQU     $5A02   ; current player index (1-based)
ENTITY_PTR          EQU     $F8     ; entity record pointer (2 bytes, $F8/$F9)

    ; --- Character index record field offsets (9-byte, via CHAR_PTR) ---
CFIELD_NEXT         EQU     $02     ; byte 2: next link pointer
CFIELD_POSITION     EQU     $03     ; byte 3: map position (packed col/row)
CFIELD_APPEARANCE   EQU     $04     ; byte 4: appearance index
CFIELD_STYLE        EQU     $05     ; byte 5: location style (bits 6-0)
CFIELD_EVENTS       EQU     $06     ; bytes 6-7: pointer to event list (2 bytes)
CFIELD_XP           EQU     $08     ; byte 8: status (7) | pending XP (6-4) | group count (3-0)

    ; --- Mob data record field offsets (16-byte, via ENTITY_PTR/MOB_PTR) ---
MFIELD_TYPE         EQU     $01     ; byte 1: entity type/class (for CLASSIFY_ENTITY_TYPE)
MFIELD_NEXT         EQU     $02     ; byte 2: next link pointer
MFIELD_POSITION     EQU     $03     ; byte 3: map position (packed col/row)
MFIELD_APPEARANCE   EQU     $04     ; byte 4: appearance index
MFIELD_STRENGTH     EQU     $05     ; byte 5: bits 4-0 = strength / bits 4-1 = defense
MFIELD_MOB_TYPE     EQU     $06     ; byte 6: bits 5-0 = mob type (>= 3 = active)
MFIELD_ATTACK       EQU     $07     ; byte 7: attack stat
MFIELD_XP           EQU     $08     ; byte 8: status (7) | pending XP (6-4) | group count (3-0)
MFIELD_DEFENSE      EQU     $09     ; byte 9: defense stat
MFIELD_LEVEL        EQU     $0B     ; byte 11: class/faction (7-5) | level (4-0)
MFIELD_LEVEL_ENC    EQU     $0C     ; byte 12: level encoding (hi nib = XP mult, lo nib = base)
MFIELD_GOLD_LO      EQU     $0D     ; byte 13: gold counter low byte
MFIELD_GOLD_HI      EQU     $0E     ; byte 14: gold counter high byte
MFIELD_CHAR         EQU     $00     ; byte 0: display character
MFIELD_FLAGS        EQU     $0F     ; byte 15: status flags (bit 2 = combat engaged)
@ %def BLINK_COL LOCATION_POS LOCATION_STYLE CURRENT_PLAYER ENTITY_PTR CFIELD_NEXT CFIELD_POSITION CFIELD_APPEARANCE CFIELD_STYLE CFIELD_EVENTS CFIELD_XP MFIELD_NEXT MFIELD_POSITION MFIELD_APPEARANCE MFIELD_STRENGTH MFIELD_MOB_TYPE MFIELD_ATTACK MFIELD_XP MFIELD_DEFENSE MFIELD_LEVEL

<<game init>>=
    ORG     $78C7
GAME_INIT:
    SUBROUTINE GAME_INIT

    LDX     #$6F                   ; \
    LDY     #$A5                   ;  | reset vector = $A56F
    STX     $03F2                  ;  |
    STY     $03F3                  ; /
    JSR     $FB6F                  ; ROM: set reset vector
    STOB    #$14,BLINK_COL ; disable blink cursor
    JSR     RELOCATE_HIRES_STAGING ; copy $2000+ to $9600+/$B300+
    LDA     $C050                  ; graphics mode
    LDA     $C052                  ; full screen (no text split)
    LDA     $C054                  ; page 1
    LDA     $C057                  ; hi-res
    JSR     INIT_DISK_IOB
    JSR     INIT_HRCG
    JSR     SET_TEXT_WINDOW_WRAP
    JSR     INIT_STUB
    JSR     INIT_GAME_STATE
    JSR     FILL_MAP
    JSR     SET_TEXT_WINDOW_BOTTOM
    JSR     INIT_STUB2
    STOB    #$00,LOCATION_POS ;  clear state variables
    STA     LOCATION_STYLE         ;  |
    STA     ENTITY_PTR+1           ; /
    JSR     SELECT_INPUT_MODE
    JSR     INIT_WORLD
    JSR     INIT_MOB_COUNT
    STOB    #$01,CURRENT_PLAYER
    RTS
@ %def GAME_INIT
During startup, tracks [[$0F]] and [[$10]] are loaded into the hi-res
page area [[$2000--$3FFF]] as a staging area.  [[RELOCATE_HIRES_STAGING]],
called from [[GAME_INIT]], copies the staged data to its runtime addresses
and clears the hi-res page:

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{ccl}
\toprule
\thead{Source} & \thead{Destination} & \thead{Size} \\
\midrule
\$2000--\$32FF & \$9600--\$A8FF & 19 pages (HRCG code + standard font) \\
\$3300--\$3FFF & \$B300--\$BFFF & 13 pages (disk I/O routines) \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

The copy loop at [[.copy]] also clears each source byte, leaving the
hi-res page zeroed for use as a graphics buffer.

@ [[RELOCATE_HIRES_STAGING]] uses two zero-page pointer pairs for
its block copy: [[COPY_SRC]] ([[$BC/$BD]]) points to the source
address in the staging area, and [[COPY_DEST]] ([[$BA/$BB]]) points
to the runtime destination.  The loop copies one byte at a time,
zeroing the source as it goes.

<<zero page defines>>=
COPY_SRC                EQU     $BC     ; block copy source pointer (2 bytes)
COPY_DEST               EQU     $BA     ; block copy destination pointer (2 bytes)
@ %def COPY_SRC COPY_DEST

<<relocate hires staging>>=
    ORG     $6DA5
RELOCATE_HIRES_STAGING:
    SUBROUTINE RELOCATE_HIRES_STAGING

    STOB    #$00,COPY_DEST ; dest = $9600
    STA     COPY_SRC      ; \  src  = $2000
    STOB    #$20,COPY_SRC+1 ; src hi
    STOB    #$96,COPY_DEST+1 ; dest hi
    LDY     #$00
    LDX     #$13          ; 19 pages: $2000-$32FF -> $9600-$A8FF
    JSR     .copy
    LDX     #$0D          ; 13 pages: $3300-$3FFF -> $B300-$BFFF
    STOB    #$B3,COPY_DEST+1 ; dest hi = $B3
    INC     COPY_SRC+1    ; src hi = $33 (was $32 after first pass)

.copy:
    LDA     (COPY_SRC),Y  ; load from source
    STA     (COPY_DEST),Y ; store to dest
    LDA     #$00
    STA     (COPY_SRC),Y  ; clear source byte
    DEY
    BNE     .copy         ; inner loop (256 bytes)
    DEX
    BNE     .next_page    ; more pages?
    RTS

.next_page:
    INC     COPY_SRC+1    ; next source page
    INC     COPY_DEST+1   ; next dest page
    JMP     .copy
@ %def RELOCATE_HIRES_STAGING

@ \subsection{Zeroed hi-res page (\$2000--\$3FFF)}

After [[RELOCATE_HIRES_STAGING]] copies \$2000--\$32FF to
\$9600--\$A8FF and \$3300--\$3FFF to \$B300--\$BFFF, it clears
each source byte to zero.  The result is 8192 bytes of zeros at
\$2000--\$3FFF, making the hi-res page available for graphics.

<<zeroed hires page>>=
    ORG     $2000
HIRES_PAGE:
    DS      $2000,$00          ; 8192 bytes zeroed by game_init
@ %def HIRES_PAGE

The plain text screen (using the standard Apple text characters) is 40
columns by 24 rows. The [[TEXT_COL]] and [[TEXT_ROW]] locations keep track
of the cursor position when ROM routines are used for printing text.

We can set the text window to start either from row 0 using [[SET_TEXT_WINDOW_UPPER_LEFT_ALL]],
or from row 21 using [[SET_TEXT_WINDOW_UPPER_LEFT_LOW]]. Using the bottom of the
screen allows us to use it as a status and input window while the map is displayed
above.

Initializes the Hi-Res Character Generator (HRCG) by patching two
locations in the HRCG code and then jumping to its entry point at
[[$92A8]].  The patches modify the HRCG initialization to work within
the game's environment:

\begin{itemize}
\item [[$94B6]] $\leftarrow$ \texttt{RTS} (\$60): causes HRCG init to
  return early, skipping the remainder of its setup.
\item [[$92D5--$92D7]] $\leftarrow$ three \texttt{NOP}s (\$EA): patches
  out a [[JSR $03EA]] that would reconnect DOS, which the game does not
  want.
\end{itemize}

After patching, the routine tail-calls the HRCG init via [[JMP $92A8]],
which returns to [[GAME_INIT]] via the patched RTS.

@ [[INIT_HRCG]] patches two locations in the HRCG library before calling
its initialization entry point.  First, it writes an RTS opcode at~\$94B6,
causing the HRCG's internal initialization to return early---skipping
setup steps that the game handles differently.  Second, it writes three NOP
opcodes over the JSR at~\$92D5, disabling the HRCG's attempt to reconnect
DOS (which would conflict with the game's custom disk routines).  With these
patches in place, the routine jumps to [[HRCG_INIT]] at~\$92A8 to
complete the HRCG startup.

<<init hrcg>>=
    ORG     $791A
INIT_HRCG:
    SUBROUTINE INIT_HRCG

    STOB    #$60,$94B6 ; RTS opcode
    STOB    #$EA,$92D5 ; NOP opcode
    STA     $92D6     ;  | (skip DOS reconnect)
    STA     $92D7     ; /
    JMP     HRCG_INIT ; enter HRCG initialization
@ %def INIT_HRCG
A single [[RTS]]---a no-op stub called from [[GAME_INIT]].  Likely a
hook point or a disabled feature from development.


<<init stub>>=
