INIT_STUB2:
    RTS
@ %def INIT_STUB2

@ [[INIT_DISK_IOB]] sets the zero-page pointer [[RWTS_IOB_PTR]]
([[$08/$09]]) to the address of the RWTS Input/Output Block
([[RWTS_IOB]] at [[$B7E8]]).  This single-assignment call during
[[GAME_INIT]] enables all subsequent disk operations to access the IOB
fields through indirect-indexed addressing (e.g.\ [[LDA ($08),Y]]
with~Y selecting the field).

<<defines>>=
RWTS_IOB                EQU     $B7E8   ; RWTS Input/Output Block (14 bytes)
@ %def RWTS_IOB

<<zero page defines>>=
RWTS_IOB_PTR            EQU     $08     ; ZP pointer to RWTS IOB ($B7E8)
@ %def RWTS_IOB_PTR

<<init disk iob>>=
    ORG     $6C2E
INIT_DISK_IOB:
    SUBROUTINE INIT_DISK_IOB

    LDA     #>RWTS_IOB     ; \ set RWTS IOB pointer
    LDY     #<RWTS_IOB     ;  | $08/$09 = $B7E8
    STA     RWTS_IOB_PTR+1 ;  |
    STY     RWTS_IOB_PTR   ; /
    RTS
@ %def INIT_DISK_IOB
<<defines>>=
INPUT_MODE          EQU     $5A00   ; 0 = keyboard, 1 = joystick
@ %def INPUT_MODE

Prompts the player to choose keyboard or joystick input.  Displays
message~\$38 (the prompt), then polls the keyboard and paddle button~1
in a tight loop.  If the player presses the space bar, [[INPUT_MODE]]
is set to~0 (keyboard).  If the paddle button state changes (pressed or
released), [[INPUT_MODE]] is set to~1 (joystick), the cursor is
repositioned, and message~\$2F (joystick confirmation) is displayed.

<<select input mode>>=
    ORG     $084E
SELECT_INPUT_MODE:
    SUBROUTINE SELECT_INPUT_MODE

    LDA     #MSG_INPUT_PROMPT           ; message $38: input mode prompt
    JSR     DISPLAY_MESSAGE
    LDA     $C061          ; read paddle button 1
    AND     #$80           ; isolate bit 7 (pressed state)
    STA     $BA            ; save initial button state
.clear:
    STA     $C010          ; clear keyboard strobe
.poll:
    LDX     $C000          ; read keyboard
    BMI     .key           ; key pressed -> check it
    LDA     $C061          ; re-read paddle button
    EOR     $BA            ; compare with initial state
    BMI     .joystick      ; button state changed -> joystick
    BPL     .poll          ; keep polling
.key:
    BXEQ    #$A0,.keyboard ; yes -> keyboard mode
    BNE     .clear         ; other key -> ignore, clear strobe
.keyboard:
    STOB    #$00,INPUT_MODE ; 0 = keyboard
    RTS
.joystick:
    STOB    #$01,INPUT_MODE ; 1 = joystick
    JSR     SET_CURSOR_ROW21
    LDA     #MSG_JOYSTICK_MODE           ; message $2F: joystick confirmation
    JMP     DISPLAY_MESSAGE
@ %def SELECT_INPUT_MODE

@ [[INIT_MOB_COUNT]] is called once during [[GAME_INIT]] to initialize
[[TOTAL_MOB_COUNT]].  It walks all 9-byte character records using
[[CHAR_PTR]] ([[$FA/$FB]]) starting from index~1 (skipping the group-0
header at [[$4000]]), summing byte~8 (group member count) of each record
until the end sentinel (byte~1 = [[$FF]]) is reached.

The result in [[TOTAL_MOB_COUNT]] is the total number of mobs assigned to
groups~1 and above.  At startup, byte~8 contains only the group count in
bits~3--0 (the upper bits---pending XP and status flag---are zero), so the
sum is simply the total mob count.

<<zero page defines>>=
CHAR_PTR                EQU     $FA     ; character record pointer (2 bytes, $FA/$FB)
@ %def CHAR_PTR

<<defines>>=
TOTAL_MOB_COUNT     EQU     $5A01   ; total mobs across all groups (excl. group 0)
@ %def TOTAL_MOB_COUNT

<<init mob count>>=
    ORG     $0C51
INIT_MOB_COUNT:
    SUBROUTINE INIT_MOB_COUNT

    STOB    #$00,TOTAL_MOB_COUNT ; clear total
    STOW    $4009,CHAR_PTR ; $FA/$FB = $4009 (record 1)
.loop:
    LDY     #$01
    LDA     (CHAR_PTR),Y    ; byte 1 of record
    BANE    #$FF,.count     ; $FF = end sentinel
    RTS
.count:
    LDY     #$08
    LDA     (CHAR_PTR),Y    ; byte 8 = group member count
    CLC
    ADC     TOTAL_MOB_COUNT ; accumulate
    STA     TOTAL_MOB_COUNT
    LDA     #$09            ; \ advance $FA by 9 (next record)
    ADC     CHAR_PTR        ;  |
    STA     CHAR_PTR        ;  |
    BCC     .loop           ;  |
    INC     CHAR_PTR+1      ;  |
    BCS     .loop           ; / always taken
@ %def INIT_MOB_COUNT

\chapter{Apple II Hi-Res Graphics}

Hi-res graphics on the Apple II is odd. Graphics are memory-mapped, not exactly
consecutively, and bits don't always correspond to pixels. Color especially is
odd, compared to today's luxurious 32-bit per pixel RGBA.

The Apple II has two hi-res graphics pages, and maps the area from [[$2000-$3FFF]] to
high-res graphics page 1 (HGR1), and [[$4000-$5FFF]] to page 2 (HGR2).

First we'll talk about pixels. Nominally, the resolution of the hi-res graphics screen
is 280 pixels wide by 192 pixels tall. In the memory map, each row is represented
by 40 bytes. The high bit of each byte is not used for pixel data, but is used to
control color.

Here are some rules for how these bytes are turned into pixels:
\begin{itemize}
  \item Pixels are drawn to the screen from byte data least significant bit first.
        This means that for the first byte bit 0 is column 0, bit 1 is column 1,
        and so on.
  \item A pattern of [[11]] results in two white pixels at the [[1]] positions.
  \item A pattern of [[010]] results at least in a colored pixel at the [[1]] position.
  \item A pattern of [[101]] results at least in a colored pixel at the [[0]] position.
  \item So, a pattern of [[01010]] results in at least three consecutive colored
        pixels starting from the first [[1]] to the last [[1]]. The last [[0]] bit
        would also be colored if followed by a [[1]].
  \item Likewise, a pattern of [[11011]] results in two white pixels, a colored pixel,
        and then two more white pixels.
  \item The color of a [[010]] pixel depends on the column that the [[1]] falls on, and
        also whether the high bit of its byte was set or not.
  \item The color of a [[11011]] pixel depends on the column that the [[0]] falls on, and
        also whether the high bit of its byte was set or not.

        \begin{center}
        \begin{tabular}{@{}rcc@{}} \toprule
        & Odd & Even \\ \cmidrule(r){2-3}
        High bit clear & Green & Violet \\
        High bit set & Orange & Blue \\ \bottomrule
        \end{tabular}
        \end{center}

        The implication is that you can only select one pair of colors per byte.
\end{itemize}

An example would probably be good here. We will take one of the font characters from the game,
the lower-case [[r]]:

