\chapter{The HRCG Text Engine}

The Hi-Res Character Generator (HRCG) is a library provided by the Applesoft Toolkit
which allows a developer to display a custom font. Applesoft Toolkit also
contains Animatrix, which is a utility used to create fonts for the HRCG.

The \href{https://archive.org/details/applesoft-toolkit}{manual for the Applesoft Toolkit}
can be found on the Internet Archive.

The HRCG defines 96 characters as a character set. These characters are the
``printing'' characters, which are ASCII 32 (space) through 127 (delete).
Character set~0 is always the standard set of Apple text characters. The
font data for this standard set is stored at [[$97A5--$9AA4]], consisting of
8~bytes per character. Each byte represents 7~consecutive pixels since the
high bit is used for color set selection.

Note: the standard font data and the HRCG code at [[$9600--$97A4]] are not
loaded directly to their final addresses by the EALDR\@.  Instead, the EALDR
loads them into the hi-res page area [[$2000--$32FF]] (tracks~[[$0F]] and
[[$10]]).  During [[GAME_INIT]], the routine at [[$6DA5]] copies
[[$2000--$32FF]] to [[$9600--$A8FF]] and clears [[$2000--$3FFF]].

The Ali Baba font data for HRCG is stored at [[$83A5-$92A4]], starting with character set 1.
Each character is 32 bytes, broken
up into four blocks of eight bytes (7x8 blocks) each. The first block is the upper left of the character, the second block is
the upper right, the third is the lower left, and the fourth is the lower right.
Thus, each character is 14x16.

Here are the font characters. There are 120 defined: 96 for character set 1,
and 24 for character set 2. Characters 114-119 (character set 2, characters 18-23)
form the EA logo that is displayed on the splash screen. Then character set 0
defines the fallback characters 32 through 127.

<<font data>>=
    ORG     $83A5
FONT_DATA:
    INCLUDE "fontdata.asm"
@ %def FONT_DATA

<<std font data>>=
    ORG     $97A5
STD_FONT_DATA:
    INCLUDE "stdfontdata.asm"
@ %def STD_FONT_DATA
@ Immediately following the entry table is the HRCG version string.  The
string is stored in high-bit ASCII (the standard Apple II text encoding) and
is prefixed with a ctrl-P character, which triggers the HRCG's ``home cursor''
command.  A carriage return ([[$8D]]) terminates the string.
[[HRCG_PRINT_VERSION]] prints this string to the screen character by character
via [[ROM_COUT1]]; it is not used during normal gameplay.

<<hrcg version string>>=
    ORG     $92E8
HRCG_VERSION_STR:
; "HI-RES CHAR GEN VERSION 1.0" with ctrl-P prefix and CR suffix (high-bit ASCII)
    HEX     90 C8 C9 AD D2 C5 D3 A0 C3 C8 C1 D2 A0 C7 C5 CE
    HEX     A0 D6 C5 D2 D3 C9 CF CE A0 B1 AE B0 8D
@ %def HRCG_VERSION_STR

\input{font_data.tex}

The HRCG hooks the character output (CSW)
and keyboard input (KSW) vectors to render text on the hi-res graphics
screen.  The library is self-contained at \$92A8--\$97A4 and provides:
\begin{itemize}
\item Character rendering in multiple fonts (up to 10 charsets of 8-byte glyphs)
\item Video modes: replace, OR, AND, XOR with optional page-2 overlay
\item Inverse, lowercase-invert, and shifted-character support
\item A full set of control-character handlers for cursor movement,
      screen clearing, window management, and state save/restore
\item Cursor blinking in the keyboard input handler
\item Scrolling and line-wrap modes
\end{itemize}

The game's [[INIT_HRCG]] routine patches out the DOS reconnect call
and injects an early RTS into [[HRCG_DISPLAY_PAGE]] before jumping
to [[HRCG_INIT]].

<<hrcg init>>=
    ORG     $92A8
HRCG_INIT:
; --- HRCG entry jump table ---
    JMP     HRCG_INIT_BODY ; main init entry
HRCG_NUM_CHARSETS:
    DC.B    $0A            ; 10 custom charsets
HRCG_FONT_BASE:
    DC.W    FONT_DATA      ; font base address ($83A5)
HRCG_ENTRY2:
    JMP     HRCG_RTS       ; secondary entry (disabled)
HRCG_ENTRY3:
    JMP     HRCG_RTS       ; secondary entry (disabled)
; --- HRCG_PRINT_VERSION ---
HRCG_PRINT_VERSION:
    SUBROUTINE HRCG_PRINT_VERSION
    JSR     HRCG_INIT_BODY
    LDY     #$00
.loop:
    LDA     HRCG_VERSION_STR,Y
    JSR     ROM_COUT1
    INY
    CPY     #$1D           ; 29 chars
    BCC     .loop
    RTS
; --- HRCG_INIT_BODY ---
HRCG_INIT_BODY:
    SUBROUTINE HRCG_INIT_BODY
    STOW    HRCG_GETKEY,$38 ; KSW low
    STOW    HRCG_COUT,$36 ; CSW low
    JSR     $03EA          ; reconnect DOS (patched to NOPs by game)
    BIT     $C052          ; full-screen mode (no mixed)
    BIT     $C057          ; hi-res mode
    JSR     HRCG_RESET
    JSR     HRCG_DISPLAY_PAGE
    BIT     $C050          ; graphics mode on
    RTS
@ %def HRCG_INIT HRCG_NUM_CHARSETS HRCG_FONT_BASE HRCG_ENTRY2 HRCG_ENTRY3 HRCG_PRINT_VERSION HRCG_INIT_BODY
@ The HRCG maintains its state in a self-modifying parameter block at
[[$9305--$9319]].  These 21~bytes control every aspect of text rendering:
which font is active, whether characters are drawn in replace, OR, AND, or
XOR mode, whether inverse video is enabled, and whether the cursor wraps or
scrolls at the bottom of the text window.

The parameter block is laid out so that it can be saved and restored in bulk
by the ctrl-B and ctrl-D handlers.  The first 8~bytes ([[HRCG_VIDEO_MODE]]
through [[HRCG_FONT_PTR_HI]]) are the saveable state; these are followed by
a saved copy, a ``saved'' flag byte, and the saved cursor position.

<<hrcg params>>=
    ORG     $9305
HRCG_SHIFT_FLAG:
    DC.B    $00                             ; $00=normal, $40=next-shifted, $80=charset-select
@ %def HRCG_SHIFT_FLAG

<<hrcg video mode>>=
    ORG     $9307
HRCG_VIDEO_MODE:
    DC.B    $20                             ; $20=replace, $40=OR, $80=AND, $C0=XOR
@ %def HRCG_VIDEO_MODE
@ The HRCG replaces both the Apple II's character output vector (CSW at
[[$36/$37]]) and its keyboard input vector (KSW at [[$38/$39]]).
[[HRCG_GETKEY]] is the KSW handler.  Its primary job is to blink the cursor
while waiting for a keypress, but it also interprets ESC-key sequences for
cursor movement and screen editing---a miniature line editor built into the
input routine.

The blinking works by toggling the 7~pixel bits at the cursor's screen
position.  A countdown register ([[X]]) controls the blink rate: every time
the high byte of the blink timer overflows, [[X]] decrements, and when it
reaches zero the cursor pixels are inverted.  The blink timer at [[$4E/$4F]]
ticks continuously while the routine polls [[$C000]] for a keypress.

When a key arrives, the routine checks whether it was called from the ROM
input routine at [[$F8xx]] (by peeking at the return address on the stack).
If so, it processes ESC sequences---ESC followed by I/J/K/M for cursor
movement, or ESC-@/E/F/C for screen editing.  If the caller is not the ROM,
the raw keycode is returned immediately.

<<hrcg getkey>>=
    ORG     $931A
HRCG_GETKEY:
    SUBROUTINE HRCG_GETKEY
; --- KSW handler: cursor blink + keyboard input ---
    STA     ($28),Y            ; save char at cursor pos (BASL)
    STX     $EB                ; save X
    MOVB    $28,$2A ; BASL
    LDA     $29                ; BASH
    ORA     #$1C               ; set hi-res page offset bits
    ORA     HRCG_VIDEO_MODE
    STA     $2B                ; store hi byte
    LDX     #$01               ; blink counter init
.blink_loop:
    LDA     ($2A),Y            ; read screen byte at cursor
    PHA                        ; save it
.blink_wait:
    INC     $4E                ; increment blink timer low
    BNE     .blink_check
    INC     $4F                ; increment blink timer high
    DEX                        ; decrement blink counter
    BNE     .blink_check
    EOR     #$7F               ; toggle cursor (invert bits 0-6)
    STA     ($2A),Y            ; write toggled cursor
    LDX     #$50               ; reset blink counter
.blink_check:
    BIT     $C000              ; check keyboard
    BPL     .blink_wait        ; no key -> keep blinking
    PLA                        ; restore original screen byte
    STA     ($2A),Y            ; restore cursor position
    TSX                        ; get stack pointer
    LDA     $0104,X            ; peek at return address high byte
    CMP     #$F8               ; called from ROM input ($F8xx)?
    LDA     $C000              ; read key
    BIT     $C010              ; clear keyboard strobe
    BCC     .return_direct     ; not from ROM -> return key directly
    PHA                        ; save key
    BIT     HRCG_SHIFT_FLAG    ; check shift flag
    BMI     .shifted           ; if set -> handle shifted key
    BANE    #$9B,.check_cr     ; ESC key?
    STOB    #$80,HRCG_SHIFT_FLAG ; set shift flag
    BNE     .discard_key       ; always branch -> return
.check_cr:
    BANE    #$8D,.discard_key  ; CR key?
    JSR     HRCG_CLREOL        ; clear rest of line
.reload_ch:
    LDY     $24                ; reload cursor X
.discard_key:
    PLA                        ; discard saved key
.return_direct:
    LDX     $EB                ; restore X
    RTS
; --- Shifted key handling (ESC was pressed) ---
.shifted:
    BALT    #$C9,.try_other    ; 'I' ?
    BAEQ    #$CD,.scroll_down  ; 'M' ?
    BCS     .try_other         ; > 'M' -> try as normal
    BAEQ    #$CB,.cursor_right ; 'K' ?
    BCC     .discard_key       ; < 'K' (='J') -> ignore
.try_other:
    ASL     HRCG_SHIFT_FLAG    ; clear shift flag
    BANE    #$C0,.try_e        ; '@' ?
    JSR     HRCG_HOME
    JMP     .reload_ch
.try_e:
    BANE    #$C5,.try_f        ; 'E' ?
    JSR     HRCG_CLREOL
    JMP     .reload_ch
.try_f:
    BANE    #$C6,.try_c        ; 'F' ?
    JSR     HRCG_CLRLINE
    JMP     .reload_ch
.try_c:
    BAEQ    #$C3,.scroll_down  ; 'C' ?
    BANE    #$C1,.discard_key  ; not recognized -> return
.cursor_right:
    INY                        ; cursor right: Y++
    CPY     $21                ; past right edge (WNDWDTH)?
    BCC     .reload_ch
.scroll_down:
    LDY     $25                ; get cursor Y (CV)
    INY
    CPY     $23                ; past bottom (WNDBTM)?
    BCC     .reload_ch
    JSR     HRCG_SCROLL_UP
    JMP     .reload_ch
@ %def HRCG_GETKEY
@ The dispatch table maps each control character (ctrl-@~through ctrl-Z)
to a handler address, stored as address-minus-one for the RTS trick.  The
HRCG supports a ``shifted'' variant of each control character: if the
previous character was ctrl-A or ctrl-O, a flag is set in
[[HRCG_MODE_FLAGS]], and when the next handler is entered, the carry flag
will be set (from the [[ASL HRCG_MODE_FLAGS]] in [[HRCG_PROCESS_CHAR]]).
Each handler checks carry on entry to decide between its normal and shifted
behavior.

<<hrcg dispatch table>>=
    ORG     $93EE
HRCG_DISPATCH_TBL:
; Control character dispatch table (address-1 for RTS trick)
; ctrl-@: no-op
    DC.W    HRCG_CTRL_NOP-1
; ctrl-A: set shift/charset flag
    DC.W    HRCG_CTRL_A-1
; ctrl-B: save state
    DC.W    HRCG_CTRL_B_SAVE-1
; ctrl-C: restore cursor / XOR mode
    DC.W    HRCG_CTRL_C-1
; ctrl-D: restore state / display page
    DC.W    HRCG_CTRL_D-1
; ctrl-E: clear EOL
    DC.W    HRCG_CTRL_E-1
; ctrl-F: clear to end of screen
    DC.W    HRCG_CTRL_F-1
; ctrl-G: bell
    DC.W    $FBDC
; ctrl-H: backspace
    DC.W    HRCG_CTRL_H-1
; ctrl-I: inverse video
    DC.W    HRCG_CTRL_I-1
; ctrl-J: line feed
    DC.W    HRCG_LINE_FEED-1
; ctrl-K: clear invert flag
    DC.W    HRCG_CTRL_K-1
; ctrl-L: set invert flag
    DC.W    HRCG_CTRL_L-1
; ctrl-M: carriage return
    DC.W    HRCG_CTRL_M-1
; ctrl-N: normal video
    DC.W    HRCG_CTRL_N-1
; ctrl-O: next-shifted / OR mode
    DC.W    HRCG_CTRL_O-1
; ctrl-P: home / clear draw mode
    DC.W    HRCG_CTRL_P-1
; ctrl-Q: goto saved cursor
    DC.W    HRCG_CTRL_Q-1
; ctrl-R: XOR draw mode
    DC.W    HRCG_CTRL_R-1
; ctrl-S: XOR invert / clear wrap
    DC.W    HRCG_CTRL_S-1
; ctrl-T: AND draw mode
    DC.W    HRCG_CTRL_T-1
; ctrl-U: no-op
    DC.W    HRCG_CTRL_NOP-1
; ctrl-V: set text window
    DC.W    HRCG_CTRL_V-1
; ctrl-W: set margins
    DC.W    HRCG_CTRL_W-1
; ctrl-X: no-op
    DC.W    HRCG_CTRL_NOP-1
; ctrl-Y: clear screen
    DC.W    HRCG_CTRL_Y-1
; ctrl-Z: reset
    DC.W    HRCG_CTRL_Z-1
@ %def HRCG_DISPATCH_TBL
@ [[HRCG_COUT]] is the CSW handler---the replacement for the Apple II's
standard character output routine.  Every [[JSR ROM_COUT1]] in the game
ultimately lands here.  The handler is a thin wrapper: it saves the CPU
registers, calls [[HRCG_PROCESS_CHAR]], and restores them.

[[HRCG_PROCESS_CHAR]] strips the high bit from the character (Apple II text
uses high-bit ASCII) and decides what to do with it.  If the ``charset
select'' flag is set in [[HRCG_MODE_FLAGS]], the character is treated as a
charset number and routed to [[HRCG_CHARSET_SELECT]].  Otherwise, printable
characters ([[$20]] and above) go to [[HRCG_DRAW_CHAR]] for rendering, and
control characters (below [[$20]]) are dispatched through a 27-entry
RTS-trick jump table.  The dispatch doubles the control code to form a
table index, pushes the handler address (minus one) onto the stack, and
falls through to [[RTS]]---the classic 6502 technique for computed jumps.

<<hrcg mode flags>>=
    ORG     $9306
HRCG_MODE_FLAGS:
    DC.B    $00                             ; bit 7/6 shifted by ASL during dispatch
@ %def HRCG_MODE_FLAGS

<<hrcg cout>>=
    ORG     $93BE
HRCG_COUT:
    SUBROUTINE HRCG_COUT
; --- CSW handler: save regs, process char, restore ---
    STA     $FF                   ; save A
    STX     $EB                   ; save X
    STY     $35                   ; save Y
    JSR     HRCG_PROCESS_CHAR
    LDY     $35                   ; restore Y
    LDX     $EB                   ; restore X
    LDA     $FF                   ; restore A
    RTS
; --- HRCG_PROCESS_CHAR ---
HRCG_PROCESS_CHAR:
    AND     #$7F                  ; strip high bit
    ASL     HRCG_MODE_FLAGS       ; shift mode bit 7 into carry
    BCS     HRCG_CHARSET_SELECT   ; if set -> charset select
    BALT    #$20,.ctrl_dispatch ; printable char (>= space)?
    JMP     HRCG_DRAW_CHAR
.ctrl_dispatch:
    BAGE    #$1B,.shift_and_rts ; >= ESC ($1B)?
    ASL                           ; char * 2 for table index
    TAX
    LDA     HRCG_DISPATCH_TBL+1,X ; high byte of handler-1
    PHA
    LDA     HRCG_DISPATCH_TBL,X   ; low byte of handler-1
    PHA
.shift_and_rts:
    ASL     HRCG_MODE_FLAGS       ; shift mode bit 6 into carry
    RTS                           ; RTS-trick dispatch
@ %def HRCG_COUT HRCG_PROCESS_CHAR
@ \subsubsection{Control character handlers}

The control character handlers follow.  Each one checks the carry flag on
entry to distinguish its normal behavior from its shifted variant.

Ctrl-A is the charset selector.  In normal mode, it sets [[HRCG_MODE_FLAGS]]
so that the \emph{next} character output will be interpreted as a charset
number (``1'' through ``9'') rather than printed.  In shifted mode (entered via
ctrl-A, ctrl-A, \emph{char}), it resets the video mode to replace.

When the charset-select path fires, the character is converted to a font
pointer by multiplying the charset index by 3~pages (768~bytes per charset of
96~characters at 8~bytes each) and adding the font base address.  Charset~0
always maps to the standard font at [[$97A5]].

<<hrcg font ptr>>=
    ORG     $930D
HRCG_FONT_PTR_LO:
    DC.B    $A5                             ; font data pointer low
HRCG_FONT_PTR_HI:
    DC.B    $97                             ; font data pointer high ($97A5 = standard font)
@ %def HRCG_FONT_PTR_LO HRCG_FONT_PTR_HI

<<hrcg ctrl a>>=
    ORG     $9424
HRCG_CTRL_A:
    SUBROUTINE HRCG_CTRL_A
; --- ctrl-A handler: set shift flag ---
    BCS     HRCG_SET_REPLACE  ; shifted -> set replace mode
    STOB    #$80,HRCG_MODE_FLAGS ; set bit 7 (next char -> charset select)
    RTS
; --- Charset select (entered from HRCG_PROCESS_CHAR BCS) ---
HRCG_CHARSET_SELECT:
    SBC     #$31              ; A = char - '1' (carry set)
    BAGE    #$09,HRCG_SET_STD_FONT ; valid charset 1-9?
    LDX     HRCG_FONT_BASE    ; font base low ($A5)
    STA     $EE               ; save index
    ASL                       ; A * 2
    ADC     $EE               ; A * 3 (3 pages per charset)
    ADC     HRCG_FONT_BASE+1  ; add font base high ($83)
    BNE     .store_font       ; always branches
HRCG_SET_STD_FONT:
    LDX     #<STD_FONT_DATA   ; standard font low
    LDA     #>STD_FONT_DATA   ; standard font high ($97A5)
.store_font:
    STX     HRCG_FONT_PTR_LO  ; font pointer low
    STA     HRCG_FONT_PTR_HI  ; font pointer high
    RTS
@ %def HRCG_CTRL_A HRCG_CHARSET_SELECT HRCG_SET_STD_FONT
@ Ctrl-B saves the HRCG's rendering state---the 8-byte parameter block
(video mode through font pointer) plus the cursor position---so it can be
restored later with ctrl-D.  Only one level of save is supported; if the
state has already been saved, only the cursor position is updated.  The
shifted variant sets OR video mode instead.

This save/restore mechanism is used by the game to temporarily switch fonts
or video modes for status display, then return to the previous rendering
context.

<<hrcg saved state>>=
    ORG     $930F
HRCG_SAVED_PARAMS:
    DC.B    $20,$00,$00,$00,$00,$00,$A5,$97 ; saved copy of video mode..font ptr (8 bytes)
    DC.B    $FF                             ; HRCG_SAVED_FLAG ($00=not saved, $FF=saved)
HRCG_SAVED_CH:
    DC.B    $01                             ; saved cursor X
HRCG_SAVED_CV:
    DC.B    $17                             ; saved cursor Y (23)
@ %def HRCG_SAVED_PARAMS HRCG_SAVED_CH HRCG_SAVED_CV

<<hrcg ctrl b>>=
    ORG     $944A
HRCG_SET_REPLACE:
; --- ctrl-A shifted: set replace video mode ---
    STOB    #$20,HRCG_VIDEO_MODE ; video mode = replace ($20)
    RTS
; --- ctrl-B: save params + cursor ---
HRCG_CTRL_B_SAVE:
    SUBROUTINE HRCG_CTRL_B_SAVE
    BCS     .set_or             ; double-shifted -> set OR mode
    BIT     HRCG_SAVED_PARAMS+8 ; already saved?
    BMI     .save_cursor        ; yes -> just update cursor
    STOB    #$FF,HRCG_SAVED_PARAMS+8 ; mark as saved
    LDY     #$07                ; 8 bytes to save
.save_loop:
    LDA     HRCG_VIDEO_MODE,Y   ; active params
    STA     HRCG_SAVED_PARAMS,Y ; saved copy
    DEY
    BPL     .save_loop
.save_cursor:
    MOVB    $24,HRCG_SAVED_CH ; cursor X (CH)
    MOVB    $25,HRCG_SAVED_CV ; cursor Y (CV)
    RTS
; --- ctrl-B double-shifted: OR video mode ---
.set_or:
    STOB    #$40,HRCG_VIDEO_MODE ; video mode = OR ($40)
    RTS
@ %def HRCG_SET_REPLACE HRCG_CTRL_B_SAVE
@ Ctrl-C restores the saved cursor position (from ctrl-B).  If the saved
column matches the current column, it also performs a line feed.  If the
saved column is to the right of the current column, it does nothing---this
prevents the cursor from jumping backwards unexpectedly.  The shifted
variant enables XOR draw mode on page~1.

<<hrcg draw mode>>=
    ORG     $9309
HRCG_DRAW_MODE:
    DC.B    $00                             ; video mode for drawing ($00/$80/$C0)
HRCG_PAGE_MASK:
    DC.B    $00                             ; $00=page1, $60=page2
@ %def HRCG_DRAW_MODE HRCG_PAGE_MASK

<<hrcg ctrl c>>=
    ORG     $9478
HRCG_CTRL_C:
    SUBROUTINE HRCG_CTRL_C
; --- ctrl-C normal: restore cursor position ---
    BCS     .set_xor_draw  ; shifted -> XOR draw mode
    LDA     HRCG_SAVED_CH  ; saved CH
    CMP     $24            ; compare to current CH
    STA     $24            ; restore CH
    BEQ     .do_lf         ; same -> just do line feed
    BCS     HRCG_CTRL_NOP  ; saved > current -> RTS
.do_lf:
    JMP     HRCG_LINE_FEED
; --- ctrl-C shifted: XOR draw mode ---
.set_xor_draw:
    STOB    #$C0,HRCG_DRAW_MODE ; draw mode = XOR ($C0)
    STOB    #$00,HRCG_PAGE_MASK ; page mask = 0
    RTS
@ %def HRCG_CTRL_C
@ Ctrl-D is the companion to ctrl-B: it restores the full 8-byte parameter
block that was previously saved.  If nothing was saved, it does nothing.
The shifted variant calls [[HRCG_DISPLAY_PAGE]], which selects hi-res page~1
or page~2 based on the current video mode---the game patches this to an
early [[RTS]], effectively disabling page switching.

<<hrcg ctrl d>>=
    ORG     $9493
HRCG_CTRL_D:
    SUBROUTINE HRCG_CTRL_D
; --- ctrl-D normal: restore saved params ---
    BCS     HRCG_DISPLAY_PAGE   ; shifted -> display page
    BIT     HRCG_SAVED_PARAMS+8 ; params saved?
    BPL     HRCG_CTRL_NOP       ; no -> NOP return
    LDY     #$07                ; 8 bytes
.restore_loop:
    LDA     HRCG_SAVED_PARAMS,Y ; saved params
    STA     HRCG_VIDEO_MODE,Y   ; restore to active
    DEY
    BPL     .restore_loop
    STOB    #$00,HRCG_SAVED_PARAMS+8 ; clear saved flag
    STA     HRCG_SAVED_CH       ; clear saved CH
    MOVB    $22,HRCG_SAVED_CV ; WNDTOP
    RTS
; --- HRCG_DISPLAY_PAGE: page flip based on video mode ---
HRCG_DISPLAY_PAGE:
    BIT     $C054               ; select page 1
    LDA     HRCG_VIDEO_MODE     ; video mode
    BANE    #$40,HRCG_CTRL_NOP  ; no -> return (stay on page 1)
    BIT     $C055               ; yes -> select page 2
    RTS
@ %def HRCG_CTRL_D HRCG_DISPLAY_PAGE
@ The next group of handlers covers screen clearing, cursor movement, and
inverse video.  Ctrl-E clears from the cursor to the end of the current
line.  Ctrl-F clears from the cursor to the end of the screen.  Both
delegate to the HRCG's own clear routines and then call the corresponding
ROM routine to update the text-page shadow.

Ctrl-H is backspace: it decrements the cursor column, and if it wraps past
column~0, it moves to the end of the previous row (provided the cursor is
not already at the top of the text window).  Ctrl-I enables inverse video by
setting [[HRCG_MASK]] to [[$7F]], which causes every font byte to be XORed
with [[$7F]] before rendering---flipping all 7~pixel bits.

All shifted variants in this group are no-ops.

<<hrcg mask>>=
    ORG     $9308
HRCG_MASK:
    DC.B    $00                             ; $00=normal, $7F=inverse
@ %def HRCG_MASK

<<hrcg ctrl efhi>>=
    ORG     $94C1
HRCG_CTRL_E:
; --- ctrl-E normal: clear to end of line ---
    BCS     HRCG_CTRL_NOP ; shifted -> NOP
    JSR     HRCG_CLREOL
    JMP     $FC9C         ; ROM CLREOLZ
; --- ctrl-F normal: clear to end of screen ---
HRCG_CTRL_F:
    BCS     HRCG_CTRL_NOP ; shifted -> NOP
    JSR     HRCG_CLRLINE
    JMP     $FC42         ; ROM CLREOP
; --- ctrl-H: backspace ---
HRCG_CTRL_H:
    SUBROUTINE HRCG_CTRL_H
    DEC     $24           ; CH--
    BPL     HRCG_CTRL_NOP ; still >= 0 -> done
    MOVB    $21,$24 ; WNDWDTH
    DEC     $24           ; CH = WNDWDTH - 1
    LDA     $22           ; WNDTOP
    BAGE    $25,HRCG_CTRL_NOP ; CV >= WNDTOP?
    DEC     $25           ; CV--
    JMP     $FC22         ; ROM VTAB
; --- ctrl-I: inverse video ---
HRCG_CTRL_I:
    BCS     HRCG_CTRL_NOP ; shifted -> NOP
    STOB    #$7F,HRCG_MASK ; mask = $7F (invert all 7 pixels)
HRCG_CTRL_NOP:
    RTS                   ; shared NOP return
@ %def HRCG_CTRL_E HRCG_CTRL_F HRCG_CTRL_H HRCG_CTRL_I HRCG_CTRL_NOP
@ Ctrl-K and ctrl-L control the ``lowercase invert'' feature.
[[HRCG_INVERT_FLAG]] has three states: [[$00]] (normal), [[$80]] (invert
lowercase letters), and [[$C0]] (XOR-invert, toggled by ctrl-S).  When set to
[[$80]], uppercase letters A--Z are rendered using the font data for their
lowercase counterparts without subtracting [[$20]]---effectively swapping
case in the display.  Ctrl-K clears the flag; ctrl-L sets it to [[$80]].

Ctrl-M is carriage return.  Before moving the cursor, it checks the keyboard
for ctrl-S (the pause key, [[$93]]).  If a pause is detected, the routine
waits for another keypress before continuing.  Ctrl-C ([[$83]]) cancels the
pause.  After the pause check, the handler sets the cursor column to zero
and falls through to the line feed logic.

<<hrcg invert flag>>=
    ORG     $930C
HRCG_INVERT_FLAG:
    DC.B    $00                             ; $00=normal, $80=lowercase, $C0=XOR-invert
@ %def HRCG_INVERT_FLAG

<<hrcg ctrl klm>>=
    ORG     $94EE
HRCG_CTRL_K:
; --- ctrl-K: clear invert flag ---
    BCS     HRCG_CTRL_NOP    ; shifted -> NOP
    STOB    #$00,HRCG_INVERT_FLAG ; clear invert flag
    RTS
; --- ctrl-L: set invert flag ---
HRCG_CTRL_L:
    BCS     HRCG_CTRL_NOP    ; shifted -> NOP
    STOB    #$80,HRCG_INVERT_FLAG ; invert flag = $80
    RTS
; --- ctrl-M: carriage return (with pause check) ---
HRCG_CTRL_M:
    SUBROUTINE HRCG_CTRL_M
    LDY     $C000            ; check keyboard
    BPL     .no_pause        ; no key -> skip pause
    BYNE    #$93,.no_pause   ; ctrl-S (pause)?
    BIT     $C010            ; clear strobe
.wait_key:
    LDY     $C000            ; wait for key
    BPL     .wait_key
    BYEQ    #$83,.no_pause   ; ctrl-C (cancel)?
    BIT     $C010            ; clear strobe
.no_pause:
    JMP     HRCG_CR_ENTRY    ; -> set CH=0, line feed
@ %def HRCG_CTRL_K HRCG_CTRL_L HRCG_CTRL_M
@ Ctrl-N returns to normal video by clearing the inverse mask.  Ctrl-O in
normal mode sets [[HRCG_MODE_FLAGS]] to [[$40]], which causes the \emph{next}
control character to enter its shifted variant (the ``next-shifted'' flag);
in shifted mode, it sets OR draw mode.  Ctrl-P homes the cursor and clears
the screen; its shifted variant clears the draw mode and page mask.

Ctrl-Q moves the cursor to the saved position (from ctrl-B) without
restoring any other state---a ``goto'' for the cursor.

<<hrcg ctrl nopq>>=
    ORG     $9519
HRCG_CTRL_N:
; --- ctrl-N: normal video ---
    BCS     HRCG_CTRL_NOP   ; shifted -> NOP
    STOB    #$00,HRCG_MASK ; clear mask (normal video)
    RTS
; --- ctrl-O: set next-shifted / OR mode ---
HRCG_CTRL_O:
    SUBROUTINE HRCG_CTRL_O
    BCS     .set_or_draw    ; shifted -> OR draw mode
    STOB    #$40,HRCG_MODE_FLAGS ; next ctrl -> shifted variant
    RTS
.set_or_draw:
    STOB    #$80,HRCG_DRAW_MODE ; draw mode = OR ($80)
    STOB    #$00,HRCG_PAGE_MASK ; page mask = 0
    RTS
; --- ctrl-P: home cursor ---
HRCG_CTRL_P:
    SUBROUTINE HRCG_CTRL_P
    BCS     .clear_draw     ; shifted -> clear draw mode
    JSR     HRCG_HOME
    JMP     $FC58           ; ROM HOME (clear text screen)
.clear_draw:
    STOB    #$00,HRCG_DRAW_MODE ; draw mode = 0
    STA     HRCG_PAGE_MASK  ; page mask = 0
    RTS
; --- ctrl-Q: goto saved cursor ---
HRCG_CTRL_Q:
    BCS     HRCG_CTRL_NOP   ; shifted -> NOP
    MOVB    HRCG_SAVED_CH,$24 ; saved CH
    MOVB    HRCG_SAVED_CV,$25 ; saved CV
    JMP     $FC24           ; ROM VTAB
@ %def HRCG_CTRL_N HRCG_CTRL_O HRCG_CTRL_P HRCG_CTRL_Q
@ Ctrl-R, ctrl-S, and ctrl-T configure the advanced draw modes.  These modes
control how new character pixels combine with existing screen content:

\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Replace} (the default): new pixels overwrite the screen.
\item \textbf{OR}: new pixels are ORed with existing screen content, allowing
      characters to overlay graphics without erasing the background.
\item \textbf{AND}: new pixels are ANDed with the screen, masking out areas.
\item \textbf{XOR}: new pixels are XORed with the screen, useful for
      flashing cursors or toggling sprites.
\end{itemize}

Ctrl-R (shifted only) sets XOR draw mode with page-2 overlay.  Ctrl-S sets
the XOR-invert flag (for character-level inversion); its shifted variant
clears the wrap flag, switching to scroll mode.  Ctrl-T (shifted only) sets
AND draw mode with page-2 overlay.  The normal variants of ctrl-R and ctrl-T
are no-ops.

<<hrcg wrap flag>>=
    ORG     $930B
HRCG_WRAP_FLAG:
    DC.B    $00                             ; $00=scroll, $FF=wrap
@ %def HRCG_WRAP_FLAG

<<hrcg ctrl rst>>=
    ORG     $9554
HRCG_CTRL_R:
; --- ctrl-R shifted: XOR draw + page2 ---
    BCC     HRCG_RTS         ; normal -> RTS (no-op)
    STOB    #$C0,HRCG_DRAW_MODE ; draw mode = XOR ($C0)
    STOB    #$60,HRCG_PAGE_MASK ; page mask = $60 (page 2)
    RTS
; --- ctrl-S: XOR invert / clear wrap ---
HRCG_CTRL_S:
    SUBROUTINE HRCG_CTRL_S
    BCS     .clear_wrap      ; shifted -> clear wrap
    STOB    #$C0,HRCG_INVERT_FLAG ; invert = XOR ($C0)
    RTS
.clear_wrap:
    STOB    #$00,HRCG_WRAP_FLAG ; wrap = 0 (scroll mode)
    RTS
; --- ctrl-T shifted: AND draw mode ---
HRCG_CTRL_T:
    BCC     HRCG_RTS         ; normal -> RTS (no-op)
    STOB    #$80,HRCG_DRAW_MODE ; draw mode = AND ($80)
    STOB    #$60,HRCG_PAGE_MASK ; page mask = $60
    RTS
@ %def HRCG_CTRL_R HRCG_CTRL_S HRCG_CTRL_T
@ Ctrl-V and ctrl-W together define the text window---a rectangular region
of the screen where text output is confined.  Ctrl-V sets the left edge and
top row: the current cursor column (relative to [[WNDLFT]]) becomes the new
left margin, and the current row becomes the new top.  Ctrl-W sets the right
edge and bottom row, and its shifted variant enables wrap mode (where the
cursor wraps to the top of the window instead of scrolling).

Ali Baba uses these extensively to confine status messages and input prompts
to the bottom portion of the screen, while the map occupies the upper area.

<<hrcg ctrl vw>>=
    ORG     $957C
HRCG_CTRL_V:
    SUBROUTINE HRCG_CTRL_V
; --- ctrl-V: set text window ---
    BCS     HRCG_RTS            ; shifted -> RTS
    LDA     $24                 ; CH
    ADC     $20                 ; + WNDLFT
    BALT    #$28,.store_lft ; >= 40?
    LDA     #$27                ; clamp to 39
.store_lft:
    STA     $20                 ; WNDLFT = CH + old WNDLFT
    SEC
    LDA     $21                 ; WNDWDTH
    SBC     $24                 ; - CH
    STA     $21                 ; new WNDWDTH
    STOB    #$00,$24 ; CH = 0
    LDA     $25                 ; CV
    BALT    #$18,.store_top ; >= 24?
    LDA     #$17                ; clamp to 23
.store_top:
    STA     $22                 ; WNDTOP = CV
    BIT     HRCG_SAVED_PARAMS+8 ; params saved?
    BMI     .do_vtab            ; yes -> skip saving CV
    STA     HRCG_SAVED_CV       ; saved CV = WNDTOP
.do_vtab:
    JMP     $FC22               ; ROM VTAB
; --- ctrl-W: set right margin + bottom ---
HRCG_CTRL_W:
    SUBROUTINE HRCG_CTRL_W
    BCS     .set_wrap           ; shifted -> set wrap
    MOVB    $24,$21 ; CH
    ADC     $20                 ; + WNDLFT
    BALT    #$28,.width_ok ; >= 40?
    LDA     #$27                ; clamp to 39
    SBC     $20                 ; - WNDLFT
    STA     $21                 ; WNDWDTH = 39 - WNDLFT
.width_ok:
    INC     $21                 ; WNDWDTH + 1
    LDA     $25                 ; CV
    BALT    #$18,.bottom_ok ; >= 24?
    LDA     #$17                ; clamp to 23
.bottom_ok:
    STA     $23                 ; WNDBTM = CV
    INC     $23                 ; WNDBTM + 1
HRCG_RTS:
    RTS                         ; shared RTS
; --- ctrl-W shifted: set wrap mode ---
.set_wrap:
    STOB    #$FF,HRCG_WRAP_FLAG ; wrap flag = $FF (wrap mode)
    RTS
@ %def HRCG_CTRL_V HRCG_CTRL_W HRCG_RTS
@ Ctrl-Y clears the entire screen by resetting the text window to full size
(40 columns by 24 rows) and filling it.  Its shifted variant jumps to
[[HRCG_ENTRY2]], one of the secondary entry points in the jump table---which
the game patches to a simple [[RTS]].

Ctrl-Z is the full reset:
\begin{enumerate}
  \item Clears the entire parameter block (19~bytes).
  \item Resets the text window.
  \item Selects the standard font.
  \item Sets replace video mode.
  \item Patches both secondary entry points to [[RTS]].
\end{enumerate}
This brings the HRCG back to its power-on state.  The shifted variant jumps to [[HRCG_ENTRY3]]
(also patched to [[RTS]]).

<<hrcg ctrl yz>>=
    ORG     $95D1
HRCG_CTRL_Y:
    SUBROUTINE HRCG_CTRL_Y
; --- ctrl-Y normal: clear screen (reset window to full) ---
    BCS     .jump_entry2        ; shifted -> JMP HRCG_ENTRY2
HRCG_RESET_WINDOW:
; --- shared: reset window to full screen ---
    LDA     $20                 ; WNDLFT
    ADC     $24                 ; + CH
    STA     $24                 ; CH = absolute column
    STOB    #$00,$20 ; WNDLFT = 0
    STA     $22                 ; WNDTOP = 0
    BIT     HRCG_SAVED_PARAMS+8 ; params saved?
    BMI     .set_dims           ; yes -> skip
    STA     HRCG_SAVED_CH       ; saved CH = 0
    STA     HRCG_SAVED_CV       ; saved CV = 0
.set_dims:
    STOB    #$28,$21 ; 40
    STOB    #$18,$23 ; 24
    JMP     $FC22               ; ROM VTAB
.jump_entry2:
    JMP     HRCG_ENTRY2         ; -> secondary entry (disabled)
; --- ctrl-Z: full reset ---
HRCG_CTRL_Z:
    SUBROUTINE HRCG_CTRL_Z
    BCS     .jump_entry3        ; shifted -> JMP HRCG_ENTRY3
HRCG_RESET:
    LDA     #$00
    LDY     #$12                ; 19 bytes (indices 0-18)
.clear_loop:
    STA     HRCG_VIDEO_MODE,Y   ; clear param block
    DEY
    BPL     .clear_loop
    JSR     HRCG_RESET_WINDOW   ; reset window
    JSR     HRCG_SET_STD_FONT   ; set standard font ($97A5)
    JSR     HRCG_SET_REPLACE    ; set replace video mode ($20)
    STOB    #<HRCG_RTS,HRCG_ENTRY2+1 ; patch entry2 low
    STA     HRCG_ENTRY3+1       ; patch entry3 low
    STOB    #>HRCG_RTS,HRCG_ENTRY2+2 ; patch entry2 high
    STA     HRCG_ENTRY3+2       ; patch entry3 high
    RTS
.jump_entry3:
    JMP     HRCG_ENTRY3         ; -> secondary entry (disabled)
@ %def HRCG_CTRL_Y HRCG_RESET_WINDOW HRCG_CTRL_Z HRCG_RESET
@ \subsubsection{Character rendering}

[[HRCG_DRAW_CHAR]] is the heart of the HRCG: the routine that actually puts
pixels on the hi-res screen.  For each printable character, it computes a
pointer into the active font data, calculates the hi-res screen address for
the current cursor position, and renders 8~scan lines of font data.

The font address calculation multiplies the character index (character code
minus [[$20]]) by~8 and adds the font pointer.  The multiplication is done
by three successive [[ASL]]/[[ROL]] pairs, shifting the index left 3~bits
while propagating the carry into [[$EF]] for the high byte.

The lowercase-invert feature adds a twist: when [[HRCG_INVERT_FLAG]] is set
to [[$80]], letters A--Z skip the subtraction of [[$20]], so they index into
the lowercase range of the font instead.  The [[$C0]] (XOR-invert) state
toggles only once and then reverts to [[$80]].

Once the font address is in [[$EE/$EF]] and the screen address is in
[[$2A/$2B]], the render loop processes 8~bytes.  Each font byte is XORed
with [[HRCG_MASK]] (for inverse video), then combined with the screen
according to the draw mode: replace writes directly, OR combines with the
existing screen content, AND masks it, and XOR toggles it.  The screen
address advances by [[$0400]] per scan line---the standard Apple II
hi-res interleaving within a character cell.

<<hrcg draw char>>=
    ORG     $9621
HRCG_DRAW_CHAR:
    SUBROUTINE HRCG_DRAW_CHAR
; --- Main character rendering ---
    ASL     HRCG_MODE_FLAGS     ; shift mode flags
    BCS     HRCG_RTS            ; shifted -> RTS (ignore shifted printable)
    BIT     HRCG_INVERT_FLAG    ; check invert flag
    BPL     .normal_char        ; not set -> normal
    BVC     .check_lower        ; bit 6 clear -> check lowercase
    ASL     HRCG_INVERT_FLAG    ; shift invert flag ($C0 -> $80)
    BCS     .normal_char        ; was $C0, now $80 -> treat as normal
.check_lower:
    BALT    #$41,.normal_char ; 'A' ?
    BALT    #$5B,.calc_offset ; '[' ?
.normal_char:
    SEC
    SBC     #$20                ; convert to font index (char - $20)
.calc_offset:
    ASL                         ; \ index * 8 = byte offset in font
    ROL     $EF                 ;  |
    ASL                         ;  |
    ROL     $EF                 ;  |
    ASL                         ;  |
    ROL     $EF                 ; /
    CLC
    ADC     HRCG_FONT_PTR_LO    ; + font pointer low
    STA     $EE                 ; font address low
    LDA     $EF
    AND     #$07                ; mask to 3 bits
    ADC     HRCG_FONT_PTR_HI    ; + font pointer high
    STA     $EF                 ; font address high
    JSR     HRCG_CALC_HIRES_ADDR
    ADC     $24                 ; + cursor X
    STA     $2A                 ; screen address low
    STA     $EC                 ; save copy
    LDA     $2B                 ; screen address high
    EOR     HRCG_PAGE_MASK      ; XOR with page mask (0 or $60)
    STA     $ED                 ; alt-page address high
    LDY     $24                 ; cursor X
    LDA     $FF                 ; original character
    STA     ($28),Y             ; store char in text page
    LDX     #$00
    LDY     #$00
; --- Render loop: 8 scan lines ---
.render_loop:
    LDA     ($EE),Y             ; load font byte
    EOR     HRCG_MASK           ; apply mask (inverse)
    BIT     HRCG_DRAW_MODE      ; check draw mode
    BPL     .store              ; $00 -> replace mode
    BVS     .xor_mode           ; $C0 -> XOR mode
    BIT     HRCG_MASK           ; check mask for AND vs OR
    BVS     .and_mode           ; mask $7F + draw $80 -> AND
    ORA     ($EC,X)             ; OR mode: combine with screen
    BVC     .store              ; always -> store
.and_mode:
    AND     ($EC,X)             ; AND mode: mask with screen
    BVS     .store              ; always -> store
.xor_mode:
    EOR     ($EC,X)             ; XOR mode: toggle screen bits
.store:
    STA     ($2A,X)             ; write to screen
    INY                         ; next font byte
    CPY     #$08                ; done 8 bytes?
    BCS     HRCG_ADVANCE_CURSOR ; yes -> advance cursor
    LDA     $2B                 ; screen high byte
    ADC     #$04                ; next scan line group (+$0400)
    STA     $2B
    EOR     HRCG_PAGE_MASK      ; update alt-page address
    STA     $ED
    BCC     .render_loop        ; loop (always, carry clear)
@ %def HRCG_DRAW_CHAR
@ After rendering a character, [[HRCG_ADVANCE_CURSOR]] moves the cursor one
column to the right.  If the cursor reaches the right edge of the text
window ([[WNDWDTH]]), it wraps to column~0 and performs a line feed.

The line feed logic increments [[CV]] (cursor row).  If the cursor passes
the bottom of the text window ([[WNDBTM]]), the behavior depends on the
wrap flag: in scroll mode, the window scrolls up one line (via
[[HRCG_SCROLL_UP]]) and the cursor stays at the bottom row; in wrap mode,
the cursor jumps back to the top of the window.

This chunk also contains [[HRCG_CR_ENTRY]], which the carriage return handler
(ctrl-M) uses to set the column to zero and fall through into the line feed.

<<hrcg advance cursor>>=
    ORG     $969E
HRCG_ADVANCE_CURSOR:
    SUBROUTINE HRCG_ADVANCE_CURSOR
; --- Advance cursor after character ---
    INC     $24            ; CH++
    LDA     $24
    BALT    $21,.done ; >= WNDWDTH?
HRCG_CR_ENTRY:
    STOB    #$00,$24 ; (CR entry point: set CH=0)
; --- HRCG_LINE_FEED ---
HRCG_LINE_FEED:
    INC     $25            ; CV++
    LDA     $25
    BALT    $23,.update_cursor ; >= WNDBTM?
    BIT     HRCG_WRAP_FLAG ; check wrap flag
    BVS     .wrap          ; wrap mode -> wrap to top
    DEC     $25            ; CV-- (stay at bottom)
    JSR     HRCG_SCROLL_UP
    JMP     $FC70          ; ROM SCROLL
.wrap:
    MOVB    $22,$25 ; WNDTOP
.update_cursor:
    JSR     $FC24          ; ROM VTAB
.done:
    RTS
@ %def HRCG_ADVANCE_CURSOR HRCG_CR_ENTRY HRCG_LINE_FEED
@ [[HRCG_SCROLL_UP]] shifts the entire text window up by one character row.
Since each text row occupies 8~hi-res scan lines, the routine must copy
8~rows of pixel data for every text row in the window.  It walks from the
top of the window downward, using [[HRCG_CALC_HIRES_ROW]] to compute the
hi-res address for both the source (row below) and destination (current row),
then copies all columns across all 8~scan lines.

After all rows have been shifted up, the bottom row is cleared using
[[HRCG_FILL_LINE]] with the draw mode temporarily forced to replace.  This
ensures the last row is erased cleanly regardless of the current video mode.

<<hrcg scroll up>>=
    ORG     $96C7
HRCG_SCROLL_UP:
    SUBROUTINE HRCG_SCROLL_UP
    LDA     $22                 ; WNDTOP (top row)
    PHA                         ; save for later
.next_row:
    JSR     HRCG_CALC_HIRES_ROW ; calc hi-res addr for row A
.copy_row:
    MOVB    $2A,$EC ; dest address low
    LDA     $2B                 ; dest address high
    AND     #$E3                ; mask off scan line bits
    STA     $ED
    PLA                         ; restore source row
    CLC
    ADC     #$01                ; source = dest + 1
    BAGE    $23,.clear_last ; >= WNDBTM?
    PHA
    JSR     HRCG_CALC_HIRES_ROW ; calc hi-res addr for source row
    LDX     #$07                ; 8 scan lines
.copy_scanline:
    LDY     $21                 ; WNDWDTH
    DEY                         ; index = WNDWDTH - 1
.copy_byte:
    LDA     ($2A),Y             ; read source
    STA     ($EC),Y             ; write dest
    DEY
    BPL     .copy_byte          ; next column
    DEX
    BMI     .copy_row           ; all 8 lines done -> next row
    CLC
    LDA     $2B                 ; advance source
    ADC     #$04
    STA     $2B
    LDA     $ED                 ; advance dest
    ADC     #$04
    STA     $ED
    BNE     .copy_scanline      ; always -> continue
.clear_last:
    LDA     HRCG_DRAW_MODE      ; save draw mode
    PHA
    LDA     $23                 ; WNDBTM
    SBC     #$01                ; last row index
    LDY     #$00
    STY     HRCG_DRAW_MODE      ; draw mode = 0 (replace)
    JSR     HRCG_FILL_LINE      ; clear last row
    PULB    HRCG_DRAW_MODE ; restore draw mode
    RTS
@ %def HRCG_SCROLL_UP
@ This chunk contains the screen-clearing family of routines, all built on
top of [[HRCG_FILL_LINE]].  [[HRCG_HOME]] sets the cursor to the top-left
corner of the text window and clears the entire window.
[[HRCG_CLRLINE]] clears from the current row to the bottom of the window.
[[HRCG_CLREOL]] clears from the cursor position to the end of the current
line.

[[HRCG_FILL_LINE]] is the shared workhorse: it fills a single text row
(8~scan lines) starting at a given column.  The fill value is
[[HRCG_MASK]]---normally [[$00]] (black), but [[$7F]] when inverse video is
active, producing a white bar.  In OR or XOR draw modes, the fill
operation reads the existing screen content and combines it with the mask,
allowing selective clearing without disturbing the other hi-res page.

<<hrcg home clr>>=
    ORG     $9716
HRCG_HOME:
    SUBROUTINE HRCG_HOME
; --- Set cursor to top-left and clear screen ---
    MOVB    $22,$25 ; WNDTOP
    LDY     #$00
    STY     $24                 ; CH = 0
    BEQ     .clear_entry        ; always -> fall into clear loop
; --- HRCG_CLRLINE: clear from current row to bottom ---
HRCG_CLRLINE:
    LDY     $24                 ; preserve CH for fill start column
    LDA     $25                 ; CV = starting row
.clear_entry:
    PHA                         ; save row
    JSR     HRCG_FILL_LINE      ; clear this row
    PLA
    CLC
    ADC     #$01                ; next row
    CMP     $23                 ; >= WNDBTM?
    LDY     #$00                ; fill from column 0 for next rows
    BCC     .clear_entry        ; continue loop
    RTS
; --- HRCG_CLREOL: clear from cursor to end of line ---
HRCG_CLREOL:
    LDY     $24                 ; start column = CH
    LDA     $25                 ; current row = CV
; --- HRCG_FILL_LINE: fill one row ---
HRCG_FILL_LINE:
    STY     $EE                 ; save start column
    JSR     HRCG_CALC_HIRES_ROW ; calc hi-res addr for row A
    LDX     #$07                ; 8 scan lines
.fill_byte:
    LDA     HRCG_MASK           ; fill byte (mask value)
    BIT     HRCG_DRAW_MODE      ; check draw mode
    BPL     .write              ; replace mode -> write directly
    MOVB    $2A,$EC ; compute alt-page address
    LDA     $2B
    EOR     HRCG_PAGE_MASK
    STA     $ED
    LDA     ($EC),Y             ; read existing screen byte
    BIT     HRCG_DRAW_MODE      ; check draw mode again
    BVC     .write              ; OR mode -> skip XOR
    EOR     HRCG_MASK           ; XOR with mask
.write:
    STA     ($2A),Y             ; write to screen
    INY                         ; next column
    CPY     $21                 ; >= WNDWDTH?
    BCC     .fill_byte          ; no -> continue
    DEX                         ; next scan line
    BMI     .fill_done          ; all 8 done -> return
    LDY     $EE                 ; reset column to start
    LDA     $2B                 ; advance to next scan line
    CLC
    ADC     #$04
    STA     $2B
    BNE     .fill_byte          ; always -> continue
.fill_done:
    RTS
@ %def HRCG_HOME HRCG_CLRLINE HRCG_CLREOL HRCG_FILL_LINE
@ Every character rendering and screen clearing operation needs to convert a
text row number into a hi-res screen address.  [[HRCG_CALC_HIRES_ADDR]]
performs this conversion.  The Apple II hi-res screen has a notoriously
non-linear address layout---consecutive text rows do not map to consecutive
memory addresses.  The HRCG solves this with a 12-entry lookup table
([[HRCG_ROW_TABLE]]) indexed by row/2, combined with bit manipulation to
encode the row's position within the hi-res page.

The computation works as follows: the row is divided by~2 (the carry from the
[[LSR]] is preserved for later), the quotient mod~4 selects which [[$0400]]
group the row falls in, and the table provides the base offset ([[$00]],
[[$50]], or [[$A0]]).  The saved carry bit (odd vs.\ even row) is rotated
back in via [[ROR]] to set bit~7 of the low byte, and [[WNDLFT]] is added
to account for the left margin.

The 20~trailing bytes after the table are of unknown purpose---they may be
residual data from the HRCG development environment or unused padding.

<<hrcg calc addr>>=
    ORG     $9771
HRCG_CALC_HIRES_ADDR:
; --- Compute hi-res screen address from CV ---
; Input: ZP $25 (CV)   Output: $2A/$2B
    LDA     $25              ; CV (cursor Y)
HRCG_CALC_HIRES_ROW:
; --- Alternate entry: row in A ---
    LSR                      ; A = row / 2
    TAX                      ; X = row / 2 (table index)
    AND     #$03             ; A = (row/2) % 4
    ORA     HRCG_VIDEO_MODE  ; combine with page base ($20/$40)
    STA     $2B              ; screen high byte
    LDA     HRCG_ROW_TABLE,X ; row base from table
    ROR                      ; rotate carry from LSR into bit 7
    ADC     $20              ; + WNDLFT
    STA     $2A              ; screen low byte
    RTS
; --- Row address table (12 entries) ---
HRCG_ROW_TABLE:
    HEX     00 00 00 00 50 50 50 50 A0 A0 A0 A0
; --- Trailing data (20 bytes, purpose unknown) ---
HRCG_TRAILING_DATA:
    HEX     B9 A2 A0 D2 E9 A0 F2 A0 A5 B9 C1 80 C4 CD A0 8C
    HEX     A0 AC A0 A0
@ %def HRCG_CALC_HIRES_ADDR HRCG_CALC_HIRES_ROW HRCG_ROW_TABLE HRCG_TRAILING_DATA

\chapter{Text and Display Primitives}

The [[PRINT_STRING]] routine prints a Pascal-style string (length first),
from an address stored in [[PRINT_STRING_ADDR]], at the current cursor
position.

@ [[PRINT_STRING_AT_ADDR]] stores the X and Y registers into
[[PRINT_STRING_ADDR]] as a 16-bit string pointer, then falls through to
[[PRINT_STRING]].  This provides a convenient entry point for callers that
pass the string address in registers rather than pre-loading the zero-page
pointer.

<<print string>>=
    ORG     $7758
PRINT_STRING_AT_ADDR:
    SUBROUTINE PRINT_STRING_AT_ADDR

    STX     PRINT_STRING_ADDR
    STY     PRINT_STRING_ADDR+1

    ; falls through to PRINT_STRING at $775C
@ %def PRINT_STRING_AT_ADDR
[[PRINT_STRING]] prints a length-prefixed string from
[[\PRINT_STRING_ADDR/\PRINT_STRING_ADDR+1]] via COUT.
[[PRINT_STRING_AT_ADDR]] at [[$7758]] stores [[X/Y]] into
[[\PRINT_STRING_ADDR/\PRINT_STRING_ADDR+1]] first, then falls through.

<<print string>>=
    ORG     $775C
PRINT_STRING:
    SUBROUTINE PRINT_STRING

    LDY     #$00
    LDA     (PRINT_STRING_ADDR),Y ; first byte = length
    TAX
.loop:
    DEX
    BPL     .next
    RTS                           ; done

.next:
    INY
    LDA     (PRINT_STRING_ADDR),Y ; read next char
    JSR     ROM_COUT1
    JMP     .loop
@ %def PRINT_STRING
Sends Ctrl-A and [['0']] to COUT (selects character set~0 in the HRCG):

<<print ctrl ab>>=
    ORG     $774E
PRINT_CTRL_AB:
    SUBROUTINE PRINT_CTRL_AB

    LDA     #$81 ; Ctrl-A with high bit
    JSR     ROM_COUT1
    LDA     #$B0 ; '0' with high bit
    JMP     ROM_COUT1
@ %def PRINT_CTRL_AB
Outputs Ctrl-N (normal video mode) to the Apple~II character output
routine via [[COUT1]].  [[$8E]] is [[Ctrl-N]] with the high bit set.
This is distinct from [[SET_NORMAL_VIDEO]] at [[$75F9]] which uses
[[COUT]] instead.

<<print ctrl n>>=
    ORG     $7735
PRINT_CTRL_N:
    SUBROUTINE PRINT_CTRL_N

    LDA     #$8E      ; Ctrl-N with high bit
    JMP     ROM_COUT1 ; output via COUT1
@ %def PRINT_CTRL_N
Ali Baba provides several convenience routines which translate to HRCG control codes.

<<control routines>>=
    ORG     $7730
SET_INVERSE_VIDEO:
    SUBROUTINE SET_INVERSE_VIDEO

    LDA     #$89        ; ctrl-I
    JMP     ROM_COUT1
@ %def SET_INVERSE_VIDEO
@ Two more convenience wrappers set the text window behavior.
[[SET_TEXT_WINDOW_WRAP]] sends ctrl-O (next-shifted) followed by ctrl-W
(shifted: enable wrap mode), so that text reaching the bottom of the window
wraps to the top instead of scrolling.  [[SET_TEXT_WINDOW_SCROLL]] sends
ctrl-O followed by ctrl-S (shifted: clear wrap flag), restoring normal scroll
behavior.  These are used when switching between the status area (which
scrolls) and the map area (which wraps or is managed manually).

<<text window routines>>=
    ORG     $773A
SET_TEXT_WINDOW_WRAP:
    SUBROUTINE SET_TEXT_WINDOW_WRAP

    LDA     #$8F ; ctrl-O
    JSR     ROM_COUT1
    LDA     #$97 ; ctrl-W
    JMP     ROM_COUT1

SET_TEXT_WINDOW_SCROLL:
    SUBROUTINE SET_TEXT_WINDOW_SCROLL

    LDA     #$8F ; ctrl-O
    JSR     ROM_COUT1
    LDA     #$93 ; ctrl-S
    JMP     ROM_COUT1

; PRINT_CTRL_AB (PRINT_CTRL_AB) follows at $774E, defined in its own chunk

@ %def SET_TEXT_WINDOW_WRAP SET_TEXT_WINDOW_SCROLL
@ The game screen is divided into an upper map area and a lower status/input
area.  These routines set the text window's top-left corner via the HRCG's
ctrl-V command.  [[SET_TEXT_WINDOW_UPPER_LEFT_ALL]] sets the window to start
at row~0, giving access to the full screen.
[[SET_TEXT_WINDOW_UPPER_LEFT_LOW]] sets it to row~21, confining output to the
bottom three rows used for status messages and player input.

<<set text window upper left>>=
    ORG     $792D
SET_TEXT_WINDOW_UPPER_LEFT_ALL:
    SUBROUTINE SET_TEXT_WINDOW_UPPER_LEFT_ALL

    LDA     #0
    JMP     SET_TEXT_WINDOW_UPPER_LEFT

SET_TEXT_WINDOW_UPPER_LEFT_LOW:
    LDA     #21

    ; fall through

SET_TEXT_WINDOW_UPPER_LEFT:

    STA     TEXT_ROW
    STOB    #0,TEXT_COL
    LDA     #$96        ; ctrl-V (set text window upper left)
    JMP     ROM_COUT1
@
\label{sec:set_text_window}

These two routines share the same code; they differ only in the
window-bottom value loaded in~A.  The BNE at [[$76C0]] forms a
``stretchy branch'' that skips the [[LDA \#$14]], so both entry points
share all code from [[$76C4]] onward.

<<set text window bottom>>=
    ORG     $76BE
SET_CURSOR_ROW21:
    SUBROUTINE SET_CURSOR_ROW21

    LDA     #$15     ; WNDBTM = 21
    BNE     .shared  ; always taken (stretchy branch)

SET_TEXT_WINDOW_BOTTOM:
    LDA     #$14     ; WNDBTM = 20

.shared:
    STA     TEXT_ROW
    STOB    #$00,TEXT_COL ; WNDLFT = 0
    JSR     PRINT_CTRL_AB
    LDA     #$86     ; Ctrl-F with high bit
    JMP     ROM_COUT1
@ %def SET_CURSOR_ROW21 SET_TEXT_WINDOW_BOTTOM
Since text on the lower part always starts at row 21, and the column number only
needs 6 bits, we can specify a compressed 8-bit version of the cursor, where the
row number can be specified by upper two bits (so 20 through 23).

\textbf{Dead code:} No callers found in the binary (Ghidra confirms zero xrefs).
Possibly an unused utility left over from development.

<<set cursor compressed>>=
    ORG     $776E
SET_CURSOR_COMPRESSED:
    SUBROUTINE SET_CURSOR_COMPRESSED
; DEAD CODE — no callers found (for future investigation)

    PHA
    AND     #$3F
    STA     TEXT_COL
    PLA
    LSR
    LSR
    LSR
    LSR
    LSR
    LSR
    CLC
    ADC     #20
    STA     TEXT_ROW
    RTS
@
The [[PRINT_BOTTOM_CENTERED]] centers text on row 23, which is the bottom of
the screen.

<<print bottom centered>>=
    ORG     $7705
PRINT_BOTTOM_CENTERED:
    SUBROUTINE PRINT_BOTTOM_CENTERED

    STOB    #$17,TEXT_ROW
    STOB    #$00,TEXT_COL
    JMP     PRINT_CENTERED_PLUS_COL
@ %def PRINT_BOTTOM_CENTERED
The [[PRINT_CENTERED_PLUS_COL]] centers text, but moves it right by the
current cursor's column. If the column is zero, the routine would center the text on the screen.


<<print centered plus col>>=
    ORG     $7710
PRINT_CENTERED_PLUS_COL:
    SUBROUTINE PRINT_CENTERED_PLUS_COL

    LDA     #40
    SEC
    LDY     #$00
    SBC     (PRINT_STRING_ADDR),Y
    CLC
    LSR                             ; accumulator
    ADC     TEXT_COL
    STA     TEXT_COL
    JSR     PRINT_CTRL_AB
    JMP     PRINT_STRING
@ %def PRINT_CENTERED_PLUS_COL
Converts a 16-bit unsigned value in~[[NUM_VALUE]] to up to 5~ASCII
decimal digits, stored sequentially at [[$(DECIMAL_OUT_PTR),Y$]] (with Y incrementing).
Leading zeros are suppressed unless the value is exactly zero (prints
``0'').  The output uses Apple~II high-ASCII ($\$B0$--$\$B9$).

The driver at~\$0DA1 calls the digit-extraction helper at~\$0DE1 five
times with divisors 10000, 1000, 100, 10, and~1.  The helper performs
repeated subtraction of [[$5A1C/$5A1D]] from [[NUM_VALUE]], counting
iterations as the digit value.

A second entry point at~[[$0DA4]] (1~caller) skips the initialization
of~Y and the leading-zero flag, allowing the caller to control the
starting output position and suppression behavior.

@ [[NUM_TO_DECIMAL]] converts a 16-bit value in [[NUM_VALUE]] ([[$BC/$BD]])
to a decimal ASCII string stored at [[DECIMAL_OUT_PTR]] ([[$BA/$BB]]).  It
divides repeatedly by powers of ten (10000, 1000, 100, 10, 1), accumulating
each digit in [[NUM_DIGIT]] and writing it to the output buffer.
[[NUM_LEADING]] suppresses leading zeros: it starts at~0 (suppress) and
flips to~1 after the first nonzero digit.  [[NUM_DIVISOR]] ([[$5A1C/$5A1D]])
holds the current power-of-ten divisor.

<<defines>>=
NUM_LEADING         EQU     $5A1E   ; leading-zero suppress flag (0=suppress, 1=print)
NUM_DIVISOR         EQU     $5A1C   ; 16-bit divisor for decimal conversion (2 bytes)
NUM_DIGIT           EQU     $5A1B   ; current digit accumulator (ASCII $B0-$B9)
@ %def NUM_LEADING NUM_DIVISOR NUM_DIGIT

<<zero page defines>>=
DECIMAL_OUT_PTR         EQU     $BA     ; num-to-decimal output buffer pointer (2 bytes)
NUM_VALUE               EQU     $BC     ; 16-bit numeric value for division (2 bytes)
@ %def DECIMAL_OUT_PTR NUM_VALUE

<<num to decimal>>=
    ORG     $0DA1
NUM_TO_DECIMAL:
    SUBROUTINE NUM_TO_DECIMAL

    LDY     #$00                ; output index = 0
    STY     NUM_LEADING         ; leading-zero flag = 0 (suppress)
NUM_TO_DECIMAL_CONT:
    STOW    $2710,NUM_DIVISOR ; divisor = $2710 = 10000
    JSR     .extract_digit      ; ten-thousands digit
    STOW    $03E8,NUM_DIVISOR ; divisor = $03E8 = 1000
    JSR     .extract_digit      ; thousands digit
    STOW    $0064,NUM_DIVISOR ; divisor = $0064 = 100
    JSR     .extract_digit      ; hundreds digit
    STOB    #$0A,NUM_DIVISOR ; divisor = $000A = 10
    JSR     .extract_digit      ; tens digit
    STOB    #$01,NUM_DIVISOR ; divisor = $0001 = 1
    STA     NUM_LEADING         ; /  force output (no suppress)
    JSR     .extract_digit      ; ones digit
    RTS

; --- Digit extraction helper ($0DE1) ---
; Divides NUM_VALUE/NUM_VALUE+1 by $5A1C/$5A1D via repeated subtraction.
; Stores ASCII digit at (DECIMAL_OUT_PTR),Y. Suppresses leading zeros.
.extract_digit:
    STOB    #$B0,NUM_DIGIT ; digit = '0' (high ASCII)
.cmp_loop:
    LDX     #$01                ; start comparing high byte
.cmp_x:
    LDA     NUM_VALUE,X         ; \
    CMP     NUM_DIVISOR,X       ;  | compare NUM_VALUE/NUM_VALUE+1 with divisor
    BCC     .output             ;  | if less, done (digit found)
    BNE     .subtract           ; /  if greater, subtract
    DEX                         ; \  high bytes equal: check low
    BNE     .subtract           ; /  (if X was 1, now 0 -> recompare)
    JMP     .cmp_x              ;    compare low byte (X=0)
.subtract:
    SUBW    NUM_VALUE,NUM_DIVISOR,NUM_VALUE ;  NUM_VALUE/NUM_VALUE+1 -= divisor
    INC     NUM_DIGIT           ; digit++
    JMP     .cmp_loop           ; try again (reset X=1)
.output:
    LDA     NUM_DIGIT           ; \
    BANE    #$B0,.store         ; and leading-zero suppress active
    LDA     NUM_LEADING         ;  |   skip output
    BANE    #$01,.skip
    LDA     #$B0                ; (reload '0' for final digit)
.store:
    STA     (DECIMAL_OUT_PTR),Y ; store digit at output buffer
    STOB    #$01,NUM_LEADING ; clear leading-zero suppress
.skip:
    INY                         ; advance output index
    RTS
@ %def NUM_TO_DECIMAL NUM_TO_DECIMAL_CONT
