Displays a message from the game's message table.  Takes the message
index in~A.  The message table base address is stored at
[[$4005/$4006]]; each entry is a length-prefixed string.  The routine
walks the table to find the Xth entry, then displays up to three lines
in the status window.

The display behavior depends on the line number:
\begin{itemize}
  \item Line~1 ([[MSG_LINE_COUNT]]~=~0): calls [[PRINT_BOTTOM_CENTERED]], then scrolls.
  \item Line~2 ([[MSG_LINE_COUNT]]~=~1): scrolls first, then prints.
  \item Line~3+: scrolls, prints, then calls [[$0D10]] (delay) and [[$774E]] ([[PRINT_CTRL_AB]]) before looping back.
\end{itemize}

An entry with a zero length byte terminates the message.  If exactly
two lines were printed, a final scroll is performed on exit.

@ [[DISPLAY_MESSAGE]] indexes into the message table at [[MSG_TABLE_PTR]]
([[$4005/$4006]]) to find the string for message number~A.  It walks the
table by skipping length-prefixed entries until the desired index is
reached.  [[MSG_LINE_COUNT]] tracks how many lines have been printed so
far, which controls whether the routine scrolls before or after printing.

<<defines>>=
MSG_TABLE_PTR           EQU     $4005   ; message table base (2 bytes)
MSG_LINE_COUNT          EQU     $5A57   ; lines printed so far
@ %def MSG_TABLE_PTR MSG_LINE_COUNT

@ The routine below implements the message display.

<<display message>>=
    ORG     $761E
DISPLAY_MESSAGE:
    SUBROUTINE DISPLAY_MESSAGE

    TAX                           ; X = message index
    MOVW    MSG_TABLE_PTR,PRINT_STRING_ADDR ; load table base into PRINT_STRING_ADDR/PRINT_STRING_ADDR+1
    STOB    #$00,MSG_LINE_COUNT ; reset line counter

    JMP     .check_index          ; skip to index check

.skip_entry:
    LDY     #$00
    LDA     (PRINT_STRING_ADDR),Y ; get string length
    TAY
    SEC                           ; +1 for length byte itself
    ADC     PRINT_STRING_ADDR     ; advance pointer past this entry
    STA     PRINT_STRING_ADDR
    LDA     PRINT_STRING_ADDR+1
    ADC     #$00
    STA     PRINT_STRING_ADDR+1
    BYNE    #$00,.skip_entry      ; no -- keep skipping within group
.next_index:
    DEX
.check_index:
    BXNE    #$00,.skip_entry      ; more entries to skip

DISPLAY_MESSAGE_LOOP:
.print_loop:
    LDY     #$00
    LDA     (PRINT_STRING_ADDR),Y ; get length of current string
    BNE     .has_text             ; nonzero -- print it

    ; length is zero -- message is done
    LDA     MSG_LINE_COUNT
    BAEQ    #$02,.final_scroll    ; printed exactly 2 lines?
    RTS                           ; otherwise just return
.final_scroll:
    JMP     SCROLL_STATUS_LINE    ; scroll once more and return

.has_text:
    LDA     MSG_LINE_COUNT
    BAMI    #$01,.first_line ; line_count < 1: first line
    BEQ     .second_line          ; line_count == 1: second line

    ; third+ line: scroll, then print
    JSR     SCROLL_STATUS_LINE    ; scroll status window
.second_line:
    JSR     PRINT_BOTTOM_CENTERED ; print centered on row 23
    JMP     .advance

.first_line:
    JSR     PRINT_BOTTOM_CENTERED ; print centered on row 23
    JSR     SCROLL_STATUS_LINE    ; scroll status window

.advance:
    INC     MSG_LINE_COUNT
    LDY     #$00
    LDA     PRINT_STRING_ADDR
    SEC
    ADC     (PRINT_STRING_ADDR),Y ; add length + 1 (SEC sets carry)
    STA     PRINT_STRING_ADDR
    LDA     PRINT_STRING_ADDR+1
    ADC     #$00
    STA     PRINT_STRING_ADDR+1
    LDA     #$01
    BALT    MSG_LINE_COUNT,.pause ; printed <= 1 lines?
    LDY     #$00
    LDA     (PRINT_STRING_ADDR),Y ; peek at next entry
    BNE     .print_loop           ; more text -- keep printing

.pause:
    JSR     DELAY_WITH_ANIMATION  ; delay
    JSR     PRINT_CTRL_AB         ; reset character set
    JMP     .print_loop           ; continue with next line
@ %def DISPLAY_MESSAGE DISPLAY_MESSAGE_LOOP
@ [[SCROLL_STATUS_LINE]] restores the HRCG text window to its default
configuration after a status message.  It sets the window to scroll mode,
positions the cursor at row~23, outputs control character~\$83 (which
triggers a scroll-up in the HRCG handler), and then resets the window
boundaries.  This sequence effectively clears the bottom status area while
preserving the rest of the display.


<<scroll status line>>=
    ORG     $769B
SCROLL_STATUS_LINE:
    SUBROUTINE SCROLL_STATUS_LINE
    ; Text display: init HRCG, set window bottom, output char $83, reset
    JSR     SET_TEXT_WINDOW_SCROLL
    JSR     SET_TEXT_WINDOW_UPPER_LEFT_LOW
    STOB    #$17,TEXT_ROW ; cursor to row 23
    LDA     #$83
    JSR     ROM_COUT1
    JSR     SET_TEXT_WINDOW_UPPER_LEFT_ALL
    JMP     SET_TEXT_WINDOW_WRAP
@ %def SCROLL_STATUS_LINE

\chapter{Sound}

The [[TONE_RANDOMIZE_MASK]] is initially set to 1 to apply a little bit of
randomness to the song notes. However, this can be set to [[00]] via opcode [[NORAND]]
to play exact notes, or set to [[0F]] via opcode [[HIRAND]] to provide high
randomness.

\begin{table}[]
\begin{tabular}{llll}
\multicolumn{1}{c}{Byte} & \multicolumn{1}{c}{Opcode} & \multicolumn{1}{c}{Argument} & \multicolumn{1}{c}{Operation} \\
[[1F]] & [[MARK2]] & none & [[TUNE_LOOP_ADDR <- IP+1]] \\
[[20]] & [[MARK1]] & none & [[TUNE_GOSUB_ADDR <- IP+1]] \\
[[21]] & [[GOTO1]] & none & [[IP <- TUNE_GOSUB_ADDR]] \\
[[22]] & [[LOW]] & none & [[TONE_ROUTINE_ADDR <- tone]] \\
[[23]] & [[HIGH]] & none & [[TONE_ROUTINE_ADDR <- high_tone]] \\
[[24]] & [[END]] & none & Ends the song routine \\
[[25]] & [[HIRAND]] & none & [[TONE_RANDOMIZE_MASK <- 0F]] \\
[[26]] & [[NORAND]] & none & [[TONE_RANDOMIZE_MASK <- 00]] \\
[[27-FF]] & [[NOTE]] & duration & Plays note \\
\end{tabular}
\caption{Song program opcodes}
\label{table:song}
\end{table}

Playing a tone involves accessing the speaker address twice per audio cycle.
The [[tone]] routine delays [[10X+31]] cycles between speaker accesses, and
based on an average Apple II cycle time of [[0.98]] microseconds, this means
that the frequency of the note played will be equal to [[510204 / (10X+31)]] Hz.
See \href{https://6502disassembly.com/a2-rom/}{The Oft Misunderstood WAIT} for a derivation of average cycle time.

@ Note: the [[tone]] and [[high_tone]] routines referenced in the old
song table documentation are identical to [[PLAY_LOW_TONE]] (\$7A91) and
[[PLAY_HIGH_TONE]] (\$7A7F) respectively.  The names came from an earlier
analysis before the tune player was fully understood.

@ [[PLAY_HIGH_TONE]] generates a square wave tone by toggling the Apple~II
speaker at [[$C030]].  The outer loop runs 10~iterations (Y), each toggling
the speaker then delaying by~X cycles.  After all 10~toggles, the whole
sequence repeats [[SOUND_DURATION]] times.  [[SOUND_FREQ]] controls the
pitch (higher value = lower frequency).

<<zero page defines>>=
SOUND_FREQ              EQU     $E1     ; sound frequency / tune modified action
SOUND_DURATION          EQU     $E2     ; sound duration / tune parameter byte
@ %def SOUND_FREQ SOUND_DURATION

<<play tone>>=
    ORG     $7A7F
PLAY_HIGH_TONE:
    SUBROUTINE PLAY_HIGH_TONE

.cycle:
    LDY     #$0A           ; 10 speaker toggles per cycle
.toggle:
    LDA     $C030          ; toggle speaker
.delay:
    DEX
    BNE     .delay         ; inner delay loop (no toggle)
    LDX     SOUND_FREQ     ; reload pitch counter
    DEY
    BNE     .toggle        ; next toggle
    DEC     SOUND_DURATION ; repeat whole cycle
    BNE     .cycle
    RTS
@ %def PLAY_HIGH_TONE

@ [[PLAY_LOW_TONE]] generates a low-octave tone.  It has the same
structure as [[PLAY_HIGH_TONE]] but with extra cycles in the inner loop
(ROL/ROR [[$E3]] plus three NOPs), producing a longer toggle period and
thus a lower frequency for the same X~value.  The formula is
[[510204 / (10X+31)]]~Hz, roughly one octave below [[PLAY_HIGH_TONE]].

The ROL/ROR pair on~[[$E3]] cancels out (no net effect on the shift
register); it exists purely for cycle padding.

<<zero page defines>>=
TONE_PADDING            EQU     $E3     ; byte used for cycle padding in PLAY_LOW_TONE
@ %def TONE_PADDING

<<play low tone>>=
    ORG     $7A91
PLAY_LOW_TONE:
    SUBROUTINE PLAY_LOW_TONE

.cycle:
    LDY     #$0A           ; 10 toggles per cycle
.toggle:
    LDA     $C030          ; toggle speaker
.delay:
    ROL     TONE_PADDING   ; cycle padding (5 cycles)
    DEX
    BNE     .delay         ; inner delay loop (no toggle)
    LDX     SOUND_FREQ     ; reload pitch counter
    ROL     TONE_PADDING   ; \ more cycle padding
    ROR     TONE_PADDING   ; / (ROL+ROR cancels out)
    NOP                    ; \
    NOP                    ;  | timing padding
    NOP                    ; /
    DEY
    BNE     .toggle        ; next toggle
    DEC     SOUND_DURATION ; repeat whole cycle
    BNE     .cycle
    RTS
@ %def PLAY_LOW_TONE
