\chapter{Utility Routines}

\chapter{Utility Routines}


\section{Random number generation}

The pseudo-random number generator computes:
$$\texttt{val}_{n+1} = 69 \cdot \texttt{val}_n + \$53 \pmod{256}$$
and stores both the full result and a shifted copy.

@ [[STEP_PRNG]] maintains three state variables: [[PRNG_STATE]] holds the
full LCG state, [[PRNG_TEMP]] is a scratch byte used during the $69\times$
multiplication, and [[PRNG_OUTPUT]] receives the state shifted right by one
bit---this is the value most callers test for random decisions.

<<defines>>=
PRNG_STATE          EQU     $5A19   ; PRNG full state: val = 69*val + $53 (mod 256)
PRNG_TEMP           EQU     $5A1A   ; PRNG temporary for multiplication
PRNG_OUTPUT         EQU     $5A18   ; PRNG output (state >> 1), used for random tests
@ %def PRNG_STATE PRNG_TEMP PRNG_OUTPUT

<<step prng>>=
    ORG     $78A8
STEP_PRNG:
    SUBROUTINE STEP_PRNG

    LDA     PRNG_STATE  ; val
    ASL                 ; val*2
    ASL                 ; val*4
    STA     PRNG_TEMP   ; temp = val*4
    ASL                 ; val*8
    ASL                 ; val*16
    ASL                 ; val*32
    ASL                 ; val*64
    CLC
    ADC     PRNG_TEMP   ; val*64 + val*4 = val*68
    CLC
    ADC     PRNG_STATE  ; val*68 + val = val*69
    CLC
    ADC     #$53        ; + $53
    STA     PRNG_STATE  ; store full result
    LSR                 ; val >> 1
    STA     PRNG_OUTPUT ; shifted copy (used for random tests)
    RTS
@ %def STEP_PRNG
Two shifts produce [[val*4]], saved to [[PRNG_TEMP]].  Four more shifts give
[[val*64]].  Adding [[val*4]] gives [[val*68]], then adding [[val]] gives
[[val*69]].  Adding [[$53]] completes the LCG step.  This is a linear
congruential generator with multiplier 69, increment \$53, and modulus 256.

Returns a uniform random integer in [[0..A$-$1]] using rejection sampling.
The routine finds the smallest bitmask that covers the range, then repeatedly
calls [[STEP_PRNG]] and masks [[PRNG_OUTPUT]] until the result is less than
or equal to the shifted limit.  This avoids modulo bias.

Input: A~=~range limit (1--127).  If A~=~0, returns~0 immediately.
Output: A~=~random value in [[0..limit$-$1]].

@ [[RANDOM_IN_RANGE]] saves the limit in [[RNG_LIMIT]] and computes a
bitmask in [[RNG_MASK]] that covers the range.  It then loops, calling
[[STEP_PRNG]] and masking [[PRNG_OUTPUT]] with [[RNG_MASK]], rejecting
values that exceed the limit.

<<defines>>=
RNG_LIMIT           EQU     $5A11   ; random_in_range temporary (limit/shift count)
RNG_MASK            EQU     $5A12   ; random_in_range bit mask
@ %def RNG_LIMIT RNG_MASK

@ The implementation below uses bit-mask tables for each power-of-two range
bracket to minimize the number of PRNG calls.

<<random in range>>=
    ORG     $1317
RANDOM_IN_RANGE:
    SUBROUTINE RANDOM_IN_RANGE

    STA     RNG_LIMIT         ; save range limit
    BANE    #$00,.nonzero
    RTS                       ; range=0 -> return 0

.nonzero:
    BAPL    #$02,.ge2
    LDY     #$06              ;  | range 1: mask=$40, shift=6
    LDA     #$40              ;  |
    BNE     .have_mask        ; /
.ge2:
    BAPL    #$04,.ge4
    LDY     #$05              ;  | range 2-3: mask=$60, shift=5
    LDA     #$60              ;  |
    BNE     .have_mask        ; /
.ge4:
    BAPL    #$08,.ge8
    LDY     #$04              ;  | range 4-7: mask=$70, shift=4
    LDA     #$70              ;  |
    BNE     .have_mask        ; /
.ge8:
    BAPL    #$10,.ge16
    LDY     #$03              ;  | range 8-15: mask=$78, shift=3
    LDA     #$78              ;  |
    BNE     .have_mask        ; /
.ge16:
    BAPL    #$20,.ge32
    LDY     #$02              ;  | range 16-31: mask=$7C, shift=2
    LDA     #$7C              ;  |
    BNE     .have_mask        ; /
.ge32:
    BAPL    #$40,.ge64
    LDY     #$01              ;  | range 32-63: mask=$7E, shift=1
    LDA     #$7E              ;  |
    BNE     .have_mask        ; /
.ge64:
    LDY     #$00              ; range 64-127: mask=$7F, shift=0
    LDA     #$7F

.have_mask:
    STA     RNG_MASK          ; save bit mask
    LDA     RNG_LIMIT         ; reload range limit
    STY     RNG_LIMIT         ; save shift count in RNG_LIMIT
.shift_loop:
    DEY                       ; \
    BMI     .shifted          ;  | shift limit left by (shift count)
    CLC                       ;  | positions so it aligns with the
    ROL                       ;  | mask bits
    BNE     .shift_loop       ; /
.shifted:
    LDY     RNG_LIMIT         ; Y = shift count
    STA     RNG_LIMIT         ; save shifted limit

.sample:
    JSR     STEP_PRNG         ; get next random byte
    LDA     PRNG_OUTPUT
    AND     RNG_MASK          ; mask to relevant bits
    BAEQ    RNG_LIMIT,.accept ; equal -> accept
    BPL     .sample           ; greater -> reject, retry

.accept:
    DEY                       ; \
    BPL     .shift_right      ;  | shift result right by (shift count)
    RTS                       ;  | to recover the final value
.shift_right:
    CLC                       ;  |
    ROR                       ;  |
    BCC     .accept           ; / (always taken: masked bit is 0)
@ %def RANDOM_IN_RANGE

\section{Coordinate conversion}

Converts a packed map position (0--199) into separate column and row
values by dividing by~20.  The map is 20~columns wide, so
[[column = pos mod 20]] and [[row = pos / 20]].

The loop repeatedly subtracts~20 (via [[ADC \#$EC]] with carry clear,
since [[$EC = 256 $-$ 20]]), counting iterations in~[[Y]].  When the
subtraction underflows (carry clear on exit), it adds~20 back to recover
the remainder.

<<pos to colrow>>=
    ORG     $0C25
POS_TO_COLROW:
    SUBROUTINE POS_TO_COLROW

    LDY      #$00  ; row = 0
.loop:
    CLC
    ADC      #$EC  ; A -= 20 (unsigned)
    BCC      .done ; underflow -> remainder is negative
    INY            ; row++
    BCS      .loop ; always taken (carry set)
.done:
    ADC      #$14  ; add 20 back -> A = column (remainder)
    RTS            ; A = column (0-19), Y = row (0-9)
@ %def POS_TO_COLROW
The inverse of [[POS_TO_COLROW]]: converts a column in~A and row in~Y
to a linear map position [[A = col + row * 20]].  The carry is cleared
once on entry; thereafter the loop adds~20 per row and exits early if
carry occurs (overflow past 255).


<<colrow to pos>>=
    ORG     $0D98
COLROW_TO_POS:
    SUBROUTINE COLROW_TO_POS

    CLC
.loop:
    DEY           ; row--
    BPL     .add  ; still >= 0 -> add another 20
    RTS           ; Y exhausted, A = result
.add:
    ADC     #$14  ; A += 20
    BCC     .loop ; no overflow -> continue
                                ; carry set -> return (overflow)
@ %def COLROW_TO_POS

@ [[GET_MOB_DATA]] computes a pointer into the game data from a 1-based
index in~A.  Each record is 16~bytes.  The result [[MOB_DATA_PTR]]
([[$BA/$BB]]) = [[$4000/$4001]] base + (index$-$1)$\times$16.

<<zero page defines>>=
MOB_DATA_PTR            EQU     $BA     ; mob data record pointer (2 bytes, $BA/$BB)
@ %def MOB_DATA_PTR

<<get mob data>>=
    ORG     $0C32
GET_MOB_DATA:
    SUBROUTINE GET_MOB_DATA

    CLC
    ADC     #$FF           ; A = index - 1
    ROL2 ;  rotate left 4 times
    ROL2 ;  = multiply by 16 (with carry)
    TAY                    ; save intermediate
    ROL                    ; one more rotate
    AND     #$0F           ; high nybble -> page offset
    CLC
    ADC     $4001          ; add base page
    STA     MOB_DATA_PTR+1 ; high byte
    TYA
    AND     #$F0           ; low nybble -> byte offset
    CLC
    ADC     $4000          ; add base offset
    STA     MOB_DATA_PTR   ; low byte
    BCC     .done
    INC     MOB_DATA_PTR+1 ; carry
.done:
    RTS
@ %def GET_MOB_DATA

\section{Timing and animation}

@ [[DELAY_WITH_ANIMATION]] delays for a configurable duration while keeping
the status window animation running.  It loads an iteration count from
[[DELAY_COUNT]] and calls [[ANIM_TICK_AND_WAIT]] that many times.

<<defines>>=
DELAY_COUNT             EQU     $7ABF   ; number of delay iterations
@ %def DELAY_COUNT

@ The routine below implements the delay loop.

<<delay with animation>>=
    ORG     $0D10
DELAY_WITH_ANIMATION:
    SUBROUTINE DELAY_WITH_ANIMATION

    LDA     DELAY_COUNT        ; load iteration count
.loop:
    PHA                        ; save counter
    JSR     ANIM_TICK_AND_WAIT ; tick animation + timed wait
    PLA                        ; restore counter
    TAY
    DEY                        ; decrement
    TYA
    BNE     .loop              ; loop until zero
    RTS
@ %def DELAY_WITH_ANIMATION

@ [[TICK_ANIM_COUNTER]] decrements [[ANIM_FRAME_CTR]].  When it reaches
zero, it calls [[$74CB]] to advance the animation frame, then reloads the
wait loop count from [[ANIM_WAIT_TABLE]] (indexed by [[ANIM_INDEX]]) into
[[WAIT_LOOP_COUNT]].

<<defines>>=
ANIM_FRAME_CTR          EQU     $7AAF   ; animation frame countdown
ANIM_INDEX              EQU     $7ABD   ; current animation table index
ANIM_WAIT_TABLE         EQU     $7AB0   ; per-frame wait counts (indexed)
WAIT_LOOP_COUNT         EQU     $5A8C   ; inner wait loop counter
@ %def ANIM_FRAME_CTR ANIM_INDEX ANIM_WAIT_TABLE WAIT_LOOP_COUNT

@ The routine below implements the animation tick.

<<tick anim counter>>=
    ORG     $0D1E
TICK_ANIM_COUNTER:
    SUBROUTINE TICK_ANIM_COUNTER

    DEC     ANIM_FRAME_CTR    ; tick frame counter
    BNE     .reload           ; not zero -> just reload wait count
    JSR     DRAW_BLINK_ALT    ; counter hit zero -> draw alt char
.reload:
    LDX     ANIM_INDEX        ; current animation index
    LDA     ANIM_WAIT_TABLE,X ; look up wait count for this frame
    STA     WAIT_LOOP_COUNT   ; store for timed_wait to use
    RTS
@ %def TICK_ANIM_COUNTER

@ [[ANIM_TICK_AND_WAIT]] combines an animation tick and a timed wait.
It calls [[TICK_ANIM_COUNTER]], then [[TIMED_WAIT]] to burn time.  If
the frame counter has reached zero, it calls [[DRAW_BLINK_NORMAL]] to
restore the display and reloads [[ANIM_FRAME_CTR]] from the frame
duration table [[ANIM_FRAME_TABLE]] (indexed by [[ANIM_INDEX]]).

<<defines>>=
ANIM_FRAME_TABLE        EQU     $7AB6   ; per-frame frame counts (indexed)
@ %def ANIM_FRAME_TABLE

<<anim tick and wait>>=
    ORG     $0D30
ANIM_TICK_AND_WAIT:
    SUBROUTINE ANIM_TICK_AND_WAIT

    JSR     TICK_ANIM_COUNTER  ; tick counter, reload wait count
    JSR     TIMED_WAIT         ; burn time
    LDA     ANIM_FRAME_CTR     ; did frame counter expire?
    BEQ     .advance           ; yes -> advance animation
    RTS                        ; no -> return

.advance:
    JSR     DRAW_BLINK_NORMAL  ; redraw blink char in normal video
    LDX     ANIM_INDEX         ; reload animation index
    LDA     ANIM_FRAME_TABLE,X ; look up frame duration
    STA     ANIM_FRAME_CTR     ; reset frame counter
    RTS
@ %def ANIM_TICK_AND_WAIT

@ [[TIMED_WAIT]] calls the ROM [[WAIT]] wrapper [[CALL_ROM_WAIT]]
repeatedly, decrementing [[WAIT_LOOP_COUNT]] until it reaches zero.
If the count is already zero on entry, it returns immediately.

<<timed wait>>=
    ORG     $0D49
TIMED_WAIT:
    SUBROUTINE TIMED_WAIT

    LDA     WAIT_LOOP_COUNT ; anything to wait for?
    BNE     .wait           ; yes -> enter wait loop
    RTS                     ; no -> return immediately

.wait:
    JSR     CALL_ROM_WAIT   ; delay one unit
    DEC     WAIT_LOOP_COUNT ; decrement counter
    BNE     .wait           ; loop until zero
    RTS
@ %def TIMED_WAIT

@ [[CALL_ROM_WAIT]] loads the wait duration from [[WAIT_DURATION]] and
tail-calls the Apple~II ROM [[WAIT]] routine ([[ROM_WAIT]] at [[$FCA8]]),
which delays for approximately $A \times 2.5 + 13.5$ microseconds.

<<defines>>=
ROM_WAIT                EQU     $FCA8   ; Apple II ROM WAIT routine
WAIT_DURATION           EQU     $7AAD   ; ROM WAIT duration parameter
@ %def ROM_WAIT WAIT_DURATION

<<call rom wait>>=
    ORG     $0D58
CALL_ROM_WAIT:
    SUBROUTINE CALL_ROM_WAIT

    LDA     WAIT_DURATION ; load duration parameter
    JMP     ROM_WAIT      ; tail-call ROM WAIT
@ %def CALL_ROM_WAIT
@ [[DISPATCH_ON_MODE]] provides a timing delay appropriate to the current
display mode.  It checks [[PLAY_HIGH_TONE]]: if the byte is~\$60 (an RTS opcode,
used as a ``sound disabled'' sentinel), it calls [[DELAY_WITH_ANIMATION]] for
a longer pause with blinking; otherwise it calls [[ANIM_TICK_AND_WAIT]] for a
shorter animation step.  This keeps the game's pacing consistent whether sound
is enabled or not.


<<dispatch on mode>>=
    ORG     $1F0C
    SUBROUTINE DISPATCH_ON_MODE
; Dispatches on PLAY_HIGH_TONE: if $60 (RTS) then DELAY_WITH_ANIMATION else ANIM_TICK_AND_WAIT
DISPATCH_ON_MODE:
    LDA     PLAY_HIGH_TONE
    BAEQ    #$60,.mode_60
    JMP     ANIM_TICK_AND_WAIT
.mode_60:
    JMP     DELAY_WITH_ANIMATION
@ %def DISPATCH_ON_MODE

\section{Field utilities}

@ [[CLAMP_CHAR_FIELD]] ensures that byte~6 of the record at [[MOB_PTR]]
([[$F4/$F5]]) has its lower 6~bits at least as large as byte~5's lower
5~bits.  If byte~6 is smaller, its low bits are replaced with byte~5's
value (preserving byte~6's top 2~bits).  This clamps a stat floor---
likely ensuring current HP does not fall below a minimum derived from
another field.

<<zero page defines>>=
MOB_PTR                 EQU     $F4     ; mob data pointer (2 bytes, $F4/$F5)
@ %def MOB_PTR

<<clamp char field>>=
    ORG     $0A93
CLAMP_CHAR_FIELD:
    SUBROUTINE CLAMP_CHAR_FIELD

    LDY     #$05
    LDA     (MOB_PTR),Y ; byte 5 of record
    AND     #$1F        ; low 5 bits = minimum
    STA     $BA
    INY
    LDA     (MOB_PTR),Y ; byte 6 of record
    AND     #$3F        ; low 6 bits = current value
    BALT    $BA,.clamp ; current < minimum -> clamp
    RTS                 ; current >= minimum -> done
.clamp:
    LDA     (MOB_PTR),Y ; reload byte 6
    AND     #$C0        ; preserve top 2 bits
    ORA     $BA         ; set low bits to minimum
    STA     (MOB_PTR),Y
    RTS
@ %def CLAMP_CHAR_FIELD

\subsection{Character selection browsing (\$0AAE--\$0B61)}

These routines implement character selection browsing for the scene event
menu.  They walk the mob linked list (starting from the head pointer at
[[$4002]]) looking for player characters (byte~4 of the mob data record
$<$~\$15).

\begin{itemize}
\item [[FIND_FIRST_PC]] walks the list from the head, returning the first
  player character found.
\item [[COPY_PC_NAME_TO_BUF]] copies the selected character's name string
  into the 20-byte display buffer at [[CHAR_SELECT_NAME]].
\item [[FIND_NEXT_PC]] follows the link from the current [[MOB_PTR]] to
  find the next player character, wrapping to the head if the chain ends.
\item [[FIND_PREV_PC]] walks the entire list forward until wrapping back
  to the current character, yielding the predecessor.
\item [[INIT_CHAR_SELECT]] is a scene event entry point: it sets up the
  scene, finds the first player character, and jumps to the character
  selection menu or back to [[MOVE_LOOP]] if none found.
\end{itemize}

@ [[BROWSE_CHAR_INDEX]] holds the mob index of the currently browsed
character during selection.  [[CHAR_SELECT_NAME]] is a 20-byte buffer
inside the menu option strings area where the selected character's name
is displayed.

<<defines>>=
BROWSE_CHAR_INDEX   EQU     $5A07   ; mob index of browsed character
CHAR_SELECT_NAME    EQU     $7B4B   ; 20-byte name display buffer in menu
@ %def BROWSE_CHAR_INDEX CHAR_SELECT_NAME

@ [[FIND_FIRST_PC]] scans the mob linked list from the head pointer at
[[$4002]], following byte-2 links.  For each mob whose byte~4 (appearance)
is $<$~\$15 and bit~7 clear, it is a player character.  On success, copies
the name into [[CHAR_SELECT_NAME]] and returns with carry clear.  If the
list is exhausted (byte-2 link = 0), returns with carry set.

<<find first pc>>=
    ORG     $0AAE
FIND_FIRST_PC:
    SUBROUTINE FIND_FIRST_PC

    LDA     $4002              ; head of character linked list
.check:
    CMP     #$00               ; end of list?
    BNE     .have_entry        ; no -> examine this entry
    SEC                        ; yes -> not found
    RTS
.have_entry:
    STA     BROWSE_CHAR_INDEX  ; save current mob index
    JSR     GET_MOB_DATA       ; -> MOB_DATA_PTR = mob record
    LDY     #$04
    LDA     (MOB_DATA_PTR),Y   ; byte 4 = appearance
    BMI     .skip              ; bit 7 set -> not a PC
    CMP     #$15               ; < 21?
    BMI     COPY_PC_NAME_TO_BUF ; yes -> player character, go copy name
.skip:
    LDY     #$02
    LDA     (MOB_DATA_PTR),Y   ; byte 2 = next link
    JMP     .check             ; follow chain
@ %def FIND_FIRST_PC

@ [[COPY_PC_NAME_TO_BUF]] copies the name of the mob pointed to by
[[MOB_DATA_PTR]] into the [[CHAR_SELECT_NAME]] display buffer.  It first
copies [[MOB_DATA_PTR]] to [[MOB_PTR]], reads bytes~0--1 of the record
(the name string pointer) into [[TARGET_REC]], then loops 20 times
copying characters.  Byte~0 of the name string is the length; characters
beyond the length are replaced with spaces (\$20).  Returns with carry
clear (success).

<<find first pc>>=
    ORG     $0ACE
COPY_PC_NAME_TO_BUF:
    LDA     MOB_DATA_PTR       ; \
    STA     MOB_PTR            ;  | MOB_PTR = MOB_DATA_PTR
    LDA     MOB_DATA_PTR+1     ;  |
    STA     MOB_PTR+1          ; /
    LDY     #$00
    LDA     (MOB_PTR),Y        ; byte 0 = name ptr low
    STA     TARGET_REC         ; \
    INY                        ;  | TARGET_REC = name string pointer
    LDA     (MOB_PTR),Y        ;  |
    STA     TARGET_REC+1       ; /
    LDA     #<CHAR_SELECT_NAME ; \
    STA     MOB_DATA_PTR       ;  | MOB_DATA_PTR = display buffer
    LDA     #>CHAR_SELECT_NAME ;  |
    STA     MOB_DATA_PTR+1     ; /
    LDY     #$00
    LDA     (TARGET_REC),Y     ; byte 0 = name length
    TAX                        ; X = chars remaining
.copy_loop:
    INY
    LDA     (TARGET_REC),Y     ; load name character
    DEX                        ; decrement remaining count
    BPL     .store             ; if count >= 0, keep character
    LDA     #$20               ; else pad with space
.store:
    STA     (MOB_DATA_PTR),Y   ; store into display buffer
    CPY     #$14               ; copied 20 chars?
    BNE     .copy_loop         ; no -> continue
    CLC                        ; success
    RTS
@ %def COPY_PC_NAME_TO_BUF

@ [[FIND_NEXT_PC_WRAP]] is a trivial wrapper that calls [[FIND_NEXT_PC]]
and returns.  This exists as a separate entry point at \$0AFE so callers
can [[JSR]] to it.

<<find first pc>>=
    ORG     $0AFE
FIND_NEXT_PC_WRAP:
    JSR     FIND_NEXT_PC
    RTS
@ %def FIND_NEXT_PC_WRAP

@ [[FIND_NEXT_PC]] follows the byte-2 link from [[MOB_PTR]] to find the
next player character in the list.  If byte~2 is zero (end of chain), it
wraps around by calling [[FIND_FIRST_PC]].  Otherwise it resolves the
link via [[GET_MOB_DATA]], checks byte~4 for a PC (appearance $<$~\$15,
bit~7 clear), and either copies the name or recurses.

<<find first pc>>=
    ORG     $0B02
FIND_NEXT_PC:
    LDY     #$02
    LDA     (MOB_PTR),Y       ; byte 2 = next link
    BNE     .have_link         ; nonzero -> follow it
    JSR     FIND_FIRST_PC      ; zero -> wrap to first PC
    RTS
.have_link:
    STA     BROWSE_CHAR_INDEX  ; save mob index
    JSR     GET_MOB_DATA       ; -> MOB_DATA_PTR = mob record
    LDA     MOB_DATA_PTR       ; \
    STA     MOB_PTR            ;  | MOB_PTR = MOB_DATA_PTR
    LDA     MOB_DATA_PTR+1     ;  |
    STA     MOB_PTR+1          ; /
    LDY     #$04
    LDA     (MOB_PTR),Y        ; byte 4 = appearance
    BMI     FIND_NEXT_PC       ; bit 7 set -> skip, try next
    CMP     #$15               ; < 21?
    BPL     FIND_NEXT_PC       ; no -> skip, try next
    JSR     COPY_PC_NAME_TO_BUF ; yes -> copy name
    RTS
@ %def FIND_NEXT_PC

@ [[FIND_PREV_PC]] finds the player character that precedes the current
one in the circular linked list.  It saves the current
[[BROWSE_CHAR_INDEX]] in [[INPUT_BUFFER]], then walks forward from the
first PC, recording each PC's index in [[INPUT_BUFFER]]+1, until wrapping
back to the saved index.  At that point [[INPUT_BUFFER]]+1 holds the
predecessor.  It then resolves that index and copies the name.

<<find first pc>>=
    ORG     $0B28
FIND_PREV_PC:
    LDA     BROWSE_CHAR_INDEX  ; \
    STA     INPUT_BUFFER       ; / save current index
    JSR     FIND_FIRST_PC      ; start from first PC
.scan:
    LDA     BROWSE_CHAR_INDEX  ; \
    STA     INPUT_BUFFER+1     ; / save as candidate predecessor
    JSR     FIND_NEXT_PC       ; advance to next PC
    LDA     BROWSE_CHAR_INDEX  ; did we wrap back to original?
    CMP     INPUT_BUFFER       ;
    BNE     .scan              ; no -> keep scanning
    LDA     INPUT_BUFFER+1     ; yes -> predecessor index
    STA     BROWSE_CHAR_INDEX  ; set as current
    JSR     GET_MOB_DATA       ; resolve to record pointer
    JSR     COPY_PC_NAME_TO_BUF ; copy name to buffer
    RTS
@ %def FIND_PREV_PC

@ [[INIT_CHAR_SELECT]] is a scene event handler entry point.  It marks
the event as handled ([[SCENE_EVENT_RESULT]]~=~1), calls [[SCENE_SETUP]]
to initialize the scene, then searches for the first player character.
If found (carry clear), it jumps to [[ENTER_CHAR_SELECT]].
If no player characters exist (carry set), it falls back to
[[MOVE_LOOP]].

<<find first pc>>=
    ORG     $0B4F
INIT_CHAR_SELECT:
    STOB    #$01,SCENE_EVENT_RESULT ; mark event handled
    JSR     SCENE_SETUP        ; set up scene boundaries
    JSR     FIND_FIRST_PC      ; find first player character
    BCC     .found             ; carry clear -> found
    JMP     MOVE_LOOP          ; carry set -> no PCs, back to main loop
.found:
    JMP     ENTER_CHAR_SELECT  ; -> character selection menu
@ %def INIT_CHAR_SELECT
The scene loop calls [[$A478]] (a game support routine in the relocated
block at [[$9600]]--[[$A8FF]]) each iteration to check for user input.
If carry is set (key pressed), the loop exits.  Otherwise, it displays
the status bar, renders the scene text from [[$5C00]], runs tune~\#3
(the attract animation at [[$A300]]), and checks [[$5CFF]] for a scene
transition.

The [[$5C00]] region is populated dynamically by [[LOAD_SCENE_DATA]]
from disk.  Its contents change with each scene.

@ [[SAVE_ZP_POINTERS]] and [[RESTORE_ZP_POINTERS]] save and restore four
zero-page pointer pairs to/from fixed addresses in the [[$5A00]] page.
The saved pairs are [[$BC/$BD]] ([[TARGET_REC]]/[[PRINT_STRING_ADDR]]),
[[$F8/$F9]] ([[ENTITY_PTR]]), [[$BE/$BF]] ([[CHAR_REC]]/[[DATA_PTR]]), and
[[$F4/$F5]] ([[MOB_PTR]]).  These pointers are heavily aliased---the same
zero-page bytes serve different roles in different routines---so saving
and restoring them is necessary when entering nested operations like
scene loading or disk I/O.

<<defines>>=
SAVED_BC            EQU     $5A9A   ; saved TARGET_REC/PRINT_STRING_ADDR (2 bytes)
SAVED_F8            EQU     $5A9C   ; saved ENTITY_PTR pointer (2 bytes)
SAVED_BE            EQU     $5A9E   ; saved CHAR_REC/ENTITY_REC (2 bytes)
SAVED_F4            EQU     $5AA0   ; saved MOB_PTR pointer (2 bytes)
@ %def SAVED_BC SAVED_F8 SAVED_BE SAVED_F4

<<zero page defines>>=
DATA_PTR                EQU     $BE     ; general data pointer / return value (2 bytes)
@ %def DATA_PTR

<<zero page defines>>=
TARGET_REC              EQU     $BC     ; secondary entity record pointer in combat/reorder (2 bytes)
@ %def TARGET_REC

<<save zp pointers>>=
    ORG     $6D53
SAVE_ZP_POINTERS:
    SUBROUTINE SAVE_ZP_POINTERS

    MOVW    TARGET_REC,SAVED_BC
    MOVW    ENTITY_PTR,SAVED_F8
    MOVW    DATA_PTR,SAVED_BE
    MOVW    MOB_PTR,SAVED_F4
    RTS
@ %def SAVE_ZP_POINTERS
@ [[RESTORE_ZP_POINTERS]] is the inverse: it copies the saved values back
into zero page, restoring the caller's pointer context after a scene loop
or other operation that may have clobbered them.

<<restore zp pointers>>=
    ORG     $6D7C
RESTORE_ZP_POINTERS:
    SUBROUTINE RESTORE_ZP_POINTERS

    MOVW    SAVED_BC,TARGET_REC
    MOVW    SAVED_F8,ENTITY_PTR
    MOVW    SAVED_BE,DATA_PTR
    MOVW    SAVED_F4,MOB_PTR
    RTS
@ %def RESTORE_ZP_POINTERS

\chapter{Game Data}


\section{Character and location records}

Computes a pointer to a character record from a 1-based index in~A.
Each character record is 9~bytes, stored sequentially starting at [[$4000]].
Returns [[\CHAR_REC/\CHAR_REC+1 = $4000 + A $\times$ 9]].  If A~=~0, returns
[[\CHAR_REC/\CHAR_REC+1 = $4000]] immediately (index 0 is the base/header record).

@ [[CHAR_REC]] is a 2-byte zero-page pointer at [[$BE/$BF]] that holds the
result of [[GET_CHAR_RECORD]].  The routine below computes
$4000 + \text{index} \times 9$ and stores the address in [[CHAR_REC]],
giving the caller a pointer to the selected character's 9-byte record.

<<zero page defines>>=
CHAR_REC                EQU     $BE     ; character record pointer from GET_CHAR_RECORD (2 bytes)
@ %def CHAR_REC

<<get char record>>=
    ORG     $1053
GET_CHAR_RECORD:
    SUBROUTINE GET_CHAR_RECORD

    TAX                ; X = index (loop counter)
    STOW    $4000,CHAR_REC ;  CHAR_REC/CHAR_REC+1 = $4000 (base)
.loop:
    DEX
    BPL     .advance   ; more records to skip
    RTS                ; done: CHAR_REC/CHAR_REC+1 points to record
.advance:
    CLC                ; \
    LDA     CHAR_REC   ;  | CHAR_REC/CHAR_REC+1 += 9
    ADC     #$09       ;  | (9 bytes per record)
    STA     CHAR_REC   ;  |
    LDA     CHAR_REC+1 ;  |
    ADC     #$00       ;  |
    STA     CHAR_REC+1 ; /
    BNE     .loop      ; always taken ($BF >= $40)
@ %def GET_CHAR_RECORD
Location data and character data share the same 9-byte record table at
[[$4000]].  [[GET_CHAR_RECORD]] indexes into this table (index~$\times$~9
+ \$4000).  Record~0 at \$4000 is a header; records~1--62 are the actual
entries.  [[LOCATION_DATA]] points to record~1 (\$4009).

Each record is 9~bytes:

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{cll}
\textbf{Offset} & \textbf{Name}     & \textbf{Description} \\
\hline
0--1 & name\_ptr   & 16-bit pointer to length-prefixed location name \\
2    & mob\_head   & Head of mob linked list (character index, 0~=~none) \\
3    & min\_pos    & Top-left bounding box (row $\times$ 20 + col) \\
4    & max\_pos    & Bottom-right bounding box (row $\times$ 20 + col) \\
5    & map\_id     & Bits 0--6: map scene ID.  Bit~7: visited flag (set at runtime) \\
6--7 & event\_ptr  & 16-bit pointer to event/object list (3-byte entries) \\
8    & mob\_count  & Number of mobs (summed into [[TOTAL_MOB_COUNT]])
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

The event list at [[EVENT_PTR]] consists of 3-byte entries (see
\S\ref{sec:event-format} for the full format).  Byte~0 is a map position
(\$FE~=~empty slot, \$FF~=~end-of-list); byte~1 encodes the event type
and status; byte~2 is type-dependent action data.

The map scene~ID (field~5, bits~0--6) is compared with [[LOCATION_FLAG2]]
(\$5A56); when it changes, [[FILL_MAP]] is called to redraw the map.
Bit~7 is set on first entry via [[ORA \#$80]] and tested with [[BMI]] to
skip first-visit logic on subsequent entries.

The sentinel [[FFFF]] in the name pointer marks the end of the table.

