\label{sec:a478}

The scene loop calls [[JSR $A478]] every iteration to check for user
input.  This address is in the EALDR region ([[$A000]]--[[$BFFF]]),
which remains in memory after the main program starts.

The bytes at [[$A478]] include the undocumented NMOS 6502 opcode [[$04]]
(a 2-byte NOP).  This could mean the code legitimately uses undocumented
instructions, or that the region is modified at runtime before being called.

Partial decode:

\begin{verbatim}
    A478: 04 E5         ; NOP $E5 (DOP: 2-byte NOP, reads zp $E5)
    A47A: 19 03 64      ; ORA $6403,Y
    ...
    A483: CA            ; DEX
    A484: D0 FD         ; BNE $A483   (inner delay loop)
    A486: 38            ; SEC
    A487: E9 01         ; SBC #$01
    A489: D0 F6         ; BNE $A481   (outer delay loop)
    A48B: 60            ; RTS
\end{verbatim}

The inner loop at [[$A483]]--[[$A484]] ([[DEX; BNE]]) is a standard
delay loop.  The outer loop decrements A and repeats, making this a
nested delay.  The carry flag state on exit likely indicates whether a
key was pressed (C=1) or the timer expired (C=0).  Further analysis
requires an emulator that supports undocumented 6502 opcodes.

The attract screen call flow:

\begin{itemize}
  \item [[MAIN_ENTRY]] ([[$0800]]): calls [[GAME_INIT]], then
        [[ATTRACT_SCREEN]] if [[TOTAL_MOB_COUNT]] is zero.
  \item [[ATTRACT_SCREEN]] ([[$09F4]]): sets scene index 1, calls
        [[GET_MOB_DATA]], tail-calls [[SCENE_LOOP]] with scene \$26.
  \item [[SCENE_LOOP]] ([[$6C37]]): saves ZP pointers, steps PRNG,
        conditionally loads scene data from disk.  In a loop: checks
        keyboard/timer via [[$A478]], displays status bar, renders scene
        text via [[TEXT_RENDERER]], runs [[TUNE_PLAYER]] with tune~\#3.
        Exits when user presses a key or scene sequence ends.
\end{itemize}

Key subsystems:
\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{Text renderer} ([[TEXT_RENDERER]]): Reads byte streams with
        position commands, pause/reset control codes, and character data
        for the HRCG font.
  \item \textbf{Tune player} ([[TUNE_PLAYER]]): Plays sound effects and
        music from [[TUNE_TABLE]].  Supports loops, gosub, high/low
        octave selection, and PRNG-based note randomization.
  \item \textbf{Resident interpreter} ([[$0500]]--[[$07FF]]): A
        secondary VM copied from EALDR, using context-swapped zero-page
        state and XOR-encrypted addresses.
  \item \textbf{PRNG} ([[STEP_PRNG]]): Linear congruential generator with
        formula $\texttt{val}_{n+1} = 69 \cdot \texttt{val}_n + \$53
        \pmod{256}$.
\end{itemize}


The [[start_splash_screen]] routine first loads up the initial splash screen,
sets [[indirect_routine]] to [[note_played]], and begins the sound routine by
calling [[start_sound]].

[[note_played]] plots a mob, then sets [[indirect_routine]] to [[splash_routine_2]]
and jumps to [[next_table_entry]].

[[splash_routine_2]] calls a routine first with [[$5E1F]] then with [[$5E3A]],
then jumps to [[splash_screen_step]].

[[splash_screen_step]] then sets [[indirect_routine]] to [[splash_routine_1]]
then [[splash_routine_0]] and calls [[set_splash_routine]] within [[note_played]].
After that, [[splash_screen_step]] presumably moves mobs around.


When the user ends the splash screen, the [[start_splash_screen]] routine
replaces the indirect jump to [[indirect_routine]] in [[start_sound]] to an
absolute jump to [[next_table_entry]], since there is no further need to
animate while playing sound.

Immediately after the event lists, the region [[$4C80--$5AFF]] holds
the mob data table and associated name strings.

\begin{itemize}
\item [[$4C80--$547F]]: 128 mob data records, 16~bytes each.  Bytes
  0--1 are a pointer to the mob's name string; the remaining 14~bytes
  encode combat stats, group linkage, position, appearance, and level.
  [[GET_MOB_DATA]] indexes into this table via the base pointer
  at~[[$4000/$4001]].
\item [[$5480--$59C8]]: Length-prefixed high-bit ASCII name strings
  for all 128 mobs (``ALI BABA'', ``SCHEHERAZADE'', ``MINOTAUR'',~etc.).
\item [[$59C9--$5AFF]]: Residual debug/diagnostic text (unused at
  runtime).
\end{itemize}

<<mob data>>=
    ORG     $4C80
MOB_DATA_TABLE:
    INCLUDE "mobdata.asm"
@ %def MOB_DATA_TABLE
@
@ [[s_PRINT_FONT_CHAR]] at [[$80A4]] is the 10-byte self-modifying HRCG
control string that [[RENDER_FONT_CHAR]] patches with character-set and
glyph codes before passing to [[PRINT_STRING]].  It is a 9-byte
self-modifying string: the routine patches [[CHAR_CHARSET]],
[[CHAR_UPPER_LEFT]], [[CHAR_UPPER_RIGHT]], [[CHAR_LOWER_LEFT]], and
[[CHAR_LOWER_RIGHT]] in place before each call.  The HRCG control codes
embedded in the string switch charset (ctrl-A), enter block mode (ctrl-B),
move to the lower half (ctrl-C), and finish the block (ctrl-D), so that a
single [[PRINT_STRING]] call renders an entire $2\times2$ font character.

<<defines>>=
CHAR_LOWER_LEFT     EQU     $80AB
CHAR_LOWER_RIGHT    EQU     $80AC
CHAR_UPPER_RIGHT    EQU     $80A9
CHAR_CHARSET        EQU     $80A6
CHAR_UPPER_LEFT     EQU     $80A8
@ %def CHAR_LOWER_LEFT CHAR_LOWER_RIGHT CHAR_UPPER_RIGHT CHAR_CHARSET CHAR_UPPER_LEFT

The [[PLOT_CHAR]] routine prints the character number in [[A]], at the text
coordinate in [[X]] and [[Y]].

<<plot char>>=
    ORG     $5DB0
PLOT_CHAR:
    SUBROUTINE PLOT_CHAR

    STA     FONT_CHARNUM
    STX     TEXT_COL
    STY     TEXT_ROW
    STOB    #$01,FONT_CHARSET
    JMP     PRINT_FONTCHAR_AT_TEXT_POS
@ %def PLOT_CHAR

\chapter{Map and Scene}

Initializes a scene for display:
\begin{enumerate}
  \item Loads the character record for index [[ACTIVE_CHAR]].
  \item Reads the character's bounding box from bytes~3--4 of the record at [[\CHAR_REC]].
  \item Converts to column/row ranges.
  \item Picks a random position within those bounds.
  \item Sets the font cursor there.
  \item Performs additional character-record bookkeeping.
\end{enumerate}

The bounding box bytes are packed map positions decoded by
[[POS_TO_COLROW]].  The routine increments the minimums (so the range
is exclusive of the border), then calls [[RANDOM_IN_RANGE]] twice to
pick a random column and row within the bounds.

@ [[SOURCE_CHAR]] records which character is being reordered.
[[BOUNDS_MIN_COL]], [[BOUNDS_MIN_ROW]], [[BOUNDS_MAX_COL]], and
[[BOUNDS_MAX_ROW]] hold the scene's bounding box after unpacking.
[[FONT_COL]] is the font column coordinate, used here to store the
randomly chosen column.  [[SCENE_SETUP]] initializes all of these from
the character record and calls [[RANDOM_IN_RANGE]] for placement.

<<defines>>=
SOURCE_CHAR         EQU     $5A28   ; source character for reorder
BOUNDS_MAX_COL      EQU     $5A52   ; scene setup: right column boundary
BOUNDS_MAX_ROW      EQU     $5A54   ; scene setup: bottom row boundary
BOUNDS_MIN_COL      EQU     $5A51   ; scene setup: left column boundary
BOUNDS_MIN_ROW      EQU     $5A53   ; scene setup: top row boundary
FONT_COL        EQU     $5A0C
@ %def SOURCE_CHAR BOUNDS_MAX_COL BOUNDS_MAX_ROW BOUNDS_MIN_COL BOUNDS_MIN_ROW FONT_COL

<<defines>>=
ACTIVE_CHAR         EQU     $5A29   ; character index being processed
@ %def ACTIVE_CHAR

<<scene setup>>=
    ORG     $0A17
SCENE_SETUP:
    SUBROUTINE SCENE_SETUP

    LDA     ACTIVE_CHAR       ; character/scene index
    JSR     GET_CHAR_RECORD   ; index -> CHAR_REC = char record
    LDY     #$03
    LDA     (CHAR_REC),Y      ; byte 3: min position (packed)
    JSR     POS_TO_COLROW     ; -> A=min_col, Y=min_row
    STA     BOUNDS_MIN_COL    ; min_col
    STY     BOUNDS_MIN_ROW    ; min_row
    LDY     #$04
    LDA     (CHAR_REC),Y      ; byte 4: max position (packed)
    JSR     POS_TO_COLROW     ; -> A=max_col, Y=max_row
    STA     BOUNDS_MAX_COL    ; max_col
    STY     BOUNDS_MAX_ROW    ; max_row
    INC     BOUNDS_MIN_COL    ; min_col++ (exclusive border)
    INC     BOUNDS_MIN_ROW    ; min_row++
    CLC
    LDA     BOUNDS_MAX_COL    ; \
    SBC     BOUNDS_MIN_COL    ;  | col_range = max_col - min_col
    JSR     RANDOM_IN_RANGE   ;  | random column offset
    CLC                       ;  |
    ADC     BOUNDS_MIN_COL    ;  | col = min_col + offset
    STA     FONT_COL          ; / set font column
    CLC
    LDA     BOUNDS_MAX_ROW    ; \
    SBC     BOUNDS_MIN_ROW    ;  | row_range = max_row - min_row
    JSR     RANDOM_IN_RANGE   ;  | random row offset
    CLC                       ;  |
    ADC     BOUNDS_MIN_ROW    ; / row = min_row + offset
    TAY                       ; Y = row
    LDA     FONT_COL          ; A = col
    JSR     COLROW_TO_POS     ; -> A = linear position
    LDY     #$03
    STA     (MOB_PTR),Y       ; store position in record byte 3
    MOVW    MOB_PTR,TARGET_REC ;  TARGET_REC/TARGET_REC+1 = MOB_PTR/MOB_PTR+1
    STOB    #$00,SOURCE_CHAR ; clear source char index
    JSR     REORDER_CHAR      ; reorder character in linked list
    LDY     #$0D
    LDA     #$00              ; \
    STA     (MOB_PTR),Y       ;  | clear bytes 13-14 of record
    INY                       ;  |
    STA     (MOB_PTR),Y       ; /
    JSR     CLAMP_CHAR_FIELD  ; ensure byte 6 >= byte 5 minimum
    LDA     CURRENT_PLAYER    ; current player index
    BANE    ACTIVE_CHAR,.done ; not current player -> skip
    LDY     #$03
    LDA     (MOB_PTR),Y       ; load position from record
    JSR     DRAW_CHAR_AT_POS  ; draw character at position
.done:
    RTS
@ %def SCENE_SETUP
\label{sec:scene_loop}

This is the main scene display loop.  It is called with the scene number
in~A.

@ [[SCENE_NUMBER]] holds the current scene index.  [[SCENE_TEXT_DATA]] is
the base address of the scene's text byte stream, loaded from disk by
[[LOAD_SCENE_DATA]].  [[SCENE_TRANSITION]] is a flag byte: when nonzero,
[[SCENE_LOOP]] treats its value as a new scene number and restarts the
display cycle.

<<defines>>=
SCENE_TRANSITION    EQU     $5CFF   ; scene transition flag (nonzero = new scene number)
SCENE_TEXT_DATA     EQU     $5C00   ; base address of scene text data (loaded by LOAD_SCENE_DATA)
SCENE_NUMBER        EQU     $5A99   ; current scene number
@ %def SCENE_TRANSITION SCENE_TEXT_DATA SCENE_NUMBER

<<scene loop>>=
    ORG     $6C37
SCENE_LOOP:
    SUBROUTINE SCENE_LOOP

    STA     SCENE_NUMBER                    ; store scene number
    STOB    #$14,BLINK_COL ; disable blink cursor

    JSR     SAVE_ZP_POINTERS

    JSR     STEP_PRNG
    LDA     PRNG_OUTPUT                     ; PRNG output
    AND     #$0A                            ; test bits 1 and 3
    BNE     .display                        ; if any set, skip disk load
    JSR     LOAD_SCENE_DATA

.display:
    JSR     $A478                           ; keyboard/timing check (relocated block)
    BCS     .exit                           ; carry set = user pressed key

    JSR     DISPLAY_STATUS_BAR
    STOW    SCENE_TEXT_DATA,TEXT_STREAM_PTR ; scene text data -> $06/$07
    JSR     TEXT_RENDERER

    LDX     #$06                            ; tune 3: attract/opening
    JSR     TUNE_PLAYER
    LDA     SCENE_TRANSITION                ; scene transition flag
    BEQ     .done                           ; zero = no transition
    STA     SCENE_NUMBER                    ; set new scene number
    JMP     .display                        ; continue

.done:
    JSR     SET_TEXT_WINDOW_BOTTOM
    LDA     #$00
    STA     LOCATION_POS                    ; clear location flags
    STA     LOCATION_STYLE
    JSR     ENTER_LOCATION                  ; redraw map if location changed
    JMP     RESTORE_ZP_POINTERS             ; restore and return

.exit:
    JSR     SET_TEXT_WINDOW_BOTTOM
    LDA     #MSG_BREAKS_FREE
    JSR     DISPLAY_MESSAGE                 ; display message (mode off)
    JMP     .done
@ %def SCENE_LOOP
Loads scene-specific data from disk into the [[$5C00]] region.  The disk
read calls [[DISK_READ_FIELD]] at [[$B300]], which enters the disk~VM
interpreter to perform the multi-sector read.  If the read fails, the
routine fills a byte with PRNG output (a graceful degradation rather than
crashing).


<<load scene data>>=
    ORG     $6DD8
LOAD_SCENE_DATA:
    SUBROUTINE LOAD_SCENE_DATA

    BIT     $C0E9           ; check disk controller
    LDA     #$05            ; \
    LDY     #$04            ;  | ($08)+4 = 5 (track configuration)
    STA     ($08),Y         ; /
    LDA     #$00
    JSR     RWTS_DISPATCH   ; execute RWTS command
    CLC
    JSR     DISK_READ_FIELD ; read sector data from disk
    BCS     .error
    RTS

.error:
    LDY     PRNG_OUTPUT     ; on error: fill with PRNG data
    JSR     STEP_PRNG
    LDA     PRNG_OUTPUT
    STA     $9AA6,Y
    RTS
@ %def LOAD_SCENE_DATA
@ [[TILE_DEFAULT_TAB]], [[TILE_FILL_TAB]], and [[TILE_BLINK_TAB]] are
three 4-entry lookup tables indexed by the 2-bit style code from
[[LOCATION_STYLE]] bits 6--5.  [[LOAD_MAP_TILES]] reads all three tables
to set [[DEFAULT_CHAR]], [[MAP_FILL_CHAR]], and [[BLINK_ALT_CHAR]] for
the current location.

<<defines>>=
TILE_DEFAULT_TAB        EQU     $7AD0   ; 4-byte table: default char per style
TILE_FILL_TAB           EQU     $7AD4   ; 4-byte table: fill char per style
TILE_BLINK_TAB          EQU     $7AD8   ; 4-byte table: blink alt char per style
@ %def TILE_DEFAULT_TAB TILE_FILL_TAB TILE_BLINK_TAB

@ The routine below implements this tile-set selection.


<<defines>>=
BLINK_ALT_CHAR          EQU     $7AC3   ; alternate blink character
DEFAULT_CHAR            EQU     $7AC2   ; default entity character ($2C)
MAP_FILL_CHAR           EQU     $7AC1   ; character used to fill the map grid
@ %def BLINK_ALT_CHAR DEFAULT_CHAR MAP_FILL_CHAR

<<load map tiles>>=
    ORG     $746C
LOAD_MAP_TILES:
    SUBROUTINE LOAD_MAP_TILES

    LDA     LOCATION_STYLE ; location style byte
    ROL2 ; rotate bits 7-6 down to bits 1-0
    ROL2
    AND     #$03           ; mask to 2-bit style index
    TAX
    LDA     TILE_BLINK_TAB,X
    STA     BLINK_ALT_CHAR
    LDA     TILE_FILL_TAB,X
    STA     MAP_FILL_CHAR
    LDA     TILE_DEFAULT_TAB,X
    STA     DEFAULT_CHAR
    RTS
@ %def LOAD_MAP_TILES
Two basic routines print the font character stored in [[FONT_CHARNUM]].
[[PRINT_FONTCHAR_AT_TEXT_POS]] converts the font position to a text position
before calling [[RENDER_FONT_CHAR]]. A stored control string at [[s_PRINT_FONT_CHAR]]
has slots for the character set and the four character blocks that
[[RENDER_FONT_CHAR]] fills in before printing.

When printing using the 2x2 font characters, we can set up the HRCG's
"block display mode". This takes four characters and plots them in a 2x2
array with the upper left at the text cursor position.

Because our font table consists of 4 "normal" characters, we need to be able
to map a font character onto its character set and character. The font table
contains 120 font characters, or 480 "normal" characters. Since each
character set is 96 characters, the entire font table spans five character
sets, with character set 1 starting off the table.

Not only that, but the first character in the character set is ASCII 32
(space), so we have to take that into account also.

This is what the [[RENDER_FONT_CHAR]], [[PRINT_FONTCHAR_AT_TEXT_POS]], and
[[PLOT_FONTCHAR]] routines do.


@ The blink cursor is a saved font position used to flash a character on the
hi-res screen.  Three bytes at [[$5AA2]]--[[$5AA4]] mirror [[FONT_COL]],
[[FONT_ROW]], and [[FONT_CHARNUM]]: they record which character to blink and
where.  The rendering path (\$74E0) copies them into the [[FONT_]] variables
before calling [[RENDER_FONT_CHAR]].

A [[BLINK_COL]] value of [[$14]] (20) acts as a sentinel meaning ``no active
blink position,'' since valid font--column values are 0--19.  Both
[[GAME_INIT]] and [[SCENE_LOOP]] store [[$14]] here to disable the blink
cursor at startup and at each new scene.


@ Draws the ``alternate'' blink character (the blink-off frame).
Temporarily replaces [[BLINK_CHAR]] with the alternate character from
[[$7AC3]], calls [[DRAW_BLINK_CHAR]] to render it, then restores
the original [[BLINK_CHAR]].  Called by [[TICK_ANIM_COUNTER]] when
the animation frame counter reaches zero.

Renders a custom font character at the current font position:
\begin{enumerate}
  \item Converts [[FONT_CHARNUM]] and [[FONT_CHARSET]] into four block-character indices (upper-left, upper-right, lower-left, lower-right) for a $2\times2$ character cell.
  \item Patches the [[s_PRINT_FONT_CHAR]] control string with the glyph indices.
  \item Calls [[PRINT_STRING]] to output the character.
\end{enumerate}

Each charset holds 24~characters (\$18).  Characters beyond~\$18 bump the
charset index.  The four glyph indices are consecutive starting at
[[charnum * 4 + $20]].

Called when entering a new scene.  Initialises the AI wait delay:
if [[CHAR_AI_MODE]] is non-zero (AI-controlled character), sets
[[AI_WAIT_FLAG]] to~\$0A and calls [[TUNE_PLAYER]] with index~\$10;
otherwise clears the flag.  Then draws the character, sets
[[WAIT_LOOP_COUNT]] to twice the wait flag (via ROL), and jumps to
[[DRAW_SPRITE]].

@ [[CHAR_AI_MODE]] distinguishes player-controlled characters (0) from
AI-controlled mobs (modes 2--5).  [[AI_WAIT_FLAG]] is set to [[$0A]] when
entering a scene with an AI character and cleared otherwise.
[[SETUP_SCENE_DISPLAY]] tests both values to decide whether to invoke the
[[TUNE_PLAYER]] and how long to delay before drawing the sprite.

<<defines>>=
CHAR_AI_MODE    EQU     $5A05   ; 0 = player, 2-5 = AI behavior modes
AI_WAIT_FLAG    EQU     $5A06   ; wait delay for AI moves (0 or $0A)
@ %def CHAR_AI_MODE AI_WAIT_FLAG

<<setup scene display>>=
    ORG     $0901
SETUP_SCENE_DISPLAY:
    SUBROUTINE SETUP_SCENE_DISPLAY

    STOB    #$00,AI_WAIT_FLAG
    BANE    CHAR_AI_MODE,.not_ai
    STOB    #$0A,AI_WAIT_FLAG
    LDX     #$10                ; tune 8: AI turn effect
    JSR     TUNE_PLAYER
.not_ai:
    JSR     SETUP_CHAR_SPRITE
    JSR     LOAD_CHAR_NAME_PTR
    LDA     AI_WAIT_FLAG
    ROL
    STA     WAIT_LOOP_COUNT
    JMP     TIMED_WAIT
@ %def SETUP_SCENE_DISPLAY
Called from [[SCENE_LOOP]] to set up the viewport when the player
enters a new location.  Compares [[$FA]] with [[LOCATION_POS]]; if
unchanged, returns immediately.  Otherwise:
\begin{enumerate}
  \item Stores the new position.
  \item Calls [[GET_MOB_DATA]] and [[SET_TEXT_WINDOW]] / [[CLEAR_MAP]].
  \item Computes the event position via [[MANHATTAN_DISTANCE]].
  \item Extracts the location style from record field~5; if changed, reloads the map tile set.
  \item Reads fields~3 and~4 of the location record (via [[$FA]] indirect) to obtain the viewport bounds (min/max column and row).
  \item Iterates a nested loop: for each row, for each column, calls [[DRAW_MAP_COL]] to render that cell.
  \item If bit~7 of field~5 is clear, calls [[DRAW_MAP_ENTITIES]] to overlay entity icons on the map.
\end{enumerate}

@ [[EVENT_POS]] stores the event position computed by [[MANHATTAN_DISTANCE]].
[[VIEW_MIN_COL]], [[VIEW_MIN_ROW]], [[VIEW_MAX_COL]], and [[VIEW_MAX_ROW]]
define the visible map rectangle, extracted from fields 3 and 4 of the
location record.  [[ENTER_LOCATION]] uses these bounds to drive a nested
column/row loop that redraws the entire viewport.

<<defines>>=
EVENT_POS           EQU     $5A5E   ; event position (from MANHATTAN_DISTANCE)
VIEW_MIN_ROW    EQU     $5A0B   ; viewport min row
VIEW_MIN_COL    EQU     $5A0A   ; viewport min column (from location field 3)
VIEW_MAX_ROW    EQU     $5A09   ; viewport max row
VIEW_MAX_COL    EQU     $5A08   ; viewport max column (from location field 4)
@ %def EVENT_POS VIEW_MIN_ROW VIEW_MIN_COL VIEW_MAX_ROW VIEW_MAX_COL

@ [[FONT_ROW]] is the current font row coordinate, and [[SET_TEXT_WINDOW]]
is the routine at [[$76C2]] that configures the HRCG text window parameters.
[[ENTER_LOCATION]] uses [[FONT_ROW]] as the row iterator in the map redraw
loop and calls [[SET_TEXT_WINDOW]] during viewport setup.

<<defines>>=
FONT_ROW        EQU     $5A0D
SET_TEXT_WINDOW EQU     $76C2   ; set text window parameters
@ %def FONT_ROW SET_TEXT_WINDOW

<<enter location>>=
    ORG     $72A7
ENTER_LOCATION:
    SUBROUTINE ENTER_LOCATION

    LDA     CHAR_PTR
    BANE    LOCATION_POS,.changed
    RTS
.changed:
    STA     LOCATION_POS
    JSR     ANIM_TICK_AND_WAIT
    JSR     SET_TEXT_WINDOW_BOTTOM
    JSR     CLEAR_MAP
    LDA     #$15
    STA     ENTITY_PTR
    LDA     #$5A
    STA     ENTITY_PTR+1
    JSR     FIND_NEAREST_EVENT
    STA     EVENT_POS
    LDY     #$05
    LDA     (CHAR_PTR),Y
    AND     #$7F
    BAEQ    LOCATION_STYLE,.same_style
    STA     LOCATION_STYLE
    JSR     LOAD_MAP_TILES
    JSR     FILL_MAP
.same_style:
    LDY     #$03
    LDA     (CHAR_PTR),Y
    JSR     POS_TO_COLROW
    STY     VIEW_MIN_ROW
    STY     FONT_ROW
    STA     VIEW_MIN_COL
    LDY     #$04
    LDA     (CHAR_PTR),Y
    JSR     POS_TO_COLROW
    STY     VIEW_MAX_ROW
    STA     VIEW_MAX_COL
.row_loop:
    MOVB    VIEW_MIN_COL,FONT_COL
.col_loop:
    JSR     DRAW_MAP_COL
    INC     FONT_COL
    LDA     VIEW_MAX_COL
    BAPL    FONT_COL,.col_loop
    INC     FONT_ROW
    LDA     VIEW_MAX_ROW
    BAPL    FONT_ROW,.row_loop
    LDY     #$05
    LDA     (CHAR_PTR),Y
    BMI     .skip_entities
    JSR     DRAW_MAP_ENTITIES
.skip_entities:
    RTS
@ %def ENTER_LOCATION
Checks whether the current location position lies on the viewport
boundary.  Converts [[LOCATION_ID]] to column/row via
[[POS_TO_COLROW]], then compares against all four viewport edges
([[VIEW_MIN_COL]], [[VIEW_MAX_COL]], [[VIEW_MIN_ROW]],
[[VIEW_MAX_ROW]]).  If any match, sets [[\DATA_PTR]]=1 and [[\DATA_PTR+1]]=0
(``at edge''); otherwise sets both to~0 (``interior'').

@ [[LOCATION_ID]] stores the current map position index.
[[CHECK_AT_BOUNDARY]] converts it to column/row coordinates and compares
against each viewport edge to determine whether the character is standing
on the map boundary.

<<defines>>=
LOCATION_ID     EQU     $5A17   ; current location/position index
@ %def LOCATION_ID

<<check at boundary>>=
    ORG     $0BFA
CHECK_AT_BOUNDARY:
    SUBROUTINE CHECK_AT_BOUNDARY

    LDA     LOCATION_ID
    JSR     POS_TO_COLROW
    BAEQ    VIEW_MIN_COL,.at_edge
    BAEQ    VIEW_MAX_COL,.at_edge
    TYA
    BAEQ    VIEW_MIN_ROW,.at_edge
    BAEQ    VIEW_MAX_ROW,.at_edge
    STOB    #$00,DATA_PTR
    STA     DATA_PTR+1
    RTS
.at_edge:
    STOW2    $0001,DATA_PTR
    RTS
@ %def CHECK_AT_BOUNDARY
Fills the entire 20$\times$10 map grid with a single character.  The fill
character is read from [[MAP_FILL_CHAR]] ([[$7AC1]], default [[$25]]).
The routine renders the glyph once via [[RENDER_FONT_CHAR]] to build the
HRCG control string, then loops over all 200 grid positions (from
bottom-right to top-left), re-printing the same string at each position
via [[PRINT_STRING]].

@ [[FILL_MAP]] fills the entire 20$\times$10 map grid with a single tile
character:
\begin{enumerate}
  \item Starts at column~19, row~9 (bottom-right corner).
  \item Renders the fill character once via [[RENDER_FONT_CHAR]] to build the HRCG control string.
  \item Loops through all 200 positions by decrementing the column and wrapping to the next row up when it goes negative.
  \item For each position after the first, calls [[FONT_POS_TO_TEXT_POS]] and [[PRINT_STRING]] to repeat the same pre-built glyph.
\end{enumerate}
This avoids recalculating the font data 199 additional times.

<<fill map>>=
    ORG     $743B
FILL_MAP:
    SUBROUTINE FILL_MAP

    STOB    #$13,FONT_COL ; start at column 19, row 9
    STOB    #$09,FONT_ROW
    MOVB    MAP_FILL_CHAR,FONT_CHARNUM ; fill character (default $25)
    STOB    #$01,FONT_CHARSET ; charset 1 (custom font)
    JSR     RENDER_FONT_CHAR     ; render glyph once (builds control string)
.loop:
    DEC     FONT_COL             ; next column left
    BPL     .draw                ; still >= 0 -> draw
    STOB    #$13,FONT_COL ; wrap to column 19
    DEC     FONT_ROW             ; next row up
    BPL     .draw                ; still >= 0 -> draw
    RTS                          ; all 200 positions filled
.draw:
    JSR     FONT_POS_TO_TEXT_POS ; set text cursor to font position
    JSR     PRINT_STRING         ; re-print the same glyph string
    JMP     .loop
@ %def FILL_MAP
Loads the first two bytes of the record at [[$FA/$FB]] (CHAR\_PTR)
into [[PRINT_STRING_ADDR]] and tail-calls [[SETUP_TEXT_POS]].
Used before map redraw to set the text window from the current
character's record.

<<clear map>>=
    ORG     $76B0
CLEAR_MAP:

    LDWIY    CHAR_PTR,#$00,PRINT_STRING_ADDR ; record byte 0 -> PRINT_STRING_ADDR low
    JMP     SETUP_TEXT_POS
@ %def CLEAR_MAP
Draws a single map cell at the current [[FONT_COL]]/[[FONT_ROW]].
Computes the linear position inline (col + row$\times$20) rather than
calling [[COLROW_TO_POS]], then calls [[FIND_ENTITY_AT_POS]],
[[GET_MAP_CHAR]], and [[RENDER_FONT_CHAR]] to draw the tile.


<<draw map col>>=
    ORG     $7323
DRAW_MAP_COL:
    SUBROUTINE DRAW_MAP_COL

    LDA     FONT_COL
    CLC
    LDY     FONT_ROW
.mult_loop:
    DEY
    BMI     .mult_done
    ADC     #$14                    ; +20 per row
    BCC     .mult_loop
.mult_done:
    JSR     FIND_ENTITY_AT_POS
    JSR     GET_ENTITY_FONTCHAR
    JSR     RENDER_FONT_CHAR
    RTS
@ %def DRAW_MAP_COL
Draws entity icons on the map.  Three modes:

\begin{enumerate}
\item If [[MAP_REDRAW_FLAG]] is set, skip straight to drawing mobs.
\item If [[LOCATION_STYLE]] bits 5--6 are set, scroll the map and
      set the redraw flag.
\item Otherwise, scan the full grid cell by cell: for each cell that
      contains a non-\$FE entity in the drawable range, draw its icon
      via [[DRAW_MAP_ICON_B]].
\end{enumerate}

After the grid scan (or redraw), iterates the mob group via
[[FIRST_GROUP_MEMBER]]/[[NEXT_GROUP_MEMBER]], drawing each mob's
icon using [[DRAW_BLINK_CHAR]] (or [[RENDER_FONT_CHAR]] if the
mob has no blink animation).

@ [[MAP_REDRAW_FLAG]] at [[$7AC4]] is a nonzero/zero flag.  When set,
[[DRAW_MAP_ENTITIES]] skips the cell-by-cell grid scan and jumps directly
to the mob-drawing phase, avoiding redundant work when the entire map has
already been redrawn by a scroll operation.

<<defines>>=
MAP_REDRAW_FLAG         EQU     $7AC4   ; non-zero = full map redraw needed
@ %def MAP_REDRAW_FLAG

@ [[ENTITY_REC]] is a 2-byte zero-page pointer at [[$BE/$BF]] that
receives the result of [[FIND_ENTITY_AT_POS]]: a pointer to the entity
record occupying a given map position.  Bit 7 of the high byte
distinguishes mobs (set) from player characters (clear).
[[DRAW_MAP_ENTITIES]] uses it during the cell-by-cell grid scan.

<<zero page defines>>=
ENTITY_REC              EQU     $BE     ; entity lookup result from FIND_ENTITY_AT_POS (2 bytes)
@ %def ENTITY_REC

<<draw map entities>>=
    ORG     $733B
DRAW_MAP_ENTITIES:
    SUBROUTINE DRAW_MAP_ENTITIES

    LDY     #$05
    LDA     (CHAR_PTR),Y
    ORA     #$80
    STA     (CHAR_PTR),Y   ; mark entities drawn (set bit 7)
    LDA     MAP_REDRAW_FLAG
    BEQ     .no_redraw
    JMP     .draw_mobs
.no_redraw:
    LDA     LOCATION_STYLE
    AND     #$60           ; check style bits 5-6
    BEQ     .scan_grid
    JSR     SET_CURSOR_ROW21
    LDA     #MSG_ROCK_FALLS
    JSR     DISPLAY_MESSAGE
    STOB    #$FF,MAP_REDRAW_FLAG
    BNE     .draw_mobs     ; always taken
.scan_grid:
    MOVB    VIEW_MIN_COL,FONT_COL
    MOVB    VIEW_MIN_ROW,FONT_ROW
    LDY     #$02
    LDA     (CHAR_PTR),Y
    PHA                    ; save record byte 2
    LDA     #$00
    STA     (CHAR_PTR),Y   ; clear it during scan
.cell_check:
    LDA     FONT_COL
    LDY     FONT_ROW
    JSR     COLROW_TO_POS
    JSR     FIND_ENTITY_AT_POS
    LDA     ENTITY_REC+1
    BEQ     .next_col      ; no entity here
    JSR     GET_ENTITY_FONTCHAR
    LDY     #$01
    LDA     (ENTITY_REC),Y
    BAEQ    #$FE,.next_col ; $FE = skip
    BALT    #$80,.draw_it ; $00-$7F = draw
    BALT    #$C0,.next_col ; $80-ENTITY_REC+1 = skip
.draw_it:                           ; $C0-$FF = draw
    JSR     SET_CURSOR_ROW21
    JSR     CLASSIFY_ENTITY_TYPE
    JSR     PRINT_BOTTOM_CENTERED
    JSR     DRAW_MAP_ICON_B
.next_col:
    INC     FONT_COL
    LDA     VIEW_MAX_COL
    BAPL    FONT_COL,.cell_check ; inner: next column
    MOVB    VIEW_MIN_COL,FONT_COL
    INC     FONT_ROW
    LDA     VIEW_MAX_ROW
    BAPL    FONT_ROW,.cell_check ; outer: next row
    LDY     #$02
    PLA
    STA     (CHAR_PTR),Y   ; restore record byte 2
    BNE     .draw_mobs
    RTS
.draw_mobs:
    JSR     FIRST_GROUP_MEMBER
.mob_loop:
    LDY     #$03
    LDA     (MOB_PTR),Y
    JSR     POS_TO_COLROW
    STY     FONT_ROW
    STA     FONT_COL
    STOB    #$01,FONT_CHARSET ; custom font
    LDY     #$04
    LDA     (MOB_PTR),Y
    JSR     APPEARANCE_TO_FONTCHAR
    STA     FONT_CHARNUM
    BYEQ    #$00,.mob_blink
    LDY     #$0C
    LDA     (MOB_PTR),Y
    AND     #$0F
    BEQ     .mob_anim
.mob_blink:
    JSR     SET_CURSOR_ROW21
    JSR     PRINT_MEMBER_NAME
    JSR     DRAW_MAP_ICON_B
    JMP     .mob_done
.mob_anim:
    JSR     RENDER_FONT_CHAR
.mob_done:
    JSR     NEXT_GROUP_MEMBER
    LDA     MOB_PTR+1
    BNE     .mob_loop
    RTS
@ %def DRAW_MAP_ENTITIES
After drawing a map entity, [[DRAW_MAP_ICON_B]] copies the current font
position ([[FONT_COL]]/[[FONT_ROW]]/[[FONT_CHARNUM]]) into the
blink cursor variables ([[BLINK_COL]]/[[BLINK_ROW]]/[[BLINK_CHAR]]),
then calls [[TIMED_WAIT]] with the delay from [[BLINK_DELAY]].
It finishes by resetting [[BLINK_COL]] to~\$14 (disabled).

@ [[BLINK_CHAR]], [[BLINK_ROW]], and [[BLINK_DELAY]] are the blink-cursor
state variables.  [[DRAW_MAP_ICON_B]] copies the current font position into
[[BLINK_ROW]] and [[BLINK_CHAR]], then uses [[BLINK_DELAY]] as the
argument to [[TIMED_WAIT]] so the icon flashes briefly on screen.

<<defines>>=
BLINK_CHAR      EQU     $5AA4   ; font character number
BLINK_DELAY             EQU     $7AAC   ; delay value loaded into WAIT_LOOP_COUNT by DRAW_MAP_ICON_B
BLINK_ROW       EQU     $5AA3   ; font row
@ %def BLINK_CHAR BLINK_DELAY BLINK_ROW

<<draw map icon b>>=
    ORG     $740B
DRAW_MAP_ICON_B:
    SUBROUTINE DRAW_MAP_ICON_B

    JSR     SCROLL_STATUS_LINE
    JSR     RENDER_FONT_CHAR
    MOVB    FONT_COL,BLINK_COL
    MOVB    FONT_ROW,BLINK_ROW
    MOVB    FONT_CHARNUM,BLINK_CHAR
    JSR     DRAW_BLINK_ALT
    MOVB    BLINK_DELAY,WAIT_LOOP_COUNT
    JSR     TIMED_WAIT
    JSR     DRAW_BLINK_NORMAL
    JSR     ANIM_TICK_AND_WAIT
    STOB    #$14,BLINK_COL ; disable blink cursor
    RTS
@ %def DRAW_MAP_ICON_B
@ \subsection{RWTS command dispatch (\$6C12--\$6C35)}

[[DISK_READ]] and [[DISK_WRITE]] are thin wrappers that set the RWTS
command code (IOB+\$0C: 1=read, 2=write) and fall through to
[[RWTS_DISPATCH]].

[[RWTS_DISPATCH]] stores the command at IOB+\$0C, clears the volume
field at IOB+\$03, then calls [[RWTS_ENTRY]] with the IOB pointer
from~\$08/\$09.  Carry reflects the RWTS result (clear=success).

<<defines>>=
RWTS_ENTRY              EQU     $B7B5   ; RWTS entry: PHP/SEI, JSR RWTS_CORE, CLC/SEC
@ %def RWTS_ENTRY

<<disk read write>>=
    ORG     $6C12
DISK_READ:
    LDA     #$01               ; command = read
    BNE     RWTS_DISPATCH      ; always taken

DISK_WRITE:
    LDA     #$02               ; command = write
                               ; fall through
RWTS_DISPATCH:
    SUBROUTINE RWTS_DISPATCH

    LDY     #$0C
    STA     ($08),Y            ; IOB+$0C = command (A)
    LDA     #$00
    LDY     #$03
    STA     ($08),Y            ; IOB+$03 = volume (0 = any)
    LDA     $09                ; \ A/Y = IOB pointer
    LDY     $08                ; /
    JSR     RWTS_ENTRY         ; execute RWTS command
    STOB    #$00,$48           ; clear disk status
    RTS
@ %def DISK_READ DISK_WRITE RWTS_DISPATCH

\chapter{Entities}


\section{Entity classification}

[[CLASSIFY_ENTITY_TYPE]] examines the entity record at [[ENTITY_REC]] and sets
[[HANDLER_PTR]] to the address of an appropriate handler routine.  The
classification tree checks [[ENTITY_REC+1]] first: a zero high byte means the
entity is in zero page, and the low byte further distinguishes two handler
addresses.  For entities in regular memory, byte~1 of the record determines
the category: values below~\$80 get one handler, values in \$80--\$BF get
another, \$C0--\$D1 map to a third, \$D2--\$D4 to a fourth, and \$D5--\$FD
to a fifth.  The special value~\$FE triggers a deeper check on byte~2: its
low 5~bits and upper 2~bits select among three more handler addresses, with
sub-values below~\$1B, at~\$1D, and above~\$1D each routed differently.
Nine distinct handler addresses are used in total, covering the full range
of entity types from empty slots to treasure, mobs, shops, and map features.

@ [[HANDLER_PTR]] is a 2-byte zero-page pointer at [[$BC/$BD]] that
[[CLASSIFY_ENTITY_TYPE]] sets to the address of the handler routine matching
the entity's type.  Callers use this pointer to dispatch entity-specific
behavior after classification.

<<zero page defines>>=
HANDLER_PTR             EQU     $BC     ; entity type handler address (2 bytes)
@ %def HANDLER_PTR

<<classify entity type>>=
    ORG     $116B
    SUBROUTINE CLASSIFY_ENTITY_TYPE
; Sets HANDLER_PTR/HANDLER_PTR+1 to handler address based on entity type at (ENTITY_REC)
CLASSIFY_ENTITY_TYPE:
    LDA     #$00
    BANE    ENTITY_REC+1,.not_zero_page
    BANE    ENTITY_REC,.type_C3
.type_E4:                      ; $1175 - reused by backward BMI from $1198
    STOW    $7FE4,HANDLER_PTR
    RTS
.type_C3:                      ; $117E - reused by JMP from $11F9
    STOW    $7FC3,HANDLER_PTR
    RTS
.not_zero_page:
    LDY     #$01
    LDA     (ENTITY_REC),Y
    BMI     .check_ranges
.type_FC:                      ; $118D - reused by backward BMI from $11F5
    STOW    $7FFC,HANDLER_PTR
    RTS
.check_ranges:
    BAMI    #$C0,.type_E4
    BAPL    #$D2,.check_d5
    STOW    $7FD3,HANDLER_PTR
    RTS
.check_d5:
    BAPL    #$D5,.check_fe
    STOW    $8016,HANDLER_PTR
    RTS
.check_fe:
    BAEQ    #$FE,.type_fe_entry
    STOW    $8028,HANDLER_PTR
    RTS
.type_fe_entry:
    LDY     #$02
    LDA     (ENTITY_REC),Y
    TAX
    AND     #$1F
    BNE     .check_c0_bits
    STOW    $8003,HANDLER_PTR
    RTS
.check_c0_bits:
    TXA
    AND     #$C0
    BANE    #$C0,.check_1b
.type_F0:                      ; $11DA - reused by backward BEQ from $11F7
    STOW    $7FF0,HANDLER_PTR
    RTS
.check_1b:
    TXA
    AND     #$1F
    BAPL    #$1B,.check_1d
    STOW    $7FCA,HANDLER_PTR
    RTS
.check_1d:
    BAMI    #$1D,.type_FC
    BEQ     .type_F0
    JMP     .type_C3
@ %def CLASSIFY_ENTITY_TYPE
Converts a mob appearance index (byte~4 of mob data) into a font
character number.  The custom font has 120 characters in groups of~32,
but only 21~mob glyphs occupy each group (characters 1--21 and 33--36).
Characters 5--21 repeat cyclically for higher appearance values.

The routine divides the appearance value by~21 (via repeated subtraction
of~21), producing a quotient in~[[Y]] and a 1-based remainder in~[[A]].
If the remainder is~$\ge5$, it is returned directly.  If~$<5$ and the
quotient is nonzero, 32 is added to index into the next font group.

<<appearance to fontchar>>=
    ORG     $0CF7
APPEARANCE_TO_FONTCHAR:
    SUBROUTINE APPEARANCE_TO_FONTCHAR

    LDY      #$00     ; Y = quotient (font group)
.loop:
    CLC
    ADC      #$EB     ; A -= 21 (unsigned: $EB = 256-21)
    BCC      .done    ; underflow -> done dividing
    INY               ; group++
    BCS      .loop    ; always taken
.done:
    ADC      #$16     ; restore remainder+1 (carry clear, so +22)
    BALT    #$05,.low ; remainder >= 5?
    RTS               ; yes -> return as-is (chars 5-21)
.low:
    BYEQ    #$00,.ret ; yes -> return as-is (chars 1-4)
    CLC
    ADC      #$20     ; add 32 -> next font group (chars 33-36)
.ret:
    RTS
@ %def APPEARANCE_TO_FONTCHAR
Determines the font character number for an entity whose record pointer
is in [[\ENTITY_REC/\ENTITY_REC+1]].  Sets [[FONT_CHARSET]] to~1 (custom font) and
stores the result in [[FONT_CHARNUM]].

Three cases based on the pointer value:
\begin{itemize}
\item [[ENTITY_REC = $0000]]: empty cell --- uses [[BLINK_ALT_CHAR]]
\item Bit~7 of [[ENTITY_REC+1]] set: mob --- reads byte~4 (appearance) from the
      mob record and calls [[APPEARANCE_TO_FONTCHAR]]
\item Otherwise: character record --- decodes the top~2 bits of byte~1
      to select from characters [[$18--$1D]], with further subdivision
      based on the full byte~1 value
\end{itemize}

@ The routine below implements the font-character lookup.

<<get entity fontchar>>=
    ORG     $0C7E
GET_ENTITY_FONTCHAR:
    SUBROUTINE GET_ENTITY_FONTCHAR

    STOB    #$01,FONT_CHARSET ; custom font
    LDA     #$00
    BANE    ENTITY_REC+1,.has_entity ; non-zero -> entity exists
    BANE    ENTITY_REC,.low_only     ; low != 0 -> partial pointer
.empty:
    MOVB    BLINK_ALT_CHAR,FONT_CHARNUM ;  empty cell -> blink char
    RTS                              ; /
.low_only:
    MOVB    DEFAULT_CHAR,FONT_CHARNUM ;  $BE!=0, ENTITY_REC+1=0 -> default char
    RTS                              ; /
.has_entity:
    LDA     ENTITY_REC+1
    BAPL    #$80,.mob ; bit 7 set?
    ; --- character record ---
    LDY     #$01
    LDA     (ENTITY_REC),Y           ; byte 1 of character record
    AND     #$C0                     ; top 2 bits
    BAEQ    #$C0,.both_bits          ; -> detailed check
    BAEQ    #$40,.bit6               ; bit 6 only -> char $1C
    BPL     .empty                   ; bit 7 only -> blink alt char
    LDA     #$1B                     ; neither bit -> char $1B
    BNE     .store
.bit6:
    LDA     #$1C
.store:
    STA     FONT_CHARNUM
    RTS
.both_bits:
    LDA     (ENTITY_REC),Y           ; reload byte 1
    BAEQ    #$FE,.check_byte2        ; $FE -> check byte 2
    BAMI    #$D5,.lt_d5
    LDA     #$1D                     ; >= $D5 -> char $1D
    JMP     .store
.lt_d5:
    BAMI    #$D2,.lt_d2
    LDA     #$18                     ; $D2-$D4 -> char $18
    JMP     .store
.lt_d2:
    LDA     #$1A                     ; < $D2 -> char $1A
    JMP     .store
.check_byte2:
    LDY     #$02
    LDA     (ENTITY_REC),Y           ; byte 2
    AND     #$1F                     ; low 5 bits
    BEQ     .empty                   ; zero -> blink alt char
    JMP     .store                   ; non-zero -> use as charnum
.mob:
    MOVB    ENTITY_REC,MOB_DATA_PTR ;  MOB_DATA_PTR = ENTITY_REC with bit 7 cleared
    LDA     ENTITY_REC+1             ;  |
    AND     #$7F                     ;  |
    STA     MOB_DATA_PTR+1           ; /
    LDY     #$04
    LDA     (MOB_DATA_PTR),Y         ; byte 4 = appearance
    JSR     APPEARANCE_TO_FONTCHAR
    JMP     .store
@ %def GET_ENTITY_FONTCHAR

\section{Entity rendering}


<<print font char data>>=
    ORG     $80A4
s_PRINT_FONT_CHAR:
    HEX     09 ; num chars in this string
    HEX     81 ; ctrl-A (set character set)
    HEX     B1 ; CHAR_CHARSET (self-modified)
    HEX     82 ; ctrl-B (block display mode)
    HEX     A0 ; CHAR_UPPER_LEFT (self-modified)
    HEX     A0 ; CHAR_UPPER_RIGHT (self-modified)
    HEX     83 ; ctrl-C (move to lower left of block)
    HEX     A0 ; CHAR_LOWER_LEFT (self-modified)
    HEX     A0 ; CHAR_LOWER_RIGHT (self-modified)
    HEX     84 ; ctrl-D (complete block data)
@ %def s_PRINT_FONT_CHAR
@ [[RENDER_FONT_CHAR]] is the main entry
point for drawing a 2$\times$2 custom font character on the hi-res screen.
It converts the font position to a text position, then computes which HRCG
character set and base character code correspond to the font index in
[[FONT_CHARNUM]].  The font table spans five character sets (each holding
96~characters starting at ASCII~32), so the routine divides the four-glyph
index ([[FONT_CHARNUM]]$\times$4 + \$20) by~96 to get the set number and
remainder.  These values are patched into a pre-built HRCG control string
that sets block-display mode, selects the character set, and emits the four
character codes.  [[PRINT_STRING]] then sends this string to HRCG, which
renders the 2$\times$2 block at the cursor position.

[[PRINT_FONTCHAR_AT_TEXT_POS]] is an alternate entry point that skips the
position conversion, useful when the caller has already set [[$24/$25]].

<<render font char>>=
    ORG     $7489
RENDER_FONT_CHAR:
    SUBROUTINE RENDER_FONT_CHAR

    JSR     FONT_POS_TO_TEXT_POS ; set TEXT_COL/TEXT_ROW from font pos
PRINT_FONTCHAR_AT_TEXT_POS:
    LDX     #$B1                 ; base charset page
    LDA     FONT_CHARSET
    BANE    #$02,.charset_ok
    INX                          ; charset 2 -> page $B3
    INX
.charset_ok:
    STX     CHAR_CHARSET         ; patch charset in control string
    LDA     FONT_CHARNUM
.check_range:
    BALT    #$18,.compute_glyphs ; fits in current charset page?
    INX                          ; no -> next charset page
    STX     CHAR_CHARSET
    SEC
    SBC     #$18                 ; charnum -= 24
    JMP     .check_range
.compute_glyphs:
    ASL                          ; charnum * 4
    ASL
    CLC
    ADC     #$20                 ; + $20 = base glyph code
    TAY
    STY     CHAR_UPPER_LEFT
    INY
    STY     CHAR_UPPER_RIGHT
    INY
    STY     CHAR_LOWER_LEFT
    INY
    STY     CHAR_LOWER_RIGHT
    STOW    s_PRINT_FONT_CHAR,PRINT_STRING_ADDR ;  $BC/$BD -> control string
    JMP     PRINT_STRING         ; output the 2x2 character
@ %def RENDER_FONT_CHAR PRINT_FONTCHAR_AT_TEXT_POS
Since each HRCG font character is effectively two by two "normal" characters,
there is a routine to convert from font coordinate to text cursor coordinate
so that the HRCG can locate the font character at the text coordinate (at
the upper left of the font character).

@ [[FONT_POS_TO_TEXT_POS]] converts the game's logical font position
([[FONT_COL]], [[FONT_ROW]]) to HRCG text cursor coordinates.  Since the
custom font uses 2$\times$2 character cells, each font position occupies two
text columns and two text rows, so both values are doubled (ASL) and stored
into the Apple~II cursor bytes [[$24]] and [[$25]].

<<font pos>>=
    ORG     $7723
FONT_POS_TO_TEXT_POS:
    SUBROUTINE FONT_POS_TO_TEXT_POS

    LDA     FONT_COL
    ASL
    STA     TEXT_COL
    LDA     FONT_ROW
    ASL
    STA     TEXT_ROW
    RTS
@ %def FONT_POS_TO_TEXT_POS
Searches for the entity (mob or player character) that occupies a given
map position.  Input: A~=~position (0--199), [[$FA/$FB]]~=~base address
of the character table.  Output: [[\ENTITY_REC/\ENTITY_REC+1]]~=~pointer to entity record
(bit~7 of [[\ENTITY_REC+1]] set if mob, clear if character).

The routine first walks the mob linked list.  For each record, byte~2
is the mob index; if nonzero, [[GET_MOB_DATA]] retrieves the mob's data
and byte~3 (position) is compared.  If no mob matches, the player
character table is searched: bytes~6--7 of the base record give the
start of a 3-byte-entry table whose first byte is a position.

Uses heavy self-modifying code to patch absolute address operands for
the indexed loads and table walks.

@ [[DAT_5a17_pos]] at [[$5A17]] temporarily holds the target map position
during [[FIND_ENTITY_AT_POS]].  The routine stores the search position
here on entry, then compares each mob's byte-3 position and each player
table entry against this saved value.

<<defines>>=
DAT_5a17_pos        EQU     $5A17   ; saved position for room search
@ %def DAT_5a17_pos

<<find entity at pos>>=
    ORG     $0B62
FIND_ENTITY_AT_POS:
    SUBROUTINE FIND_ENTITY_AT_POS

    STA     DAT_5a17_pos               ; save target position
    LDA     CHAR_PTR+1                 ; \ patch base address into
    STA     .load3+2                   ;  | player search (high byte)
    STA     .load2+2                   ;  | mob search (high byte)
    LDA     CHAR_PTR                   ;  |
    STA     .load3+1                   ;  | player search (low byte)
    STA     .load2+1                   ; / mob search (low byte)
    JMP     .mob_search

    ; --- Player character search ---
.player_search:
    LDX     #$06                       ; copy bytes 6-7 of record
.load3:
    LDA     $0B7B,X                    ; (self-modified base address)
    STA     .load4-5,X                 ; patch .load4 operand (+6->low, +7->high)
    INX
    BXNE    #$08,.load3
.load4:
    LDY     $0B86                      ; (self-modified: read position from table)
    BYNE    #$FF,.check_player
    JMP     CHECK_AT_BOUNDARY          ; $FF = end of table
.check_player:
    BYEQ    DAT_5a17_pos,.found_player ; matches target?
    INC     .load4+1                   ; \
    BNE     .no_carry1                 ;  |
    INC     .load4+2                   ;  | advance address by 3
.no_carry1:                         ;  | (3-byte table entries)
    INC     .load4+1                   ;  |
    BNE     .no_carry2                 ;  |
    INC     .load4+2                   ;  |
.no_carry2:                         ;  |
    INC     .load4+1                   ;  |
    BNE     .load4                     ;  |
    INC     .load4+2                   ; /
    JMP     .load4
.found_player:
    LDA     .load4+1                   ; \ ENTITY_REC/ENTITY_REC+1 = table entry address
    STA     ENTITY_REC                 ;  |
    LDA     .load4+2                   ;  |
    STA     ENTITY_REC+1               ; /
    RTS

    ; --- Mob linked-list search ---
.mob_search:
    LDX     #$02                       ; byte 2 = mob index
.load2:
    LDA     $0BBD,X                    ; (self-modified base address)
    BAEQ    #$00,.player_search        ; zero -> no more mobs, try players
    JSR     .get_mob                   ; get mob data -> patch .load1
    LDX     #$03                       ; byte 3 = position
.load1:
    LDY     $0BC9,X                    ; (self-modified: read from mob record)
    BYEQ    DAT_5a17_pos,.found_mob    ; position matches!
    LDA     .load1+1                   ; \ copy mob link address
    STA     .load2+1                   ;  | back to .load2 for next iteration
    LDA     .load1+2                   ;  |
    STA     .load2+2                   ; /
    JMP     .mob_search
.found_mob:
    LDA     #$80                       ; \ set bit 7 = mob flag
    ORA     .load1+2                   ;  |
    STA     ENTITY_REC+1               ;  |
    LDA     .load1+1                   ;  |
    STA     ENTITY_REC                 ; / ENTITY_REC/ENTITY_REC+1 = mob pointer | $80
    RTS

    ; --- Helper: get mob data and patch .load1 ---
.get_mob:
    JSR     GET_MOB_DATA               ; A = mob index -> MOB_DATA_PTR/MOB_DATA_PTR+1 = data ptr
    LDA     MOB_DATA_PTR               ; \
    STA     .load1+1                   ;  | patch .load1 operand
    LDA     MOB_DATA_PTR+1             ;  |
    STA     .load1+2                   ; /
    RTS
@ %def FIND_ENTITY_AT_POS
Given a map position in~A, sets the font cursor to the corresponding
column and row, looks up what character or mob occupies that position,
determines its font character, and draws it.

<<draw char at pos>>=
    ORG     $1156
DRAW_CHAR_AT_POS:
    SUBROUTINE DRAW_CHAR_AT_POS

    JSR     POS_TO_COLROW       ; A=pos -> A=col, Y=row
    STA     FONT_COL            ; set font column
    STY     FONT_ROW            ; set font row
    JSR     COLROW_TO_POS       ; re-linearize (A = col + row*20)
    JSR     FIND_ENTITY_AT_POS  ; look up entity at position -> ENTITY_REC
    JSR     GET_ENTITY_FONTCHAR ; determine font char from entity data
    JMP     RENDER_FONT_CHAR    ; render the font character
@ %def DRAW_CHAR_AT_POS
@ [[DRAW_BLINK_ALT]] temporarily swaps the blink character for the alternate
character ([[BLINK_ALT_CHAR]]), draws it at the blink position via
[[DRAW_BLINK_CHAR]], and restores the original.  This produces the
``blinking'' effect on the map: the animation alternates between the entity's
sprite and the location's default tile character.

<<draw blink alt>>=
    ORG     $74CB
DRAW_BLINK_ALT:
    SUBROUTINE DRAW_BLINK_ALT

    LDA     BLINK_CHAR      ; save current blink char
    PHA
    MOVB    BLINK_ALT_CHAR,BLINK_CHAR ; load alternate char
    JSR     DRAW_BLINK_CHAR ; draw at blink position
    PULB    BLINK_CHAR ; restore original char
    RTS
@ %def DRAW_BLINK_ALT
[[DRAW_BLINK_NORMAL]] sets normal video mode (via [[SET_NORMAL_VIDEO]])
then falls through into [[DRAW_BLINK_CHAR]].  Called by
[[ANIM_TICK_AND_WAIT]] when the animation frame expires.

[[DRAW_BLINK_CHAR]] copies the blink state ([[BLINK_COL]],
[[BLINK_ROW]], [[BLINK_CHAR]]) into [[FONT_COL]], [[FONT_ROW]],
[[FONT_CHARNUM]], sets [[FONT_CHARSET]]~=~1, and calls
[[RENDER_FONT_CHAR]] to render the character.  If [[BLINK_COL]]~$\ge$~20
(the disabled sentinel), it returns immediately.  Saves and restores
[[\PRINT_STRING_ADDR/\PRINT_STRING_ADDR+1]] since [[RENDER_FONT_CHAR]] uses that pointer.


<<draw blink char>>=
    ORG     $74DD
DRAW_BLINK_NORMAL:
    JSR     PRINT_CTRL_N      ; Ctrl-N -> normal video

DRAW_BLINK_CHAR:
    SUBROUTINE DRAW_BLINK_CHAR

    LDA     BLINK_COL         ; load blink column
    BALT    #$14,.draw ; >= 20? (disabled sentinel)
    RTS                       ; disabled -- do nothing

.draw:
    STA     FONT_COL          ; copy blink state to font vars
    MOVB    BLINK_ROW,FONT_ROW
    MOVB    BLINK_CHAR,FONT_CHARNUM
    STOB    #$01,FONT_CHARSET ; charset 1
    PSHW    PRINT_STRING_ADDR ; save PRINT_STRING_ADDR (used by RENDER_FONT_CHAR)
    JSR     RENDER_FONT_CHAR  ; render the character
    PULW    PRINT_STRING_ADDR ; restore PRINT_STRING_ADDR
    RTS
@ %def DRAW_BLINK_NORMAL DRAW_BLINK_CHAR
Sets up the blink cursor from the current combatant.  On the mob's turn,
the mob's packed position (byte 3 of mob data) is split into column and row,
and its appearance (byte 4) is converted to a font character number.
On the player's turn, the player's column and row are taken directly from
[[CURRENT_COL]]/[[CURRENT_ROW]], and the font character is looked up via [[$0C7E]].

@ [[IS_PLAYER_TURN]] is 0 on a mob's turn and 1 on the player's turn.
[[SET_BLINK_TARGET]] tests it to choose between unpacking the mob's
packed position or reading [[CURRENT_COL]]/[[CURRENT_ROW]] directly.

<<defines>>=
IS_PLAYER_TURN  EQU     $5A74   ; 0 = mob's turn, 1 = player's turn
@ %def IS_PLAYER_TURN
@ The routine checks [[IS_PLAYER_TURN]] to decide which source to use for the blink cursor's position and character.

<<defines>>=
CURRENT_ROW     EQU     $5A64   ; current row during turn
CURRENT_COL     EQU     $5A63   ; current column during turn
@ %def CURRENT_ROW CURRENT_COL

<<set blink target>>=
    ORG     $16A3
SET_BLINK_TARGET:
    SUBROUTINE SET_BLINK_TARGET

    LDA     IS_PLAYER_TURN
    BAEQ    #$01,.player

    ; --- mob path: convert packed position to col/row ---
    LDY     #$03
    LDA     (MOB_PTR),Y            ; mob data[3] = packed position
    JSR     POS_TO_COLROW          ; A=col, Y=row
    STA     BLINK_COL
    STY     BLINK_ROW
    LDY     #$04
    LDA     (MOB_PTR),Y            ; mob data[4] = appearance
    JSR     APPEARANCE_TO_FONTCHAR ; appearance -> font char number
    STA     BLINK_CHAR
    RTS

    ; --- player path: col/row already separate ---
.player:
    MOVB    CURRENT_COL,BLINK_COL ; player font column
    MOVB    CURRENT_ROW,BLINK_ROW ; player font row
    MOVW    MOB_PTR,ENTITY_REC ;  copy pointer MOB_PTR -> ENTITY_REC
    JSR     GET_ENTITY_FONTCHAR    ; look up player's font char
    MOVB    FONT_CHARNUM,BLINK_CHAR
    RTS
@ %def SET_BLINK_TARGET

\section{Entity management}

Performs one step of an insertion-sort on a linked list of characters,
ordered by byte~11 (level, masked to 5~bits).  It unlinks the character
at index~[[SOURCE_CHAR]] from the list and re-inserts it in sorted order
relative to index~[[ACTIVE_CHAR]].

The linked-list ``next'' pointer is byte~2 of each character record.
[[GET_MOB_DATA]] (\$0C32) resolves a byte-2 value into a record pointer
at [[\MOB_DATA_PTR/\MOB_DATA_PTR+1]].

Phase~1 (removal):
\begin{enumerate}
  \item Walks the chain from [[SOURCE_CHAR]]'s record, following byte-2 links via [[GET_MOB_DATA]] until [[\MOB_DATA_PTR/\MOB_DATA_PTR+1]] equals [[\TARGET_REC/\TARGET_REC+1]] (found the predecessor).
  \item Patches the predecessor's byte~2 to skip the removed node.
  \item Decrements the source group's member count via [[DECR_GROUP_COUNT]].
\end{enumerate}

Phase~2 (insertion):
\begin{enumerate}
  \item Walks the chain from [[ACTIVE_CHAR]]'s record, comparing byte~11 (level) values.
  \item Inserts the removed character before the first node with a lower level, or at the end if none found.
  \item Increments the destination group's member count via [[INCR_GROUP_COUNT]].
  \item Adjusts [[TOTAL_MOB_COUNT]] to track list membership changes.
\end{enumerate}

When [[ACTIVE_CHAR]] is zero, a random decision (via [[STEP_PRNG]]) determines
the insertion point instead of the level comparison.

@ [[REORDER_SORT_KEY]] temporarily holds byte 11 (level) of the node being
compared during the insertion phase.  [[REORDER_LINK]] saves the removed
node's next-link so it can be spliced back in.  [[CURRENT_ROOM]] records
which room is being processed.  [[REORDER_CHAR]] uses all three during
the two-phase unlink-and-reinsert operation.

<<defines>>=
REORDER_SORT_KEY    EQU     $5A2B   ; temp: byte 11 of node for sorted insert
CURRENT_ROOM        EQU     $5A03   ; current room/location being processed
REORDER_LINK        EQU     $5A2A   ; temp: saved next-link during reorder
@ %def REORDER_SORT_KEY CURRENT_ROOM REORDER_LINK

<<reorder char>>=
    ORG     $0F84
REORDER_CHAR:
    SUBROUTINE REORDER_CHAR

; --- Phase 1: unlink character SOURCE_CHAR from its current chain ---
    LDA     SOURCE_CHAR            ; source character index
    JSR     GET_CHAR_RECORD        ; CHAR_REC = record pointer
    JSR     DECR_GROUP_COUNT       ; source group lost a member
.walk1:
    LDY     #$02                   ; \
    LDA     (CHAR_REC),Y           ;  | REORDER_LINK = byte 2 of current record
    STA     REORDER_LINK           ; /  (the "next" link we're removing)
    JSR     GET_MOB_DATA           ; MOB_DATA_PTR/MOB_DATA_PTR+1 = resolve link; TARGET_REC/TARGET_REC+1 = mob data
    LDA     MOB_DATA_PTR           ; \
    BANE    TARGET_REC,.advance1   ; if different, keep walking
    LDA     MOB_DATA_PTR+1         ;  |
    BANE    TARGET_REC+1,.advance1
    ; Found predecessor: TARGET_REC/TARGET_REC+1 points to the node being removed
    LDY     #$02
    LDA     REORDER_LINK           ; \  if removed node's link == CURRENT_ROOM,
    BANE    CURRENT_ROOM,.patch1
    LDA     (TARGET_REC),Y         ; \
    STA     CURRENT_ROOM           ; /  CURRENT_ROOM = (TARGET_REC)[2] (successor's link)
.patch1:
    LDA     (TARGET_REC),Y         ; \  predecessor.byte2 = removed.byte2
    STA     (CHAR_REC),Y           ; /  (skip over removed node)
    JMP     .phase2
.advance1:
    MOVW    MOB_DATA_PTR,CHAR_REC ; CHAR_REC = MOB_DATA_PTR/MOB_DATA_PTR+1
    JMP     .walk1

; --- Phase 2: re-insert at correct sorted position in ACTIVE_CHAR's chain ---
.phase2:
    LDY     #$0B                   ; \
    LDA     (TARGET_REC),Y         ;  | REORDER_SORT_KEY = byte 11 of removed node
    AND     #$1F                   ;  |   (level, 5-bit)
    STA     REORDER_SORT_KEY       ; /
    LDA     ACTIVE_CHAR            ; destination character index
    JSR     GET_CHAR_RECORD        ; CHAR_REC = dest record pointer
    JSR     INCR_GROUP_COUNT       ; dest group gained a member
.walk2:
    LDY     #$02                   ; \
    LDA     (CHAR_REC),Y           ;  | check byte 2 of current record
    BAEQ    #$00,.insert
    JSR     GET_MOB_DATA           ; resolve link
    LDA     ACTIVE_CHAR            ; \
    BEQ     .random                ; /  if dest index = 0, use random decision
    LDY     #$0B                   ; \
    LDA     (MOB_DATA_PTR),Y       ;  | compare candidate's level
    AND     #$1F                   ;  | with removed node's level
    BAPL    REORDER_SORT_KEY,.advance2 ; if >= , keep walking (insert later)
.insert:
    LDY     #$02                   ; \
    LDA     (CHAR_REC),Y           ;  | (TARGET_REC)[2] = (CHAR_REC)[2]  (link successor)
    STA     (TARGET_REC),Y         ;  |
    LDA     REORDER_LINK           ;  | (CHAR_REC)[2] = saved link (insert node)
    STA     (CHAR_REC),Y           ; /
    LDY     #$04                   ; \
    LDA     (TARGET_REC),Y         ;  | if byte 4 of ($BC) >= $15, done
    BALT    #$15,.adjust
    RTS                            ; /
.adjust:
    LDA     #$00                   ; \
    BANE    ACTIVE_CHAR,.chk28     ; decrement TOTAL_MOB_COUNT
    DEC     TOTAL_MOB_COUNT        ; /
.chk28:
    BANE    SOURCE_CHAR,.done      ; increment TOTAL_MOB_COUNT
    INC     TOTAL_MOB_COUNT        ; /
.done:
    RTS
.advance2:
    MOVW    MOB_DATA_PTR,CHAR_REC ; CHAR_REC = MOB_DATA_PTR/MOB_DATA_PTR+1
    JMP     .walk2
.random:
    JSR     STEP_PRNG              ; \  random decision
    LDA     PRNG_OUTPUT            ;  | if PRNG < 1 (i.e., == 0) -> insert
    BAMI    #$01,.insert ;  else keep walking
    BPL     .advance2              ; /
@ %def REORDER_CHAR
The attract screen starts with scene index 1 (the first story character
setup) and begins playing scene \$26.

Characters are organized into groups via linked lists threaded through
byte~2 of each 16-byte mob data record (accessed via [[GET_MOB_DATA]]).
Byte~8 of the \emph{group head}'s mob data record is a packed field:
\begin{itemize}
\item bits 3--0: \textbf{group member count} --- how many characters
      are in this group's chain (0--4 in initial data)
\item bits 6--4: \textbf{pending XP} --- experience points accumulated
      but not yet applied to the character's level (0--7).
      The XP award routine at~\$7248 writes new values here; the
      flush routine at~\$6EE9 adds pending XP to byte~11's level
      field and clears it.
\item bit~7: \textbf{status flag} --- always zero in initial data;
      set during gameplay (controls message selection at~\$18AB).
      Preserved across XP flush.
\end{itemize}

These two entry points adjust the group member count (low nibble of
byte~8) on the head record pointed to by~[[\CHAR_REC/\CHAR_REC+1]]:
\begin{itemize}
\item [[$102F]] ([[DECR_GROUP_COUNT]]): decrements by~1 (source group lost a member)
\item [[$1033]] ([[INCR_GROUP_COUNT]]): increments by~1 (destination group gained a member)
\end{itemize}
Guards: bails out if [[\CHAR_REC]] is zero (null pointer) or if byte~4 of the
record at~[[TARGET_REC]] is~$\ge$~\$15 (inactive/dead character).
Called exclusively from [[REORDER_CHAR]] (\$0F84).

@ [[GROUP_COUNT_DELTA]] holds +1 or $-$1, set by the two entry points
[[INCR_GROUP_COUNT]] and [[DECR_GROUP_COUNT]] respectively.  The shared
body adds this delta to the low nibble of byte 8 of the group head record.

<<defines>>=
GROUP_COUNT_DELTA   EQU     $5A2C   ; +1 or -1 delta for group count adjustment
@ %def GROUP_COUNT_DELTA

<<adjust char byte8>>=
    ORG     $102F
DECR_GROUP_COUNT:
    SUBROUTINE DECR_GROUP_COUNT

    LDA     #$FF              ; delta = -1
    BNE     .apply            ; always taken
INCR_GROUP_COUNT:
    LDA     #$01              ; delta = +1
.apply:
    STA     GROUP_COUNT_DELTA ; save delta for later
    LDA     DATA_PTR          ; \
    BANE    #$00,.not_null
    RTS                       ; /
.not_null:
    LDY     #$04              ; \
    LDA     (TARGET_REC),Y    ;  | bail if byte 4 of (TARGET_REC) >= $15
    BALT    #NPC_APPEARANCE_MIN,.ok ;  ($15+ = inactive/dead)
    RTS                       ; /
.ok:
    LDY     #$08              ; \
    LDA     (DATA_PTR),Y      ;  | group count (low nibble) += delta
    CLC                       ;  |
    ADC     GROUP_COUNT_DELTA ;  |
    STA     (DATA_PTR),Y      ; /
    RTS
@ %def DECR_GROUP_COUNT INCR_GROUP_COUNT
Group iteration uses two zero-page pointer pairs: [[$FA/$FB]] points
to the group head (or the member currently being processed), and
[[MOB_PTR]] is the iteration cursor that advances through the chain.
Both routines follow the ``next'' link in byte~2 of a mob data record,
resolve it via [[GET_MOB_DATA]], and store the result in~[[MOB_PTR]].
If the link is zero (end of chain), [[MOB_PTR]] is set to null.

\begin{itemize}
\item [[$12FA]] ([[FIRST_GROUP_MEMBER]]): begins iteration by following
      byte~2 of the group head at~[[$FA/$FB]].  If that link is zero,
      falls through to check [[MOB_PTR]] as a fallback.
\item [[$1300]] ([[NEXT_GROUP_MEMBER]]): continues iteration by following
      byte~2 of the current cursor at~[[MOB_PTR]].
\end{itemize}


<<advance group link>>=
    ORG     $12FA
FIRST_GROUP_MEMBER:
    SUBROUTINE FIRST_GROUP_MEMBER

    LDY     #$02           ; \
    LDA     (CHAR_PTR),Y   ;  | check byte 2 of group head ($FA)
    BNE     .resolve       ; /  if nonzero, follow it
NEXT_GROUP_MEMBER:
    LDY     #$02           ; \
    LDA     (MOB_PTR),Y    ;  | check byte 2 of cursor ($F4)
    BNE     .resolve       ; /  if nonzero, follow it
    STA     MOB_PTR        ; \  end of chain:
    STA     MOB_PTR+1      ; /  null out MOB_PTR/MOB_PTR+1
    RTS
.resolve:
    JSR     GET_MOB_DATA   ; resolve link -> MOB_DATA_PTR/MOB_DATA_PTR+1
    MOVW    MOB_DATA_PTR,MOB_PTR ;  MOB_PTR/MOB_PTR+1 = MOB_DATA_PTR/MOB_DATA_PTR+1
    RTS
@ %def FIRST_GROUP_MEMBER NEXT_GROUP_MEMBER
@ [[PRINT_ENTITY_NAME]] positions the cursor at row~21, loads the name string
pointer from bytes~0--1 of the record at [[EFFECT_REC]], prints it centered at
the bottom of the screen via [[PRINT_BOTTOM_CENTERED]], and resets the text
window.  This is the standard way to identify which character is being affected
in damage, death, and status messages.

<<zero page defines>>=
EFFECT_REC              EQU     $F6     ; target entity record for damage/stats (2 bytes)
@ %def EFFECT_REC

<<print entity name>>=
    ORG     $1142
PRINT_ENTITY_NAME:
    SUBROUTINE PRINT_ENTITY_NAME
    ; Print entity name: cursor to row 21, load name ptr from (EFFECT_REC)[0..1],
    ; print centered at bottom, then reset text window.
    JSR     SET_CURSOR_ROW21
    LDWIY    EFFECT_REC,#$00,PRINT_STRING_ADDR ; name pointer low
    JSR     PRINT_BOTTOM_CENTERED
    JMP     SCROLL_STATUS_LINE
@ %def PRINT_ENTITY_NAME
Loads the name pointer from bytes~0--1 of the mob record at~[[ENTITY_PTR]]
into~[[\PRINT_STRING_ADDR/\PRINT_STRING_ADDR+1]], then tail-calls the text centering routine
at~\$7705, which centers and prints the name on screen row~23.
Used by 13~callers throughout the combat and interaction code.

<<print mob name>>=
    ORG     $0D8A
PRINT_MOB_NAME:
    SUBROUTINE PRINT_MOB_NAME

    LDWIY    ENTITY_PTR,#$00,PRINT_STRING_ADDR ;  PRINT_STRING_ADDR/PRINT_STRING_ADDR+1 = bytes 0-1 of ($F8)
    JMP     PRINT_BOTTOM_CENTERED ; center and print on row 23
@ %def PRINT_MOB_NAME
@ [[PRINT_MEMBER_NAME]] is a thin wrapper that copies the first two bytes of
the record at [[MOB_PTR]]---which hold a pointer to the member's name
string---into [[PRINT_STRING_ADDR]], then tail-calls [[PRINT_BOTTOM_CENTERED]]
to display the name centered on the status line.

<<print member name>>=
    ORG     $1406
PRINT_MEMBER_NAME:
    SUBROUTINE PRINT_MEMBER_NAME
    ; Copy (MOB_PTR)[0..1] -> PRINT_STRING_ADDR/PRINT_STRING_ADDR+1, then JMP $7705
    LDWIY    MOB_PTR,#$00,PRINT_STRING_ADDR
    JMP     PRINT_BOTTOM_CENTERED
@ %def PRINT_MEMBER_NAME
@ [[LOAD_CHAR_NAME_PTR]] loads the name string pointer from the first two
bytes of the entity record at [[ENTITY_PTR]] into [[PRINT_STRING_ADDR]], then
tail-calls [[SETUP_TEXT_POS_COL20]] to position the text cursor in column~20
(the right-side status panel).  This prepares the display for printing the
current character's name during the status display.


<<load char name ptr>>=
    ORG     $0925
LOAD_CHAR_NAME_PTR:
    SUBROUTINE LOAD_CHAR_NAME_PTR
    LDWIY    ENTITY_PTR,#$00,PRINT_STRING_ADDR
    JMP     SETUP_TEXT_POS_COL20
@ %def LOAD_CHAR_NAME_PTR
@ [[SETUP_CHAR_SPRITE]] reads the current entity's packed position from
byte~3 of [[ENTITY_PTR]], unpacks it to column and row, and stores the
coordinates in both the font parameters ([[FONT_COL]], [[FONT_ROW]]) and the
blink-cursor parameters ([[BLINK_COL]], [[BLINK_ROW]]).  It then loads the
character's sprite index from [[CHAR_SPRITE]], sets [[FONT_CHARSET]] to~1
(custom font), and tail-calls [[RENDER_FONT_CHAR]] to draw the sprite at the
entity's position.  This is the standard way to draw or redraw a character's
map icon.

<<defines>>=
CHAR_SPRITE         EQU     $5A04   ; character's font char number for display
@ %def CHAR_SPRITE

<<setup char sprite>>=
    ORG     $0933
SETUP_CHAR_SPRITE:
    SUBROUTINE SETUP_CHAR_SPRITE
    LDY     #$03
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y
    JSR     POS_TO_COLROW
    STA     FONT_COL
    STY     FONT_ROW
    STA     BLINK_COL
    STY     BLINK_ROW
    TAX
    MOVB    CHAR_SPRITE,FONT_CHARNUM
    STA     BLINK_CHAR
    STOB    #$01,FONT_CHARSET
    JMP     RENDER_FONT_CHAR
@ %def SETUP_CHAR_SPRITE
@ [[LOAD_CHAR_TO_FA]] is a thin wrapper: it calls [[GET_CHAR_RECORD]] and
copies the result from [[DATA_PTR]] to [[CHAR_PTR]] ([[$FA/$FB]]).  Several
callers use this as a shortcut to both look up a character and set the
main iteration pointer.

<<load char to fa>>=
    ORG     $6EC9
LOAD_CHAR_TO_FA:
    SUBROUTINE LOAD_CHAR_TO_FA
    ; Wrapper: GET_CHAR_RECORD then copy CHAR_REC -> $FA/$FB.
    JSR     GET_CHAR_RECORD
    MOVW    DATA_PTR,CHAR_PTR
    RTS
@ %def LOAD_CHAR_TO_FA
@ [[REORDER_CURRENT_CHAR]] is a convenience wrapper that copies [[ENTITY_PTR]]
into [[TARGET_REC]] and [[CURRENT_PLAYER]] into [[SOURCE_CHAR]], then
tail-calls [[REORDER_CHAR]] to re-sort the current character within its group's
linked list.  This is used after stat changes that might affect the character's
position in the sorted order.

<<reorder current char>>=
    ORG     $1414
REORDER_CURRENT_CHAR:
    SUBROUTINE REORDER_CURRENT_CHAR
    ; Copy ENTITY_PTR/ENTITY_PTR+1 -> TARGET_REC/TARGET_REC+1, store CURRENT_PLAYER -> SOURCE_CHAR, JMP $0F84
    MOVW    ENTITY_PTR,TARGET_REC
    MOVB    CURRENT_PLAYER,SOURCE_CHAR
    JMP     REORDER_CHAR
@ %def REORDER_CURRENT_CHAR

<<press button string>>=
    ORG     $7EBA
S_PRESS_BUTTON:
    ; Length $22 (34): CR + "  PRESS THE BUTTON TO CONTINUE  " + CLR
    DC.B    $22,$8C
    HEX     A0 A0 D0 D2 C5 D3 D3 A0 D4 C8 C5 A0 C2 D5 D4 D4
    HEX     CF CE A0 D4 CF A0 C3 CF CE D4 C9 CE D5 C5 A0 A0
    DC.B    $8B
@ %def S_PRESS_BUTTON

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{cl}
\toprule
\thead{Byte} & \thead{Meaning} \\
\midrule
\$7D & Reset to full-screen mode (col=0, row=0, width=20) \\
\$7E & Pause: run tune player and status bar, then resume \\
\$7F & End of stream \\
\$80--\$FE & Set row (byte \& \$7F), next byte = column \\
Other & Character code for HRCG font \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

The text renderer data at [[STATUS_BORDER_DATA]] draws a decorative
