@ %def STATUS_BORDER_DATA

\chapter{Game Display}

Draws the ``PRESS SPACE BAR TO CONTINUE'' (or ``PRESS THE BUTTON TO
CONTINUE'') message in the text window at the bottom of the screen.

<<display status bar>>=
    ORG     $6D1F
DISPLAY_STATUS_BAR:
    SUBROUTINE DISPLAY_STATUS_BAR

    LDA     #$90                               ; ctrl-P with high bit (toggle inverse)
    JSR     ROM_COUT1
    STOW    STATUS_BORDER_DATA,TEXT_STREAM_PTR ; status bar border data -> $06/$07
    JSR     TEXT_RENDERER                      ; draw border box
    JSR     PRINT_CTRL_AB                      ; Ctrl-A, '0'
    STOB    #$17,TEXT_ROW ; WNDBTM = 23

    LDA     $5A00                              ; joystick/keyboard flag
    BNE     .joystick

    ; Keyboard path:
    STOB    #<S_PRESS_SPACE,PRINT_STRING_ADDR
    LDA     #>S_PRESS_SPACE
.store_hi_and_print:
    STA     PRINT_STRING_ADDR+1
.set_margin:
    STOB    #$04,TEXT_COL ; WNDLFT = 4
    JMP     PRINT_STRING                       ; print string, return

.joystick:
    STOB    #<S_PRESS_BUTTON,PRINT_STRING_ADDR
    LDA     #>S_PRESS_BUTTON
    JMP     .store_hi_and_print                ; reuse STA PRINT_STRING_ADDR+1 from keyboard path
@ %def DISPLAY_STATUS_BAR
@ [[SETUP_TEXT_POS]] and [[SETUP_TEXT_POS_COL20]] configure the HRCG text
window for the status panel.  The first entry point sets column~0 (left side);
the second sets column~20 (right side).  Both set the cursor to row~20, send
HRCG control codes A/B, output a carriage return (\$8C) to position the
cursor, fill 20~columns with spaces, then configure the text window width
via [[SET_TEXT_WINDOW]] and output ctrl-K (\$8B) to finalize.

<<setup text pos>>=
    ORG     $76D2
    SUBROUTINE SETUP_TEXT_POS
; Two entry points: $76D2 (col 0) and $76D8 (col 20)
SETUP_TEXT_POS:
    STOB    #$00,$24
    BEQ     .set_row
SETUP_TEXT_POS_COL20:          ; $76D8 - original SETUP_TEXT_POS_COL20 entry
    STOB    #$14,$24
.set_row:
    STOB    #$14,$25
    JSR     PRINT_CTRL_AB
    LDA     #$8C
    JSR     ROM_COUT1
    LDX     #$14
.space_loop:
    LDA     #$A0
    JSR     ROM_COUT1
    DEX
    BNE     .space_loop
    STOB    #$14,$25
    LDA     #$0A
    SEC
    SBC     $24
    STA     $24
    JSR     PRINT_CENTERED_PLUS_COL
    LDA     #$8B
    JMP     ROM_COUT1
@ %def SETUP_TEXT_POS SETUP_TEXT_POS_COL20
\label{sec:text_renderer}

Reads a byte stream from the pointer at [[$06/$07]] and renders
characters on the hi-res screen.  It maintains column/row state and
supports several control codes.

@ [[TEXT_LEFT_MARGIN]] and [[TEXT_RIGHT_MARGIN]] define the column bounds
for text wrapping.  [[TEXT_STREAM_IDX]] saves the Y index into the byte
stream across [[RENDER_FONT_CHAR]] calls, since rendering may clobber~Y.
[[TEXT_RENDERER]] initializes the margins (2 and 18) and row, then loops
through bytes, advancing the column and wrapping to the next row when it
passes the right margin.

<<defines>>=
TEXT_RIGHT_MARGIN        EQU     $5A96   ; right margin column for text wrap
TEXT_LEFT_MARGIN         EQU     $5A97   ; left margin column for text wrap
TEXT_STREAM_IDX          EQU     $5A98   ; saved Y index into byte stream
@ %def TEXT_RIGHT_MARGIN TEXT_LEFT_MARGIN TEXT_STREAM_IDX

@ The routine below processes the byte stream.

<<text renderer>>=
    ORG     $6C8E
TEXT_RENDERER:
    SUBROUTINE TEXT_RENDERER

    LDY     #$00
.init:
    STOB    #$02,TEXT_LEFT_MARGIN ; left margin = 2
    STA     FONT_COL            ; current column = 2
    STOB    #$12,TEXT_RIGHT_MARGIN ; right margin = $12 (18)
    STOB    #$01,FONT_ROW ; current row = 1

    ; --- Main byte-reading loop ---
.fetch:
    LDA     (TEXT_STREAM_PTR),Y ; read byte from stream
    BMI     .set_pos            ; bit 7 set -> position command
    BANE    #$7F,.not_end
    RTS                         ; $7F = end of stream

.not_end:
    BAEQ    #$7E,.pause         ; $7E = pause
    BAEQ    #$7D,.reset         ; $7D = reset to full-screen mode

    ; --- Character output ---
    STY     TEXT_STREAM_IDX     ; save stream index
    STA     FONT_CHARNUM        ; character code
    STOB    #$02,FONT_CHARSET ; character width = 2
    JSR     RENDER_FONT_CHAR    ; draw at current position
    INC     FONT_COL            ; advance column
    LDA     FONT_COL
    BALT    TEXT_RIGHT_MARGIN,.next ; past right margin?
    INC     FONT_ROW            ; yes -> next row
    MOVB    TEXT_LEFT_MARGIN,FONT_COL ;   reset column to left margin
.next:
    LDY     TEXT_STREAM_IDX     ; restore stream index
    INY                         ; advance to next byte
    BNE     .fetch              ; loop (max 256 per page)
    JMP     MOVE_LOOP           ; overflow handler

    ; --- Position command ($80-$FE) ---
.set_pos:
    AND     #$7F                ; row = byte & $7F
    STA     FONT_ROW
    INY
    LDA     (TEXT_STREAM_PTR),Y ; next byte = column
    STA     FONT_COL
    INY
    JMP     .fetch

    ; --- Pause ($7E): run tune player, show status bar ---
.pause:
    TYA                         ; \
    PHA                         ;  | save stream index
    NOP
    LDX     #$06                ; tune 3: attract/opening
    JSR     TUNE_PLAYER
    PSHW    TEXT_STREAM_PTR     ; save stream pointer
    JSR     DISPLAY_STATUS_BAR  ; (clobbers TEXT_STREAM_PTR)
    PULW    TEXT_STREAM_PTR     ; restore stream pointer
    PLA                         ; restore stream index
    TAY
    NOP
    INY                         ; advance past $7E
    JMP     .init               ; reinit margins/position

    ; --- Reset ($7D): full-screen text mode ---
.reset:
    STOB    #$00,TEXT_LEFT_MARGIN ; left margin = 0
    STA     FONT_COL            ; column = 0
    STA     FONT_ROW            ; row = 0
    STOB    #$14,TEXT_RIGHT_MARGIN ; right margin = $14 (20)
    INY                         ; advance past $7D
    JMP     .fetch
@ %def TEXT_RENDERER

\chapter{The Main Loop}

The [[start_sound]] routine goes through a sound table, executing each
instruction until it encounters a [[TONE]] instruction. It then
plays that tone, and then jumps to a routine given by [[indirect_routine]]. This
routine should do something, and then return to the song-playing loop by
jumping to [[next_table_entry]]. This allows the game to play a sound while doing
something else, for example, animating the splash screen at the beginning of the
game, and also interrupts the sound on keypress or joystick button press.

If [[start_sound]] encounters an [[END]] instruction, it returns, and that ends
the song.

[[start_sound]] also checks for a keypress or a joystick button press, and this
is the same as an [[END]] instruction.

\label{ch:attract}

When the main program starts at [[$0800]], it calls [[GAME_INIT]] to set up
hardware and graphics, then checks [[TOTAL_MOB_COUNT]]. If zero (first run), it enters
the \emph{attract screen}---the title sequence that cycles through story scenes
until the player presses a key.

The entry point at [[$0800]] is where the EALDR transfers control after loading
and decrypting the game data.  On entry:
\begin{enumerate}
  \item Calls [[GAME_INIT]], which initializes the Apple~II hardware, sets up hi-res graphics mode, and relocates the HRCG library and disk I/O routines to their runtime addresses.
  \item Sets [[CHAR_PTR]] ([[$FA/$FB]]) to [[$4009]], the base of the character record array.
  \item Inspects [[TOTAL_MOB_COUNT]]---a count of all active mob groups in the game world.  On the very first run this count is zero, so the code branches into [[ATTRACT_SCREEN]], the title sequence that plays until the player presses a key.
\end{enumerate}

Once the attract screen exits (or is skipped on subsequent rounds), the main
loop begins.  It iterates through each character record in sequence, nine
bytes at a time.  For each active character (record byte~8 nonzero), it calls
[[ENTER_LOCATION]] to redraw the map if the player has moved to a new
location, dispatches scene events for players~1 and~3, and then hands off to
[[PROCESS_MOB_GROUPS]] to run AI turns for all mob groups attached to this
character.  After all characters have been processed, [[RANDOM_EVENTS]] runs
the between-round event system, and the loop restarts.

<<main entry>>=
    ORG     $0800
MAIN_ENTRY:
    SUBROUTINE MAIN_ENTRY

    JSR     GAME_INIT
.restart:
    STOW    $4009,CHAR_PTR ;  $FA/$FB = $4009 (character record base)
    LDA     TOTAL_MOB_COUNT    ; zero on first run (no mobs yet)
    BNE     .has_mobs          ; nonzero = game in progress
    JSR     ATTRACT_SCREEN
.has_mobs:
    STOB    #$01,CURRENT_PLAYER ; start with player 1
.char_loop:
    LDY     #$08
    LDA     (CHAR_PTR),Y       ; char record byte 8 (status/group)
    BEQ     .next_char         ; zero = inactive, skip
    JSR     ENTER_LOCATION     ; draw map if location changed
    LDA     CURRENT_PLAYER
    BAEQ    #$01,.run_scene    ; player 1?
    BANE    #$03,.process_mobs ; player 3?
.run_scene:
    JSR     CHECK_SCENE_EVENTS ; scene event dispatch (players 1 & 3)
.process_mobs:
    JSR     PROCESS_MOB_GROUPS ; walk mob list, run turns
.next_char:
    INC     CURRENT_PLAYER
    CLC
    LDA     #$09               ; advance to next 9-byte record
    ADC     CHAR_PTR
    STA     CHAR_PTR
    BCC     .no_carry
    INC     CHAR_PTR+1
.no_carry:
    LDY     #$01
    LDA     (CHAR_PTR),Y       ; byte 1 of next record
    BANE    #$FF,.char_loop    ; more characters -> loop
    JSR     RANDOM_EVENTS      ; between-round random event dispatch
    JMP     .restart           ; restart the game loop
@ %def MAIN_ENTRY
@ Each character in the game world owns a linked list of mob groups, threaded
through byte~2 of the character record.  [[PROCESS_MOB_GROUPS]] walks this
list, resolving each link through [[GET_MOB_DATA]] to obtain a pointer to the
16-byte mob data record.

The routine classifies each group by its type field (bits~5--0 of mob data
byte~6).  Types below~3 are \emph{inactive}---friendly NPCs or party members
not currently in a scene.  For these, the game displays a brief status message
via [[SHOW_IDLE_STATUS]] and runs [[AUTO_HEAL]] to gradually restore hit
points.  Types~3 and above are \emph{active}: the routine sets up the
character sprite, checks whether the group actually needs a turn, and if so
enters [[GAME_TURN_LOOP]].

There is also a 1-in-24 chance (based on a PRNG roll masked with [[$17]]) of
calling a periodic disk checkpoint at [[$A508]] in the relocated block.

<<process mob groups>>=
    ORG     $0884
PROCESS_MOB_GROUPS:
    SUBROUTINE PROCESS_MOB_GROUPS
    ; Walk the mob linked list for the current character.
    ; For each group: inactive (type < 3) -> display message + auto-heal;
    ; active (type >= 3) -> set up scene and enter GAME_TURN_LOOP.
    LDY     #$02
    LDA     (CHAR_PTR),Y     ; char record byte 2 = first group link
    STA     CURRENT_ROOM     ; save as current link
    JSR     CLEAR_MAP
    JSR     STEP_PRNG
    LDA     PRNG_OUTPUT
    AND     #$17             ; 1-in-24 chance (bits 0-2,4)
    BNE     .walk_list
    JSR     $A508            ; periodic disk checkpoint (relocated block)
.walk_list:
    LDA     CURRENT_ROOM     ; current link in chain
    BNE     .has_mob
    RTS                      ; zero = end of list
.has_mob:
    JSR     GET_MOB_DATA     ; resolve link -> MOB_DATA_PTR/MOB_DATA_PTR+1
    MOVW    MOB_DATA_PTR,ENTITY_PTR ;  ENTITY_PTR/ENTITY_PTR+1 = mob data pointer
    LDY     #$02
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y   ; mob data byte 2 = next link
    STA     CURRENT_ROOM     ; save for next iteration
    LDY     #$06
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y   ; mob data byte 6
    AND     #$3F             ; bits 5-0 = mob type
    BAPL    #$03,.active_mob ; type >= 3?
    JSR     SHOW_IDLE_STATUS ; inactive: print name + message
    JSR     AUTO_HEAL        ; heal party members
    JMP     .walk_list
.active_mob:
    JSR     START_MOB_TURN   ; active: set up sprite, enter turn loop
    STOB    #$14,BLINK_COL ; reset blink column to 20
    JMP     .walk_list
@ %def PROCESS_MOB_GROUPS
@ When an inactive mob group is encountered during the list walk,
[[SHOW_IDLE_STATUS]] prints a quick status line.  It scrolls the status area,
prints the mob's name, scrolls again, and displays message [[$20]]---the idle
status text.

<<show idle status>>=
    ORG     $08D1
SHOW_IDLE_STATUS:
    SUBROUTINE SHOW_IDLE_STATUS
    ; Display a status message for an inactive mob group.
    JSR     SCROLL_STATUS_LINE
    JSR     PRINT_MOB_NAME
    JSR     SCROLL_STATUS_LINE
    LDA     #MSG_REST_STRONGER                    ; message $20: idle status text
    JMP     DISPLAY_MESSAGE
@ %def SHOW_IDLE_STATUS
@ For active mob groups (type $\geq$~3), [[START_MOB_TURN]] prepares the
display and enters the turn loop.  It reads the mob's appearance byte (mob
data byte~4), converts it to a font character number via
[[APPEARANCE_TO_FONTCHAR]], and stores the result in [[CHAR_SPRITE]].  The
Y~register after this conversion holds the font group, which doubles as the
AI behavior mode---this determines whether the mob is player-controlled, a
friendly NPC, or a hostile creature.

The routine then calls [[CHECK_MOB_NEEDS_TURN]] to decide whether this group
actually requires a turn.  If the carry flag comes back clear, the mob is
skipped.  Otherwise, the cursor is positioned to row~21, the scene display is
set up, and control falls through to [[GAME_TURN_LOOP]].

<<start mob turn>>=
    ORG     $08DF
START_MOB_TURN:
    SUBROUTINE START_MOB_TURN
    ; Set up the character sprite and enter the game turn loop
    ; for an active mob group (type >= 3).
    LDY     #$04
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y       ; mob data byte 4 = appearance
    JSR     APPEARANCE_TO_FONTCHAR
    STA     CHAR_SPRITE          ; save font character
    STY     CHAR_AI_MODE         ; Y = font group -> AI behavior mode
    JSR     CHECK_MOB_NEEDS_TURN ; carry set = needs a turn
    BCS     .enter_turn
    RTS                          ; carry clear = skip this mob
.enter_turn:
    JSR     SET_CURSOR_ROW21
    JSR     SETUP_SCENE_DISPLAY
    MOVB    CHAR_AI_MODE,$5AA6 ; save AI mode (unused in main.bin)
    JMP     GAME_TURN_LOOP
@ %def START_MOB_TURN
@ Not every mob group needs to act every round.  [[CHECK_MOB_NEEDS_TURN]]
applies three filters, returning with carry set if the mob should take a turn
and carry clear if it can be skipped.

Player-controlled characters (AI mode~0) always get a turn.  For
AI-controlled mobs, the routine checks mob data byte~12's low nibble: if
nonzero, the mob has a pending action queued from a previous round.  Failing
that, it checks the mob's current position for encounters (via
[[CHECK_ENCOUNTER]]) and adjacent threats (via [[CHECK_ADJACENT_THREATS]]).
If neither is found, the mob has nothing to react to, so
[[CLEAR_RESTRICTED]] is called and the turn is skipped.  This keeps the game
moving briskly---mobs in empty corridors don't waste time.

<<defines>>=
ADJACENT_THREAT         EQU     $5A26   ; accumulated adjacent threat level
ENCOUNTER_RESULT        EQU     $5A1F   ; 0/1/2 from CHECK_ENCOUNTER
@ %def ADJACENT_THREAT ENCOUNTER_RESULT

<<check mob needs turn>>=
    ORG     $0958
CHECK_MOB_NEEDS_TURN:
    SUBROUTINE CHECK_MOB_NEEDS_TURN
    ; Check whether a mob group needs a game turn.
    ; Returns: carry set = needs turn, carry clear = skip.
    ; Skips if: AI mode is player (0), or record byte 12 low nibble
    ; is nonzero, or no encounter and no adjacent threats.
    LDA     CHAR_AI_MODE
    BEQ     .needs_turn      ; player-controlled always gets a turn
    LDY     #$0C
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y   ; mob data byte 12
    AND     #$0F             ; low nibble
    BNE     .needs_turn      ; nonzero = pending action -> turn
    LDY     #$03
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y   ; mob data byte 3 = position
    JSR     CHECK_ENCOUNTER  ; check for encounter at this position
    LDA     ENCOUNTER_RESULT
    BNE     .needs_turn      ; encounter found -> turn
    LDY     #$03
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y   ; position again
    JSR     CHECK_ADJACENT_THREATS
    LDA     ADJACENT_THREAT
    BNE     .needs_turn      ; threats nearby -> turn
    JSR     CLEAR_RESTRICTED ; no action needed -> clear restricted flag
    CLC                      ; carry clear = skip
    RTS
.needs_turn:
    SEC                      ; carry set = needs turn
    RTS
@ %def CHECK_MOB_NEEDS_TURN

\chapter{The Game Turn}

According to the original manual:

Strike probability

Whenever any character tries to strike another character, the game will
compute his chance of success. Any character's base chance of striking
his victim is 3.125% times their dexterity. Thus, a player with a dexterity of
11 has a 34.375% chance of striking his victim. However, the base chance is
adjusted by several factors:

If the victim is:

particularly difficult to hit

(halflings and elves have this ability to dodge) . . .. .. . ... subtract 12.5%
particularly easy to hit. . . . . . ....... . .. . .. .. .. .. . .. . . . .. . add 12.5%
extremely easy to hit ....... . . ... . . .. . . .. .. .. . .. . . . .. ... . add 25%
down (unconscious, in hand to hand combat, or resting) .. . . add 18.75%
currently resting (this is in
addition to the adjustment for being down) . . . .. .. . . . . . .. . add 9.375 %
defending . .. .. ..... .. .. . ... . . . ... . ........ . ..... subtract 9.375%
attacking ..... . ... . ... . ..... . ... ... ..... .... . . ... . no adjustment
running . . .... . .. . ..... .. .... . ... . .. .. .. . ..... . .. subtract 3.125 %
on the same space with attacker, the stronger character is
is given an advantage .. . .. . add 1.5625% times attackers strength and
subtract 1.5625% times victim's strength

The chance of striking the victim is then adjusted, if necessary, so that it
is never less than 3.125% nor greater than 96.875%.

The probabilities are in increments of 1/32. In the code, 1/32 is represented by
a single count in 6 bits, so the maximum count is 31 (96.875%).

