\label{sec:game-turn-loop}

Handles one character's complete turn---movement, input, encounters,
and event dispatch.  Called once per character per game tick.

\paragraph{Setup.}
The character's current position (field~3 of the record at [[ENTITY_PTR]])
is split into column and row.  Movement flags are cleared, and the
number of movement points is read from field~12 (low nibble).
If the character's constitution (field~6, bits~0--5) is below~3,
or if [[CHECK_ENCOUNTER]] returns~2 (hostile territory), a
``restricted'' flag is set (bit~2 of field~15).

\paragraph{Input.}
For the player ([[$5A05]]~=~0), keyboard input is read via the
keyboard input routine at [[$A44C]] (relocated block).  For NPCs, [[AI_CHOOSE_TARGET]]
selects a destination and [[FUN_6742]] computes a direction.
The direction value encodes both movement and commands:

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{cl}
\textbf{Value} & \textbf{Action} \\
\hline
1 & North (row$-$) \\
2 & South (row$+$) \\
3 & West (col$-$) \\
4 & East (col$+$) \\
5 & Pass (skip turn) \\
6 & Action 6 $\to$ \$14CD \\
7 & Action 7 $\to$ \$14B7 \\
8 & Action 8 $\to$ set state~1 \\
9 & Fight/attack $\to$ \$143F
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

\paragraph{Movement.}
After applying the direction, the new position is converted via
[[COLROW_TO_POS]] and checked with [[FIND_ENTITY_AT_POS]].
If the cell is empty, the move is committed (position updated, sprite
redrawn) and adjacent threats are re-checked.  Finding no threats
ends the turn early.

\paragraph{Encounter dispatch.}
If something occupies the destination cell, the result from
[[FIND_ENTITY_AT_POS]] determines the handler:
\begin{itemize}
\item [[$BF]] $\geq$ \$80 --- mob encounter $\to$ \$1E5A
\item Event byte~1 bits~7--6 $\neq$ \$C0 --- [[HANDLE_ENCOUNTER]]
\item \$C0--\$D1 --- [[PICKUP_TREASURE]]
\item \$D2--\$D4 --- [[TRIGGER_SCENE_EVENT]]
\item \$D5--\$DA --- map/area event $\to$ \$70DF
\item \$FE --- empty-slot interaction $\to$ \$1D4D
\end{itemize}

@ [[TURN_START_COL]] and [[TURN_START_ROW]] record the character's
position at the start of the turn (for restoring the old cell after a
move).  [[MOVE_POINTS]] is the movement budget; [[STEPS_TAKEN]] counts
steps consumed so far.  [[INPUT_DIR]] holds the direction or command
code (1--9) from the player or AI.  [[TURN_ACTIVE]] is set to 1 while
the turn loop is running.  All six variables are initialized by
[[GAME_TURN_LOOP]] at the start of each character's turn.

<<defines>>=
TURN_START_COL  EQU     $5A61   ; column at start of turn
TURN_START_ROW  EQU     $5A62   ; row at start of turn
MOVE_POINTS     EQU     $5A65   ; movement points remaining
STEPS_TAKEN     EQU     $5A66   ; steps taken this turn
INPUT_DIR       EQU     $5A67   ; direction/command from input (1-9)
TURN_ACTIVE     EQU     $5B27   ; 1 while turn is in progress
@ %def TURN_START_COL TURN_START_ROW MOVE_POINTS STEPS_TAKEN INPUT_DIR TURN_ACTIVE

[[GAME_TURN_LOOP]] is the central routine that executes a single character's
turn.  It handles both player-controlled characters (where input comes from
the keyboard or joystick) and AI-controlled mobs (where
[[AI_CHOOSE_TARGET]] selects a destination and [[NPC_MOVE_AI]] picks
directions).

The routine begins by recording the character's starting position and
clearing movement state.  It checks constitution (field~6): characters with
fewer than~3 HP are restricted from moving.  It also checks for hostile
encounters at the current position and restricts movement if found.

For AI characters, [[AI_CHOOSE_TARGET]] runs first to pick a target
position.  Then the movement point budget is computed from field~12's low
nibble, biased by one extra point if the character's level exceeds its
steps taken.

The main loop reads directional input (from the player or the AI), applies
it to the current position, and checks what occupies the destination cell.
Empty cells allow movement; occupied cells trigger the encounter dispatch
table described above.  The loop continues until movement points are
exhausted, the character enters combat, or a special event fires.

<<game turn loop>>=
    ORG     $19AD
GAME_TURN_LOOP:
    SUBROUTINE GAME_TURN_LOOP

    ; --- setup: save position, clear flags ---
    STOB    #$01,TURN_ACTIVE
    LDY     #$03
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y           ; char field 3 = packed position
    JSR     POS_TO_COLROW
    STA     CURRENT_COL
    STA     TURN_START_COL
    STY     CURRENT_ROW
    STY     TURN_START_ROW
    STOB    #$00,STEPS_TAKEN
    JSR     CLEAR_RESTRICTED         ; clear restricted flag (bit 2 of field 15)

    ; --- check constitution and encounters ---
    LDY     #$06
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y           ; char field 6 (constitution/HP)
    AND     #$3F
    BAPL    #$03,.con_ok
    JSR     SET_RESTRICTED           ; set restricted (too weak)
.con_ok:
    LDY     #$03
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y
    JSR     CHECK_ENCOUNTER
    LDA     ENCOUNTER_RESULT
    BANE    #$02,.enc_ok
    JSR     SET_RESTRICTED           ; set restricted (hostile territory)
.enc_ok:
    LDA     CHAR_AI_MODE
    BEQ     .get_speed
    JSR     AI_CHOOSE_TARGET         ; NPC: pick a destination

    ; --- determine movement points ---
.get_speed:
    LDY     #$0C
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y           ; char field 12
    AND     #$0F                     ; low nibble = speed
    STA     MOVE_POINTS

    ; --- adjust points based on threats ---
    LDA     ENCOUNTER_RESULT
    BAEQ    #$02,.chk_limit          ; hostile -> check if enough to limit
    JSR     CHECK_THREATS_HERE       ; check adjacent threats
    BAEQ    #$01,.move_loop          ; exactly 1 threat -> keep full
    LDA     MOVE_POINTS
    BALT    #$02,.move_loop ; < 2 points -> keep as is
    JSR     RANDOM_IN_RANGE          ; random(move_points)
    BAEQ    #$00,.do_limit           ; random == 0 -> force limit
    STA     MOVE_POINTS              ; reduce randomly
    BNE     .move_loop
.chk_limit:
    LDA     MOVE_POINTS
    BALT    #$02,.move_loop ; < 2 -> use as is
.do_limit:
    LDA     #$01
    JSR     RANDOM_IN_RANGE          ; random(1) -> 0 or 1
    CLC
    ADC     #$01                     ; 1 or 2
    STA     MOVE_POINTS
    BNE     .move_loop               ; always

    ; === MOVEMENT LOOP ===
MOVE_LOOP:                     ; $1A31 - external entry point
.move_loop:
    LDA     #$00
    BANE    MOVE_POINTS,.has_points
    BANE    STEPS_TAKEN,.end_turn    ; out of points, took steps -> done
    BAEQ    CHAR_AI_MODE,.has_points ; player with 0 points, 0 steps -> still prompt
.end_turn:
    JMP     END_TURN                 ; end turn

.has_points:
    BAEQ    CHAR_AI_MODE,.player_input
    JSR     NPC_MOVE_AI              ; NPC movement AI
    JMP     .dispatch_cmd

    ; --- player input ---
.player_input:
    JSR     CONFIGURE_INPUT          ; set up input UI
    LDA     GAME_INPUT_TABLE+4       ; check if movement enabled
    BNE     .have_input
    JMP     TEARDOWN_INPUT           ; no input -> exit
.have_input:
    JSR     GET_INPUT_TABLE_PTR
    JSR     SETUP_INPUT
    JSR     $A44C                    ; read keyboard (relocated block)
    STA     INPUT_DIR
    BANE    #$00,.do_move            ; player goes straight to movement
    JMP     TEARDOWN_INPUT           ; cancelled

    ; --- NPC command dispatch (player skips this) ---
.dispatch_cmd:
    STA     INPUT_DIR
    BALT    #$05,.do_move ; 1-4: movement direction
    BNE     .not_pass
    JMP     .move_loop               ; 5: pass
.not_pass:
    BANE    #$09,.not_fight
    JSR     SET_RESTRICTED           ; 9: fight -> set restricted
    LDA     #$00
    JSR     SET_CHAR_STATE
    JMP     AUTO_HEAL
.not_fight:
    PHA
    JSR     CHECK_AND_RESTRICT       ; re-check encounter
    PLA
    BANE    #$07,.not_cmd7
    JMP     ENTER_COMBAT_STATE       ; 7: action
.not_cmd7:
    BCS     .cmd8
    JMP     START_COMBAT             ; 6: action
.cmd8:
    JMP     SET_STATE_FIGHT          ; 8: set state 1

    ; --- apply movement direction ---
.do_move:
    LDA     ENCOUNTER_RESULT
    BAMI    #$02,.move_ok
    JSR     CHECK_CAN_LEAVE          ; can we leave hostile zone?
    BAEQ    #$01,.move_ok
    JMP     END_TURN                 ; blocked -> end turn
.move_ok:
    STOB    #$00,ENCOUNTER_RESULT
    LDA     INPUT_DIR
    DEC     MOVE_POINTS
    INC     STEPS_TAKEN
    BAPL    #$02,.not_north
    DEC     CURRENT_ROW              ; 1: north
    JMP     .check_dest
.not_north:
    BNE     .not_south
    INC     CURRENT_ROW              ; 2: south
    JMP     .check_dest
.not_south:
    BANE    #$03,.go_east
    DEC     CURRENT_COL              ; 3: west
    JMP     .check_dest
.go_east:
    INC     CURRENT_COL              ; 4: east

    ; --- check what's at the destination ---
.check_dest:
    LDA     CURRENT_COL
    LDY     CURRENT_ROW
    JSR     COLROW_TO_POS
    JSR     FIND_ENTITY_AT_POS       ; -> ENTITY_REC/ENTITY_REC+1
    LDA     #$00
    BANE    ENTITY_REC+1,.something  ; ENTITY_REC+1 != 0 -> occupied
    BAEQ    ENTITY_REC,.empty        ; ENTITY_REC == 0 -> empty cell
    LDX     #$0E                     ; tune 7: entity interaction
    JSR     TUNE_PLAYER
    JMP     SHOW_LOCKED_MSG

.empty:
    JSR     COMMIT_MOVE              ; commit move (update pos, draw sprite)
    JSR     CHECK_THREATS_HERE       ; check adjacent threats
    BANE    #$00,.keep_moving        ; threats remain -> continue
    STA     MOVE_POINTS              ; no threats -> stop
    STA     TURN_ACTIVE
.keep_moving:
    JMP     .move_loop

    ; --- destination occupied: dispatch by type ---
.something:
    LDA     ENTITY_REC+1
    BAMI    #$80,.event ; ENTITY_REC+1 < $80 -> event entry
    JMP     HANDLE_MOB_ENCOUNTER     ; ENTITY_REC+1 >= $80 -> mob encounter

.event:
    LDY     #$01
    LDA     (ENTITY_REC),Y           ; event byte 1
    TAX
    AND     #$C0
    BAEQ    #$C0,.activated
    JMP     HANDLE_ENCOUNTER         ; non-activated -> encounter

.activated:
    TXA
    BAPL    #$D2,.not_treasure
    JMP     PICKUP_TREASURE          ; $C0-$D1: treasure

.not_treasure:
    BAPL    #$D5,.not_scene
    JMP     TRIGGER_SCENE_EVENT      ; $D2-$D4: scene event

.not_scene:
    BAPL    #$DB,.not_map_event
    PSHW    ENTITY_REC               ; $D5-$DA: save ENTITY_REC/ENTITY_REC+1
    JSR     COMMIT_MOVE              ; commit move first
    PULW    ENTITY_REC               ; restore ENTITY_REC/ENTITY_REC+1
    JMP     DISPLAY_SHOP

.not_map_event:
    BAEQ    #$FE,.empty_slot
    JMP     TEARDOWN_INPUT           ; $DB-$FD: unknown

.empty_slot:
    JMP     HANDLE_EVENT_SLOT        ; $FE: empty slot interaction
@ %def GAME_TURN_LOOP MOVE_LOOP
@ [[TURN_DISPATCH]] is the decision point after a character finishes moving.
If [[CHAR_AI_MODE]] is zero, the character is under player control and
execution jumps to [[TEARDOWN_INPUT]] to present the action menu.  Otherwise,
the character is AI-controlled: [[SELECT_COMBAT_TARGET]] evaluates the
situation and returns a status code.  A return of~2 means a hostile is present
at the same position, so execution enters [[ENTER_COMBAT_STATE]].  A negative
value means the AI has committed to an attack, jumping to [[START_COMBAT]].
Any other value means the area is safe, so the character attempts
[[AUTO_HEAL]] to recover between fights.


<<turn dispatch>>=
    ORG     $14A3
TURN_DISPATCH:
    SUBROUTINE TURN_DISPATCH
    LDA     CHAR_AI_MODE
    BEQ     .no_combat
    JSR     SELECT_COMBAT_TARGET
    BAEQ    #$02,ENTER_COMBAT_STATE
    BMI     START_COMBAT
    JMP     AUTO_HEAL
.no_combat:
    JMP     TEARDOWN_INPUT
@ %def TURN_DISPATCH
@ [[COMMIT_MOVE]] finalizes a character's movement on the map:
\begin{enumerate}
  \item Writes [[CURRENT_COL]] and [[CURRENT_ROW]] into the font and blink-cursor parameters.
  \item Packs them into a single byte with [[COLROW_TO_POS]].
  \item Stores the result in the entity's position field (byte~3 of [[ENTITY_PTR]]).
  \item Draws the character's sprite at the new location via [[RENDER_FONT_CHAR]].
  \item Sets [[TURN_TUNE_GUARD]] to~\$16.
\end{enumerate}
Execution falls through into [[RESET_TURN_POS]], which:
\begin{enumerate}
  \item Converts the turn's starting position back into a packed byte.
  \item Calls [[DRAW_CHAR_AT_POS]] to restore whatever was underneath the character's old location.
  \item Updates the starting position to the new current position.
\end{enumerate}
If [[TURN_TUNE_GUARD]] is exactly~\$16---meaning this is the
first call since [[COMMIT_MOVE]] set it---the guard is decremented and the
[[TUNE_PLAYER]] is invoked to play the movement sound effect.

<<defines>>=
TURN_TUNE_GUARD   EQU     $5AA9   ; turn reset: guards one-shot script execution
@ %def TURN_TUNE_GUARD

<<commit move>>=
    ORG     $1B52
COMMIT_MOVE:
    SUBROUTINE COMMIT_MOVE
    ; Commit move: store CURRENT_COL/ROW, convert to packed pos,
    ; update char field 3, set font char, draw sprite
    MOVB    CURRENT_COL,FONT_COL
    STA     BLINK_COL
    LDY     CURRENT_ROW
    STY     FONT_ROW
    STY     BLINK_ROW
    JSR     COLROW_TO_POS
    LDY     #$03
    STA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y   ; update char packed position
    MOVB    CHAR_SPRITE,FONT_CHARNUM
    STA     BLINK_CHAR
    STOB    #$01,FONT_CHARSET
    JSR     RENDER_FONT_CHAR ; draw sprite
    LDX     #$16
    STX     TURN_TUNE_GUARD
    ; falls through to RESET_TURN_POS
RESET_TURN_POS:
    ; Reset to turn start: convert start col/row to packed pos,
    ; call $1156, update current->start, conditionally play tune
    LDA     TURN_START_COL
    LDY     TURN_START_ROW
    JSR     COLROW_TO_POS
    JSR     DRAW_CHAR_AT_POS
    MOVB    CURRENT_COL,TURN_START_COL
    MOVB    CURRENT_ROW,TURN_START_ROW
    LDX     TURN_TUNE_GUARD ; X=$16 = tune 11: movement effect
    BXEQ    #$16,.run_script
    RTS
.run_script:
    DEC     TURN_TUNE_GUARD
    JMP     TUNE_PLAYER     ; X still $16 from LDX above
@ %def COMMIT_MOVE RESET_TURN_POS
@ [[END_TURN]] wraps up a character's turn:
\begin{enumerate}
  \item Clears [[TURN_ACTIVE]].
  \item Calls [[CHECK_AND_RESTRICT]] to update the restricted flag based on the encounter at the character's final position.
  \item Checks whether the character has enough steps remaining for another action: if [[STEPS_TAKEN]] is zero, loops back to [[TURN_DISPATCH]]; otherwise compares the character's level (field~\$0C, bits~2--0 after ROR) against [[STEPS_TAKEN]], and if the level is high enough, the character gets another turn via [[TURN_DISPATCH]].
\end{enumerate}

<<end turn>>=
    ORG     $1BA7
END_TURN:
    SUBROUTINE END_TURN
    ; End turn: clear TURN_ACTIVE, check encounter, compare level vs STEPS_TAKEN
    STOB    #$00,TURN_ACTIVE
    JSR     CHECK_AND_RESTRICT
    LDA     STEPS_TAKEN
    BNE     .check_level
    JMP     TURN_DISPATCH
.check_level:
    LDY     #$0C
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y
    ROR
    AND     #$07
    BAMI    STEPS_TAKEN,.too_low
    JMP     TURN_DISPATCH
.too_low:
@ %def END_TURN
@ [[SET_CHAR_STATE]] writes a new value into the low two bits of byte~15 of
the current entity record, preserving the upper six bits.  The two-bit field
encodes the character's turn phase: 0~for idle, 1~for fighting, 2~for
entering combat, and 3~for actively attacking.  Multiple routines call this
to advance or reset the character through the turn state machine.

<<set char state>>=
    ORG     $1BE0
SET_CHAR_STATE:
    SUBROUTINE SET_CHAR_STATE
    ; Set char field 15 low 2 bits to A
    STA     $5A60
    LDY     #$0F
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y
    AND     #$FC  ; clear low 2 bits
    ORA     $5A60 ; set to new value
    STA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y
    RTS
@ %def SET_CHAR_STATE
@ [[SET_STATE_FIGHT]] sets the character's turn state to~1 (fighting) by
loading~\$01 and tail-calling [[SET_CHAR_STATE]].  This state indicates the
character is engaged in combat but has not yet committed to an attack.

<<set state fight>>=
    ORG     $1BC6
SET_STATE_FIGHT:
    SUBROUTINE SET_STATE_FIGHT
    ; Set char field 15 state to 1
    LDA     #$01
    JMP     SET_CHAR_STATE
@ %def SET_STATE_FIGHT
@ [[CHECK_AND_RESTRICT]] evaluates the encounter at the character's current
position and updates the restricted flag accordingly.  It reads byte~3 of
[[ENTITY_PTR]] (the packed position), calls [[CHECK_ENCOUNTER]], clears the
restricted flag, and then re-sets it only if the encounter result is~2
(hostile present).  This ensures characters at hostile positions cannot
freely move away without the flee mechanic.

<<check and restrict>>=
    ORG     $1BCB
CHECK_AND_RESTRICT:
    SUBROUTINE CHECK_AND_RESTRICT
    ; Check encounter at char position, clear restricted flag,
    ; set it if encounter type is 2.
    LDY     #$03
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y
    JSR     CHECK_ENCOUNTER
    JSR     CLEAR_RESTRICTED
    LDA     ENCOUNTER_RESULT
    BANE    #$02,.done
    JSR     SET_RESTRICTED
.done:
    RTS
@ %def CHECK_AND_RESTRICT
@ [[CLEAR_RESTRICTED]] clears bit~2 of the entity's field~15, removing the
restricted-movement flag.  This is typically called at the start of encounter
evaluation before conditionally re-setting the flag.

<<clear restricted>>=
    ORG     $1BEF
CLEAR_RESTRICTED:
    SUBROUTINE CLEAR_RESTRICTED
    ; Clear restricted flag (bit 2 of char field 15)
    LDY     #$0F
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y
    AND     #$FB
    STA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y
    RTS
@ %def CLEAR_RESTRICTED
@ [[SET_RESTRICTED]] sets bit~2 of the entity's field~15, marking the
character as movement-restricted.  Restricted characters cannot freely walk
away from their current position---they must either fight or attempt a
flee check.


<<set restricted>>=
    ORG     $1BF8
SET_RESTRICTED:
    SUBROUTINE SET_RESTRICTED
    ; Set restricted flag (bit 2 of char field 15)
    LDY     #$0F
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y
    ORA     #$04
    STA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y
    RTS
@ %def SET_RESTRICTED

\chapter{Input System}

The game's menu-driven input system uses a table-based architecture.  Each
menu is defined by a descriptor block pointed to by [[$C0/$C1]]: byte~0 is
the number of options, byte~1 is the default selection, bytes~2--3 hold a
pointer to an initialization routine, and each option record contains display
data and an exit handler.  [[INPUT_LOOP]] drives the cycle: it calls
[[SETUP_INPUT]] to initialize the menu, then enters a loop that calculates the
record pointer for the current selection, sets up the cursor highlight, and
waits for keyboard input.  If the player presses return (indicated by a zero
return from [[READ_KEYBOARD]]), the exit handler address is loaded from bytes
8--9 of the option record and executed via an indirect jump.  Any other
keypress is validated by [[VALIDATE_INPUT]]; if it changes the selection, the
cursor is repositioned and the loop continues; if the selection stays the
same, the tune player is called with tune~\$12 to play the
in-place action.

@ [[INPUT_JMP_VEC]] at [[$5F5E]] is a 2-byte indirect jump vector used by
[[INPUT_LOOP]] to dispatch exit handlers and initialization callbacks.
[[CURRENT_SELECTION]] tracks which menu option is currently highlighted.
[[INPUT_LOOP]] writes the exit handler address from the selected record
into [[INPUT_JMP_VEC]] and executes it via [[JMP (INPUT_JMP_VEC)]].

<<defines>>=
INPUT_JMP_VEC   EQU     $5F5E   ; indirect jump vector for input callbacks
CURRENT_SELECTION EQU   $5AAB   ; current menu selection index
@ %def INPUT_JMP_VEC CURRENT_SELECTION

@ [[READ_KEYBOARD]] at [[$A44C]] is the keyboard input routine in the
relocated block (\$9600--\$A8FF).  [[INPUT_LOOP]] calls it to wait for
a keypress; a zero return indicates the player pressed return (select),
while any other value is passed to [[VALIDATE_INPUT]].

<<input loop>>=
    ORG     $5F19
INPUT_LOOP:
    SUBROUTINE INPUT_LOOP
    JSR     SETUP_INPUT
    LDY     #$01
    LDA     ($C0),Y
    STA     CURRENT_SELECTION
.loop:
    LDA     CURRENT_SELECTION
    JSR     CALC_RECORD_PTR
    JSR     SETUP_CURSOR_EXT
    JSR     READ_KEYBOARD
    BEQ     .exit
    JSR     VALIDATE_INPUT
    BAEQ    CURRENT_SELECTION,.run_script
    BAEQ    #$00,.run_script
    STA     CURRENT_SELECTION
    JSR     SETUP_CURSOR
    JMP     .loop
.run_script:
    LDX     #$12                ; tune 9: menu selection effect
    JSR     TUNE_PLAYER
    JMP     .loop
.exit:
    LDWIY    $C2,#$08,INPUT_JMP_VEC
    JMP     (INPUT_JMP_VEC)
@ %def INPUT_LOOP
@ [[SETUP_INPUT]] initializes a menu interaction.  It stores the X and~Y
register values as the high and low bytes of the menu descriptor pointer
([[$C1]] and [[$C0]]), calls the menu's initialization routine through
[[CALL_INPUT_INIT]], clears the 120-byte input display buffer, draws all menu
options with [[DRAW_INPUT_OPTIONS]], and renders the buffer to the screen.

<<setup input>>=
    ORG     $5F60
SETUP_INPUT:
    SUBROUTINE SETUP_INPUT
    ; Set up input: store X/Y in $C1/$C0, call setup routines.
    STX     $C1
    STY     $C0
    JSR     CALL_INPUT_INIT
    JSR     CLEAR_INPUT_BUFFER
    JSR     DRAW_INPUT_OPTIONS
    JMP     RENDER_INPUT_BUFFER
@ %def SETUP_INPUT
@ [[DRAW_INPUT_OPTIONS]] iterates through all menu options in reverse order
(from the count stored in byte~0 of the menu descriptor down to~1).  For each
option, it calls [[CALC_RECORD_PTR]] to locate the option's data record, checks
whether byte~0 of the record is non-zero (enabled), and if so copies the
record's display data into the input buffer with [[COPY_RECORD_DATA]].

<<defines>>=
INPUT_OPTION_COUNT EQU  $5AAA   ; number of input options to draw
@ %def INPUT_OPTION_COUNT

<<draw input options>>=
    ORG     $5F70
DRAW_INPUT_OPTIONS:
    SUBROUTINE DRAW_INPUT_OPTIONS
    LDY     #$00
    LDA     ($C0),Y
    STA     INPUT_OPTION_COUNT
.loop:
    LDA     INPUT_OPTION_COUNT
    JSR     CALC_RECORD_PTR
    LDY     #$00
    LDA     ($C2),Y
    BEQ     .skip
    JSR     COPY_RECORD_DATA
.skip:
    DEC     INPUT_OPTION_COUNT
    BNE     .loop
    RTS
@ %def DRAW_INPUT_OPTIONS
@ [[CALC_RECORD_PTR]] translates a 1-based option index in~A to a pointer to
that option's 10-byte record.  The formula is [[$C2/$C3]] =
[[$C0/$C1]] + A$\times$10 $-$ 6, which accounts for the 4-byte table
header (so option~1 maps to the first record after the header).  The
resulting pointer in [[$C2/$C3]] is used by [[SETUP_CURSOR]],
[[VALIDATE_INPUT]], and other input routines to access the selected option's
data.

<<calc record ptr>>=
    ORG     $5F8C
    SUBROUTINE CALC_RECORD_PTR
; $C2/$C3 = $C0/$C1 + A*10 - 6
CALC_RECORD_PTR:
    ASL
    STA     $BA
    ASL
    ASL
    CLC
    ADC     $BA
    ADC     #$FA
    CLC
    ADC     $C0
    STA     $C2
    LDA     $C1
    ADC     #$00
    STA     $C3
    RTS
@ %def CALC_RECORD_PTR
@ [[SETUP_CURSOR_EXT]] extends [[SETUP_CURSOR]] by first calling
[[SET_INVERSE_VIDEO]] to enable inverse-video mode, then falling through into
[[SETUP_CURSOR]].  This highlights the currently selected menu option.

<<setup cursor ext>>=
    ORG     $5FA2
    SUBROUTINE SETUP_CURSOR_EXT
; JSR SET_INVERSE_VIDEO then falls through to SETUP_CURSOR
SETUP_CURSOR_EXT:
    JSR     SET_INVERSE_VIDEO
@ %def SETUP_CURSOR_EXT
@ [[SETUP_CURSOR]] positions the cursor at the location specified by the
current option record, sends HRCG control codes A/B via [[PRINT_CTRL_AB]]
to enter character output mode, loads the option's display string pointer
from bytes~6--7 of the record at [[$C2]], prints it with
[[PRINT_STRING]], and finishes with ctrl-N to restore normal video.

<<setup cursor>>=
    ORG     $5FA5
    SUBROUTINE SETUP_CURSOR
; Sets up cursor: calls $5FBC, positions, loads ptr from ($C2)+6/7, prints
SETUP_CURSOR:
    JSR     SET_CURSOR_POS
    JSR     PRINT_CTRL_AB
    LDWIY    $C2,#$06,PRINT_STRING_ADDR
    JSR     PRINT_STRING
    JMP     PRINT_CTRL_N
@ %def SETUP_CURSOR
@ [[SET_CURSOR_POS]] converts the linear position stored in byte~1 of the
option record at [[$C2]] into screen coordinates.  Positions 0--39 map to
row~21, 40--79 to row~22, and 80+ to row~23.  The column within each row is
the remainder after subtracting the row offset.  The result is written to
the Apple~II cursor position bytes [[$24]] (HTAB) and [[$25]] (VTAB).

<<set cursor pos>>=
    ORG     $5FBC
    SUBROUTINE SET_CURSOR_POS
; Maps linear position at ($C2)+1 to VTAB ($25) and HTAB ($24)
; Positions 0-39 -> row 21, 40-79 -> row 22, 80+ -> row 23
SET_CURSOR_POS:
    LDY     #$01
    LDA     ($C2),Y
    BAGE    #$28,.row2
    LDY     #$15 ; row 21
    BNE     .set_pos
.row2:
    SEC
    SBC     #$28
    BAGE    #$28,.row3
    LDY     #$16 ; row 22
    BNE     .set_pos
.row3:
    LDY     #$17 ; row 23
    SEC
    SBC     #$28
.set_pos:
    STY     $25
    STA     $24
    RTS
@ %def SET_CURSOR_POS
@ [[VALIDATE_INPUT]] saves the current record pointer and repeatedly calls
[[READ_INPUT_CHAR]] until a valid (enabled) option is found.  For each
candidate, it calls [[CALC_RECORD_PTR]] and checks byte~0 of the record:
if non-zero, the option is valid and its index is returned in~A.  Zero or
the current selection are returned directly (indicating ``no change'' or
``same selection'').  The saved [[$C2/$C3]] pointer is restored before
returning so the caller's record context is preserved.

<<validate input>>=
    ORG     $5FDD
    SUBROUTINE VALIDATE_INPUT
; Validates input: saves $C2/$C3, loops reading input until valid record found
VALIDATE_INPUT:
    STA     $5B24
    PSHW    $C2 ; save $C2/$C3
.retry:
    JSR     READ_INPUT_CHAR
    BAEQ    #$00,.done
    BAEQ    CURRENT_SELECTION,.done
    PHA
    JSR     CALC_RECORD_PTR
    LDY     #$00
    LDA     ($C2),Y
    BNE     .found
    PLA
    JMP     .retry
.found:
    PLA
.done:
    TAY
    PULW    $C2 ; restore $C2/$C3
    TYA
    RTS
@ %def VALIDATE_INPUT
@ [[READ_INPUT_CHAR]] reads a character code from the option record by
indexing into the record at [[$C2]] using the offset stored at~\$5B24 plus~1.
This returns the key code that would select the option one position after the
stored offset, used by [[VALIDATE_INPUT]] to scan through valid inputs.

<<read input char>>=
    ORG     $600A
    SUBROUTINE READ_INPUT_CHAR
; Returns character at ($C2) + $5B24 + 1
READ_INPUT_CHAR:
    CLC
    LDA     $5B24
    ADC     #$01
    TAY
    LDA     ($C2),Y
    RTS
@ %def READ_INPUT_CHAR
@ [[CALL_INPUT_INIT]] reads the initialization routine address from bytes~2--3
of the menu descriptor at [[$C0]] and executes it via an indirect jump through
[[INPUT_JMP_VEC]].  This allows each menu to run custom setup code---for
example, enabling or disabling options based on the current game state---before
the input loop begins.


<<call input init>>=
    ORG     $6014
CALL_INPUT_INIT:
    SUBROUTINE CALL_INPUT_INIT
    LDWIY    $C0,#$02,INPUT_JMP_VEC
    JMP     (INPUT_JMP_VEC)
@ %def CALL_INPUT_INIT
@ [[CLEAR_INPUT_BUFFER]] fills the 120-byte input display buffer
([[INPUT_BUFFER]] through [[INPUT_BUFFER]]+\$77) with high-bit spaces (\$A0).
This provides a clean slate before menu options are drawn into the buffer.

<<defines>>=
INPUT_BUFFER    EQU     $5AAC   ; 120-byte input text display buffer
@ %def INPUT_BUFFER

<<clear input buffer>>=
    ORG     $6024
CLEAR_INPUT_BUFFER:
    SUBROUTINE CLEAR_INPUT_BUFFER
    LDY     #$77
    LDA     #$A0
.loop:
    STA     INPUT_BUFFER,Y
    DEY
    BPL     .loop
    RTS
@ %def CLEAR_INPUT_BUFFER
@ [[RENDER_INPUT_BUFFER]] copies the 120-byte input display buffer to the
screen.  It positions the cursor at row~\$15 (21), column~0, issues a ctrl-A/B
sequence via [[PRINT_CTRL_AB]] to configure HRCG display mode, then outputs
each byte of the buffer through [[ROM_COUT1]].  The Y~register serves as the
loop index and is saved/restored around each COUT call (since COUT may clobber
it).

<<render input buffer>>=
    ORG     $602F
RENDER_INPUT_BUFFER:
    SUBROUTINE RENDER_INPUT_BUFFER
    STOW2    $1500,$24
    JSR     PRINT_CTRL_AB
    LDY     #$00
.loop:
    LDA     INPUT_BUFFER,Y
    STY     $BA
    JSR     ROM_COUT1
    LDY     $BA
    INY
    BYNE    #$78,.loop
    RTS
@ %def RENDER_INPUT_BUFFER
@ [[COPY_RECORD_DATA]] copies an option's display string into the input
display buffer.  It loads the string pointer from bytes~6--7 of the record
at [[$C2]], reads the string length from byte~0 of the string, uses byte~1
of the record as a column offset, and copies the string's characters into
[[INPUT_BUFFER]] at the computed position.  The copy runs backwards (from
last character to first) to avoid needing a separate length counter.

<<copy record data>>=
    ORG     $604C
    SUBROUTINE COPY_RECORD_DATA
; Copies data from pointer at ($C2)+6/7 into INPUT_BUFFER
COPY_RECORD_DATA:
    LDWIY    $C2,#$06,PRINT_STRING_ADDR
    LDY     #$01
    LDA     ($C2),Y
    STA     $BA
    DEY
    LDA     (PRINT_STRING_ADDR),Y
    TAY
    DEC     $BA
    CLC
    ADC     $BA
    TAX
.copy_loop:
    LDA     (PRINT_STRING_ADDR),Y
    STA     INPUT_BUFFER,X
    DEX
    DEY
    BNE     .copy_loop
    RTS
@ %def COPY_RECORD_DATA
@ [[GAME_INPUT_TABLE]] is the 74-byte data block at~\$607D that defines the
player's main action menu.  It has a 4-byte header (option count, max movement
range, and a pointer to [[CONFIGURE_INPUT]] as the initialization routine)
followed by seven 10-byte option records.  Each record contains an enable flag
(byte~0, patched at runtime by [[CONFIGURE_INPUT]]), a column offset (byte~1),
a key code (byte~2), a display string pointer (bytes~6--7), and an exit
handler address (bytes~8--9).  The seven options correspond to movement,
two combat choices, flee, and three additional actions (one of which is rest).

<<defines>>=
SAFE_TO_REST    EQU     $5B26   ; 1 if no adjacent threats or encounters
UNDER_LEVEL     EQU     $5B25   ; 1 if char level < steps taken
@ %def SAFE_TO_REST UNDER_LEVEL

<<game input table>>=
    ORG     $607D
; Game input option table (7 records x 10 bytes + 4-byte header).
; Record format: [enable, col_offset, key, ?, ?, ?, str_ptr_lo, str_ptr_hi, ?, ?]
; Byte 0 of records 1-6 is patched by CONFIGURE_INPUT based on combat state.
; Header: option count, max_range (patched), init_ptr lo/hi
GAME_INPUT_TABLE:
.header:
    HEX 07   ; 7 options
.max_range = *
    HEX 03   ; max movement range (patched: UNDER_LEVEL*3+3)
    HEX D260 ; init function pointer ($60D2 = CONFIGURE_INPUT)
.rec1:                  ; record 1 ($6081) - movement
.rec1_enable = *
    HEX 01   ; enable (patched: MOVE_POINTS or 0)
    HEX 07040207
    HEX 05537D311A
.rec2:                  ; record 2 ($608B) - combat option
.rec2_enable = *
    HEX 01   ; enable (patched: ~UNDER_LEVEL)
    HEX 2F0103
    HEX 05063E7D0761
.rec3:                  ; record 3 ($6095) - combat option
.rec3_enable = *
    HEX 01   ; enable (patched: ~UNDER_LEVEL)
    HEX 570204
    HEX 0604787BB714
.rec4:                  ; record 4 ($609F) - flee option
.rec4_enable = *
    HEX 01   ; enable (patched: UNDER_LEVEL)
    HEX 570301
    HEX 03077F7BC61B
.rec5:                  ; record 5 ($60A9)
    HEX 01140706
    HEX 0102457D8C61
.rec6:                  ; record 6 ($60B3) - rest option
.rec6_enable = *
    HEX 01   ; enable (patched: SAFE_TO_REST)
    HEX 3C0507
    HEX 0203737B3F14
.rec7:                  ; record 7 ($60BD)
    HEX 01640605
    HEX 0401667B0161
@ %def GAME_INPUT_TABLE
@ [[TEARDOWN_INPUT]] bridges the turn system and the input system: it calls
[[GET_INPUT_TABLE_PTR]] to load the default game input table pointer, then
jumps to [[INPUT_LOOP]] to present the player with the standard action menu.
This is the entry point used by [[TURN_DISPATCH]] when the current character
is under player control.

<<teardown input>>=
    ORG     $60C7
TEARDOWN_INPUT:
    SUBROUTINE TEARDOWN_INPUT
    ; Teardown input and jump to $5F19.
    JSR     GET_INPUT_TABLE_PTR
    JMP     INPUT_LOOP
@ %def TEARDOWN_INPUT
@ [[GET_INPUT_TABLE_PTR]] simply returns the address of the game's main input
table in X (high byte~\$60) and Y (low byte~\$7D).  Callers pass these
registers to [[SETUP_INPUT]] to initialize the standard action menu.

<<get input table ptr>>=
    ORG     $60CD
GET_INPUT_TABLE_PTR:
    SUBROUTINE GET_INPUT_TABLE_PTR
    ; Return X=$60, Y=$7D (pointer to input table).
    LDX     #$60
    LDY     #$7D
    RTS
@ %def GET_INPUT_TABLE_PTR
@ [[CONFIGURE_INPUT]] patches the game's main input table to enable or disable
menu options based on the current turn state.  It first calls
[[CHECK_COMBAT_ELIGIBILITY]], then writes the values of [[SAFE_TO_REST]],
[[UNDER_LEVEL]], [[MOVE_POINTS]], and [[TURN_ACTIVE]] into specific byte
offsets within [[GAME_INPUT_TABLE]].  The logic is straightforward: if the
character has an active encounter ([[UNDER_LEVEL]] is set), the combat options
(records~2 and~3) are enabled and the flee option (record~4) is disabled;
otherwise the reverse.  The maximum movement range in the table is set to~3
or~4 depending on the encounter state.  If [[TURN_ACTIVE]] is zero, the
movement option (record~1) is also disabled.

<<configure input>>=
    ORG     $60D2
CONFIGURE_INPUT:
    SUBROUTINE CONFIGURE_INPUT
    ; Configure input handler: patch game input table enable flags
    ; from UNDER_LEVEL/SAFE_TO_REST/MOVE_POINTS/TURN_ACTIVE.
    JSR     CHECK_COMBAT_ELIGIBILITY
    MOVB    SAFE_TO_REST,GAME_INPUT_TABLE+54 ; rec6 byte 0 (rest option)
    MOVB    UNDER_LEVEL,GAME_INPUT_TABLE+34 ; rec4 byte 0 (flee option)
    EOR     #$01
    STA     GAME_INPUT_TABLE+14 ; rec2 byte 0 (combat option)
    STA     GAME_INPUT_TABLE+24 ; rec3 byte 0 (combat option)
    EOR     #$01
    CLC
    ADC     #$03
    STA     GAME_INPUT_TABLE+1  ; max movement range
    MOVB    MOVE_POINTS,GAME_INPUT_TABLE+4 ; rec1 byte 0 (movement)
    LDA     TURN_ACTIVE
    BEQ     .clear
    RTS
.clear:
    STA     GAME_INPUT_TABLE+4  ; rec1 byte 0 (movement)
    RTS
@ %def CONFIGURE_INPUT

\subsection{Menu handler routines (\$6101--\$62E4)}

The main game menu at [[GAME_INPUT_TABLE]] dispatches to sub-menus and
actions throughout the \$6101--\$62E4 region.  Each sub-menu has a
descriptor table (same format as [[GAME_INPUT_TABLE]]: 4-byte header
followed by 10-byte records) and a small code entry point that loads
the table address into X/Y and jumps to [[INPUT_LOOP]].

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{clll}
\hline
\textbf{Table} & \textbf{Entry} & \textbf{Menu} & \textbf{Options} \\
\hline
\$607D & \$60C7 & Main actions & Move, Attack, Defend, Stop, Other, Rest, See Your Lot \\
\$610F & \$6145 & Attack direction & Defend, Attack Left/Above/Right/Below \\
\$614C & \$618C & Other options & Move, Drop Gold/Armor, Retire, Add Someone, more... \\
\$6193 & \$61F6 & Game settings & Move, Game Speed, Sound, Danger, Save Game \\
\$623F & \$6261 & Attack target & Attack [target], Someone Else, Cancel \\
\$626C & \$62A2 & Drop gold & Ducats to Drop, Drop Gold, Keep All Gold \\
\$62B9 & --- & Save/load & Begin New Game, Continue Game Number \\
\hline
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

@ ``See Your Lot'' (\$6101) shows the character stats screen, then returns to
the main menu.  ``Attack'' (\$6107) checks eligibility via [[$1564]], then
either enters the attack direction menu or exits.

<<menu handlers>>=
    ORG     $6101
MENU_SEE_YOUR_LOT:
    JSR     DISPLAY_CHAR_STATS ; show character stats
    JMP     TEARDOWN_INPUT     ; return to main menu

MENU_CHECK_ATTACK:
    JSR     CHECK_ATTACK_ELIGIBLE ; check for hostile at same position
    BCC     ENTER_ATTACK_MENU  ; no hostile here -> choose direction
    JMP     FIND_ATTACK_TARGET ; hostile here -> target directly
@ %def MENU_SEE_YOUR_LOT MENU_CHECK_ATTACK

@ The attack direction menu at [[$610F]].

<<attack direction table>>=
    ORG     $610F
ATTACK_DIR_TABLE:
    ; 5 options, max_range=1, init=$626B
    HEX     05 01 6B 62
    ; rec0: DEFEND
    HEX     01 39 03 05 02 04
    DC.W    $7B78              ; "DEFEND"
    DC.W    ENTER_COMBAT_STATE
    ; rec1: LEFT
    HEX     01 29 03 05 04 01
    DC.W    $7C6A              ; left arrow
    DC.W    ATTACK_LEFT
    ; rec2: ABOVE
    HEX     01 0C 05 01 02 04
    DC.W    $7C59              ; up arrow
    DC.W    ATTACK_UP
    ; rec3: RIGHT
    HEX     01 44 03 05 01 02
    DC.W    $7C76              ; right arrow
    DC.W    ATTACK_RIGHT
    ; rec4: BELOW
    HEX     01 5C 01 03 02 04
    DC.W    $7C83              ; down arrow
    DC.W    ATTACK_DOWN

    ; --- enter attack (target of BCC from MENU_CHECK_ATTACK) ---
ENTER_ATTACK_MENU:
    LDX     #>ATTACK_DIR_TABLE ; X = high byte
    LDY     #<ATTACK_DIR_TABLE ; Y = low byte
    JMP     INPUT_LOOP
@ %def ATTACK_DIR_TABLE ENTER_ATTACK_MENU
@ The ``Other Options'' sub-menu at [[$614C]].  Record~5 (``Other
Options'') chains to the game settings menu via [[$61F1]].

<<other options table>>=
    ORG     $614C
OTHER_OPTIONS_TABLE:
    ; 6 options, max_range=1, init=$626B
    HEX     06 01 6B 62
    ; rec0: MOVE       rec1: DROP GOLD   rec2: DROP ARMOR
    ; rec3: OTHER OPT  rec4: RETIRE      rec5: ADD SOMEONE
    HEX     01 05 03 02 06 04 53 7D 31 1A
    HEX     01 2D 01 03 04 05 FA 7A 17 6F
    HEX     01 55 02 01 05 06 DC 7A E9 6E
    HEX     01 15 06 05 01 02 45 7D F1 61
    HEX     01 3D 04 06 02 03 E7 7A E7 09
    ; rec5: ADD SOMEONE
    HEX     01 65 05 04 03 01
    DC.W    $7AEE              ; "ADD SOMEONE"
    DC.W    CHAR_SELECT_INIT
@ %def OTHER_OPTIONS_TABLE

<<other options entry>>=
    ORG     $618C
MENU_OTHER_OPTIONS:
    LDX     #>OTHER_OPTIONS_TABLE
    LDY     #<OTHER_OPTIONS_TABLE
    JMP     INPUT_LOOP
@ %def MENU_OTHER_OPTIONS

@ The game settings menu at [[$6193]].  This includes game speed
adjustment (records~1--3 with arrow keys), sound toggle, danger level
(records~5--7), and save game.  The ``game settings'' entry at [[$61F1]]
is an indirect jump through [[$A963]], a resident vector.  [[$61F6]] is
the direct entry that loads the settings table and enters [[INPUT_LOOP]].
[[$61FD]] initializes the settings display: it calls the splash routine
at [[SETTINGS_DISPLAY_INIT]] ([[$09AC]]), then formats the current game speed (\$7ABD) as a digit
into the ``GAME SPEED'' label string at [[$7D66]].

<<game settings table>>=
    ORG     $6193
GAME_SETTINGS_TABLE:
    ; 9 options, max_range=1, init=$61FD
    ; header: 9 options, max_range=1, init=MENU_SETTINGS_INIT
    DC.B    $09,$01
    DC.W    MENU_SETTINGS_INIT
    ; rec0: MOVE             rec1: GAME SPEED      rec2: # (speed up)
    ; rec3: @ (speed down)   rec4: SOUND IS ON      rec5: DANGER :
    ; rec6: # (danger up)    rec7: @ (danger down)  rec8: SAVE GAME
    HEX     01 03 05 09 08 03 53 7D 31 1A
    HEX     01 13 00 00 00 00 58 7D 6B 62
    HEX     01 23 07 07 01 04 60 7B 09 62
    HEX     01 25 08 08 03 09 62 7B 20 62
    HEX     01 53 09 01 09 07 04 7B 84 09
    HEX     01 66 00 00 00 00 1B 7B 6B 62
    HEX     01 73 03 03 05 08 60 7B 2D 62
    HEX     01 75 04 04 07 01 62 7B 36 62
    ; rec8: SAVE GAME
    HEX     01 2B 01 05 04 05
    DC.W    $7B11              ; "SAVE GAME"
    DC.W    ENTER_SAVE_GAME_SLOT
@ %def GAME_SETTINGS_TABLE

<<game settings entry>>=
    ORG     $61F1
MENU_GAME_SETTINGS:
    SUBROUTINE MENU_GAME_SETTINGS
    LDA     #$01
    STA     GAME_SETTINGS_TABLE+1 ; patch max_range = 1
MENU_GAME_SETTINGS_ENTER:
    LDX     #>GAME_SETTINGS_TABLE
    LDY     #<GAME_SETTINGS_TABLE
    JMP     INPUT_LOOP

MENU_SETTINGS_INIT:
    JSR     $09AC              ; splash screen setup
    LDA     $7ABD              ; game speed value
    ORA     #$B0               ; convert to ASCII digit
    STA     $7D66              ; patch into "GAME SPEED : X" string
    RTS
@ %def MENU_GAME_SETTINGS MENU_SETTINGS_INIT

@ The settings adjustment handlers increment or decrement the game speed
([[$7ABD]]) and danger threshold, then re-enter the settings menu.
[[$7ABC]] is the maximum game speed.

<<settings handlers>>=
    ORG     $6209
SETTINGS_SPEED_UP:
    SUBROUTINE SETTINGS_SPEED_UP
    JSR     $6071              ; patch menu record
    INC     $7ABD              ; speed++
    LDA     $7ABD
    CMP     $7ABC              ; at max?
    BCC     .done
    LDA     $7ABC              ; clamp to max
    STA     $7ABD
.done:
    JMP     MENU_GAME_SETTINGS_ENTER ; re-enter settings menu

SETTINGS_SPEED_DOWN:
    JSR     $6071              ; patch menu record
    DEC     $7ABD              ; speed--
    BNE     .done              ; nonzero -> ok
    INC     $7ABD              ; clamp to 1
    BNE     .done              ; (always taken)

SETTINGS_DANGER_UP:
    JSR     $6071              ; patch menu record
    JSR     $09CF              ; increment danger threshold
    JMP     MENU_GAME_SETTINGS_ENTER

SETTINGS_DANGER_DOWN:
    JSR     $6071              ; patch menu record
    JSR     $09CB              ; decrement danger threshold
    JMP     MENU_GAME_SETTINGS_ENTER
@ %def SETTINGS_SPEED_UP SETTINGS_SPEED_DOWN SETTINGS_DANGER_UP SETTINGS_DANGER_DOWN

@ The attack target menu at [[$623F]].

<<attack target table>>=
    ORG     $623F
ATTACK_TARGET_TABLE:
    ; 3 options, max_range=2, init=MENU_ATTACK_INIT
    HEX     03 02
    DC.W    MENU_ATTACK_INIT
    ; rec0: ATTACK [target]
    HEX     01 06 03 02 00 00
    DC.W    $7C94              ; "ATTACK" + name buffer
    DC.W    RESOLVE_ATTACK
