@ \section{Save/Load Disk I/O}

\subsection{Disk I/O data (\$7AC5--\$7ACF)}

The save/load system uses a block of configuration data in the menu
option strings area.  [[GAME_DISK_SLOTS]] determines how many save
slots fit on the game disk itself (just~1); higher-numbered slots
require a separate scenario disk.  [[SAVE_TRACK_BASE]] is a two-byte
table of base track numbers indexed by disk (0=game disk at track~\$13,
1=scenario disk at track~\$01).  Each slot occupies two tracks (26
sectors at 13~sectors per track).

[[SAVE_SECTOR_COUNT]] is the number of sectors per save game (26).
[[GAME_SIG_TRACK]] and [[GAME_SIG_SECTOR]] specify where the game disk
signature lives (track~\$11, sector~\$00).  [[DISK_SIGNATURE]] is the
3-byte ``ALI'' signature (high ASCII \$C1,\$CC,\$C9) used to identify
valid scenario disks.  [[SHUFFLE_COUNT]] controls how many iterations
the entity-shuffle routine performs (100).

<<defines>>=
GAME_DISK_SLOTS     EQU     $7AC5   ; save slots on game disk (1)
SAVE_TRACK_BASE     EQU     $7AC7   ; base track table: [0]=game disk, [1]=scenario disk
SAVE_SECTOR_COUNT   EQU     $7AC9   ; sectors per save game (26)
GAME_SIG_TRACK      EQU     $7ACA   ; game disk signature track ($11)
GAME_SIG_SECTOR     EQU     $7ACB   ; game disk signature sector ($00)
DISK_SIGNATURE      EQU     $7ACC   ; 3-byte "ALI" signature (high ASCII)
SHUFFLE_COUNT       EQU     $7ACF   ; entity shuffle iterations (100)
@ %def GAME_DISK_SLOTS SAVE_TRACK_BASE SAVE_SECTOR_COUNT GAME_SIG_TRACK GAME_SIG_SECTOR DISK_SIGNATURE SHUFFLE_COUNT

@ \subsection{Continue game handler (\$69C8--\$69FC)}

[[CONTINUE_GAME]] is the handler for the ``CONTINUE'' option in the
save/load menu ([[SAVE_LOAD_TABLE]]).
\begin{itemize}
\item If [[SLOT_NUMBER]] is below [[GAME_DISK_SLOTS]] (i.e.\ slot~0 on
  the game disk), it calls [[ENSURE_GAME_DISK]] to verify the game
  disk, then jumps to [[READ_GAME_DATA]] to load the save.
\item Otherwise the save is on a scenario disk.  It displays message~\$33
  (insert scenario disk prompt), waits for a keypress, then calls
  [[VERIFY_DISK_SIGNATURE]] to check the disk has the ``ALI'' signature.
  If valid, it reads the save and writes it back to the game disk via
  [[ENSURE_GAME_DISK]].  If invalid, it displays message~\$16 (error)
  and returns to [[INIT_WORLD]].
\end{itemize}

<<continue game>>=
    ORG     $69C8
CONTINUE_GAME:
    SUBROUTINE CONTINUE_GAME
    LDA     SLOT_NUMBER
    CMP     GAME_DISK_SLOTS
    BCS     .scenario          ; slot >= 1 -> scenario disk needed
    JSR     ENSURE_GAME_DISK   ; verify game disk
    JMP     READ_GAME_DATA     ; load save from game disk

.scenario:
    JSR     SET_CURSOR_ROW21
    LDA     #MSG_INSERT_SCENARIO               ; "INSERT SCENARIO DISK"
    JSR     DISPLAY_MESSAGE
    JSR     WAIT_KEYPRESS      ; wait for user
    JSR     VERIFY_DISK_SIGNATURE ; check "ALI" signature
    BCS     .bad_disk          ; carry set -> signature mismatch
    JSR     READ_GAME_DATA     ; load from scenario disk
    JSR     PROMPT_INSERT_DISK ; "INSERT GAME DISK"
    JMP     ENSURE_GAME_DISK   ; re-verify game disk

.bad_disk:
    JSR     SET_CURSOR_ROW21
    LDA     #MSG_TOUGH_HIDE               ; error message
    JSR     DISPLAY_MESSAGE
    JSR     ENSURE_GAME_DISK
    JMP     INIT_WORLD         ; back to save/load menu
@ %def CONTINUE_GAME

@ \subsection{Shuffle entities (\$69FD--\$6A46)}

[[SHUFFLE_ENTITIES]] randomly reorders the entity linked list by
performing [[SHUFFLE_COUNT]] (100) iterations of a pick-and-relink
algorithm.  Each iteration:
\begin{itemize}
\item Picks a random position (0--63) in the list via [[RANDOM_IN_RANGE]].
\item Walks that many links forward from the list head at~\$4000.
\item Unlinks the reached node and re-appends it at the end of the chain.
\end{itemize}
This effectively shuffles entity ordering so that saved games do not
preserve a deterministic entity sequence.

<<shuffle entities>>=
    ORG     $69FD
SHUFFLE_ENTITIES:
    SUBROUTINE SHUFFLE_ENTITIES
    DEC     SHUFFLE_COUNT
    BPL     .go
    RTS

.go:
    LDA     #$3F               ; random 0-63
    JSR     RANDOM_IN_RANGE
    STA     $5AA5              ; temp: walk count
    LDA     #$00               ; \ $BA/$BB = $4000 (list head)
    STA     $BA                ;  |
    LDA     #$40               ;  |
    STA     $BB                ; /

.walk:
    LDA     $BA                ; \ copy $BA/$BB -> $BE/$BF
    STA     $BE                ;  | (previous pointer)
    LDA     $BB                ;  |
    STA     $BF                ; /
    LDY     #$02
    LDA     ($BE),Y            ; get next-pointer (byte 2)
    STA     CURRENT_ROOM       ; temp: save next-pointer
    JSR     GET_MOB_DATA       ; advance $BA/$BB to next record
    DEC     $5AA5              ; decrement walk count
    BPL     .walk              ; loop until count exhausted

    ; Unlink: splice current node out of chain
    LDY     #$02
    LDA     ($BA),Y            ; source's next-pointer
    STA     ($BE),Y            ; patch previous to skip source
    LDA     #$00
    STA     ($BA),Y            ; clear source's next-pointer

    ; Re-append: walk to end of chain, link source there
    LDA     ($BE),Y            ; follow chain from previous
.find_end:
    JSR     GET_MOB_DATA       ; advance
    LDY     #$02
    LDA     ($BA),Y
    BNE     .find_end          ; loop until next = 0 (end of list)

    LDA     CURRENT_ROOM       ; restore saved next-pointer
    STA     ($BA),Y            ; link source at end
    JMP     SHUFFLE_ENTITIES   ; next iteration
@ %def SHUFFLE_ENTITIES

@ \subsection{Save game handler (\$6A47--\$6A6D)}

[[SAVE_GAME]] is the handler for the ``SAVE GAME IN SLOT NUMBER NN''
option in the save game slot menu.
\begin{itemize}
\item If [[SLOT_NUMBER]] is below [[GAME_DISK_SLOTS]], it saves directly
  to the game disk via [[WRITE_GAME_DATA]], then returns to [[MOVE_LOOP]].
\item Otherwise, it checks the self-modifying flag at [[$6A58]]
  ([[SCENARIO_INIT_FLAG]]).  On first use, it calls [[ENSURE_GAME_DISK]]
  and enters scene~\$42 (the scenario disk prompt scene), then sets the
  flag.  Subsequent calls jump directly to [[ENTER_SCENARIO_DISK]].
\end{itemize}

<<defines>>=
SCENARIO_INIT_FLAG  EQU     $6A58   ; self-modifying: 0=first scenario save, 1=initialized
@ %def SCENARIO_INIT_FLAG

<<save game>>=
    ORG     $6A47
SAVE_GAME:
    SUBROUTINE SAVE_GAME
    LDA     SLOT_NUMBER
    CMP     GAME_DISK_SLOTS
    BCS     .scenario          ; slot >= 1 -> scenario disk
    JSR     ENSURE_GAME_DISK
    JSR     WRITE_GAME_DATA
    JMP     MOVE_LOOP

    DC.B    $00                ; SCENARIO_INIT_FLAG ($6A58)

.scenario:
    LDA     SCENARIO_INIT_FLAG
    BNE     .already_init      ; flag set -> skip scene
    JSR     ENSURE_GAME_DISK
    LDA     #$42               ; scene $42: scenario disk prompt
    JSR     SCENE_LOOP
    LDA     #$01
    STA     SCENARIO_INIT_FLAG ; set flag (self-modifying)
.already_init:
    JMP     ENTER_SCENARIO_DISK
@ %def SAVE_GAME

@ \subsection{Scenario disk handlers (\$6A6E--\$6AB6)}

[[CANCEL_SCENARIO]] cancels the scenario disk menu and returns to
[[MOVE_LOOP]] after verifying the game disk.

[[SCENARIO_INSERT_PROMPT]] displays message~\$33 (insert scenario disk)
and re-enters the scenario disk menu.

[[FORMAT_SCENARIO_DISK]] formats a new scenario disk:
\begin{itemize}
\item Calls [[VERIFY_GAME_DISK]] to confirm the inserted disk.
  If invalid, prompts and re-enters the scenario menu.
\item Verifies the ``ALI'' signature via [[VERIFY_DISK_SIGNATURE]].
  If the disk already has saved data, prompts with [[FORMAT_DISK_TRACK]].
\item If the signature check indicates a blank disk, writes the signature
  via [[WRITE_DISK_SIGNATURE]], then falls through to write game data.
\item On success, displays message~\$1B (confirmation) and returns to
  [[MOVE_LOOP]].
\end{itemize}

[[USE_SCENARIO_DISK]] uses a previously formatted scenario disk:
verifies the signature, and if valid, writes game data.  If invalid,
displays message~\$16 (error).

[[DISPLAY_INSERT_MSG]] displays message~\$1B (``INSERT SCENARIO DISK''
or similar confirmation).

<<scenario disk handlers>>=
    ORG     $6A6E
CANCEL_SCENARIO:
    JSR     ENSURE_GAME_DISK
    JMP     MOVE_LOOP

SCENARIO_INSERT_PROMPT:
    JSR     SET_CURSOR_ROW21
    LDA     #MSG_INSERT_SCENARIO               ; "INSERT SCENARIO DISK"
    JSR     DISPLAY_MESSAGE
    JMP     ENTER_SCENARIO_DISK

FORMAT_SCENARIO_DISK:
    SUBROUTINE FORMAT_SCENARIO_DISK
    JSR     VERIFY_GAME_DISK   ; check game disk inserted
    BCC     SCENARIO_INSERT_PROMPT ; not game disk -> prompt
    JSR     VERIFY_DISK_SIGNATURE ; check "ALI" signature
    BCC     .write             ; no signature -> blank disk, write
    JSR     FORMAT_DISK_TRACK  ; format the track
    BCC     .check_sig         ; format ok -> check signature
.show_msg:
    JSR     DISPLAY_INSERT_MSG ; display confirmation
.cleanup:
    JSR     PROMPT_INSERT_DISK ; "INSERT GAME DISK"
    JSR     ENSURE_GAME_DISK
    JMP     MOVE_LOOP

.check_sig:
    JSR     WRITE_DISK_SIGNATURE ; write "ALI" to disk
    BCS     .show_msg          ; carry set -> show insert msg, then cleanup
    BCC     .write             ; carry clear -> write data

USE_SCENARIO_DISK:
    JSR     VERIFY_DISK_SIGNATURE ; check "ALI" signature
    BCS     .sig_error         ; no match -> error
.write:
    JSR     WRITE_GAME_DATA    ; save game data to disk
    JMP     .cleanup

.sig_error:
    JSR     SET_CURSOR_ROW21
    LDA     #MSG_TOUGH_HIDE               ; error message
    JSR     DISPLAY_MESSAGE
    JMP     .cleanup

DISPLAY_INSERT_MSG:
    JSR     SET_CURSOR_ROW21
    LDA     #MSG_BREAKS_FREE               ; "INSERT" confirmation message
    JMP     DISPLAY_MESSAGE
@ %def CANCEL_SCENARIO SCENARIO_INSERT_PROMPT FORMAT_SCENARIO_DISK USE_SCENARIO_DISK DISPLAY_INSERT_MSG

@ \subsection{Game disk verification (\$6ABF--\$6AE0)}

[[ENSURE_GAME_DISK]] loops until the game disk is detected.  It calls
[[VERIFY_GAME_DISK]] and if carry is set (wrong disk), displays the
insert prompt and retries.

[[PROMPT_INSERT_DISK]] displays messages~\$03 and~\$30, then waits for
a keypress.

[[WAIT_KEYPRESS]] displays message~\$30 (``PRESS ANY KEY''), clears the
keyboard strobe, and polls until a key is pressed.

<<ensure game disk>>=
    ORG     $6ABF
ENSURE_GAME_DISK:
    JSR     VERIFY_GAME_DISK
    BCS     .wrong_disk
    RTS
.wrong_disk:
    JSR     PROMPT_INSERT_DISK
    JMP     ENSURE_GAME_DISK

PROMPT_INSERT_DISK:
    JSR     SET_CURSOR_ROW21
    LDA     #MSG_INSERT_GAME               ; "INSERT GAME DISK"
    JSR     DISPLAY_MESSAGE

WAIT_KEYPRESS:
    LDA     #MSG_PRESS_KEY               ; "PRESS ANY KEY"
    JSR     DISPLAY_MESSAGE
    STA     $C010              ; clear keyboard strobe
.wait:
    LDA     $C000              ; read keyboard
    BPL     .wait              ; loop until key pressed
    RTS
@ %def ENSURE_GAME_DISK PROMPT_INSERT_DISK WAIT_KEYPRESS

@ \subsection{Disk format and signature (\$6AE1--\$6B26)}

[[FORMAT_DISK_TRACK]] issues an RWTS format command (command~4) for
track~\$04 with 12~sectors.

[[WRITE_DISK_SIGNATURE]] writes the 3-byte ``ALI'' signature
([[DISK_SIGNATURE]]) to the disk via [[SETUP_DATA_IOB]].  It copies
the signature to [[SCENE_TEXT_DATA]], sets up the IOB, then calls
[[DISK_WRITE]] with up to~3 retries.  Returns carry clear on success.

[[VERIFY_DISK_SIGNATURE]] reads the disk and compares the first~3 bytes
against [[DISK_SIGNATURE]].  Returns carry clear if the signature
matches.

<<format and signature>>=
    ORG     $6AE1
FORMAT_DISK_TRACK:
    LDY     #$0C               ; \ RWTS format command
    LDA     #$04               ;  | command = 4 (format track)
    JMP     RWTS_DISPATCH      ; /

WRITE_DISK_SIGNATURE:
    SUBROUTINE WRITE_DISK_SIGNATURE
    LDA     #$02               ; retry counter
    STA     $BF
    LDX     #$02
.copy:
    LDA     DISK_SIGNATURE,X   ; copy "ALI" to buffer
    STA     SCENE_TEXT_DATA,X
    DEX
    BPL     .copy
    JSR     SETUP_DATA_IOB     ; set IOB buffer = $5C00
.retry:
    JSR     DISK_WRITE         ; write to disk
    BCS     .error
    RTS                        ; success (carry clear)
.error:
    DEC     $BF
    BPL     .retry
    SEC                        ; all retries failed
    RTS

VERIFY_DISK_SIGNATURE:
    SUBROUTINE VERIFY_DISK_SIGNATURE
    JSR     SETUP_DATA_IOB     ; set IOB buffer = $5C00
    LDA     #$02               ; retry counter
    STA     $BF
.retry:
    JSR     DISK_READ          ; read from disk
    BCC     .check             ; success -> verify bytes
    DEC     $BF
    BPL     .retry
.fail:
    SEC                        ; all retries failed / mismatch
    RTS
.check:
    LDX     #$02
.cmp:
    LDA     DISK_SIGNATURE,X   ; expected "ALI"
    CMP     SCENE_TEXT_DATA,X  ; actual
    BNE     .fail              ; mismatch -> fail immediately
    DEX
    BPL     .cmp
    CLC                        ; signature match
    RTS
@ %def FORMAT_DISK_TRACK WRITE_DISK_SIGNATURE VERIFY_DISK_SIGNATURE

@ \subsection{IOB setup and game disk check (\$6B27--\$6B71)}

[[SETUP_DATA_IOB]] configures the RWTS IOB for a single-sector
operation with the data buffer at [[SCENE_TEXT_DATA]] (\$5C00).
It clears the track/sector fields and sets the buffer pointer.

[[VERIFY_GAME_DISK]] reads the game disk at [[GAME_SIG_TRACK]]/
[[GAME_SIG_SECTOR]] and checks for the magic signature bytes
\$03,\$0F,\$10.  Returns carry clear if the game disk is present.

<<setup data iob>>=
    ORG     $6B27
SETUP_DATA_IOB:
    LDA     #$00
    LDY     #$04
    STA     (RWTS_IOB_PTR),Y   ; IOB+4 = track 0
    INY
    STA     (RWTS_IOB_PTR),Y   ; IOB+5 = sector 0
    LDA     #$00
    LDY     #$08
    STA     (RWTS_IOB_PTR),Y   ; IOB+8 = buffer lo ($00)
    INY
    LDA     #$5C
    STA     (RWTS_IOB_PTR),Y   ; IOB+9 = buffer hi ($5C -> $5C00)
    RTS

VERIFY_GAME_DISK:
    SUBROUTINE VERIFY_GAME_DISK
    JSR     SETUP_DATA_IOB
    LDA     GAME_SIG_TRACK     ; track $11
    LDY     #$04
    STA     (RWTS_IOB_PTR),Y   ; IOB+4 = track
    LDA     GAME_SIG_SECTOR    ; sector $00
    INY
    STA     (RWTS_IOB_PTR),Y   ; IOB+5 = sector
    LDA     #$02               ; retry counter
    STA     $BE
.retry:
    JSR     DISK_READ
    BCC     .check
    DEC     $BE
    BNE     .retry
.fail:
    SEC                        ; all retries failed / mismatch
    RTS
.check:
    LDA     SCENE_TEXT_DATA    ; byte 0
    CMP     #$03
    BNE     .fail
    LDA     SCENE_TEXT_DATA+1  ; byte 1
    CMP     #$0F
    BNE     .fail
    LDA     SCENE_TEXT_DATA+2  ; byte 2
    CMP     #$10
    BNE     .fail
    CLC                        ; game disk confirmed
    RTS
@ %def SETUP_DATA_IOB VERIFY_GAME_DISK

@ \subsection{Write game data (\$6B72--\$6B93)}

[[WRITE_GAME_DATA]] writes [[SAVE_SECTOR_COUNT]] (26) sectors of game
state from the \$4000 buffer to disk.  It calls [[SETUP_SLOT_IOB]] to
calculate the starting track/sector from [[SLOT_NUMBER]], then writes
each sector via [[DISK_WRITE]], calling [[ADVANCE_SECTOR]] to step
through consecutive sectors.  Returns A=0 on success, A=1 on failure.

<<write game data>>=
    ORG     $6B72
WRITE_GAME_DATA:
    SUBROUTINE WRITE_GAME_DATA
    LDA     #$02               ; outer retry counter
    STA     $BF
    JSR     SETUP_SLOT_IOB     ; calculate track from slot
    LDA     SAVE_SECTOR_COUNT  ; 26 sectors
    STA     $BE
.sector:
    JSR     DISK_WRITE
    BCS     .error
    JSR     ADVANCE_SECTOR
    DEC     $BE
    BNE     .sector
    LDA     #$00               ; success
    RTS
.error:
    DEC     $BF
    BNE     .sector            ; retry remaining sectors
    LDA     #$01               ; failure
    RTS
@ %def WRITE_GAME_DATA

@ \subsection{Read game data and IOB helpers (\$6B95--\$6C11)}

[[READ_GAME_DATA]] reads [[SAVE_SECTOR_COUNT]] (26) sectors of save
data from disk into the \$4000 buffer.  On persistent failure, it
displays message~\$3B and jumps to [[COLD_RESTART]] at [[$A56F]].

[[SETUP_SLOT_IOB]] calculates the disk track for a given slot:
\begin{itemize}
\item If [[SLOT_NUMBER]]~< [[GAME_DISK_SLOTS]], uses disk~0 (game disk)
  with base track from [[SAVE_TRACK_BASE]][0].
\item Otherwise, subtracts [[GAME_DISK_SLOTS]] and uses disk~1 (scenario
  disk) with base track from [[SAVE_TRACK_BASE]][1].
\item Track = base + slot $\times$ 2 (each slot spans 2~tracks).
\end{itemize}
Sets the IOB buffer to \$4000 and clears the byte-count field.

[[ADVANCE_SECTOR]] increments the buffer page (IOB+9) and sector
(IOB+5).  When the sector reaches~13 (\$0D), it wraps to~0 and
increments the track (IOB+4), starting the next track.

<<read game data>>=
    ORG     $6B95
READ_GAME_DATA:
    SUBROUTINE READ_GAME_DATA
    LDA     #$02               ; outer retry counter
    STA     $BF
    JSR     SETUP_SLOT_IOB
    LDA     SAVE_SECTOR_COUNT  ; 26 sectors
    STA     $BE
.sector:
    JSR     DISK_READ
    BCS     .error
    JSR     ADVANCE_SECTOR
    DEC     $BE
    BNE     .sector
    LDA     #$00               ; success
    RTS
.error:
    DEC     $BF
    BNE     .sector
    JSR     SET_CURSOR_ROW21
    LDA     #MSG_READ_ERROR               ; read error message
    JSR     DISPLAY_MESSAGE
    JMP     COLD_RESTART       ; fatal: reboot from disk

SETUP_SLOT_IOB:
    SUBROUTINE SETUP_SLOT_IOB
    LDX     #$00               ; disk index 0 (game disk)
    LDA     SLOT_NUMBER
    CMP     GAME_DISK_SLOTS
    BCC     .set_track         ; slot < threshold -> game disk
    SEC
    SBC     GAME_DISK_SLOTS    ; adjust for scenario disk
    INX                        ; disk index 1 (scenario disk)
.set_track:
    ASL                        ; slot * 2 (2 tracks per slot)
    CLC
    ADC     SAVE_TRACK_BASE,X  ; add base track for this disk
    LDY     #$04
    STA     (RWTS_IOB_PTR),Y   ; IOB+4 = track
    INY
    LDA     #$00
    STA     (RWTS_IOB_PTR),Y   ; IOB+5 = sector 0
    LDA     #$00
    LDY     #$08
    STA     (RWTS_IOB_PTR),Y   ; IOB+8 = buffer lo ($00)
    LDA     #$40
    INY
    STA     (RWTS_IOB_PTR),Y   ; IOB+9 = buffer hi ($40 -> $4000)
    LDA     #$00
    LDY     #$0B
    STA     (RWTS_IOB_PTR),Y   ; IOB+$0B = byte count (0 = 256)
    RTS

ADVANCE_SECTOR:
    SUBROUTINE ADVANCE_SECTOR
    LDY     #$09
    LDA     (RWTS_IOB_PTR),Y   ; buffer page
    TAX
    INX                        ; next page
    TXA
    STA     (RWTS_IOB_PTR),Y
    LDY     #$05
    LDA     (RWTS_IOB_PTR),Y   ; sector number
    TAX
    INX
    CPX     #$0D               ; 13 sectors per track
    BCS     .next_track
    TXA
    STA     (RWTS_IOB_PTR),Y   ; store incremented sector
    RTS
.next_track:
    LDA     #$00               ; sector = 0
    STA     (RWTS_IOB_PTR),Y
    DEY                        ; Y = 4 (track)
    LDA     (RWTS_IOB_PTR),Y
    TAX
    INX                        ; next track
    TXA
    STA     (RWTS_IOB_PTR),Y
    RTS
@ %def READ_GAME_DATA SETUP_SLOT_IOB ADVANCE_SECTOR

@ [[CHECK_COMBAT_ELIGIBILITY]] determines which turn options are available to
the current entity.  It clears [[SAFE_TO_REST]] and [[UNDER_LEVEL]], then
checks the entity's level (field~\$0C, bits~2--0 after ROR) against
[[STEPS_TAKEN]].  If the level is below the step count, [[UNDER_LEVEL]] is
set, which enables the flee menu option and disables combat options.  If
[[STEPS_TAKEN]] is zero, the routine performs a deeper check: it compares
offense (field~5) against defense (field~6), and if offense exceeds defense
and there are no adjacent threats or hostile encounters at the entity's
position, it sets [[SAFE_TO_REST]] to enable the rest option.

<<check combat eligibility>>=
    ORG     $750C
CHECK_COMBAT_ELIGIBILITY:
    SUBROUTINE CHECK_COMBAT_ELIGIBILITY
    STOB    #$00,SAFE_TO_REST
    STA     UNDER_LEVEL
    LDY     #$0C
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y
    ROR
    AND     #$07
    BAMI    STEPS_TAKEN,.under_level
    LDA     STEPS_TAKEN
    BNE     .done
    LDY     #$05
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y
    AND     #$1F
    STA     $BA
    INY
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y
    AND     #$3F
    BAPL    $BA,.done
    LDY     #$03
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y
    JSR     CHECK_ADJACENT_THREATS
    LDA     ADJACENT_THREAT
    BNE     .done
    LDY     #$03
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y
    JSR     CHECK_ENCOUNTER
    LDA     ENCOUNTER_RESULT
    BAEQ    #$02,.done
    STOB    #$01,SAFE_TO_REST
    JMP     .done
.under_level:
    STOB    #$01,UNDER_LEVEL
.done:
    RTS
@ %def CHECK_COMBAT_ELIGIBILITY

\chapter{Combat}


\section{Encounter detection}

Checks whether a given character (by char index in~[[A]]) is co-located
with a mob from an opposing faction.  Calls [[FIND_ENTITY_AT_POS]] to
resolve the character to a mob pointer, then walks the group chain via
[[FIND_MOB_AT_SAME_POS]] looking for another mob at the same map
position.  Candidate mobs must have byte~6 bits~5--0~$\ge3$ (active mob
type) and be from a different faction (checked via [[CHECK_HOSTILE]]).

Result stored in [[$5A1F]]:
\begin{itemize}
\item 0 --- no mob found at same position (or character is not a mob)
\item 1 --- found co-located mob but same faction (wrapped search)
\item 2 --- found co-located mob from opposing faction (enemy encounter)
\end{itemize}

Callers use the result to set or clear bit~2 of byte~\$0F of the
character's record, which appears to be a ``combat engaged'' flag.

@ The routine below implements the encounter check.

<<check encounter>>=
    ORG     $0E25
CHECK_ENCOUNTER:
    SUBROUTINE CHECK_ENCOUNTER

    JSR     FIND_ENTITY_AT_POS   ; look up char -> ENTITY_REC/ENTITY_REC+1
    LDA     ENTITY_REC+1
    BAEQ    #$00,.none           ; null pointer -> return 0
    BAMI    #$80,.none ; not a mob (bit 7 clear) -> return 0
    AND     #$7F                 ; clear mob flag
    STA     MOB_PTR+1            ; \ MOB_PTR/MOB_PTR+1 = mob data pointer
    MOVB    ENTITY_REC,MOB_PTR
.search:
    MOVW    MOB_PTR,TARGET_REC ; TARGET_REC/TARGET_REC+1 = current mob pointer
    JSR     FIND_MOB_AT_SAME_POS ; find next mob at same position
    BAMI    #$01,.none ; 0 = no co-located mob -> return 0
    BEQ     .friendly            ; 1 = found (wrapped) -> return 1
    LDY     #$06                 ; result >= 2: found ahead
    LDA     (MOB_PTR),Y          ; byte 6 of found mob
    AND     #$3F                 ; bits 5-0
    BALT    #$03,.search ; active mob type?
    JSR     CHECK_HOSTILE        ; compare factions
    BAEQ    #$00,.search         ; same faction -> skip
    STOB    #$02,ENCOUNTER_RESULT ; enemy found -> return 2
    RTS
.none:
    LDA     #$00
    BEQ     .store
.friendly:
    LDA     #$01
.store:
    STA     ENCOUNTER_RESULT
    RTS
@ %def CHECK_ENCOUNTER
Walks the group chain starting from the current mob ([[MOB_PTR]]),
looking for another mob at the same map position (byte~3 of mob data).
If the current mob is the last in the chain (byte~2 = 0), the search
wraps around to the first mob via the group head ([[$FA/$FB]]).

Returns in~[[A]]:
\begin{itemize}
\item 0 --- no other mob at same position (full circle)
\item 1 --- found co-located mob (search wrapped past end of chain)
\item 2 --- found co-located mob ahead in the chain
\end{itemize}

On success, [[MOB_PTR]] is updated to point to the found mob.

@ [[COLOCATE_POS]] saves the current mob's position (byte 3) as the
comparison target.  [[COLOCATE_LINK]] saves the starting mob's next-link
(byte 2) as a stop condition to detect a full circle.  [[COLOCATE_WRAPPED]]
is set to 2 initially (found ahead in chain) and changed to 1 if the search
wraps past the end.  [[FIND_MOB_AT_SAME_POS]] returns this value on success.

<<defines>>=
COLOCATE_POS            EQU     $5A21   ; saved position for co-location search
COLOCATE_LINK           EQU     $5A20   ; saved next-link (stop condition)
COLOCATE_WRAPPED        EQU     $5A22   ; 1 if wrapped, 2 if ahead
@ %def COLOCATE_POS COLOCATE_LINK COLOCATE_WRAPPED

@ The routine below implements the co-location search.

<<find mob at same pos>>=
    ORG     $0E6C
FIND_MOB_AT_SAME_POS:
    SUBROUTINE FIND_MOB_AT_SAME_POS

    LDY     #$03
    LDA     (MOB_PTR),Y             ; byte 3 = position of current mob
    STA     COLOCATE_POS
    DEY
    LDA     (MOB_PTR),Y             ; byte 2 = next link of current mob
    STA     COLOCATE_LINK
    STY     COLOCATE_WRAPPED        ; $5A22 = 2 (found ahead)
.check_link:
    BANE    #$00,.resolve           ; has next -> follow it
    LDY     #$01
    STY     COLOCATE_WRAPPED        ; wrapped to start
    INY                             ; Y = 2
    LDA     (CHAR_PTR),Y            ; byte 2 of group head = first mob
.resolve:
    JSR     GET_MOB_DATA            ; A = mob index -> MOB_DATA_PTR/MOB_DATA_PTR+1
    LDY     #$02
    LDA     (MOB_DATA_PTR),Y        ; byte 2 of resolved mob
    BANE    COLOCATE_LINK,.not_self ; same next-link as original?
    LDA     #$00                    ; full circle -> not found
    RTS
.not_self:
    INY                             ; Y = 3
    LDA     (MOB_DATA_PTR),Y        ; byte 3 = position
    BAEQ    COLOCATE_POS,.found     ; same position as original?
    DEY                             ; Y = 2
    LDA     (MOB_DATA_PTR),Y        ; follow next link
    JMP     .check_link
.found:
    MOVW    MOB_DATA_PTR,MOB_PTR ; update MOB_PTR/MOB_PTR+1 to found mob
    LDA     COLOCATE_WRAPPED        ; return 1 (wrapped) or 2 (ahead)
    RTS
@ %def FIND_MOB_AT_SAME_POS
Determines whether two mobs are hostile to each other by comparing their
faction classifications.  Reads byte~4 (appearance index) from the mob
at [[MOB_PTR]] and the mob at [[\TARGET_REC/\TARGET_REC+1]], converts each via
[[APPEARANCE_TO_FONTCHAR]] to get the font group (quotient of dividing
by~21), then classifies via [[GET_HOSTILITY]]: groups 0--2 and~7 are
``friendly'' (Y=0), groups 3--6 are ``hostile'' (Y=1).

Returns [[A]]=1 if the two mobs are on different sides, [[A]]=0 if same.
When both are hostile (Y=1), they are still hostile to each other if
their font-char remainders differ (different hostile sub-factions).

@ [[HOSTILE_APP]] saves the appearance byte of the second mob so
[[CHECK_HOSTILE]] can classify both mobs without losing state.
[[HOSTILE_A]] and [[HOSTILE_Y]] save the return values (remainder and
faction flag) from the first [[GET_HOSTILITY]] call, allowing the routine
to compare both factions after the second call completes.

<<defines>>=
HOSTILE_APP             EQU     $5A23   ; saved appearance for hostility check
HOSTILE_A               EQU     $5A24   ; saved A from first GET_HOSTILITY
HOSTILE_Y               EQU     $5A25   ; saved Y from first GET_HOSTILITY
@ %def HOSTILE_APP HOSTILE_A HOSTILE_Y

@ The routine below implements the hostility comparison.

<<check hostile>>=
    ORG     $0EB1
CHECK_HOSTILE:
    SUBROUTINE CHECK_HOSTILE

    LDY     #$04
    LDA     (MOB_PTR),Y            ; byte 4 of found mob (appearance)
    STA     HOSTILE_APP
    LDA     (TARGET_REC),Y         ; byte 4 of original mob (appearance)
    JSR     APPEARANCE_TO_FONTCHAR ; -> A=remainder, Y=group
    JSR     GET_HOSTILITY          ; -> Y=0 (friendly) or 1 (hostile)
    STA     HOSTILE_A
    STY     HOSTILE_Y
    LDA     HOSTILE_APP            ; appearance of found mob
    JSR     APPEARANCE_TO_FONTCHAR
    JSR     GET_HOSTILITY
    BYNE    HOSTILE_Y,.different   ; different sides -> hostile
    BYEQ    #$00,.same             ; both friendly -> same side
    BANE    HOSTILE_A,.different   ; different -> hostile to each other
.same:
    LDA     #$00
    RTS
.different:
    LDA     #$01
    RTS
@ %def CHECK_HOSTILE
Classifies a font group number (in~[[Y]], from [[APPEARANCE_TO_FONTCHAR]])
as friendly or hostile.  Groups 0--2 and~7 are friendly (Y$\leftarrow$0),
groups 3--6 are hostile (Y$\leftarrow$1).  The value in~[[A]] is preserved.

<<get hostility>>=
    ORG     $0EE3
GET_HOSTILITY:
    SUBROUTINE GET_HOSTILITY

    CPY     #$03           ; factions 0-2 = friendly
    BCC     .friendly
    BYEQ    #$07,.friendly ; faction 7 = friendly
    LDY     #$01           ; factions 3-6 = hostile
    RTS
.friendly:
    LDY     #$00
    RTS
@ %def GET_HOSTILITY
Checks the four cardinal neighbors of a map position for hostile mobs
and accumulates their combined threat level.  Input: [[A]]~= position
(0--199), [[ENTITY_PTR]]~= character record pointer,
[[\TARGET_REC/\TARGET_REC+1]]~= character's mob data pointer.

For each adjacent position (left, right, up, down), calls
[[SUM_HOSTILE_AT_POS]] to find hostile mobs not already in combat and
sum their strength (byte~5 bits~4--0) into [[$5A26]].  After checking
all neighbors, compares the accumulated threat against the character's
defense value (byte~5 bits~4--1 of the [[ENTITY_PTR]] record).

Returns [[A]]=1 if defense~$\ge$~threat (safe), [[A]]=0 if overwhelmed.
The threat total remains in [[$5A26]] for callers that check it directly.

Boundary checks prevent wrapping: position~0 has no left neighbor,
position~199 no right, positions~0--19 no up, positions~180--199 no down.

@ [[ADJACENT_POS]] saves the target map position on entry to
[[CHECK_ADJACENT_THREATS]].  The routine adds and subtracts offsets (1 for
left/right, 20 for up/down) from this saved position to compute the four
cardinal neighbors, passing each to [[SUM_HOSTILE_AT_POS]].

<<defines>>=
ADJACENT_POS            EQU     $5A27   ; saved position for adjacency check
@ %def ADJACENT_POS

@ The routine below implements the four-direction threat scan.

<<check adjacent threats>>=
    ORG     $0EF1
CHECK_ADJACENT_THREATS:
    SUBROUTINE CHECK_ADJACENT_THREATS

    STA     ADJACENT_POS       ; save target position
    STOB    #$00,ADJACENT_THREAT ; clear threat accumulator
    MOVW    ENTITY_PTR,TARGET_REC ; TARGET_REC/TARGET_REC+1 = character record pointer
    LDA     ADJACENT_POS       ; reload position
    BEQ     .skip_left         ; position 0 -> no left neighbor
    SEC
    SBC     #$01               ; position - 1
    JSR     SUM_HOSTILE_AT_POS ; check left
.skip_left:
    LDA     ADJACENT_POS
    BAEQ    #$C7,.skip_right   ; -> no right neighbor
    CLC
    ADC     #$01               ; position + 1
    JSR     SUM_HOSTILE_AT_POS ; check right
.skip_right:
    LDA     ADJACENT_POS
    BMI     .do_up             ; >= 128 -> always has up neighbor
    BAMI    #$14,.skip_up ; < 20?
.do_up:
    SEC
    SBC     #$14               ; position - 20
    JSR     SUM_HOSTILE_AT_POS ; check up
.skip_up:
    LDA     ADJACENT_POS
    BPL     .do_down           ; < 128 -> always has down neighbor
    BAPL    #$B4,.skip_down ; >= 180?
.do_down:
    CLC
    ADC     #$14               ; position + 20
    JSR     SUM_HOSTILE_AT_POS ; check down
.skip_down:
    LDY     #$05
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y     ; byte 5 of character record
    ROR                        ; \ bits 4-1 -> defense value
    AND     #$0F               ; /
    BAPL    ADJACENT_THREAT,.safe ; compare with threat total
    LDA     #$00
    RTS                        ; return 0 = overwhelmed
.safe:
    LDA     #$01
    RTS                        ; return 1 = safe
@ %def CHECK_ADJACENT_THREATS
Finds all hostile mobs at a given map position and adds their strength
to the threat accumulator [[$5A26]].  Input: [[A]]~= position,
[[\TARGET_REC/\TARGET_REC+1]]~= reference mob for faction comparison.

For each mob found at the position, checks hostility via
[[CHECK_HOSTILE]] and skips mobs that are already combat-engaged
(bit~2 of byte~\$0F set).  Hostile mobs contribute their strength
(byte~5 bits~4--0) to the running total, clamped at~127.

<<sum hostile at pos>>=
    ORG     $0F49
SUM_HOSTILE_AT_POS:
    SUBROUTINE SUM_HOSTILE_AT_POS

    JSR     FIND_ENTITY_AT_POS   ; A = position -> ENTITY_REC/ENTITY_REC+1
    LDA     ENTITY_REC+1
    BEQ     .done                ; null -> nothing here
    BAMI    #$80,.done ; not a mob -> skip
    AND     #$7F                 ; clear mob flag
    STA     MOB_PTR+1            ; \ MOB_PTR/MOB_PTR+1 = mob data pointer
    MOVB    ENTITY_REC,MOB_PTR
.check_mob:
    JSR     CHECK_HOSTILE        ; is this mob hostile to (TARGET_REC)?
    BAEQ    #$00,.next           ; not hostile -> skip
    LDY     #$0F
    LDA     (MOB_PTR),Y          ; byte $0F of mob
    AND     #$04                 ; bit 2 = combat engaged flag
    BNE     .next                ; already in combat -> skip
    LDY     #$05
    LDA     (MOB_PTR),Y          ; byte 5 of mob
    AND     #$1F                 ; bits 4-0 = strength
    CLC
    ADC     ADJACENT_THREAT      ; accumulate threat
    BPL     .store
    LDA     #$7F                 ; clamp to 127
.store:
    STA     ADJACENT_THREAT
.next:
    JSR     FIND_MOB_AT_SAME_POS ; find next mob at same position
    BAEQ    #$02,.check_mob      ; more mobs -> check them too
.done:
    RTS
@ %def SUM_HOSTILE_AT_POS
@ [[CHECK_THREATS_HERE]] is a convenience wrapper that packs [[CURRENT_COL]]
and [[CURRENT_ROW]] into a single position byte via [[COLROW_TO_POS]] and
tail-calls [[CHECK_ADJACENT_THREATS]] to evaluate whether hostile entities are
present at that position.


<<check threats here>>=
    ORG     $645F
CHECK_THREATS_HERE:
    SUBROUTINE CHECK_THREATS_HERE
    ; Check adjacent threats at current col/row position.
    LDA     CURRENT_COL
    LDY     CURRENT_ROW
    JSR     COLROW_TO_POS
    JMP     CHECK_ADJACENT_THREATS
@ %def CHECK_THREATS_HERE

\section{Combat resolution}

@ [[CALC_COMBAT_STRENGTH]] computes the effective attack power for the current
combatant.  If the attacker is the player or is at a different position from
the target, field~7 (ranged attack) is used; if attacker and target share a
position, field~9 (melee attack) is used instead.  The chosen field's low
nibble becomes the base: two calls to [[RANDOM_IN_RANGE]] produce a value
between 0 and twice the base (with a carry add), stored in
[[COMBAT_STRENGTH]].  For player-controlled characters (AI mode~0) when it is
not the player's turn, there is an additional critical-hit/fumble check:
depending on the high bit of the chosen field, a random roll against either
\$0D or \$50 determines whether a special event triggers.  On a roll of zero,
the field is marked~\$81, scene~1 is displayed, and a bonus of 0--9 is added
to the combat strength (capped at~\$1F).

<<defines>>=
COMBAT_STRENGTH EQU     $5A78   ; result of CALC_COMBAT_STRENGTH
@ %def COMBAT_STRENGTH

<<calc combat strength>>=
    ORG     $16E0
    SUBROUTINE CALC_COMBAT_STRENGTH
; Calculates combat strength using RANDOM_IN_RANGE
CALC_COMBAT_STRENGTH:
    LDA     IS_PLAYER_TURN
    BAEQ    #$01,.use_y7
    LDY     #$03
    LDA     (MOB_PTR),Y
    CMP     (ENTITY_PTR),Y
    BNE     .use_y7
    LDY     #$09
    BNE     .got_y
.use_y7:
    LDY     #$07
.got_y:
    TYA
    PHA
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y
    AND     #$0F
    TAX
    JSR     RANDOM_IN_RANGE
    STA     COMBAT_STRENGTH
    TXA
    JSR     RANDOM_IN_RANGE
    SEC
    ADC     COMBAT_STRENGTH
    STA     COMBAT_STRENGTH
    LDA     CHAR_AI_MODE
    BEQ     .check_5a74
.exit_pla:                     ; $1712 - reused by backward BNE from $1717
    PLA
    RTS
.check_5a74:
    LDA     IS_PLAYER_TURN
    BNE     .exit_pla
    PLA
    TAY
    TAX
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y
    AND     #$80
    BNE     .use_50
    LDA     #$0D
    BNE     .do_random
.use_50:
    LDA     #$50
.do_random:
    JSR     RANDOM_IN_RANGE
    BAEQ    #$00,.missed
    RTS
.missed:
    TXA
    TAY
    LDA     #$81
    STA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y
    JSR     SET_CURSOR_ROW21
    LDA     #$01
    JSR     SCENE_LOOP
    LDA     #$0A
    JSR     RANDOM_IN_RANGE
    SEC
    ADC     COMBAT_STRENGTH
    BALT    #$1F,.cap_ok
    LDA     #$1F
.cap_ok:
    STA     COMBAT_STRENGTH
    RTS
@ %def CALC_COMBAT_STRENGTH
@ [[ENTER_COMBAT_STATE]] transitions the character to combat readiness (state
2).  It first calls [[CHECK_ENCOUNTER]] to evaluate what is at the character's
position, then clears the restricted flag.  If the encounter result is not~2
(meaning the character is not co-located with a hostile), the restricted flag
is re-set to limit the character's options.  Finally, [[SET_CHAR_STATE]] is
called with~2 to record the new state.


<<enter combat state>>=
    ORG     $14B7
ENTER_COMBAT_STATE:
    SUBROUTINE ENTER_COMBAT_STATE
    ; Check encounter, clear restricted flag, conditionally set it,
    ; then set char state to 2.
    JSR     CHECK_ENCOUNTER
    JSR     CLEAR_RESTRICTED
    LDA     #$02
    BANE    ENCOUNTER_RESULT,.skip
    JSR     SET_RESTRICTED
.skip:
    LDA     #$02
    JSR     SET_CHAR_STATE
    RTS
@ %def ENTER_COMBAT_STATE
@ [[START_COMBAT]] advances the character to active attack state (state~3),
loads the combat target pointer from [[TARGET_PTR_LO]]/[[TARGET_PTR_HI]] via
[[LOAD_TARGET_PTR]], and jumps to [[RESOLVE_ATTACK]] where the actual
willingness check and damage calculation take place.


<<start combat>>=
    ORG     $14CD
START_COMBAT:
    SUBROUTINE START_COMBAT
    ; Set char state to 3, call $199D, jump to combat logic at $15AB.
    LDA     #$03
    JSR     SET_CHAR_STATE
    JSR     LOAD_TARGET_PTR
    JMP     RESOLVE_ATTACK
@ %def START_COMBAT

@ \subsection{Attack direction handlers (\$14D8--\$14E9)}

The attack direction menu ([[ATTACK_DIR_TABLE]]) has four direction
handlers that adjust [[CURRENT_COL]] or [[CURRENT_ROW]] by~$\pm$1,
then fall through to [[FIND_ATTACK_TARGET]].  Each handler undoes
the adjustment if it causes the value to go negative (underflow past
zero wraps to \$FF, which is $>$\$7F).

\begin{itemize}
\item [[ATTACK_RIGHT]]: increment column
\item [[ATTACK_LEFT]]: decrement column
\item [[ATTACK_UP]]: decrement row
\item [[ATTACK_DOWN]]: increment row
\end{itemize}

<<attack direction handlers>>=
    ORG     $14D8
ATTACK_RIGHT:
    INC     CURRENT_COL
    BPL     FIND_ATTACK_TARGET ; positive -> valid, else fall through undoes it

ATTACK_LEFT:
    DEC     CURRENT_COL
    BPL     FIND_ATTACK_TARGET ; positive -> valid, else fall through undoes it

ATTACK_UP:
    DEC     CURRENT_ROW
    BPL     FIND_ATTACK_TARGET ; positive -> valid, else fall through undoes it

ATTACK_DOWN:
    INC     CURRENT_ROW        ; fall through to FIND_ATTACK_TARGET
@ %def ATTACK_RIGHT ATTACK_LEFT ATTACK_UP ATTACK_DOWN

@ \subsection{Find attack target (\$14EA--\$1536)}

[[FIND_ATTACK_TARGET]] converts [[CURRENT_COL]]/[[CURRENT_ROW]] to a
map position via [[COLROW_TO_POS]], then calls [[FIND_ENTITY_AT_POS]]
to see what entity occupies that square.
\begin{itemize}
\item If no entity is found (\$BF~=~0) or a player character is found
  (bit~7 of \$BF clear), it sets [[IS_PLAYER_TURN]]~=~1, stores the
  entity pointer into [[MOB_PTR]], and jumps to [[RESOLVE_ATTACK]].
\item If a mob is found (bit~7 of \$BF set), it sets
  [[IS_PLAYER_TURN]]~=~0, strips bit~7, stores the pointer into
  [[MOB_PTR]], and calls [[FIND_MOB_AT_SAME_POS]] to check if there
  are multiple mobs at the position.  If there are (A$\ne$0), it calls
  [[NEXT_COLOCATED_MOB]] twice to cycle through candidates, then
  enters the attack target menu at [[MENU_ATTACK_TARGET]].  If only
  one mob, it jumps directly to [[RESOLVE_ATTACK]].
\end{itemize}

<<find attack target>>=
    ORG     $14EA
FIND_ATTACK_TARGET:
    SUBROUTINE FIND_ATTACK_TARGET
    LDA     CURRENT_COL
    LDY     CURRENT_ROW
    JSR     COLROW_TO_POS      ; A = map position
    JSR     FIND_ENTITY_AT_POS ; $BE/$BF = entity pointer
    LDA     $BF
    BEQ     .player            ; $BF = 0 -> no entity / player
    CMP     #$80
    BPL     .mob               ; bit 7 set -> mob

.player:
    LDA     #$01
    STA     IS_PLAYER_TURN
    LDA     $BE
    STA     MOB_PTR
    LDA     $BF
    STA     MOB_PTR+1
    JMP     RESOLVE_ATTACK

.mob:
    LDA     #$00
    STA     IS_PLAYER_TURN
    LDA     $BE
    STA     MOB_PTR
    LDA     $BF
    AND     #$7F               ; strip bit 7 (mob indicator)
    STA     MOB_PTR+1
    JSR     FIND_MOB_AT_SAME_POS ; check for multiple mobs
    CMP     #$00
    BNE     .multiple          ; nonzero -> multiple mobs here
    JMP     RESOLVE_ATTACK     ; only one -> attack directly

.multiple:
    JSR     NEXT_COLOCATED_MOB ; cycle to first candidate
    JSR     NEXT_COLOCATED_MOB ; cycle to second candidate
    CMP     #$00
    BNE     .choose
    JMP     RESOLVE_ATTACK     ; no valid candidate -> attack directly

.choose:
    JMP     MENU_ATTACK_TARGET ; present target selection menu
@ %def FIND_ATTACK_TARGET

@ \subsection{Init attack target display (\$1537--\$155D)}

[[INIT_ATTACK_DISPLAY]] is the initialization callback for the attack
target menu ([[ATTACK_TARGET_TABLE]]).  It reads the target's name
from the entity record at [[MOB_PTR]] and copies it into the display
buffer at [[$7C9B]].  Byte~0 of the record gives the name length;
bytes~1--20 are the name characters.  Positions beyond the name length
are filled with spaces (\$20).

<<defines>>=
ATTACK_NAME_BUF     EQU     $7C9B   ; 20-byte buffer for attack target name
@ %def ATTACK_NAME_BUF

<<init attack display>>=
    ORG     $1537
INIT_ATTACK_DISPLAY:
    SUBROUTINE INIT_ATTACK_DISPLAY
    LDY     #$00
    LDA     (MOB_PTR),Y        ; byte 0 = record pointer lo
    STA     $BC
    INY
    LDA     (MOB_PTR),Y        ; byte 1 = record pointer hi
    STA     $BD
    LDY     #$00
    LDA     ($BC),Y            ; name length
    TAX
    LDA     #<ATTACK_NAME_BUF
    STA     $BA
    LDA     #>ATTACK_NAME_BUF
    STA     $BB
.copy:
    INY
    LDA     ($BC),Y            ; name character
    DEX
    BPL     .store             ; X >= 0 -> still within name
    LDA     #$20               ; past end -> space
.store:
    STA     ($BA),Y
    CPY     #$14               ; 20 characters
    BNE     .copy
    RTS
@ %def INIT_ATTACK_DISPLAY

@ \subsection{Someone else handler and attack eligibility (\$155E--\$15AA)}

[[SELECT_SOMEONE_ELSE]] is the handler for the ``SOMEONE ELSE'' option
in the attack target menu.  It calls [[NEXT_COLOCATED_MOB]] to advance
to the next mob at the same position, then re-enters the attack target
menu.

[[CHECK_ATTACK_ELIGIBLE]] checks whether a hostile mob is co-located
with the current entity.  It copies [[ENTITY_PTR]] to [[TARGET_REC]]
and [[MOB_PTR]], then repeatedly calls [[FIND_MOB_AT_SAME_POS]] and
[[CHECK_HOSTILE]] to scan co-located mobs.  Returns carry set if a
hostile mob is at the same position (attack it directly), carry clear
if none found (player must choose a direction).

[[NEXT_COLOCATED_MOB]] advances [[MOB_PTR]] to the next mob at the
same map position.  It saves byte~2 (next link) of the current mob,
calls [[FIND_MOB_AT_SAME_POS]], and checks if the position actually
changed.  If the position is unchanged, it returns A=0 (no new mob).
If byte~4 (appearance) is~$\ge$\$15, the mob is a valid attackable
target and it returns A=1.  Otherwise it retries up to the loop limit.

<<defines>>=
SAVED_MOB_LINK      EQU     $5A75   ; temp: saved byte 2 of mob record
@ %def SAVED_MOB_LINK

<<attack eligibility>>=
    ORG     $155E
SELECT_SOMEONE_ELSE:
    ; "SOMEONE ELSE" menu handler: advance to next colocated mob.
    ; Input:  MOB_PTR — current mob
    ; Output: jumps to MENU_ATTACK_TARGET
    ; Clobbers: A, X, Y

    JSR     NEXT_COLOCATED_MOB     ; advance to next mob
    JMP     MENU_ATTACK_TARGET     ; re-enter target menu

CHECK_ATTACK_ELIGIBLE:
    SUBROUTINE CHECK_ATTACK_ELIGIBLE
    ; Check if a hostile mob is at the entity's position.
    ;
    ; Input:  ENTITY_PTR — entity to check
    ; Output: C=1 hostile found (MOB_PTR set to it)
    ;         C=0 no hostile at position
    ; Modifies: MOB_PTR, TARGET_REC
    ; Clobbers: A, X, Y

    LDA     ENTITY_PTR             ; \ copy ENTITY_PTR
    STA     TARGET_REC             ;  | to TARGET_REC
    STA     MOB_PTR                ;  | and MOB_PTR
    LDA     ENTITY_PTR+1           ;  |
    STA     TARGET_REC+1           ;  |
    STA     MOB_PTR+1              ; /
.scan:
    JSR     FIND_MOB_AT_SAME_POS
    LDA     ENTITY_PTR             ; \ check if pointer changed
    CMP     MOB_PTR                ;  |
    BNE     .found                 ;  |
    LDA     ENTITY_PTR+1           ;  |
    CMP     MOB_PTR+1              ;  |
    BEQ     .none                  ; / same pointer -> none found
.found:
    JSR     CHECK_HOSTILE          ; A=0 if friendly
    CMP     #$00
    BEQ     .scan                  ; not hostile -> keep scanning
    SEC                            ; hostile found
    RTS
.none:
    CLC                            ; no hostile found
    RTS

NEXT_COLOCATED_MOB:
    SUBROUTINE NEXT_COLOCATED_MOB
    ; Advance MOB_PTR to the next valid NPC at the same position.
    ;
    ; Input:  MOB_PTR — current mob
    ; Output: A=1 valid target found, A=0 no new mob
    ;         MOB_PTR updated if found
    ; Modifies: MOB_PTR, SAVED_MOB_LINK
    ; Clobbers: A, X, Y

    LDY     #MFIELD_NEXT           ; byte 2: next link
    LDA     (MOB_PTR),Y
    STA     SAVED_MOB_LINK         ; save current link
.retry:
    JSR     FIND_MOB_AT_SAME_POS
    LDY     #MFIELD_NEXT           ; byte 2: new mob's link
    LDA     (MOB_PTR),Y
    CMP     SAVED_MOB_LINK         ; same as saved?
    BNE     .check                 ; different -> check validity
    LDA     #$00                   ; wrapped around, none found
    RTS
.check:
    LDY     #MFIELD_APPEARANCE     ; byte 4: appearance
    LDA     (MOB_PTR),Y
    CMP     #NPC_APPEARANCE_MIN    ; >= $15 = valid NPC target?
    BCC     .retry                 ; below threshold -> skip
    LDA     #$01                   ; valid target found
    RTS
@ %def SELECT_SOMEONE_ELSE CHECK_ATTACK_ELIGIBLE NEXT_COLOCATED_MOB

@ \subsection{Combat willingness and attack resolution (\$15AB)}

[[RESOLVE_ATTACK]] determines whether an entity commits to an attack
or hesitates.  Player characters always attack; AI entities compute a
\emph{willingness score} that is tested against a random roll.

\paragraph{Willingness score.}
For players, willingness is fixed at~28.  For AI, it starts at the
entity's level (byte~11, bits~4--0) and accumulates modifiers:

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{llr}
\toprule
\textbf{Condition} & \textbf{Source} & \textbf{Delta} \\
\midrule
Attacker rage flag (bit~5 of byte~11) & attacker & $+24$ \\
Target cautious flag (bit~6 of byte~11) & target & $-4$ \\
Target aggressive flag (bit~7 of byte~11) & target & $+8$ \\
Target combat-engaged (bit~2 of byte~15) & target & $+6$ \\
Target idle (state~0, bits~1--0 of byte~15) & target & $+3$ \\
Target guarding (state~1) & target & $-1$ \\
Target retreating (state~3) & target & $-3$ \\
Target critically wounded (HP $<$ 3) & target & $+24$ \\
Defense differential (same position only) & both & attacker $-$ target \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

The final score is clamped to 0--30.

\paragraph{Attack roll.}
A random number 0--30 is generated.  If the roll is at or below the
willingness score, the attack proceeds to [[PLAYER_ATTACK]] or
[[MOB_ATTACK]] depending on [[IS_PLAYER_TURN]].  Otherwise the
attacker hesitates and ``MISSES'' is displayed.

\paragraph{Rage consumption.}
When the rage flag (bit~5) is set, the routine grants the $+24$
bonus and then clears bit~4 of byte~11, consuming the rage for
future turns.

<<defines>>=
COMBAT_WILLINGNESS EQU  $5A76   ; accumulated willingness-to-fight score
    ; --- Byte 11 (MFIELD_LEVEL) flag bit masks ---
LEVEL_BIT5_MASK     EQU     $20     ; byte 11 bit 5: rage/berserk flag
LEVEL_CLEAR_BIT4    EQU     $EF     ; byte 11: clear bit 4 (consume rage)
TARGET_BIT6_MASK    EQU     $40     ; byte 11 bit 6: cautious flag
TARGET_BIT7_MASK    EQU     $80     ; byte 11 bit 7: aggressive flag
    ; --- Byte 15 (MFIELD_FLAGS) bit masks ---
FLAGS_ENGAGED_BIT   EQU     $04     ; byte 15 bit 2: combat engaged
FLAGS_STATE_MASK    EQU     $03     ; byte 15 bits 1-0: combat state (0-3)
    ; --- Byte 5 defense mask ---
DEFENSE_HALF_MASK   EQU     $0F     ; byte 5: defense (bits 4-1 shifted down via ROR)
    ; --- Scratch ---
TARGET_DEFENSE      EQU     $5A77   ; scratch: target's defense value
@ %def COMBAT_WILLINGNESS LEVEL_BIT5_MASK LEVEL_CLEAR_BIT4 TARGET_BIT6_MASK TARGET_BIT7_MASK FLAGS_ENGAGED_BIT FLAGS_STATE_MASK DEFENSE_HALF_MASK TARGET_DEFENSE

<<resolve attack>>=
    ORG     $15AB
RESOLVE_ATTACK:
    SUBROUTINE RESOLVE_ATTACK
    ; Compute combat willingness and resolve attack or hesitation.
    ;
    ; Input:  ENTITY_PTR    — attacker record
    ;         MOB_PTR       — target record
    ;         IS_PLAYER_TURN — 1 = player, 0 = AI
    ;
    ; Output: branches to PLAYER_ATTACK or MOB_ATTACK on hit;
    ;         prints "MISSES" and returns on hesitation.
    ;
    ; Behavior:
    ;   Player willingness is fixed at 28.  AI willingness starts
    ;   at the entity's level (byte 11 bits 4-0) and accumulates
    ;   modifiers from flag bits, combat state, HP, and defense.
    ;   Clamped to 0-30, then random roll 0-30 determines hit.
    ;
    ; Modifies: COMBAT_WILLINGNESS, TARGET_DEFENSE, entity byte 11
    ; Clobbers: A, X, Y

    ; --- set blink cursor to target ---
    JSR     SET_BLINK_TARGET

    ; --- player: fixed willingness ---
    LDA     IS_PLAYER_TURN
    BANE    #$01,.not_player
    STOB    #$1C,COMBAT_WILLINGNESS ; player = 28 (always willing)
    JMP     .clamp_done

    ; --- AI: base level ---
.not_player:
    LDY     #MFIELD_LEVEL          ; byte 11: flags | level
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y
    TAX
    AND     #LEVEL_MASK            ; level (bits 4-0) = base willingness
    STA     COMBAT_WILLINGNESS

    ; --- AI: attacker flag bits (byte 11) ---
    TXA
    AND     #LEVEL_BIT5_MASK       ; bit 5: rage flag
    BEQ     .no_bit5
    TXA
    AND     #LEVEL_CLEAR_BIT4      ; consume rage: clear bit 4
    STA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y
    LDA     #$18                   ; +24 (rage bonus)
    JSR     ADD_WILLINGNESS
.no_bit5:

    ; --- AI: target flag bits (byte 11) ---
    LDA     (MOB_PTR),Y           ; target byte 11
    TAY
    AND     #TARGET_BIT6_MASK      ; bit 6: cautious
    BEQ     .no_bit6
    LDA     #$FC                   ; -4 (target cautious)
    JSR     ADD_WILLINGNESS
.no_bit6:
    TYA
    AND     #TARGET_BIT7_MASK      ; bit 7: aggressive
    BEQ     .no_bit7
    LDA     #$08                   ; +8 (target aggressive)
    JSR     ADD_WILLINGNESS

    ; --- AI: target combat state (byte 15) ---
.no_bit7:
    LDY     #MFIELD_FLAGS          ; byte 15: status flags
    LDA     (MOB_PTR),Y
    TAX
    AND     #FLAGS_ENGAGED_BIT     ; bit 2: combat engaged
    BEQ     .no_restrict
    LDA     #$06                   ; +6 (already fighting)
    JSR     ADD_WILLINGNESS
.no_restrict:
    TXA
    AND     #FLAGS_STATE_MASK      ; bits 1-0: combat state
    BAPL    #$01,.ge1
    LDA     #$03                   ; +3 (state 0: idle)
    JSR     ADD_WILLINGNESS
    JMP     .state_done
.ge1:
    BNE     .ne1
    LDA     #$FF                   ; -1 (state 1: guarding)
    JSR     ADD_WILLINGNESS
    JMP     .state_done
.ne1:
    BANE    #$03,.state_done
    LDA     #$FD                   ; -3 (state 3: retreating)
    JSR     ADD_WILLINGNESS

    ; --- AI: target HP check ---
.state_done:
    LDY     #MFIELD_MOB_TYPE       ; byte 6: HP in bits 5-0
    LDA     (MOB_PTR),Y
    AND     #HP_MASK
    BAGE    #$03,.hp_ok            ; HP >= 3 -> not critical
    LDA     #$18                   ; +24 (target critically wounded)
    JSR     ADD_WILLINGNESS

    ; --- AI: defense differential (same position only) ---
.hp_ok:
    LDY     #MFIELD_POSITION       ; byte 3: map position
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y
    CMP     (MOB_PTR),Y
    BNE     .diff_pos              ; not co-located -> skip
    LDY     #MFIELD_STRENGTH       ; byte 5: defense in bits 4-1
    LDA     (MOB_PTR),Y           ; \ target defense
    ROR                            ;  | shift bits 4-1 to 3-0
    AND     #DEFENSE_HALF_MASK     ;  |
    STA     TARGET_DEFENSE         ; /
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y        ; \ attacker defense
    ROR                            ;  | shift bits 4-1 to 3-0
    AND     #DEFENSE_HALF_MASK     ; /
    SEC
    SBC     TARGET_DEFENSE         ; delta = attacker - target
    JSR     ADD_WILLINGNESS

    ; --- clamp willingness to 0-30 ---
.diff_pos:
    LDA     COMBAT_WILLINGNESS
    BPL     .not_neg
    STOB    #$00,COMBAT_WILLINGNESS ; floor at 0
    JMP     .clamp_done
.not_neg:
    BAMI    #$1F,.clamp_done
    STOB    #$1E,COMBAT_WILLINGNESS ; ceiling at 30

    ; --- random roll: attack or hesitate ---
.clamp_done:
    LDA     #$1F                   ; range 0-30
    JSR     RANDOM_IN_RANGE
    BAMI    COMBAT_WILLINGNESS,.attack ; roll < willingness -> hit
    BEQ     .attack                ; roll == willingness -> hit

    ; --- hesitate: print "[name] MISSES" ---
    JSR     SET_CURSOR_ROW21
    JSR     PRINT_MOB_NAME
    JSR     SCROLL_STATUS_LINE
    STOW    S_MISSES,TARGET_REC
    JSR     PRINT_BOTTOM_CENTERED
    JSR     SCROLL_STATUS_LINE
    LDA     #$01
    BAEQ    IS_PLAYER_TURN,.is_player
    JSR     PRINT_MEMBER_NAME
.is_player:
    JSR     DELAY_WITH_ANIMATION
    RTS

    ; --- dispatch attack ---
.attack:
    LDA     IS_PLAYER_TURN
    BEQ     .mob_attack
    JMP     PLAYER_ATTACK
.mob_attack:
    JMP     MOB_ATTACK
@ %def RESOLVE_ATTACK
@ [[PLAYER_ATTACK]] resolves an attack initiated by the player character.  It
first computes the combat strength via [[CALC_COMBAT_STRENGTH]], displays the
attacker's name and a strength-based descriptor through [[MAP_VALUE_TO_STRING]],
then copies [[MOB_PTR]] to [[ENTITY_REC]] and classifies the target entity.
The tune player is invoked with tune~2 and the combat strength as a
parameter.  If the target's byte~1 is~\$FE (marked dead/empty), the routine
falls through to event-slot processing.  Otherwise it checks whether the
target's byte~2 flags indicate an activated event: if the high bits are~\$C0,
the low sub-type determines how to handle it---small values trigger a scene,
larger values result in the slot being cleared.  For non-event targets, a
hit roll compares a random number (0--12) against the combat strength; if the
roll is at or above the strength, the attack is ``immune'' (blocked).  A
successful hit sets bit~6 of the target's byte~1 (marking damage taken),
redraws the entity at its position, plays tune~\$0C, and displays a
hit confirmation.  The routine also handles locked containers: if the target
has a type flag and the player's strength is below the required threshold,
the attack is blocked with message~\$10.

<<player attack>>=
    ORG     $1751
PLAYER_ATTACK:
    SUBROUTINE PLAYER_ATTACK
    JSR     CALC_COMBAT_STRENGTH
    JSR     SET_CURSOR_ROW21
    JSR     PRINT_MOB_NAME
    JSR     SCROLL_STATUS_LINE
    LDA     COMBAT_STRENGTH
    JSR     MAP_VALUE_TO_STRING
    JSR     SCROLL_STATUS_LINE
    MOVW    MOB_PTR,ENTITY_REC
    JSR     CLASSIFY_ENTITY_TYPE
    JSR     PRINT_BOTTOM_CENTERED
    LDY     COMBAT_STRENGTH
    LDX     #$02                ; tune 1: combat hit effect
    JSR     TUNE_PLAYER
    LDY     #$01
    LDA     (MOB_PTR),Y
    BAEQ    #$FE,.check_event
    BALT    #$40,.roll_hit
.immune:
    JSR     DISPATCH_ON_MODE
    JSR     SCROLL_STATUS_LINE
    LDA     #MSG_TOUCHED
    JMP     DISPLAY_MESSAGE
.roll_hit:
    LDA     #$0D
    JSR     RANDOM_IN_RANGE
    BAGE    COMBAT_STRENGTH,.immune
    JSR     DISPATCH_ON_MODE
    LDY     #$01
    LDA     (ENTITY_REC),Y
    ORA     #$40
    STA     (ENTITY_REC),Y
    DEY
    LDA     (ENTITY_REC),Y
    JSR     POS_TO_COLROW
    STY     FONT_ROW
    STA     FONT_COL
    JSR     GET_ENTITY_FONTCHAR
    JSR     RENDER_FONT_CHAR
    LDX     #$0C              ; tune 6: combat avoided effect
    JSR     TUNE_PLAYER
    JSR     SET_CURSOR_ROW21
    LDA     #MSG_INSERT_DISK
    JMP     DISPLAY_MESSAGE
.check_event:
    LDY     #$02
    LDA     (MOB_PTR),Y
    TAX
    AND     #$C0
    BANE    #$C0,.check_type
    TXA
    AND     #$1F
    BAPL    #$1D,.immune
    JSR     PROCESS_ENTITY_SCRIPT
    JSR     SET_CURSOR_ROW21
    LDA     #$02
    JMP     SCENE_LOOP
.check_type:
    BAEQ    #$00,.immune
    LDA     COMBAT_STRENGTH
    BAPL    #$0A,.strong_enough
    TXA
    BAPL    #$80,.blocked
    LDA     COMBAT_STRENGTH
    BAMI    #$04,.blocked
.strong_enough:
    TXA
    AND     #$1F
    BAMI    #$1F,.take_item
    STX     $BA
    DEC     $BA
    LDA     $BA
    LDY     #$02
    STA     (MOB_PTR),Y
    LDX     #$0E              ; tune 7: entity interaction
    JSR     TUNE_PLAYER
    JSR     DISPATCH_ON_MODE
    LDY     #$00
    LDA     (MOB_PTR),Y
    JSR     DRAW_CHAR_AT_POS
    JSR     SET_CURSOR_ROW21
.show_found:
    LDA     #MSG_TOPPLES
    JSR     DISPLAY_MESSAGE
    JMP     EVENT_PRNG_CHECK
.take_item:
    JSR     PROCESS_ENTITY_SCRIPT
    JSR     SET_CURSOR_ROW21
    LDY     #$02
    LDA     (MOB_PTR),Y
    AND     #$1F
    BAPL    #$1B,.show_found
    LDA     #$03
    JSR     SCENE_LOOP
    JMP     EVENT_PRNG_CHECK
.blocked:
    JSR     DISPATCH_ON_MODE
    JSR     SET_CURSOR_ROW21
    LDA     #MSG_HEAVY_ROCK
    JMP     DISPLAY_MESSAGE
@ %def PLAYER_ATTACK
@ [[MOB_ATTACK]] resolves an attack from a mob against the current character.
The structure mirrors [[PLAYER_ATTACK]]: compute combat strength, display the
attacker name and strength descriptor, print the target's name, play tune
type~2 with the strength value, and call [[DISPATCH_ON_MODE]] for any
mode-specific behavior.  The key difference is in the defense calculation: the
routine reads byte~8 of the target ([[MOB_PTR]]) and uses its low 4~bits as a
defense value.  If defense is zero, the full combat strength is applied via
[[COPY_F4_TO_F6_AND_SET]].  Otherwise, the routine subtracts defense from
strength: a negative or zero result means the attack is absorbed, with message
indices \$19/\$1A (``blocked'' variants) or~\$34 for critical blocks when HP is
below~3.  A positive remainder after subtraction becomes the effective damage,
displayed with message \$17 or \$18 depending on whether byte~8's sign bit is
set.  For player characters (field~4 below~\$15), the scene combat flag is
cleared to signal that the player is under attack.

<<defines>>=
SCENE_COMBAT_FLAG       EQU     $423A   ; nonzero = combat pending
MOB_DEFENSE     EQU     $5A79   ; mob defense value (low 4 bits of mob byte 8)
@ %def SCENE_COMBAT_FLAG MOB_DEFENSE

<<mob attack>>=
    ORG     $1860
MOB_ATTACK:
    SUBROUTINE MOB_ATTACK
    JSR     CALC_COMBAT_STRENGTH
    JSR     SET_CURSOR_ROW21
    JSR     PRINT_MOB_NAME
    JSR     SCROLL_STATUS_LINE
    LDA     COMBAT_STRENGTH
    JSR     MAP_VALUE_TO_STRING
    JSR     SCROLL_STATUS_LINE
    JSR     PRINT_MEMBER_NAME
    LDY     COMBAT_STRENGTH
    LDX     #$02              ; tune 1: combat hit effect
    JSR     TUNE_PLAYER
    LDY     #$04
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y
    BAGE    #NPC_APPEARANCE_MIN,.npc
    STOB    #$00,SCENE_COMBAT_FLAG
.npc:
    JSR     DISPATCH_ON_MODE
    LDY     #$08
    LDA     (MOB_PTR),Y
    STA     MOB_DEFENSE
    AND     #$0F
    BANE    #$00,.has_strength
    LDA     COMBAT_STRENGTH
    JMP     COPY_F4_TO_F6_AND_SET
.has_strength:
    JSR     SCROLL_STATUS_LINE
    LDX     #$17
    LDA     MOB_DEFENSE
    BMI     .negative
    LDX     #$18
.negative:
    LDA     MOB_DEFENSE
    AND     #$0F
    STA     MOB_DEFENSE
    LDA     COMBAT_STRENGTH
    SEC
    SBC     MOB_DEFENSE
    BEQ     .weak_hit
    BPL     .partial
.weak_hit:
    INX
    INX
    LDY     #$06
    LDA     (MOB_PTR),Y
    AND     #$3F
    BAMI    #$03,.critical
    TXA
    JMP     DISPLAY_MESSAGE
.critical:
    LDA     #MSG_ENOUGH
    JMP     DISPLAY_MESSAGE
.partial:
    STA     COMBAT_STRENGTH
    TXA
    JSR     DISPLAY_MESSAGE
    LDA     COMBAT_STRENGTH
    JMP     COPY_F4_TO_F6_AND_SET
@ %def MOB_ATTACK
@ [[APPLY_DAMAGE]] is the central damage-resolution routine.  It takes a
damage amount in~A and the target character's record pointer in [[EFFECT_REC]].
The routine first computes a message index by counting the leading zero bits of
the damage value (using repeated ROR), which maps larger damage to lower
message indices---producing increasingly alarming descriptions as damage rises.
It then invokes the [[TUNE_PLAYER]] with tune~4 to play the
damage sound effect.  The actual HP reduction follows: field~6 of the
target record holds hit points in its low six bits (with flags in the upper
two), and the damage is subtracted.  If HP drops to zero or below, execution
falls into the death handler, which sets a death flag in field~15, re-sorts
the character out of its group with [[REORDER_CHAR]], zeroes the character's
gold via [[MODIFY_CHAR_STATS]], calls [[UPDATE_EVENT_LIST]] to process any
death-triggered events, and redraws the map position.  The death message itself
is chosen randomly: a 1-in-3 chance of one message, otherwise a coin flip
between two alternatives.  If the character survives, the routine checks the
remaining HP and displays a status message: ``badly hurt'' below~3, ``wounded''
below~8, or ``scratched'' at~8 or above.  Characters below~3~HP also get the
restricted flag set in field~15, limiting their actions on subsequent turns.

<<defines>>=
DAMAGE_AMOUNT       EQU     $5A10   ; damage to apply / new HP after subtraction
@ %def DAMAGE_AMOUNT

<<apply damage>>=
    ORG     $106F
APPLY_DAMAGE:
    SUBROUTINE APPLY_DAMAGE
    ; Apply damage A to char at (EFFECT_REC).
    ; Subtracts from field 6 (HP). Displays damage message,
    ; plays tune. If HP drops to 0: death handling.
    AND     #$1F
    STA     DAMAGE_AMOUNT     ; damage amount
    JSR     SET_CURSOR_ROW21
    LDA     DAMAGE_AMOUNT
    LDX     #$03
.ror_loop:
    INX
    CLC
    ROR
    BNE     .ror_loop         ; count leading zeros -> message index
    TXA
    JSR     DISPLAY_MESSAGE   ; show damage message
    LDY     DAMAGE_AMOUNT
    LDX     #$04              ; tune 2: combat damage effect
    JSR     TUNE_PLAYER
    LDY     #$06
    LDA     (EFFECT_REC),Y    ; field 6 (HP + flags)
    TAX
    AND     #$3F              ; HP only
    SEC
    SBC     DAMAGE_AMOUNT     ; HP - damage
    BCC     .dead             ; underflow -> dead
    BEQ     .dead             ; zero -> dead
    STA     DAMAGE_AMOUNT     ; new HP
    TXA
    AND     #$C0              ; preserve high bits
    ORA     DAMAGE_AMOUNT
    STA     (EFFECT_REC),Y    ; store updated field 6
    JSR     SET_CURSOR_ROW21
    LDA     DAMAGE_AMOUNT
    BAPL    #$03,.check8
    LDY     #$0F
    LDA     (EFFECT_REC),Y    ; field 15
    AND     #$F8
    ORA     #$04              ; set restricted flag
    STA     (EFFECT_REC),Y
    JSR     PRINT_ENTITY_NAME
    LDA     #MSG_FEELING_WEAK
    JSR     DISPLAY_MESSAGE   ; "badly hurt" message
    RTS
.check8:
    BAPL    #$08,.ge8
    JSR     PRINT_ENTITY_NAME
    LDA     #MSG_LOTS_OF_FIGHT
    JMP     DISPLAY_MESSAGE   ; "wounded" message
.ge8:
    JSR     PRINT_ENTITY_NAME
    LDA     #MSG_HIT_WALL
    JMP     DISPLAY_MESSAGE   ; "scratched" message

    ; --- character dies ---
.dead:
    LDY     #$04
    LDA     (EFFECT_REC),Y    ; field 4
    LDX     #$08              ; tune 4: mob death effect
    BALT    #NPC_APPEARANCE_MIN,.skip_flag
    LDY     #$0F
    LDA     (EFFECT_REC),Y
    ORA     #$10              ; set death flag
    STA     (EFFECT_REC),Y
    LDX     #$0A              ; tune 5: NPC death effect
.skip_flag:
    TXA
    PHA
    JSR     PRINT_ENTITY_NAME
    LDA     #$03
    JSR     RANDOM_IN_RANGE   ; random(3)
    BAEQ    #$00,.rand0
    LDA     #$0E
    BNE     .show_death
.rand0:
    LDA     #$02
    JSR     RANDOM_IN_RANGE   ; random(2)
    CLC
    ADC     #$27              ; message $27 or $28
.show_death:
    JSR     DISPLAY_MESSAGE   ; death message
    PLA
    TAX
    JSR     TUNE_PLAYER     ; death tune
    STOB    #$00,ACTIVE_CHAR
    MOVB    CURRENT_PLAYER,SOURCE_CHAR
    MOVW    EFFECT_REC,TARGET_REC
    JSR     REORDER_CHAR      ; cleanup
    LDWIY    EFFECT_REC,#$0D,TARGET_REC ; gold low
    LDY     #$00
    JSR     MODIFY_CHAR_STATS ; subtract gold (Y=0 -> subtract)
    LDY     #$03
    LDA     (EFFECT_REC),Y
    JSR     UPDATE_EVENT_LIST ; handle death at position
    LDY     #$03
    LDA     (EFFECT_REC),Y
    JMP     DRAW_CHAR_AT_POS  ; redraw position
@ %def APPLY_DAMAGE
@ [[APPLY_DAMAGE_TO_CURRENT]] is a convenience wrapper that copies
[[ENTITY_PTR]] into [[EFFECT_REC]] and tail-calls [[APPLY_DAMAGE]] with the
damage amount in~A.  It saves and restores~A across the pointer setup using
the X~register as a temporary.

<<apply damage to current>>=
    ORG     $1425
APPLY_DAMAGE_TO_CURRENT:
    SUBROUTINE APPLY_DAMAGE_TO_CURRENT
    ; Apply effect: copy ENTITY_PTR/ENTITY_PTR+1 -> EFFECT_REC/EFFECT_REC+1, JMP $106F with A
    TAX
    MOVW    ENTITY_PTR,EFFECT_REC
    TXA
    JMP     APPLY_DAMAGE
@ %def APPLY_DAMAGE_TO_CURRENT
When the player steps onto an occupied cell, [[HANDLE_ENCOUNTER]] determines
what happens.  The event type (byte~1 of the event entry) splits the logic
into two paths.

For random encounters (type below [[$40]]), the character's avoidance stat
(low 5~bits of field~5) is compared against a random roll out of~20.  If the
stat is high enough, the encounter is avoided: the event is marked as
activated and the character returns to its starting position.  Otherwise a
second PRNG roll decides whether this is a normal encounter (tune [[$14]])
or a rare special encounter (scene~9, which deals 1~damage).

For specific encounters (type [[$40]] and above), the routine extracts a
6-bit encounter ID and a destination position from the event entry, commits
the move, reorders the character into the appropriate group, and updates the
character's position.  If the encounter ID is zero, it is derived from the
PRNG.

@ [[EVENT_DEST_POS]] holds the destination position from event byte 2
during specific encounters (type [[$40]] and above).  [[HANDLE_ENCOUNTER]]
writes the character's updated position from this variable after committing
the move and reordering the character.

<<defines>>=
EVENT_DEST_POS      EQU     $5A5F   ; event handler: destination position
@ %def EVENT_DEST_POS

@ [[EVENT_PTR]] is a 2-byte zero-page pointer at [[$BE/$BF]] that points
to the current event list entry.  [[HANDLE_ENCOUNTER]] reads the event
type from byte 1 and the destination from byte 2 through this pointer.

<<zero page defines>>=
EVENT_PTR               EQU     $BE     ; event list entry pointer (2 bytes)
@ %def EVENT_PTR

<<handle encounter>>=
    ORG     $1C01
HANDLE_ENCOUNTER:
    SUBROUTINE HANDLE_ENCOUNTER

    ; --- random encounter path (event type $00-$3F) ---
    LDA     #$00
    JSR     SET_CHAR_STATE             ; set char field 15 state to 0
    LDY     #$01
    LDA     (EVENT_PTR),Y              ; event byte 1 = type
    BAPL    #$40,.specific ; type >= $40 -> specific encounter
    LDA     #$14
    JSR     RANDOM_IN_RANGE            ; random(20)
    STA     PRNG_OUTPUT
    LDY     #$05
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y             ; char field 5
    AND     #$1F                       ; low 5 bits = avoidance stat
    BAMI    PRNG_OUTPUT,.roll_type ; stat < random -> encounter happens
    JMP     .avoided                   ; stat >= random -> avoid encounter
.roll_type:
    JSR     STEP_PRNG
    LDA     #$74
    BAPL    PRNG_OUTPUT,.normal ; $74 >= random -> normal encounter
    JMP     .special                   ; rare: special encounter
.normal:
    JSR     SET_CURSOR_ROW21
    LDA     #MSG_DOOR_OPENS
    JSR     DISPLAY_MESSAGE            ; "encounter" message
    LDX     #$14              ; tune 10: encounter effect
    JMP     TUNE_PLAYER

    ; --- specific encounter path (type >= $40) ---
.specific:
    LDY     #$00
    LDA     (EVENT_PTR),Y              ; event byte 0 = position
    STA     EVENT_POS
    LDA     #$01
    JSR     SET_CHAR_STATE             ; set state 1
    LDY     #$01
    LDA     (EVENT_PTR),Y
    AND     #$3F                       ; low 6 bits = encounter ID
    BNE     .have_id
    JSR     STEP_PRNG                  ; ID 0 -> derive from PRNG
    LDA     PRNG_OUTPUT
    ROR
    ROR
    AND     #$1C
    ORA     #$01
.have_id:
    STA     ACTIVE_CHAR                ; store encounter ID
    ROR
    BCC     .no_clear
    LDY     #$04
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y             ; char field 4
    BMI     .no_clear
    BAMI    #$2A,.no_clear
    BAPL    #$3F,.no_clear
    STOB    #$00,ACTIVE_CHAR ; clear ID if char in range $2A-$3E
.no_clear:
    LDY     #$02
    LDA     (EVENT_PTR),Y              ; event byte 2 = destination pos
    STA     EVENT_DEST_POS
    JSR     COMMIT_MOVE                ; commit move
    MOVB    $7ABE,WAIT_LOOP_COUNT
    JSR     REORDER_CURRENT_CHAR
    JSR     TIMED_WAIT
    LDY     #$03
    LDA     EVENT_DEST_POS
    STA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y             ; update char packed position
    LDA     ACTIVE_CHAR
    BAEQ    CURRENT_PLAYER,.same_scene ; compare encounter ID with current scene
    JMP     RESET_TURN_POS             ; different -> reset position
.same_scene:
    LDA     EVENT_DEST_POS
    JSR     POS_TO_COLROW
    STA     CURRENT_COL
    STY     CURRENT_ROW
    JMP     COMMIT_MOVE                ; commit to new position

    ; --- encounter avoided ---
.avoided:
    LDY     #$01
    LDA     (EVENT_PTR),Y
    ORA     #$40                       ; mark event as activated
    STA     (EVENT_PTR),Y
    MOVB    CURRENT_COL,TURN_START_COL
    MOVB    CURRENT_ROW,TURN_START_ROW
    JSR     RESET_TURN_POS             ; reset to turn start
    MOVB    TURN_START_COL,BLINK_COL
    MOVB    TURN_START_ROW,BLINK_ROW
    MOVB    FONT_CHARNUM,BLINK_CHAR
    LDX     #$0C              ; tune 6: combat avoided effect
    JSR     TUNE_PLAYER
    JSR     SET_CURSOR_ROW21
    LDA     #MSG_INSERT_DISK
    JMP     DISPLAY_MESSAGE            ; "avoided encounter" message

    ; --- special encounter (rare) ---
.special:
    JSR     SET_CURSOR_ROW21
    LDA     #$09
    JSR     SCENE_LOOP                 ; trigger scene 9
    LDA     #$01
    JMP     APPLY_DAMAGE_TO_CURRENT
@ %def HANDLE_ENCOUNTER
@ [[HANDLE_MOB_ENCOUNTER]] is called when a character's movement brings it
into contact with another entity.  It first evaluates the threat level at the
destination by calling [[SUM_HOSTILE_AT_POS]]: if any hostiles are present,
the routine computes a flee probability based on the character's strength
(field~5, low 5~bits) plus a base of~\$10, minus the total adjacent threat,
clamped to 4--\$1C.  This value is doubled twice (ASL, ASL) and OR'd with~3 to
produce a threshold; the PRNG is compared against it, and if the random value
exceeds the threshold, the character flees---the position is reset to the
turn's starting location and [[END_TURN]] is called.  If the character does
not flee (or there was no threat), [[COMMIT_MOVE]] updates the position.
The routine then calls [[CHECK_ENCOUNTER]]: if the result is below~2 (no
hostile), it checks [[CHECK_THREATS_HERE]] and either continues the movement
loop or ends the turn.  If hostiles are present (result $\geq$ 2), it walks
the target group's linked list and sets the restricted flag on every member
at the same position, displays an encounter message (\$1F), and ends the turn.

<<handle mob encounter>>=
    ORG     $1E5A
HANDLE_MOB_ENCOUNTER:
    SUBROUTINE HANDLE_MOB_ENCOUNTER
    ; Mob encounter on movement: check flee chance, commit move,
    ; check encounter type, walk group for combat.
    STOB    #$00,ADJACENT_THREAT
    MOVW    ENTITY_PTR,TARGET_REC
    LDA     CURRENT_COL
    LDY     CURRENT_ROW
    JSR     COLROW_TO_POS
    JSR     SUM_HOSTILE_AT_POS
    LDA     ADJACENT_THREAT
    BEQ     .no_flee
    LDY     #$05
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y
    AND     #$1F
    CLC
    ADC     #$10
    SEC
    SBC     ADJACENT_THREAT
    BMI     .clamp_low
    BAMI    #$1D,.in_range
    LDA     #$1C
    BNE     .in_range
.clamp_low:
    LDA     #$04
.in_range:
    ASL
    ASL
    ORA     #$03
    TAX
    JSR     STEP_PRNG
    TXA
    BAPL    PRNG_OUTPUT,.no_flee
    JSR     SET_CURSOR_ROW21
    JSR     PRINT_MOB_NAME
    JSR     SCROLL_STATUS_LINE
    LDA     #MSG_FLYING_TACKLE
    JSR     DISPLAY_MESSAGE
    MOVB    TURN_START_COL,CURRENT_COL
    MOVB    TURN_START_ROW,CURRENT_ROW
    JMP     END_TURN
.no_flee:
    JSR     COMMIT_MOVE
    LDY     #$03
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y
    JSR     CHECK_ENCOUNTER
    LDA     ENCOUNTER_RESULT
    BAPL    #$02,.hostile
    JSR     CHECK_THREATS_HERE
    BAEQ    #$01,.one_threat
    JMP     END_TURN
.one_threat:
    JMP     MOVE_LOOP
.hostile:
    JSR     FIRST_GROUP_MEMBER
.walk_group:
    LDA     MOB_PTR+1
    BEQ     .group_done
    LDY     #$03
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y
    CMP     (MOB_PTR),Y
    BNE     .next_member
    JSR     SET_TARGET_RESTRICTED
.next_member:
    JSR     NEXT_GROUP_MEMBER
    JMP     .walk_group
.group_done:
    JSR     SET_CURSOR_ROW21
    JSR     PRINT_MOB_NAME
    JSR     SCROLL_STATUS_LINE
    LDA     #MSG_UNCONSCIOUS
    JSR     DISPLAY_MESSAGE
    JMP     END_TURN
@ %def HANDLE_MOB_ENCOUNTER
@ [[HANDLE_EVENT_SLOT]] is the main interaction handler when a character steps
onto an event tile.  It resets the character to idle state, then reads byte~2
of the event entry and branches on its top two bits.  If the high bits
are~\$C0 (activated event), the low 5~bits give a sub-type: values below~\$1D
clear the event slot and optionally trigger scene~\$0A, then the character
commits the move, checks for adjacent threats, and continues the movement
loop.  If the event is not activated, the routine plays tune~\$0E, then
dispatches on the event's high-nibble type.  Type~\$00 (no special flag) with
a small sub-value displays a message and deals~1 damage; sub-values at~\$1B
or above trigger [[SHOW_LOCKED_MSG]].  Type~\$40 or above represents a
treasure chest: a strength check (field~5 vs.\ a random threshold) determines
whether the character can open it.  Failure displays a ``can't open'' message
and converts the event to type~\$40 for the next attempt, followed by a
trap-damage check at [[EVENT_PRNG_CHECK]].  Success with a small sub-value
triggers scene~\$13; larger sub-values show message~\$12 (``found treasure'')
and either clear the event slot or decrement a counter for multi-use
containers.  [[EVENT_PRNG_CHECK]] itself rolls the PRNG and, if the result is
below~\$14, applies 1--2 points of trap damage with the restricted flag set.

<<defines>>=
EVENT_SUB_VALUE EQU     $5A5A   ; lower 5 bits of event slot byte 2
EVENT_SLOT_BYTE EQU     $5A59   ; saved byte 2 of event slot (type+value)
@ %def EVENT_SUB_VALUE EVENT_SLOT_BYTE

<<handle event slot>>=
    ORG     $1D4D
HANDLE_EVENT_SLOT:
    SUBROUTINE HANDLE_EVENT_SLOT
    ; Handle empty slot interaction: treasure pickup, traps,
    ; and event activation.
    LDA     #$00
    JSR     SET_CHAR_STATE
    LDY     #$02
    LDA     (EVENT_PTR),Y
    STA     EVENT_SLOT_BYTE
    AND     #$C0
    BANE    #$C0,.not_active
    LDA     (EVENT_PTR),Y
    AND     #$1F
    TAX
    BAPL    #$1D,.no_remove
    LDY     #$00
    LDA     #$FE
    STA     (EVENT_PTR),Y
    TXA
    BAEQ    #$00,.no_remove
    LDA     #$0A
    JSR     SCENE_LOOP
.no_remove:
    JSR     COMMIT_MOVE
    JSR     CHECK_THREATS_HERE
    BANE    #$00,.has_threat
    STA     MOVE_POINTS
.has_threat:
    JMP     MOVE_LOOP
.not_active:
    PHA
    LDX     #$0E              ; tune 7: entity interaction
    JSR     TUNE_PLAYER
    PLA
    BANE    #$00,.has_type
    LDA     EVENT_SLOT_BYTE
    AND     #$1F
    BAMI    #$1B,.small_val
    JMP     SHOW_LOCKED_MSG
.small_val:
    JSR     SET_CURSOR_ROW21
    JSR     PRINT_MOB_NAME
    JSR     SCROLL_STATUS_LINE
    LDA     #MSG_DEATH
    JSR     DISPLAY_MESSAGE
    LDA     #$01
    JMP     APPLY_DAMAGE_TO_CURRENT
.has_type:
    BAEQ    #$40,.type40
    LDA     #$19
    JSR     RANDOM_IN_RANGE
    STA     PRNG_OUTPUT
    LDY     #$05
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y
    AND     #$1F
    BAPL    PRNG_OUTPUT,.type40
    JSR     SET_CURSOR_ROW21
    LDA     #MSG_HEAVY_ROCK
    JSR     DISPLAY_MESSAGE
    LDY     #$02
    LDA     EVENT_SLOT_BYTE
    AND     #$3F
    ORA     #$40
    STA     (EVENT_PTR),Y
EVENT_PRNG_CHECK:              ; $1DDC - external entry point
    JSR     STEP_PRNG
    LDA     PRNG_OUTPUT
    BAMI    #$14,.trap_damage
    RTS
.trap_damage:
    JSR     SET_CURSOR_ROW21
    LDA     #MSG_DUST_CLOUD
    JSR     DISPLAY_MESSAGE
    JSR     SET_RESTRICTED
    JSR     PRINT_MOB_NAME
    JSR     DELAY_WITH_ANIMATION
    JSR     STEP_PRNG
    LDA     PRNG_OUTPUT
    ROL2
    LDA     #$01
    ADC     #$00
    JMP     APPLY_DAMAGE_TO_CURRENT
.type40:
    LDA     EVENT_SLOT_BYTE
    AND     #$1F
    STA     EVENT_SUB_VALUE
    BAPL    #$1B,.big_treasure
    JSR     SET_CURSOR_ROW21
    LDA     #$13
    JSR     SCENE_LOOP
    JMP     .clear_slot
.big_treasure:
    JSR     SET_CURSOR_ROW21
    LDA     #MSG_TOPPLES
    JSR     DISPLAY_MESSAGE
    LDA     EVENT_SUB_VALUE
    BAMI    #$1F,.clear_slot
    DEC     EVENT_SUB_VALUE
    LDA     EVENT_SLOT_BYTE
    AND     #$E0
    ORA     EVENT_SUB_VALUE
    LDY     #$02
    STA     (EVENT_PTR),Y
    JMP     .update_pos
.clear_slot:
    LDY     #$00
    LDA     #$FE
    STA     (EVENT_PTR),Y
.update_pos:
    MOVB    CURRENT_COL,TURN_START_COL
    MOVB    CURRENT_ROW,TURN_START_ROW
    JSR     RESET_TURN_POS
    JSR     ANIM_TICK_AND_WAIT
    JMP     EVENT_PRNG_CHECK
@ %def HANDLE_EVENT_SLOT EVENT_PRNG_CHECK
@ [[SHOW_LOCKED_MSG]] displays message~\$0C (a ``locked'' or ``blocked''
notification), prints the mob's name for context, and resets the character's
turn state to~0 (idle).  This is called when a character attempts to interact
with an event slot that requires a higher strength or special item.

<<show locked msg>>=
    ORG     $1CF1
SHOW_LOCKED_MSG:
    SUBROUTINE SHOW_LOCKED_MSG
    ; Display message $0C and set char state to 0.
    JSR     SET_CURSOR_ROW21
    JSR     PRINT_MOB_NAME
    JSR     SCROLL_STATUS_LINE
    LDA     #MSG_HIT_STATUE
    JSR     DISPLAY_MESSAGE
    LDA     #$00
    JMP     SET_CHAR_STATE
@ %def SHOW_LOCKED_MSG
@ [[SET_TARGET_RESTRICTED]] sets bit~2 of field~15 on the mob record at
[[MOB_PTR]], marking that mob as movement-restricted.  This is used by
[[HANDLE_MOB_ENCOUNTER]] to pin down every hostile at the encounter position
so they cannot simply walk away.

<<set target restricted>>=
    ORG     $1F03
SET_TARGET_RESTRICTED:
    SUBROUTINE SET_TARGET_RESTRICTED
    LDY     #$0F
    LDA     (MOB_PTR),Y
    ORA     #$04
    STA     (MOB_PTR),Y
    RTS
@ %def SET_TARGET_RESTRICTED
