\section{Target selection}

@ [[SELECT_COMBAT_TARGET]] evaluates the battlefield to decide what the
current entity should fight.  It dispatches on [[CHAR_AI_MODE]] into three
paths.  For modes below~3 (``path low''), the routine checks [[STEPS_TAKEN]],
the encounter result, and adjacent threats; if any of these indicate combat,
it returns~2, otherwise it returns~4 (safe).  For modes 3--4 (``path mid''),
the routine walks the group's linked list looking for the hostile mob with the
highest threat score (via [[GET_ENTITY_THREAT]]), saving its pointer in
[[TARGET_PTR_LO]]/[[TARGET_PTR_HI]]; if a target is found, it returns~1
(attack ready).  For mode~5 and above (``path high''), it performs the same
walk but ranks targets by field~5 strength instead of threat score, again
returning~1 if a valid target is found.  If no hostile is found in the mid or
high paths, execution falls through to the low path for a final check.

@ [[BEST_THREAT]] accumulates the highest threat or strength score seen
so far while [[SELECT_COMBAT_TARGET]] iterates through group members.

<<defines>>=
BEST_THREAT     EQU     $5A88   ; best threat level during target selection
@ %def BEST_THREAT

@ [[TARGET_PTR_LO]] and [[TARGET_PTR_HI]] record the pointer to the
mob with the best score.  When [[SELECT_COMBAT_TARGET]] finishes and
returns 1 (attack ready), the caller uses these to load the target.

<<defines>>=
TARGET_PTR_LO   EQU     $5A86   ; selected combat target pointer (low byte)
TARGET_PTR_HI   EQU     $5A87   ; selected combat target pointer (high byte)
@ %def TARGET_PTR_LO TARGET_PTR_HI
@ [[GET_ENTITY_THREAT]] evaluates the threat level of the mob at [[MOB_PTR]]
relative to the current entity.  This is a stub---the full implementation has
not yet been disassembled.

<<get entity threat>>=
    ORG     $1979
GET_ENTITY_THREAT:
@ %def GET_ENTITY_THREAT

<<select combat target>>=
    ORG     $18E4
SELECT_COMBAT_TARGET:
    SUBROUTINE SELECT_COMBAT_TARGET
    ; Select a combat target for the current AI entity.
    ;
    ; Input:  CHAR_AI_MODE  — AI behavior mode (0-5+)
    ;         ENTITY_PTR    — current entity record
    ;         STEPS_TAKEN   — steps taken this turn
    ;
    ; Output: A = 1: target found (TARGET_PTR_LO/HI set)
    ;         A = 2: engage combat (no specific target)
    ;         A = 4: safe (no threats)
    ;
    ; Modifies: BEST_THREAT, TARGET_PTR_LO, TARGET_PTR_HI
    ; Clobbers: A, X, Y

    ; --- dispatch on AI mode ---
    LDA     CHAR_AI_MODE
    BAMI    #$03,.path_low         ; mode < 3 -> check encounter/threats
    BAMI    #$05,.path_mid         ; mode 3-4 -> pick highest-threat mob

    ; --- path high (mode >= 5): pick strongest mob ---
    JSR     FIRST_GROUP_MEMBER
    STOB    #$00,BEST_THREAT
.loop_high:
    JSR     GET_ENTITY_THREAT
    BAEQ    #$00,.skip_high        ; not hostile -> skip
    LDY     #MFIELD_STRENGTH
    LDA     (MOB_PTR),Y
    AND     #STRENGTH_MASK         ; strength (bits 4-0)
    BAMI    BEST_THREAT,.skip_high ; not stronger -> skip
    STA     BEST_THREAT            ; new best
    MOVB    MOB_PTR,TARGET_PTR_LO
    MOVB    MOB_PTR+1,TARGET_PTR_HI
.skip_high:
    JSR     NEXT_GROUP_MEMBER
    LDA     #$00
    BANE    MOB_PTR+1,.loop_high   ; more members -> continue
    BAEQ    BEST_THREAT,.path_low  ; no target -> fall through
    LDA     #$01                   ; target found
    RTS

    ; --- path low (mode < 3): check encounter and threats ---
.path_low:
    LDA     #$00
    BANE    STEPS_TAKEN,.ret_2     ; already moved -> engage
    LDY     #MFIELD_POSITION
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y        ; entity's map position
    JSR     CHECK_ENCOUNTER
    LDA     #$02
    BAEQ    ENCOUNTER_RESULT,.ret_2 ; encounter found -> engage
    JSR     CHECK_THREATS_HERE
    BANE    #$01,.ret_2            ; threats present -> engage
    LDA     #$04                   ; safe
    RTS
.ret_2:
    LDA     #$02                   ; engage combat
    RTS

    ; --- path mid (mode 3-4): pick highest-threat mob ---
.path_mid:
    STOB    #$00,BEST_THREAT
    JSR     FIRST_GROUP_MEMBER
.loop_mid:
    JSR     GET_ENTITY_THREAT
    BAEQ    BEST_THREAT,.skip_mid  ; threat == 0 -> skip
    BMI     .skip_mid              ; negative threat -> skip
    STA     BEST_THREAT            ; new best threat
    MOVB    MOB_PTR,TARGET_PTR_LO
    MOVB    MOB_PTR+1,TARGET_PTR_HI
.skip_mid:
    JSR     NEXT_GROUP_MEMBER
    LDA     #$00
    BANE    MOB_PTR+1,.loop_mid    ; more members -> continue
    BAEQ    BEST_THREAT,.path_low  ; no target -> fall through
    LDA     #$01                   ; target found
    RTS
@ %def SELECT_COMBAT_TARGET
@ [[LOAD_TARGET_PTR]] copies the pre-selected combat target address from
[[TARGET_PTR_LO]]/[[TARGET_PTR_HI]] into [[MOB_PTR]] and clears
[[IS_PLAYER_TURN]] to zero, indicating that the next attack sequence is from
the AI's perspective.  [[START_COMBAT]] calls this to set up [[MOB_PTR]]
before entering [[RESOLVE_ATTACK]].

<<load target ptr>>=
    ORG     $199D
LOAD_TARGET_PTR:
    SUBROUTINE LOAD_TARGET_PTR
    ; Load the pre-selected combat target into MOB_PTR.
    ;
    ; Input:  TARGET_PTR_LO/HI — saved target from SELECT_COMBAT_TARGET
    ; Output: MOB_PTR = target pointer, IS_PLAYER_TURN = 0
    ; Clobbers: A

    MOVB    TARGET_PTR_LO,MOB_PTR
    MOVB    TARGET_PTR_HI,MOB_PTR+1
    STOB    #$00,IS_PLAYER_TURN    ; AI's turn (not player)
    RTS
@ %def LOAD_TARGET_PTR
@ [[PROCESS_ENTITY_SCRIPT]] temporarily removes an entity from the map, runs
a tune, and restores it.  The routine saves the entity's byte~0 (position
character) from [[MOB_PTR]], overwrites it with~\$FE (marking the slot empty),
plays tune~\$0E via [[TUNE_PLAYER]], calls [[DISPATCH_ON_MODE]] for
timing/animation, and then redraws the original character at the entity's
position with [[DRAW_CHAR_AT_POS]].  This is used during event interactions
where the entity needs to be temporarily invisible---for example, when opening
a chest.

<<zero page defines>>=
SAVED_CHAR              EQU     $BA     ; scratch: saved entity display character
@ %def SAVED_CHAR

<<process entity script>>=
    ORG     $1849
PROCESS_ENTITY_SCRIPT:
    SUBROUTINE PROCESS_ENTITY_SCRIPT
    ; Temporarily hide an entity, play a tune, then restore it.
    ;
    ; Input:  MOB_PTR — entity record to process
    ; Behavior:
    ;   Saves display char (byte 0), marks slot empty ($FE),
    ;   plays interaction tune, dispatches animation, then
    ;   restores and redraws the entity.
    ; Modifies: SAVED_CHAR, MOB_PTR byte 0
    ; Clobbers: A, X, Y

    LDY     #MFIELD_CHAR           ; \ save display character
    LDA     (MOB_PTR),Y            ;  |
    STA     SAVED_CHAR             ; /
    LDA     #EVENT_EMPTY           ; mark slot empty ($FE)
    STA     (MOB_PTR),Y
    LDX     #$0E                   ; tune index: entity interaction
    JSR     TUNE_PLAYER
    JSR     DISPATCH_ON_MODE
    LDA     SAVED_CHAR             ; restore saved character
    JMP     DRAW_CHAR_AT_POS       ; redraw at entity position
@ %def PROCESS_ENTITY_SCRIPT
@ [[COPY_F4_TO_F6_AND_SET]] copies [[MOB_PTR]] into [[EFFECT_REC]] and
tail-calls [[APPLY_DAMAGE]] with the damage amount in~A.  This is the
counterpart to [[APPLY_DAMAGE_TO_CURRENT]]: where that routine applies
damage to the entity at [[ENTITY_PTR]], this one applies damage to the
mob at [[MOB_PTR]]---used during mob-on-player combat.

<<copy f4 to f6 and set>>=
    ORG     $1432
COPY_F4_TO_F6_AND_SET:
    SUBROUTINE COPY_F4_TO_F6_AND_SET
    ; Apply damage to the mob at MOB_PTR.
    ;
    ; Input:  A = damage amount, MOB_PTR = target mob
    ; Output: EFFECT_REC = MOB_PTR, jumps to APPLY_DAMAGE
    ; Clobbers: X

    TAX                            ; save damage value
    MOVW    MOB_PTR,EFFECT_REC     ; copy target pointer
    TXA                            ; restore damage value
    JMP     APPLY_DAMAGE
@ %def COPY_F4_TO_F6_AND_SET
@ [[ADD_WILLINGNESS]] is a tiny helper that adds~A (signed) to the
[[COMBAT_WILLINGNESS]] accumulator.  It exists as a separate routine because
[[RESOLVE_ATTACK]] calls it from many points during the willingness
calculation and inlining each addition would waste significant code space.

<<add willingness>>=
    ORG     $169B
ADD_WILLINGNESS:
    SUBROUTINE ADD_WILLINGNESS
    ; Add A to the combat willingness accumulator.
    ;
    ; Input:  A = willingness delta (signed)
    ; Output: COMBAT_WILLINGNESS += A
    ; Clobbers: A

    CLC
    ADC     COMBAT_WILLINGNESS
    STA     COMBAT_WILLINGNESS
    RTS
@ %def ADD_WILLINGNESS
@ [[PICK_RANDOM_MEMBER]] selects a random eligible member from the current
character's group.  It reads the group size from byte~8 of the record at
[[$FA]], calls [[RANDOM_IN_RANGE]] to pick a random index, and then walks
the group's linked list with [[FIRST_GROUP_MEMBER]]/[[NEXT_GROUP_MEMBER]],
counting down to the Nth member whose field~4 falls in the valid range
(\$00--\$14).  Members with negative field~4 values or values at~\$15 or above
are skipped.  If the random roll returns zero, the routine retries.  On
success, [[MOB_PTR]] points to the selected member's record; if the group is
empty, both bytes of [[MOB_PTR]] are zeroed as a ``not found'' sentinel.

<<pick random member>>=
    ORG     $12D0
PICK_RANDOM_MEMBER:
    SUBROUTINE PICK_RANDOM_MEMBER
    ; Pick a random player character from the current group.
    ;
    ; Input:  CHAR_PTR — group leader's character record
    ; Output: MOB_PTR  — selected member (zeroed if empty group)
    ;
    ; Behavior:
    ;   Reads group size from CFIELD_XP (byte 8 bits 3-0), picks
    ;   a random index, then walks the linked list skipping dead
    ;   (bit 7 set) and NPC (appearance >= $15) members until the
    ;   Nth eligible member is found.  Retries if random index = 0.
    ;
    ; Modifies: MOB_PTR
    ; Clobbers: A, X, Y

.loop:
    LDY     #CFIELD_XP             ; byte 8: group count in bits 3-0
    LDA     (CHAR_PTR),Y
    BEQ     .zero                  ; empty group
    JSR     RANDOM_IN_RANGE        ; random(size)
    BAEQ    #$00,.loop             ; 0 -> retry
    TAX                            ; X = count down to Nth
    JSR     FIRST_GROUP_MEMBER
.check:
    LDY     #MFIELD_APPEARANCE     ; byte 4: appearance index
    LDA     (MOB_PTR),Y
    BMI     .next                  ; bit 7 set -> dead/invalid, skip
    BAPL    #NPC_APPEARANCE_MIN,.next             ; >= $15 -> NPC, skip
    DEX
    BNE     .next                  ; not Nth yet
    RTS                            ; found
.next:
    JSR     NEXT_GROUP_MEMBER
    JMP     .check
.zero:
    STA     MOB_PTR                ; \ clear pointer (A=0 from BEQ)
    STA     MOB_PTR+1              ; /
    RTS
@ %def PICK_RANDOM_MEMBER

\section{Combat utilities}

@ [[MAP_VALUE_TO_STRING]] converts a numeric value in~A into a descriptive
string for display.  Values 0--7 map directly to string indices; values
8--15 are compressed (ROR, AND~\$03, ORA~\$08) into indices 8--11; and
values 16+ are further compressed into indices 12--15.  The routine then
walks a linked list of length-prefixed strings starting at~\$803A, advancing
by each string's length byte until the target index is reached, and
tail-calls [[PRINT_BOTTOM_CENTERED]] to display it.  This provides combat
messages that scale with the magnitude of the value---for example, mapping
low damage to ``scratches'' and high damage to ``devastating blow.''


<<map value to string>>=
    ORG     $11FC
MAP_VALUE_TO_STRING:
    SUBROUTINE MAP_VALUE_TO_STRING
    ; Map a damage/effect value to a verb string and display it.
    ;
    ; Input:  A = numeric value (damage level)
    ; Output: displays the corresponding verb string
    ;
    ; Behavior:
    ;   Values 0-7 map directly to string indices 0-7.
    ;   Values 8-15 compress to indices 8-11.
    ;   Values 16+ compress to indices 12-15.
    ;   Walks the ATTACK_VERB_STRINGS list to find the
    ;   Nth entry and prints it via PRINT_BOTTOM_CENTERED.
    ;
    ; Modifies: PRINT_STRING_ADDR
    ; Clobbers: A, X, Y

    ; --- map value to string index ---
    BAMI    #$08,.use_as_is        ; < 8 -> use directly
    BAPL    #$10,.high_range       ; < 16 -> mid range
    ROR                            ; \ compress bits 2-1
    AND     #$03                   ;  | to 2-bit index
    ORA     #$08                   ; / -> index 8-11
    BNE     .use_as_is
.high_range:
    ROR                            ; \ compress bits 4-3
    ROR                            ;  | to 2-bit index
    AND     #$03                   ;  |
    ORA     #$0C                   ; / -> index 12-15
.use_as_is:
    TAX                            ; X = string index

    ; --- walk string list to Xth entry ---
    STOW    ATTACK_VERB_STRINGS,PRINT_STRING_ADDR
    LDY     #$00
.loop:
    DEX
    BNE     .next                  ; not there yet
    JMP     PRINT_BOTTOM_CENTERED  ; print and return
.next:
    SEC                            ; \ advance ptr by length + 1
    LDA     (PRINT_STRING_ADDR),Y  ;  | (length byte)
    ADC     PRINT_STRING_ADDR      ;  |
    STA     PRINT_STRING_ADDR      ;  |
    LDA     #$00                   ;  |
    ADC     PRINT_STRING_ADDR+1    ;  |
    STA     PRINT_STRING_ADDR+1    ; /
    BNE     .loop
@ %def MAP_VALUE_TO_STRING
@ [[AUTO_HEAL]] provides passive healing for characters between combat turns.
If the entity's HP (field~6, low 6~bits) is below~\$28 (40~decimal), there is
a random chance of healing: [[RANDOM_IN_RANGE]] with argument~1 gives a 50\%
chance of initiating the process.  Once started, the routine enters a loop
that increments HP via [[INCREMENT_HP]] and continues as long as the PRNG
output is at or above~\$50---so healing stops probabilistically, with each
additional point becoming less likely.  For player characters (field~4 below
\$15), the routine displays a ``healed'' message the first time, controlled by
the [[HEAL_NOTIFIED]] flag to avoid repeating the notification on subsequent
HP increments.

<<defines>>=
HEAL_NOTIFIED       EQU     $5A16   ; auto heal: nonzero = already printed heal message
@ %def HEAL_NOTIFIED

<<auto heal>>=
    ORG     $143F
AUTO_HEAL:
    SUBROUTINE AUTO_HEAL
    ; Randomly restore HP for injured entities.
    ;
    ; Input:  ENTITY_PTR — entity record
    ; Behavior:
    ;   If HP (byte 6, bits 5-0) < 40, 50% chance to start
    ;   healing.  Loops incrementing HP while PRNG >= $50.
    ;   For player characters (appearance < $15), displays
    ;   MSG_REGAIN_CONSC the first time.
    ; Modifies: HEAL_NOTIFIED, entity byte 6
    ; Clobbers: A, X, Y

    LDY     #MFIELD_MOB_TYPE       ; byte 6: HP in bits 5-0
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y
    AND     #HP_MASK               ; isolate HP (bits 5-0)
    BAMI    #$28,.do_heal          ; HP < 40 -> try healing
    RTS
.do_heal:
    LDA     #$01
    JSR     RANDOM_IN_RANGE        ; 50% chance
    BANE    #$00,.start_heal       ; nonzero -> proceed
    RTS
.start_heal:
    STOB    #$00,HEAL_NOTIFIED     ; clear notification flag
.heal_loop:
    JSR     INCREMENT_HP           ; +1 HP
    JSR     STEP_PRNG
    LDA     PRNG_OUTPUT
    BAPL    #$50,.heal_loop        ; keep healing while PRNG < $50
    LDY     #MFIELD_APPEARANCE     ; check if player character
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y
    BALT    #NPC_APPEARANCE_MIN,.player           ; appearance < $15 -> player
.done:
    RTS
.player:
    LDA     HEAL_NOTIFIED          ; already notified?
    BNE     .done
    JSR     SET_CURSOR_ROW21
    JSR     PRINT_MOB_NAME
    JSR     SCROLL_STATUS_LINE
    LDA     #MSG_REGAIN_CONSC      ; "struggles back to consciousness"
    JMP     DISPLAY_MESSAGE
@ %def AUTO_HEAL
@ [[INCREMENT_HP]] adds~1 to the entity's field~6 (which holds HP in its low
6~bits along with flags in the upper 2).  Since the HP value is less than~63,
a simple ADC~\$01 on the full byte works without disturbing the flag bits.
When the masked HP reaches exactly~3---the threshold at which a character is
no longer ``badly hurt''---the routine notifies the player by printing the
mob's name and displaying message~\$22, and sets [[HEAL_NOTIFIED]] to prevent
[[AUTO_HEAL]] from showing its own separate notification.

<<increment hp>>=
    ORG     $1482
INCREMENT_HP:
    SUBROUTINE INCREMENT_HP
    ; Add 1 to entity's HP; notify when HP reaches 3.
    ;
    ; Input:  ENTITY_PTR — entity record
    ; Behavior:
    ;   Increments byte 6 (HP in bits 5-0).  When HP
    ;   reaches exactly 3 (no longer "badly hurt"), prints
    ;   the entity name and sets HEAL_NOTIFIED = $22
    ;   (which also serves as the message number for
    ;   DISPLAY_MESSAGE via fall-through).
    ; Modifies: entity byte 6, HEAL_NOTIFIED
    ; Clobbers: A, Y

    LDY     #MFIELD_MOB_TYPE       ; byte 6: HP in bits 5-0
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y
    CLC
    ADC     #$01                   ; HP += 1
    STA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y
    AND     #HP_MASK               ; isolate HP (bits 5-0)
    BAEQ    #$03,.notify           ; HP == 3 -> threshold crossed
    RTS
.notify:
    JSR     SET_CURSOR_ROW21
    JSR     PRINT_MOB_NAME
    JSR     SCROLL_STATUS_LINE
    STOB    #$22,HEAL_NOTIFIED     ; mark notified (A=$22 = message)
    JMP     DISPLAY_MESSAGE
@ %def INCREMENT_HP
@ [[MODIFY_CHAR_STATS]] is the low-level gold modification routine.  It
operates on the character record at [[EFFECT_REC]], adding or subtracting the
16-bit value in [[NUM_VALUE]]/[[NUM_VALUE+1]] to fields~13--14 (the gold
counter).  The direction is controlled by~Y on entry: Y=0 subtracts,
Y$\neq$0 adds.  After modifying gold, the routine recomputes field~\$0C,
which encodes a derived level/XP value.  The recomputation uses field~5
(shifted left 3~bits) as a scaling factor and iterates through a level
progression, comparing accumulated thresholds against the character's gold
(fields~13--14) to determine the appropriate level encoding.

<<defines>>=
STAT_SCALE          EQU     $5A7E   ; strength-derived level threshold step
STAT_LEVEL_BITS     EQU     $5A7F   ; level bits during stat modification
@ %def STAT_SCALE STAT_LEVEL_BITS

<<zero page defines>>=
LEVEL_THRESHOLD     EQU     $BA     ; 16-bit level threshold accumulator (2 bytes)
@ %def LEVEL_THRESHOLD

<<modify char stats>>=
    ORG     $704D
MODIFY_CHAR_STATS:
    SUBROUTINE MODIFY_CHAR_STATS
    ; Modify gold and recompute level encoding.
    ;
    ; Input:  EFFECT_REC     — pointer to entity record
    ;         NUM_VALUE+0/+1 — 16-bit gold amount
    ;         Y              — 0 = subtract, nonzero = add
    ;
    ; Output: bytes $0D/$0E (gold) updated,
    ;         byte $0C (level encoding) recomputed
    ;
    ; Modifies: STAT_SCALE, STAT_LEVEL_BITS, LEVEL_THRESHOLD/HI
    ; Clobbers: A, X, Y

    ; --- add or subtract gold ---
    BYEQ    #$00,.subtract
    LDY     #MFIELD_GOLD_LO        ; \ add NUM_VALUE to gold
    LDA     (EFFECT_REC),Y         ;  |
    CLC                            ;  |
    ADC     NUM_VALUE              ;  |
    STA     (EFFECT_REC),Y         ;  |
    INY                            ;  | Y = MFIELD_GOLD_HI
    LDA     (EFFECT_REC),Y         ;  |
    ADC     NUM_VALUE+1            ;  |
    STA     (EFFECT_REC),Y         ; /
    JMP     .aftermath
.subtract:
    LDY     #MFIELD_GOLD_LO        ; \ subtract NUM_VALUE from gold
    SEC                            ;  |
    LDA     (EFFECT_REC),Y         ;  |
    SBC     NUM_VALUE              ;  |
    STA     (EFFECT_REC),Y         ;  |
    INY                            ;  | Y = MFIELD_GOLD_HI
    LDA     (EFFECT_REC),Y         ;  |
    SBC     NUM_VALUE+1            ;  |
    STA     (EFFECT_REC),Y         ; /

    ; --- recompute level encoding from gold and strength ---
.aftermath:
    LDY     #MFIELD_STRENGTH       ; \ compute threshold step
    LDA     (EFFECT_REC),Y         ;  | from strength (bits 4-0)
    ROL2                           ;  | shift left 3 bits
    ROL                            ;  |
    AND     #$F8                   ;  |
    STA     STAT_SCALE             ; /
    LDY     #MFIELD_LEVEL_ENC      ; \ unpack current level encoding
    LDA     (EFFECT_REC),Y         ;  |
    PHA                            ;  |
    AND     #$0F                   ;  | X = low nibble (base level)
    TAX                            ;  |
    PLA                            ;  |
    ROR                            ;  | \ extract high nibble
    ROR                            ;  |  | (XP multiplier)
    ROR                            ;  |  |
    ROR                            ;  | /
    AND     #$0F                   ;  |
    TAY                            ; / Y = high nibble
.decy:
    DEY                            ; \ add high nibble to base level
    BMI     .done_cnt              ;  |
    INX                            ;  |
    BPL     .decy                  ; /
.done_cnt:
    INY                            ; Y = 0
    STY     STAT_LEVEL_BITS        ; init level bits accumulator
    STY     LEVEL_THRESHOLD        ; \ init 16-bit threshold
    STY     LEVEL_THRESHOLD+1     ; / accumulator to 0
.outer_loop:
    LDY     #MFIELD_GOLD_HI
    BXEQ    #$00,.store_final      ; no levels remain -> store
    CLC                            ; \ add STAT_SCALE to threshold
    LDA     LEVEL_THRESHOLD        ;  |
    ADC     STAT_SCALE             ;  |
    STA     LEVEL_THRESHOLD        ;  |
    BCC     .no_carry              ;  |
    INC     LEVEL_THRESHOLD+1     ; /
.no_carry:
    LDA     (EFFECT_REC),Y         ; gold high byte
    BALT    LEVEL_THRESHOLD+1,.store_final ; gold_hi < thresh_hi -> done
    BNE     .next_iter             ; gold_hi > thresh_hi -> next
    DEY                            ; Y = MFIELD_GOLD_LO
    LDA     (EFFECT_REC),Y         ; gold low byte
    BALT    LEVEL_THRESHOLD,.store_final ; gold_lo < thresh_lo -> done
.next_iter:
    DEX                            ; one fewer level
    CLC                            ; \ advance level bits by $10
    LDA     STAT_LEVEL_BITS        ;  | (one level in high nibble)
    ADC     #$10                   ;  |
    STA     STAT_LEVEL_BITS        ; /
    BNE     .outer_loop
.store_final:
    TXA                            ; remaining levels = low nibble
    ORA     STAT_LEVEL_BITS        ; merge with level bits
    LDY     #MFIELD_LEVEL_ENC
    STA     (EFFECT_REC),Y         ; store recomputed encoding
    RTS
@ %def MODIFY_CHAR_STATS
@ [[MODIFY_CURRENT_STATS]] copies [[ENTITY_PTR]] into [[EFFECT_REC]] and
tail-calls [[MODIFY_CHAR_STATS]], which performs a treasure table lookup and
applies the stat modification to the target character.  This wrapper allows
callers to apply treasure effects to the current entity without manually
setting up the effect record pointer.

<<modify current stats>>=
    ORG     $70D4
MODIFY_CURRENT_STATS:
    SUBROUTINE MODIFY_CURRENT_STATS
    ; Wrapper: modify stats for the current entity.
    ;
    ; Input:  ENTITY_PTR — current entity
    ;         NUM_VALUE  — amount, Y — direction (see MODIFY_CHAR_STATS)
    ; Clobbers: A, X, Y

    MOVW    ENTITY_PTR,EFFECT_REC  ; copy entity ptr to effect rec
    JMP     MODIFY_CHAR_STATS      ; tail-call
@ %def MODIFY_CURRENT_STATS

\chapter{NPC AI}

@ [[AI_CHOOSE_TARGET]] is the decision-making hub for NPC and mob turns.  It
selects a map position for the entity to move toward, based on the AI mode
stored in [[CHAR_AI_MODE]].  Six modes are supported.  Modes~0 and~1 check
whether an NPC should join the player's party: [[PICK_RANDOM_MEMBER]] selects
a candidate, and if one is found, the game displays a ``joins party'' message,
merges the NPC's status flags into the party record, increments the group
count, and switches the character to player control (mode~0).  Mode~2 compares
the entity's offense and defense stats; if offense dominates, it calls
[[FIND_NEAREST_EVENT]] to locate the closest event on the map and targets that
position.  Mode~3 searches for the nearest hostile mob by iterating through
group members with [[CHECK_HOSTILE]] and [[MANHATTAN_DISTANCE]], keeping track
of the closest one found; if none are hostile, it falls back to a default
position.  Mode~4 produces no target at all---the entity stays put.  Mode~5
and above seek the \emph{strongest} hostile instead of the nearest, iterating
the group and tracking the highest strength value in [[AI_BEST_STR]].  After
target selection, all modes converge at a common exit that unpacks the target
position into column and row via [[POS_TO_COLROW]].

@ [[AI_PREV_DIR]] stores the last direction the NPC moved, used by
[[NPC_MOVE_AI]] as a bias to encourage straight-line travel.
[[AI_TARGET_POS]] is the packed map position that [[AI_CHOOSE_TARGET]]
selects as the destination, and [[AI_TARGET_COL]] holds the column
component after unpacking.

<<defines>>=
AI_PREV_DIR         EQU     $5A5D   ; NPC AI: previous move direction (bias avoidance)
AI_TARGET_COL   EQU     $5A72   ; AI target column / min distance temp
AI_TARGET_POS   EQU     $5A71   ; AI target position (set by AI_CHOOSE_TARGET)
@ %def AI_PREV_DIR AI_TARGET_COL AI_TARGET_POS

@ [[AI_BEST_POS]] and [[AI_BEST_STR]] are zero-page temporaries at
[[$BE]] and [[$BF]] that [[AI_CHOOSE_TARGET]] uses in mode 5 to track
the strongest hostile mob found during the group iteration.

<<zero page defines>>=
AI_SCRATCH              EQU     $BA     ; scratch byte in AI_CHOOSE_TARGET
AI_BEST_POS             EQU     $BE     ; best hostile position in ai_choose_target
AI_BEST_STR             EQU     $BF     ; best hostile strength in ai_choose_target
@ %def AI_SCRATCH AI_BEST_POS AI_BEST_STR

<<defines>>=
AI_TARGET_ROW       EQU     $5A73   ; AI target row (from POS_TO_COLROW)
@ %def AI_TARGET_ROW

<<ai choose target>>=
    ORG     $68AB
AI_CHOOSE_TARGET:
    SUBROUTINE AI_CHOOSE_TARGET
    ; Select a movement target for an NPC based on its AI mode.
    ;
    ; Input:  ENTITY_PTR    — NPC entity record
    ;         CHAR_PTR      — character index record
    ;         MOB_PTR       — mob data pointer (set by group iteration)
    ;         CHAR_AI_MODE  — AI behavior mode (0-5+)
    ;
    ; Output: AI_TARGET_POS — packed position of chosen target
    ;         AI_TARGET_COL — target column
    ;         AI_TARGET_ROW — target row
    ;         AI_PREV_DIR   — cleared to 0
    ;
    ; Behavior:
    ;   Mode 0/1: attempt to join player's party; if no match,
    ;     fall through to mode 2.
    ;   Mode 2: if strength > mob type, target nearest event;
    ;     otherwise no target.
    ;   Mode 3: scan group for nearest hostile mob.
    ;   Mode 4: no target (forced movement by NPC_MOVE_AI).
    ;   Mode 5+: scan group for strongest hostile mob.
    ;
    ; Modifies: AI_TARGET_POS, AI_TARGET_COL, AI_TARGET_ROW,
    ;           AI_PREV_DIR, AI_BEST_POS, AI_BEST_STR, TARGET_REC
    ; Clobbers: A, X, Y

    ; --- dispatch by AI mode ---
    STOB    #$00,AI_PREV_DIR
    LDA     CHAR_AI_MODE
    BAPL    #$02,.mode_ge2

    ; --- mode 0/1: check if NPC should join party ---
    JSR     PICK_RANDOM_MEMBER
    LDA     MOB_PTR+1
    BAEQ    #$00,.simple_target    ; no match -> simple target
    JSR     SET_CURSOR_ROW21
    LDA     #MSG_JOINS_PARTY                   ; "joins party" message
    JSR     DISPLAY_MESSAGE
    JSR     PRINT_MEMBER_NAME
    JSR     SCROLL_STATUS_LINE
    JSR     DELAY_WITH_ANIMATION
    LDA     #MSG_THANK_YOU                   ; confirmation message
    JSR     DISPLAY_MESSAGE
    STOB    #$00,CHAR_AI_MODE      ; switch to player control
    LDY     #MFIELD_APPEARANCE     ; \ adjust appearance (remove NPC flag)
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y         ;  |
    SEC                            ;  |
    SBC     #NPC_APPEARANCE_MIN                   ;  |
    STA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y         ; /
    LDY     #MFIELD_FLAGS          ; \ copy class bits (7-6) from source
    LDA     (MOB_PTR),Y            ;  | to entity's flags field
    AND     #FLAGS_CLASS_MASK      ;  |
    STA     AI_SCRATCH             ;  |
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y         ;  |
    AND     #FLAGS_STATUS_MASK     ;  | keep status bits (5-0)
    ORA     AI_SCRATCH             ;  | merge class bits from source
    STA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y         ; /
    LDY     #CFIELD_XP             ; \ increment party size in group record
    LDA     (CHAR_PTR),Y           ;  |
    CLC                            ;  |
    ADC     #$01                   ;  |
    STA     (CHAR_PTR),Y           ; /
    INC     TOTAL_MOB_COUNT        ; increment global count
    RTS

    ; --- mode 2: compare strength vs mob type for target ---
.mode_ge2:
    BNE     .mode_ge3
.simple_target:
    LDY     #MFIELD_STRENGTH       ; strength (bits 4-0)
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y
    AND     #STRENGTH_MASK
    STA     AI_SCRATCH
    INY                            ; Y = MFIELD_MOB_TYPE
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y        ; mob type (bits 5-0)
    AND     #MOB_TYPE_MASK
    BAPL    AI_SCRATCH,.use_encounter ; mob type >= strength -> seek encounter
    STOB    #$00,AI_TARGET_POS     ; no target
    JMP     .done
.use_encounter:
    JSR     FIND_NEAREST_EVENT
    STA     AI_TARGET_POS
    JMP     .done

    ; --- mode 3: find nearest hostile ---
.mode_ge3:
    BAPL    #$04,.mode_ge4
    MOVW    ENTITY_PTR,TARGET_REC
    STOB    #$3C,AI_TARGET_COL     ; initial min distance = 60
    JSR     FIRST_GROUP_MEMBER
.loop3:
    JSR     CHECK_HOSTILE
    BAEQ    #$00,.skip3            ; not hostile -> skip
    LDY     #MFIELD_POSITION
    LDA     (MOB_PTR),Y
    JSR     MANHATTAN_DISTANCE
    BAGE    AI_TARGET_COL,.skip3   ; not closer -> skip
    STA     AI_TARGET_COL          ; new minimum distance
    LDY     #MFIELD_POSITION
    LDA     (MOB_PTR),Y
    STA     AI_TARGET_POS          ; target = this mob's position
.skip3:
    JSR     NEXT_GROUP_MEMBER
    LDA     MOB_PTR+1
    BNE     .loop3
    LDA     AI_TARGET_COL
    BANE    #$3C,.found3           ; found one (distance changed from $3C)
    MOVB    EVENT_POS,AI_TARGET_POS ; no hostile -> fallback to event
.found3:
    JMP     .done

    ; --- mode 4: no target (forced movement) ---
.mode_ge4:
    BNE     .mode_gt4
    STOB    #$00,AI_TARGET_POS
    JMP     .done

    ; --- mode 5+: find strongest hostile ---
.mode_gt4:
    STOB    #$00,AI_BEST_STR       ; max strength seen = 0
    MOVW    ENTITY_PTR,TARGET_REC
    JSR     FIRST_GROUP_MEMBER
.loop5:
    JSR     CHECK_HOSTILE
    BAEQ    #$00,.skip5            ; not hostile -> skip
    LDY     #MFIELD_STRENGTH
    LDA     (MOB_PTR),Y
    AND     #STRENGTH_MASK         ; strength (bits 4-0)
    BAMI    AI_BEST_STR,.skip5     ; not stronger -> skip
    STA     AI_BEST_STR            ; new max strength
    LDY     #MFIELD_POSITION
    LDA     (MOB_PTR),Y
    STA     AI_BEST_POS            ; record position
.skip5:
    JSR     NEXT_GROUP_MEMBER
    LDA     MOB_PTR+1
    BNE     .loop5
    LDA     AI_BEST_STR
    BEQ     .no_target5            ; none found
    MOVB    AI_BEST_POS,AI_TARGET_POS
    JMP     .done
.no_target5:
    MOVB    EVENT_POS,AI_TARGET_POS ; fallback to event
    JMP     .done

    ; --- convert target to col/row ---
.done:
    LDA     AI_TARGET_POS
    JSR     POS_TO_COLROW
    STA     AI_TARGET_COL
    STY     AI_TARGET_ROW
    RTS
@ %def AI_CHOOSE_TARGET
@ [[NPC_MOVE_AI]] implements the movement decision for AI-controlled
characters.  It evaluates five options---north, south, west, east, and
stay---by assigning each a score and selecting the lowest.  The base score
starts at~\$0A (or \$13 if the AI has a non-zero target), and the previous
direction gets a bonus of~+3 to encourage straight-line movement.  Each
candidate direction is tested by [[EVALUATE_DIRECTION]], which computes a
score based on map tile traversability, distance to the target, and threat
assessment.  A randomization step multiplies each score by~4 (ROL twice) and
adds a random value (range~6 normally, range~\$0F in AI mode~4) to break
ties unpredictably.  The direction with the lowest final score wins.  The
chosen direction index is XOR'd with~3 or~7 (depending on whether it is
below~3) to convert from the internal direction numbering to the movement
encoding expected by the caller.

@ [[DIR_SCORES]] is a 5-byte array holding the score for each direction
(indices 0--4: stay, north, south, west, east).  [[AI_DIRECTION]] is the
index currently being evaluated, and [[AI_TEST_POS]] holds the candidate
position for that direction.  [[NPC_MOVE_AI]] fills the array, randomizes
the scores, and picks the direction with the lowest value.

<<defines>>=
AI_TEST_POS     EQU     $5A70   ; position being tested for direction evaluation
AI_DIRECTION    EQU     $5A6F   ; current direction being evaluated / random range
DIR_SCORES      EQU     $5A6A   ; array of 5 direction scores (indexed 0-4)
@ %def AI_TEST_POS AI_DIRECTION DIR_SCORES

<<defines>>=
MAP_WIDTH           EQU     $14     ; map grid width (20 columns)
AI_RANDOM_NORMAL    EQU     $06     ; randomization range for normal AI
AI_RANDOM_PHASE4    EQU     $0F     ; randomization range for phase 4 AI
@ %def MAP_WIDTH AI_RANDOM_NORMAL AI_RANDOM_PHASE4

<<zero page defines>>=
AI_MIN_SCORE        EQU     $BA     ; best (lowest) score during direction selection
AI_BEST_DIR         EQU     $BB     ; direction index with best score
@ %def AI_MIN_SCORE AI_BEST_DIR

<<npc move ai>>=
    ORG     $6742
NPC_MOVE_AI:
    SUBROUTINE NPC_MOVE_AI
    ; Choose a movement direction for an NPC entity.
    ;
    ; Input:  ENTITY_PTR     — entity to move
    ;         CHAR_AI_MODE   — AI mode ($04 = forced movement)
    ;         AI_TARGET_POS  — desired target position (0 = none)
    ;         AI_PREV_DIR    — previous direction (penalized to avoid loops)
    ;
    ; Output: A = chosen direction index (0-4)
    ;         AI_PREV_DIR updated
    ;
    ; Behavior:
    ;   Initializes DIR_SCORES for 5 options (stay + 4 directions).
    ;   Evaluates each direction via EVALUATE_DIRECTION, which penalizes
    ;   walls, entities, and non-improving moves.  Scores are scaled,
    ;   randomized, and the lowest-scoring direction is chosen.  The
    ;   result is XOR-encoded to produce a direction value.
    ;
    ; Modifies: DIR_SCORES, AI_DIRECTION, AI_TEST_POS, AI_BEST_DIST,
    ;           AI_SAVED_POS, AI_MIN_SCORE, AI_BEST_DIR, AI_PREV_DIR
    ; Clobbers: A, X, Y

    JSR     ANIM_TICK_AND_WAIT

    ; --- check if AI should run ---
    LDA     CHAR_AI_MODE
    BAEQ    #$04,.do_ai            ; mode 4 = forced movement
    LDA     AI_TARGET_POS
    BANE    #$00,.do_ai            ; has target -> run AI
    RTS                            ; no target, not forced -> skip

    ; --- initialize direction scores ---
.do_ai:
    STOB    #$00,DIR_SCORES+1      ; \ clear scores for 4 directions
    STA     DIR_SCORES+2           ;  |
    STA     DIR_SCORES+3           ;  |
    STA     DIR_SCORES+4           ; /
    STOB    #$0A,DIR_SCORES        ; stay score = 10 (mild penalty)
    LDA     AI_TARGET_POS
    JSR     MANHATTAN_DISTANCE
    STA     AI_BEST_DIST           ; current distance to target
    BAEQ    #$00,.no_target
    STOB    #$13,DIR_SCORES        ; stay score = 19 (strong penalty if has target)
.no_target:
    LDX     AI_PREV_DIR            ; \ penalize previous direction (+3)
    BEQ     .no_prev               ;  | to avoid back-and-forth loops
    INC     DIR_SCORES,X           ;  |
    INC     DIR_SCORES,X           ;  |
    INC     DIR_SCORES,X           ; /
.no_prev:

    ; --- evaluate 4 directions ---
    STOB    #$01,AI_DIRECTION      ; direction 1: up
    LDY     #MFIELD_POSITION
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y
    SEC
    SBC     #MAP_WIDTH             ; position - 20 = one row up
    STA     AI_TEST_POS
    JSR     EVALUATE_DIRECTION

    INC     AI_DIRECTION           ; direction 2: down
    LDA     AI_TEST_POS
    CLC
    ADC     #MAP_WIDTH*2           ; position + 20 = one row down (from up)
    STA     AI_TEST_POS
    JSR     EVALUATE_DIRECTION

    INC     AI_DIRECTION           ; direction 3: left
    LDA     AI_TEST_POS
    SEC
    SBC     #MAP_WIDTH+1           ; back to center, then -1 = one col left
    STA     AI_TEST_POS
    JSR     EVALUATE_DIRECTION

    INC     AI_DIRECTION           ; direction 4: right
    INC     AI_TEST_POS            ; \ position + 2 = one col right (from left)
    INC     AI_TEST_POS            ; /
    JSR     EVALUATE_DIRECTION

    ; --- scale scores and add randomness ---
    STOB    #AI_RANDOM_NORMAL,AI_DIRECTION ; reuse AI_DIRECTION as random range
    LDA     CHAR_AI_MODE
    BANE    #$04,.not_phase4
    STOB    #AI_RANDOM_PHASE4,AI_DIRECTION ; wider randomness in phase 4
.not_phase4:
    LDX     #$04
    CLC
.score_loop:
    LDA     DIR_SCORES,X           ; \ scale score x4
    ROL2                           ; /
    STA     DIR_SCORES,X
    LDA     AI_DIRECTION           ; random range
    JSR     RANDOM_IN_RANGE
    CLC
    ADC     DIR_SCORES,X           ; add random offset
    STA     DIR_SCORES,X
    DEX
    BPL     .score_loop

    ; --- find direction with lowest score ---
    STOB    #$7F,AI_MIN_SCORE      ; initial min = 127
    LDX     #$04
.find_min:
    LDA     DIR_SCORES,X
    BAGE    AI_MIN_SCORE,.not_lower
    STA     AI_MIN_SCORE           ; new minimum
    STX     AI_BEST_DIR            ; record direction
.not_lower:
    DEX
    BPL     .find_min

    ; --- encode direction index to movement value ---
    LDA     AI_BEST_DIR
    BAPL    #$03,.ge3
    EOR     #$03                   ; directions 0-2: XOR 3
    BPL     .store_dir
.ge3:
    EOR     #$07                   ; directions 3-4: XOR 7
.store_dir:
    STA     AI_PREV_DIR            ; save for next turn's bias
    LDA     AI_BEST_DIR            ; return direction index
    RTS
@ %def NPC_MOVE_AI
@ [[EVALUATE_DIRECTION]] scores a single candidate direction for the NPC
movement AI.  It temporarily moves the entity to the test position
([[AI_TEST_POS]]) and evaluates the result.  If the test position matches the
AI's target, a large penalty is added (the entity is already there).  The
routine computes the Manhattan distance to the target from the test position;
if the distance is not closer than the current distance, a smaller penalty is
added.  It then calls [[FIND_ENTITY_AT_POS]] to check what occupies the
candidate square: empty squares return cleanly, walls add a large penalty,
and entities are scored based on their type byte---friendly mobs, hostile
mobs of various strength ranges, and locked/safe events each contribute
different penalty amounts via [[INC_MOB_COUNTERS]].  The entity's position
is restored before returning.

<<defines>>=
AI_BEST_DIST        EQU     $5A68   ; current best distance to AI target
AI_SAVED_POS        EQU     $5A69   ; saved entity position during direction eval
@ %def AI_BEST_DIST AI_SAVED_POS

<<evaluate direction>>=
    ORG     $6815
EVALUATE_DIRECTION:
    SUBROUTINE EVALUATE_DIRECTION
    ; Score a candidate direction for NPC movement AI.
    ;
    ; Input:  AI_TEST_POS    — candidate position to evaluate
    ;         AI_TARGET_POS  — AI's desired target position
    ;         AI_DIRECTION   — index into DIR_SCORES for this direction
    ;         AI_BEST_DIST   — current best distance to target
    ;         ENTITY_PTR     — entity being moved
    ;
    ; Output: DIR_SCORES[AI_DIRECTION] updated with penalty points
    ;
    ; Behavior:
    ;   Penalizes the direction based on: already at target (+9),
    ;   not closer than current best (+2), wall (+7), and entity
    ;   type at the candidate square (friendly +3, hostile +1..+6,
    ;   locked event +7, safe event +1).
    ;
    ; Modifies: DIR_SCORES, AI_SAVED_POS
    ; Clobbers: A, X, Y

    ; --- check if already at target ---
    LDA     AI_TARGET_POS
    BAEQ    AI_TEST_POS,.skip_target
    LDY     #$09                   ; heavy penalty: already there
    JSR     INC_MOB_COUNTERS

    ; --- check distance improvement ---
.skip_target:
    LDY     #MFIELD_POSITION       ; \ save entity's current position
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y         ;  |
    STA     AI_SAVED_POS           ; /
    LDA     AI_TEST_POS            ; \ temporarily set entity to test pos
    STA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y         ; / (for MANHATTAN_DISTANCE)
    LDA     AI_TARGET_POS
    BEQ     .no_distance           ; no target -> skip distance check
    JSR     MANHATTAN_DISTANCE
    BALT    AI_BEST_DIST,.no_distance ; closer -> no penalty
    LDY     #$02                   ; penalty: not closer
    JSR     INC_MOB_COUNTERS

    ; --- restore position and check occupant ---
.no_distance:
    LDY     #MFIELD_POSITION       ; \ restore original position
    LDA     AI_SAVED_POS           ;  |
    STA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y         ; /
    LDA     AI_TEST_POS
    JSR     FIND_ENTITY_AT_POS     ; what's at the candidate square?
    LDA     ENTITY_REC+1
    BNE     .has_entity            ; nonzero hi byte -> entity found
    LDA     ENTITY_REC
    BNE     .wall                  ; nonzero lo byte -> wall/obstacle
    RTS                            ; empty square -> no penalty

.wall:
    LDY     #$07                   ; heavy penalty: wall
    JMP     INC_MOB_COUNTERS

    ; --- classify entity by type byte ---
.has_entity:
    BALT    #$80,.mob              ; bit 7 clear -> mob
    RTS                            ; bit 7 set -> player char, no penalty

.mob:
    LDY     #MFIELD_TYPE
    LDA     (ENTITY_REC),Y        ; entity type/class byte
    BAGE    #$80,.ge80
    LDY     #$03                   ; type < $80: friendly mob
    JMP     INC_MOB_COUNTERS
.ge80:
    BAGE    #$C0,.geC0
    LDY     #$06                   ; type $80-$BF: hostile (strong)
    JMP     INC_MOB_COUNTERS
.geC0:
    BAGE    #$D2,.geD2
    LDY     #$01                   ; type $C0-$D1: hostile (weak)
    JMP     INC_MOB_COUNTERS
.geD2:
    BAGE    #$D5,.geD5
    LDY     #$02                   ; type $D2-$D4: hostile (medium)
    JMP     INC_MOB_COUNTERS
.geD5:
    BAGE    #$D8,.geD8
    LDY     #$03                   ; type $D5-$D7: shop/special
    JMP     INC_MOB_COUNTERS

    ; --- event entity: check lock status ---
.geD8:
    INY                            ; Y = MFIELD_NEXT (byte 2: event data for type >= $D8)
    LDA     (ENTITY_REC),Y
    BAGE    #$40,.safe
    LDY     #$07                   ; locked event: heavy penalty
    JMP     INC_MOB_COUNTERS
.safe:
    LDY     #$01                   ; safe event: light penalty
; falls through to INC_MOB_COUNTERS
@ %def EVALUATE_DIRECTION
@ [[INC_MOB_COUNTERS]] adds~Y to the direction score for the current AI
direction being evaluated.  The current direction index is in
[[AI_DIRECTION]], and the scores are in the [[DIR_SCORES]] array indexed by~X.
The routine decrements~Y in a loop, incrementing [[DIR_SCORES,X]] each time,
returning when~Y reaches zero.  This is used by [[EVALUATE_DIRECTION]] to
penalize directions based on what occupies the candidate square.

<<inc mob counters>>=
    ORG     $689F
INC_MOB_COUNTERS:
    SUBROUTINE INC_MOB_COUNTERS
    ; Add Y to the direction penalty score for the current AI direction.
    ;
    ; Input:  Y             — penalty count (decremented to zero)
    ;         AI_DIRECTION  — index into DIR_SCORES array
    ;
    ; Output: DIR_SCORES[AI_DIRECTION] incremented by Y
    ; Clobbers: X, Y, flags

    LDX     AI_DIRECTION           ; current direction index
    DEY                            ; pre-decrement (Y=0 -> done)
    BPL     .do_inc
    RTS
.do_inc:
    INC     DIR_SCORES,X           ; add one penalty point
    BPL     INC_MOB_COUNTERS       ; loop until Y < 0
@ %def INC_MOB_COUNTERS
@ [[FIND_NEAREST_EVENT]] scans the character's event list for the closest
non-activated event, measured by Manhattan distance from the entity's current
position.  It loads the event list pointer from bytes~6--7 of the character
record at [[$FA]] and walks the 3-byte entries: entries with byte~1 at~\$C0 or
above are already activated and are skipped, entries marked~\$FE (empty slot)
are skipped, and~\$FF marks the end of the list.  For each eligible entry,
the routine calls [[MANHATTAN_DISTANCE]] and keeps track of the nearest one
found.  The winning position is returned in~A and stored at~\$5A13 for the AI
to use as a movement target.

<<defines>>=
NEAREST_DIST        EQU     $5A14   ; current minimum distance during event search
NEAREST_POS         EQU     $5A13   ; position of nearest event found
CANDIDATE_POS       EQU     $5A15   ; position of event being evaluated
    ; --- Event record field offsets (3-byte entries) ---
EVFIELD_POSITION    EQU     $00     ; byte 0: packed map position
EVFIELD_TYPE        EQU     $01     ; byte 1: event type (>= $C0 = activated)
EVENT_RECORD_SIZE   EQU     $03     ; size of one event list entry (3 bytes)
EVENT_ACTIVATED     EQU     $C0     ; event type threshold: >= $C0 = already activated
EVENT_EMPTY         EQU     $FE     ; event list: empty slot marker
EVENT_END           EQU     $FF     ; event list: end-of-list marker
@ %def NEAREST_DIST NEAREST_POS CANDIDATE_POS EVFIELD_POSITION EVFIELD_TYPE EVENT_RECORD_SIZE EVENT_ACTIVATED EVENT_EMPTY EVENT_END

<<find nearest event>>=
    ORG     $138D
FIND_NEAREST_EVENT:
    SUBROUTINE FIND_NEAREST_EVENT
    ; Find the nearest non-activated event to the current entity.
    ;
    ; Input:  ENTITY_PTR  — entity whose position to measure from
    ;         CHAR_PTR    — bytes 6-7 of record hold event list pointer
    ;
    ; Output: A = packed position of nearest event
    ;
    ; Behavior:
    ;   Walks the 3-byte event list (position, type, data).  Skips
    ;   activated events (type >= $C0) and empty slots ($FE).  For
    ;   each candidate, computes Manhattan distance and keeps the
    ;   closest.
    ;
    ; Modifies: NEAREST_DIST, NEAREST_POS, CANDIDATE_POS, EVENT_PTR
    ; Clobbers: A, X, Y

    STOB    #$7F,NEAREST_DIST      ; initial min = 127
    LDWIY    CHAR_PTR,#CFIELD_EVENTS,EVENT_PTR ; load event list pointer
    JMP     .check_end

    ; --- evaluate one event ---
.eval:
    LDY     #EVFIELD_TYPE
    LDA     (EVENT_PTR),Y          ; event type byte
    BAGE    #EVENT_ACTIVATED,.advance ; activated -> skip
    LDY     #EVFIELD_POSITION
    LDA     (EVENT_PTR),Y          ; event position byte
    STA     CANDIDATE_POS
    JSR     MANHATTAN_DISTANCE
    BAPL    NEAREST_DIST,.advance  ; not closer -> skip
    STA     NEAREST_DIST           ; new minimum distance
    MOVB    CANDIDATE_POS,NEAREST_POS ; record its position

    ; --- advance to next entry ---
.advance:
    LDA     EVENT_PTR
    CLC
    ADC     #EVENT_RECORD_SIZE     ; next 3-byte entry
    STA     EVENT_PTR
    BCC     .check_end
    INC     EVENT_PTR+1

    ; --- check list termination ---
.check_end:
    LDY     #EVFIELD_POSITION
    LDA     (EVENT_PTR),Y
    BAEQ    #EVENT_EMPTY,.advance  ; empty slot -> skip
    BANE    #EVENT_END,.eval       ; not end -> evaluate
    LDA     NEAREST_POS            ; return nearest position
    RTS
@ %def FIND_NEAREST_EVENT
@ [[MANHATTAN_DISTANCE]] computes the taxicab distance between a given packed
position (in~A) and the current entity's position at offset~3 of
[[ENTITY_PTR]].  It unpacks both positions into column/row pairs with
[[POS_TO_COLROW]], takes the absolute value of each axis difference using the
standard 6502 negate-if-negative idiom (EOR~\$FF, ADC~\$01), and sums the
results.  The function temporarily borrows [[FONT_COL]] and [[FONT_ROW]] as
scratch storage---these are safe to clobber here since no rendering is in
progress.

<<zero page defines>>=
DIST_COL                EQU     $BA     ; |col difference| scratch in MANHATTAN_DISTANCE
@ %def DIST_COL

<<manhattan distance>>=
    ORG     $13DB
MANHATTAN_DISTANCE:
    SUBROUTINE MANHATTAN_DISTANCE
    ; Compute Manhattan distance between a position and the current entity.
    ;
    ; Input:  A = packed map position to measure from
    ; Output: A = |col_diff| + |row_diff|
    ;
    ; Uses ENTITY_PTR byte MFIELD_POSITION as the entity's position.
    ; FONT_COL/FONT_ROW and DIST_COL used as scratch.
    ; Clobbers: A, X, Y

    ; --- unpack target position ---
    JSR     POS_TO_COLROW          ; A -> col in A, row in Y
    STA     FONT_COL               ; save target col
    STY     FONT_ROW               ; save target row

    ; --- unpack entity position ---
    LDY     #MFIELD_POSITION
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y         ; entity's packed position
    JSR     POS_TO_COLROW

    ; --- |col difference| ---
    SEC
    SBC     FONT_COL               ; entity col - target col
    BCS     .pos1
    EOR     #$FF                   ; \ negate if negative
    ADC     #$01                   ; / (two's complement abs)
.pos1:
    STA     DIST_COL               ; save |delta col|

    ; --- |row difference| ---
    TYA
    SEC
    SBC     FONT_ROW               ; entity row - target row
    BCS     .pos2
    EOR     #$FF                   ; \ negate if negative
    ADC     #$01                   ; /
.pos2:
    CLC
    ADC     DIST_COL               ; A = |delta col| + |delta row|
    RTS
@ %def MANHATTAN_DISTANCE

\section{Shops}

@ [[DISPLAY_SHOP]] presents the shop interface when a character enters a store
tile.  It only runs for player-controlled characters (AI mode~0).  The routine
loads the shop data pointer and advances it past earlier shop entries based on
the event type (byte~1 minus~\$D5 gives the shop index).  It then iterates
through the 8-bit item availability mask in byte~2: for each set bit, it
computes the item's price by summing price components based on the location
style (1--4 components), formats the price with [[NUM_TO_DECIMAL]], copies
the item name string into the display buffer, and enters the game's
alternative input loop via [[START_GAME_INPUT]] so the player can choose to
buy.  The item mask is rotated right to advance through items, wrapping around
when all bits have been checked.

<<defines>>=
SHOP_PRICE          EQU     $5A81   ; shop: accumulated price low byte
SHOP_PRICE_HI       EQU     $5A82   ; shop: accumulated price high byte
SHOP_ITEM_MASK      EQU     $5A80   ; shop: bitmask for current item ($80 rotating right)
SHOP_ITEM_OFFSET EQU    $5A85   ; offset into shop record (5 per item slot)
@ %def SHOP_PRICE SHOP_PRICE_HI SHOP_ITEM_MASK SHOP_ITEM_OFFSET

<<zero page defines>>=
SHOP_DATA_PTR           EQU     $E6     ; ZP pointer to current shop item record (2 bytes)
@ %def SHOP_DATA_PTR

<<display shop>>=
    ORG     $70DF
DISPLAY_SHOP:
    SUBROUTINE DISPLAY_SHOP
    ; Display the shop menu for a trading post entity.
    ;
    ; Inputs:
    ;   CHAR_AI_MODE   — if nonzero, returns immediately (AI can't shop)
    ;   ENTITY_REC     — pointer to shop entity record:
    ;                     +SHOP_TYPE_FIELD: shop type ($D5=weapons, $D6=armor)
    ;                     +SHOP_AVAIL_FIELD: item validity bitmask
    ;   LOCATION_STYLE — bits 7-6 encode location tier (0-3), scales prices
    ;
    ; Behavior:
    ;   Selects the shop record from SHOP_TABLE, displays the shop scene,
    ;   then iterates 8 item slots.  For each valid slot (per bitmask),
    ;   computes price = base_price * (tier + 1), formats the
    ;   "PAY nnnnnn FOR [item]" string, and enters START_GAME_INPUT.
    ;
    ; Modifies:
    ;   SHOP_DATA_PTR, SHOP_VALID_MASK, SHOP_ITEM_MASK, SHOP_ITEM_OFFSET,
    ;   SHOP_PRICE, SHOP_PRICE_HI, LOCATION_STYLE_BITS,
    ;   SHOP_PRICE_DIGITS, SHOP_ITEM_NAME, PRINT_STRING_ADDR
    ; Clobbers: A, X, Y

    LDA     CHAR_AI_MODE
    BEQ     .do_shop
    RTS
.do_shop:
    STOW    SHOP_TABLE,SHOP_DATA_PTR
    LDY     #SHOP_TYPE_FIELD       ; shop type ($D5=weapons, $D6=armor)
    LDA     (ENTITY_REC),Y
    SEC
    SBC     #$D5                   ; record index (0 or 1)
    TAX
.count_loop:
    DEX
    BMI     .counted
    JSR     ADVANCE_SHOP_PTR       ; skip to selected record
    JMP     .count_loop
.counted:
    LDY     #SHOP_AVAIL_FIELD      ; item validity bitmask
    LDA     (ENTITY_REC),Y
    STA     SHOP_VALID_MASK
    JSR     SET_CURSOR_ROW21
    LDY     #SHOP_SCENE_OFFSET     ; display shop scene
    LDA     (SHOP_DATA_PTR),Y
    JSR     SCENE_LOOP
    JSR     LOAD_CHAR_NAME_PTR
    JSR     SETUP_CHAR_SPRITE

    ; --- iterate through item slots ---
.item_start:
    STOB    #$80,SHOP_ITEM_MASK    ; start at slot 0 (bit 7)
    STOB    #$00,SHOP_ITEM_OFFSET  ; start at record offset 0
.item_loop:
    LDA     SHOP_VALID_MASK        ; check if current slot is valid
    AND     SHOP_ITEM_MASK
    BNE     .show_item
    JMP     .next_item

    ; --- display one item ---
.show_item:
    STOB    #$00,SHOP_PRICE        ; clear price accumulator
    STA     SHOP_PRICE_HI
    LDY     SHOP_ITEM_OFFSET       ; Y = offset + 4 (price byte)
    INY
    INY
    INY
    INY
    LDA     LOCATION_STYLE         ; \ extract bits 7-6: location tier (0-3)
    ROL2                           ;  | rotate down to bits 1-0
    ROL2                           ;  |
    AND     #$03                   ; /
    TAX                            ; X = tier (price loop count)
    STA     LOCATION_STYLE_BITS
.price_loop:                       ; price = base_price * (tier + 1)
    JSR     ADD_PRICE_COMPONENT
    DEX
    BPL     .price_loop
    LDA     #$20                   ; \ clear price and item name fields
    LDX     #$04                   ;  | in "PAY 000000 FOR" string
.clear1:                           ;  |
    STA     SHOP_PRICE_DIGITS,X    ;  |
    DEX                            ;  |
    BPL     .clear1                ;  |
    LDX     #$13                   ;  |
.clear2:                           ;  |
    STA     SHOP_ITEM_NAME,X       ;  |
    DEX                            ;  |
    BPL     .clear2                ; /
    MOVB    SHOP_PRICE,PRINT_STRING_ADDR
    MOVB    SHOP_PRICE_HI,PRINT_STRING_ADDR+1
    STOW    SHOP_PRICE_DIGITS,$BA
    JSR     NUM_TO_DECIMAL         ; write price digits
    LDY     SHOP_ITEM_OFFSET       ; \ copy item name string address
    INY                            ;  | from shop record (+2/+3)
    INY                            ;  | into PRINT_STRING_ADDR
    LDA     (SHOP_DATA_PTR),Y      ;  |
    STA     PRINT_STRING_ADDR      ;  |
    INY                            ;  |
    LDA     (SHOP_DATA_PTR),Y      ;  |
    STA     PRINT_STRING_ADDR+1    ; /
    LDY     #$00                   ; \ copy item name into display string
    LDA     (PRINT_STRING_ADDR),Y  ;  | Y = string length
    TAY                            ;  |
    TAX                            ;  |
    DEX                            ;  | X = length - 1 (dest index)
.copy_name:                        ;  |
    LDA     (PRINT_STRING_ADDR),Y  ;  |
    STA     SHOP_ITEM_NAME,X       ;  |
    DEY                            ;  |
    DEX                            ;  |
    BPL     .copy_name             ; /
    JMP     START_GAME_INPUT       ; enter buy/browse/no-sale menu

    ; --- advance to next slot ---
BROWSE_HANDLER:                        ; entry from "BUY SOMETHING ELSE" menu
.next_item:
    CLC
    LDA     SHOP_ITEM_MASK         ; rotate mask right
    ROR
    BCC     .more_items            ; didn't carry out -> more slots
    JMP     .item_start            ; carried out -> restart
.more_items:
    STA     SHOP_ITEM_MASK
    LDA     SHOP_ITEM_OFFSET       ; advance offset by 5
    ADC     #$05
    STA     SHOP_ITEM_OFFSET
    JMP     .item_loop
@ %def DISPLAY_SHOP BROWSE_HANDLER
@ [[ADVANCE_SHOP_PTR]] adds [[SHOP_RECORD_SIZE]] (41 bytes) to
[[SHOP_DATA_PTR]], advancing it to the next shop entry in the data
table.

<<defines>>=
SHOP_RECORD_SIZE        EQU     $29     ; size of one shop record (41 bytes)
SHOP_SCENE_OFFSET       EQU     $28     ; offset of scene number within shop record
SHOP_TYPE_FIELD         EQU     $01     ; entity record byte 1: shop type ($D5=weapons, $D6=armor)
SHOP_AVAIL_FIELD        EQU     $02     ; entity record byte 2: item validity bitmask
SHOP_VALID_MASK         EQU     $5A83   ; copy of item validity bitmask during shop display
SHOP_PRICE_DIGITS       EQU     S_PAY_FOR+5  ; 6-byte price field in "PAY 000000 FOR" string
SHOP_ITEM_NAME          EQU     S_PAY_FOR+16 ; 20-byte item name field after "FOR " in pay string
@ %def SHOP_RECORD_SIZE SHOP_SCENE_OFFSET SHOP_TYPE_FIELD SHOP_AVAIL_FIELD SHOP_VALID_MASK SHOP_PRICE_DIGITS SHOP_ITEM_NAME

<<advance shop ptr>>=
    ORG     $71F0
ADVANCE_SHOP_PTR:
    SUBROUTINE ADVANCE_SHOP_PTR
    CLC
    LDA     SHOP_DATA_PTR
    ADC     #SHOP_RECORD_SIZE
    STA     SHOP_DATA_PTR
    BCC     .done
    INC     SHOP_DATA_PTR+1
.done:
    RTS
@ %def ADVANCE_SHOP_PTR
@ [[ADD_PRICE_COMPONENT]] adds one byte from the shop data (indexed by~Y) to
the running 16-bit price total in [[SHOP_PRICE]]/[[SHOP_PRICE_HI]].  It is
called in a loop, once for each price component determined by the location
style.

<<add price component>>=
    ORG     $71FC
ADD_PRICE_COMPONENT:
    SUBROUTINE ADD_PRICE_COMPONENT
    CLC
    LDA     (SHOP_DATA_PTR),Y
    ADC     SHOP_PRICE
    STA     SHOP_PRICE
    BCC     .done
    INC     SHOP_PRICE_HI
.done:
    RTS
@ %def ADD_PRICE_COMPONENT

@ \subsection{Shop buy effects (\$720B--\$7248)}

When a player buys an item, the buy handler at [[$71AC]] dispatches
through a function pointer in the shop data.  Five entry points
(indexed 0--4) apply the purchased item's effect to the entity record
at [[ENTITY_PTR]].  Each entry sets X (item type 0--4) and Y (target
field offset: 7 or~9), then falls through to the common handler.

The common handler loads a base value from the effect table at
[[$7F6D]][X], adds [[LOCATION_STYLE\_BITS]] ([[$5A84]]), and stores
the result at byte~Y of the entity record.  It then extracts bits~2--1
of byte~5 (defense field) and adds that bonus to the same field.
Finally it jumps to [[$7194]] (the browse handler, to continue
shopping).

<<defines>>=
LOCATION_STYLE_BITS EQU     $5A84   ; location style (0-3), used as modifier
SHOP_EFFECT_TABLE   EQU     $7F6D   ; 5-byte table of base effect values
@ %def LOCATION_STYLE_BITS SHOP_EFFECT_TABLE

<<shop buy effects>>=
    ORG     $720B
SHOP_BUY_EFFECT_0:
    LDX     #$00
    LDY     #MFIELD_ATTACK     ; attack stat (swords, clubs)
    BNE     APPLY_SHOP_EFFECT

SHOP_BUY_EFFECT_1:
    LDX     #$01
    LDY     #MFIELD_ATTACK
    BNE     APPLY_SHOP_EFFECT

SHOP_BUY_EFFECT_2:
    LDX     #$02
    LDY     #MFIELD_ATTACK
    BNE     APPLY_SHOP_EFFECT

SHOP_BUY_EFFECT_3:
    LDX     #$03
    LDY     #MFIELD_DEFENSE    ; defense stat (armor, daggers, shivs)
    BNE     APPLY_SHOP_EFFECT

SHOP_BUY_EFFECT_4:
    LDX     #$04
    LDY     #MFIELD_DEFENSE
    BNE     APPLY_SHOP_EFFECT

APPLY_SHOP_EFFECT:
    LDA     SHOP_EFFECT_TABLE,X ; base effect value
    CLC
    ADC     LOCATION_STYLE_BITS ; + location tier modifier
    STA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y     ; store to weapon/armor field
    TYA                        ; \ save target field offset
    TAX                        ; / in X
    LDY     #MFIELD_STRENGTH
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y     ; strength/defense byte
    ROR                        ; \ extract bits 2-1
    ROR                        ;  | as bits 1-0
    ROR                        ; /
    AND     #$03               ; mask to 2 bits (defense bonus)
    PHA
    TXA                        ; restore target field offset
    TAY
    PLA
    CLC
    ADC     (ENTITY_PTR),Y     ; add defense bonus
    STA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y
    JMP     BROWSE_HANDLER     ; return to browse handler
@ %def SHOP_BUY_EFFECT_0 SHOP_BUY_EFFECT_1 SHOP_BUY_EFFECT_2 SHOP_BUY_EFFECT_3 SHOP_BUY_EFFECT_4 APPLY_SHOP_EFFECT

@ \subsection{XP award (\$7249--\$72A6)}

Five entry points (indexed 0--4) award experience points after combat
actions.  Each sets X to the action type and falls through to the
common handler.

The common handler:
\begin{itemize}
\item Extracts the current level from byte~11 (bits~4--0) and saves
  the upper bits (7--5).
\item Extracts pending XP from byte~8 via [[EXTRACT\_PENDING\_XP]]
  (bits~6--4 $\rightarrow$ 0--7) and adds it to the saved level.
\item Loads the XP award from [[XP\_AWARD\_TABLE]][X], adds
  [[LOCATION_STYLE\_BITS]], and stores to byte~8.
\item Extracts the new pending XP, and if it exceeds the accumulated
  level, subtracts 16 (\$10) from byte~8 repeatedly until it fits.
\item Computes the remaining level (old level $-$ new pending XP) and
  merges it with the saved upper bits back into byte~11.
\item Jumps to [[$7194]] (browse handler).
\end{itemize}

<<defines>>=
XP_AWARD_TABLE      EQU     $7FBE   ; 5-byte XP award values by action type
@ %def XP_AWARD_TABLE

<<defines>>=
    ; (ENTITY_LEVEL_FIELD and ENTITY_XP_FIELD removed; use MFIELD_LEVEL and MFIELD_XP)
STRENGTH_MASK           EQU     $1F     ; byte 5: mask for strength bits 4-0
HP_MASK                 EQU     $3F     ; byte 6: mask for HP bits 5-0
LEVEL_MASK              EQU     $1F     ; byte 11: mask for level bits 4-0
LEVEL_FLAG_MASK         EQU     $E0     ; byte 11: mask for flag bits 7-5
PENDING_XP_UNIT         EQU     $10     ; byte 8: one pending XP unit (bit 4)
FLAGS_CLASS_MASK        EQU     $C0     ; byte 15: mask for class bits 7-6
FLAGS_STATUS_MASK       EQU     $3F     ; byte 15: mask for status bits 5-0
MOB_TYPE_MASK           EQU     $3F     ; byte 6: mask for mob type bits 5-0
NPC_APPEARANCE_MIN      EQU     $15     ; appearance >= $15 = NPC, < $15 = player character
@ %def LEVEL_MASK LEVEL_FLAG_MASK PENDING_XP_UNIT

<<zero page defines>>=
XP_ACCUM                EQU     $BA     ; accumulated level during XP award (scratch)
@ %def XP_ACCUM

<<xp award>>=
    ORG     $7249
XP_AWARD_0:
    LDX     #$00
    BEQ     AWARD_XP

XP_AWARD_1:
    LDX     #$01
    BNE     AWARD_XP

XP_AWARD_2:
    LDX     #$02
    BNE     AWARD_XP

XP_AWARD_3:
    LDX     #$03
    BNE     AWARD_XP

XP_AWARD_4:
    LDX     #$04
    BNE     AWARD_XP

AWARD_XP:
    SUBROUTINE AWARD_XP
    ; Award experience points after a shop buy action.
    ;
    ; Inputs:
    ;   X              — action type index (0-4), set by entry points
    ;   ENTITY_PTR     — pointer to entity receiving the XP
    ;   XP_AWARD_TABLE — base XP values indexed by action type
    ;   LOCATION_STYLE_BITS — location tier modifier (0-3)
    ;
    ; Behavior:
    ;   Extracts current level and pending XP from entity record.
    ;   Adds the award value (table[X] + tier) to byte 8, then
    ;   clamps so pending XP does not exceed the accumulated level.
    ;   Writes the updated level back to byte 11 and jumps to the
    ;   browse handler.
    ;
    ; Modifies:
    ;   ENTITY_PTR bytes 8 and 11, XP_ACCUM
    ; Clobbers: A, X, Y

    ; --- extract current level and pending XP ---
    LDY     #MFIELD_LEVEL    ; byte 11: flags|level
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y
    PHA
    AND     #LEVEL_MASK            ; level (bits 4-0)
    STA     XP_ACCUM
    PLA
    AND     #LEVEL_FLAG_MASK       ; preserve flag bits (7-5)
    STA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y         ; clear level in record
    LDY     #MFIELD_XP       ; byte 8: status|pending_xp|count
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y
    JSR     EXTRACT_PENDING_XP     ; A = pending XP (0-7)
    CLC
    ADC     XP_ACCUM               ; accumulated = level + pending
    STA     XP_ACCUM

    ; --- add XP award and clamp ---
    LDA     XP_AWARD_TABLE,X       ; base XP for action type
    CLC
    ADC     LOCATION_STYLE_BITS    ; + location tier modifier
.clamp:
    STA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y         ; write to byte 8
    JSR     EXTRACT_PENDING_XP     ; extract new pending XP
    CMP     XP_ACCUM               ; exceeds accumulated level?
    BCC     .ok                    ; no -> done
    SEC                            ; \ yes -> reduce by one XP unit
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y         ;  |
    SBC     #PENDING_XP_UNIT       ;  |
    JMP     .clamp                 ; / retry

    ; --- write updated level back ---
.ok:
    TAX                            ; X = new pending XP
    LDA     XP_ACCUM
    STX     XP_ACCUM
    SEC
    SBC     XP_ACCUM               ; remaining level = accumulated - pending
    LDY     #MFIELD_LEVEL    ; merge with saved flag bits
    ORA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y
    STA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y
    JMP     BROWSE_HANDLER

EXTRACT_PENDING_XP:
    ; Extract the pending XP field from a packed entity byte.
    ;
    ; Input:  A = entity byte 8 (status|pending_xp|count)
    ; Output: A = pending XP value (0-7), from bits 6-4
    ; Clobbers: flags
    ROR                            ; \ extract bits 6-4 of A
    ROR                            ;  | shift right 4 positions
    ROR                            ;  |
    ROR                            ; /
    AND     #$07                   ; mask to 3 bits (0-7)
    RTS
@ %def XP_AWARD_0 XP_AWARD_1 XP_AWARD_2 XP_AWARD_3 XP_AWARD_4 AWARD_XP EXTRACT_PENDING_XP

\chapter{Events and Scripting}


\section{Between-round random events}

After every character has taken a turn, [[RANDOM_EVENTS]] runs a cascading
chain of random event checks.  Each step rolls the PRNG and compares the
result against [[EVENT_THRESHOLD]] (the byte at [[$4239]], approximately a
7\% chance per roll).

The structure is deliberately cascading: each successive stage is only reached
if the previous roll \emph{failed}, meaning that on a lucky sequence of rolls,
multiple events can fire in a single round.  If all five individual checks
pass and the sixth roll also succeeds, a \emph{burst} fires: four mob spawns
in rapid succession plus a special faction event.

Most rounds see zero or one random events, but occasionally a flurry of
activity hits at once---new mobs spawn, faction skirmishes trigger, and the
game world feels unpredictably alive.

@ [[EVENT_THRESHOLD]] at [[$4239]] is the probability threshold for random
events.  [[RANDOM_EVENTS]] compares each PRNG roll against this value; a
roll below the threshold triggers the corresponding event handler.

<<defines>>=
EVENT_THRESHOLD         EQU     $4239   ; random event probability threshold (~7%)
@ %def EVENT_THRESHOLD

<<random events>>=
    ORG     $65A9
RANDOM_EVENTS:
    SUBROUTINE RANDOM_EVENTS
    ; Between-round random event dispatcher.  Each step rolls PRNG and
    ; compares against the event threshold at $4239 (~7% chance).
    ; Cascading: the deeper it goes, the more events fire at once.
    JSR     STEP_PRNG
    LDA     PRNG_OUTPUT
    BAPL    EVENT_THRESHOLD,.ev2
    JSR     EVENT_PICK_MOB           ; event type 1
.ev2:
    JSR     STEP_PRNG
    LDA     PRNG_OUTPUT
    BAPL    EVENT_THRESHOLD,.ev3
    JSR     EVENT_PICK_CHAR          ; event type 2
.ev3:
    JSR     STEP_PRNG
    LDA     PRNG_OUTPUT
    BAPL    EVENT_THRESHOLD,.ev4
    JSR     EVENT_FACTION_SCENE      ; event type 3
.ev4:
    JSR     STEP_PRNG
    LDA     PRNG_OUTPUT
    BAPL    EVENT_THRESHOLD,.ev5
    JSR     EVENT_SPAWN_MOB          ; event type 4a
.ev5:
    JSR     STEP_PRNG
    LDA     PRNG_OUTPUT
    BAPL    EVENT_THRESHOLD,.ev6
    JSR     EVENT_SPAWN_MOB          ; event type 4b
.ev6:
    JSR     STEP_PRNG
    LDA     PRNG_OUTPUT
    BAMI    EVENT_THRESHOLD,.burst
    RTS                              ; no more events this round
.burst:
    JSR     EVENT_SPAWN_MOB          ; event burst: 4 + special + tail
    JSR     EVENT_SPAWN_MOB
    JSR     EVENT_SPAWN_MOB
    JSR     EVENT_SPAWN_MOB
    JSR     PICK_RANDOM_CHAR
    JMP     EVENT_FACTION_SCENE_CONT ; tail into EVENT_FACTION_SCENE second half
@ %def RANDOM_EVENTS

@ The individual event handlers are short routines that select a random target
and dispatch to the appropriate processing function.
[[EVENT_PICK_MOB]] selects a random mob group (weighted by group size) via
[[PICK_RANDOM_MOB]] and passes it to [[PROCESS_CHAR_EVENTS]], which walks
the selected character's event list looking for triggerable entries.

<<event pick mob>>=
    ORG     $660D
EVENT_PICK_MOB:
    SUBROUTINE EVENT_PICK_CHAR
    ; Random event: pick a random mob, then process its char events.
    JSR     PICK_RANDOM_MOB
    JMP     PROCESS_CHAR_EVENTS
@ %def EVENT_PICK_MOB
@ [[EVENT_PICK_CHAR]] works the same way, but selects a random character
from the active player range (players~2 through [[CURRENT_PLAYER]]$-$1)
instead of a mob group.  The distinction is that [[EVENT_PICK_MOB]] weights
its selection by mob group count, while [[EVENT_PICK_CHAR]] selects uniformly
among characters.

<<event pick char>>=
    ORG     $6613
EVENT_PICK_CHAR:
    SUBROUTINE EVENT_FACTION_SCENE
    ; Random event: pick a random character, then process its char events.
    JSR     PICK_RANDOM_CHAR
    JMP     PROCESS_CHAR_EVENTS
@ %def EVENT_PICK_CHAR
@ [[EVENT_FACTION_SCENE]] picks a random mob and then searches the mob list
for one whose faction matches.  Factions are encoded in bits~6--5 of character
record byte~5.  If a matching mob is found, [[SCENE_SETUP]] is called to
trigger an interaction between them.  If no match exists, the routine falls
back to [[EVENT_SPAWN_MOB]] instead.

The alternate entry [[EVENT_FACTION_SCENE_CONT]] is used by the burst path
in [[RANDOM_EVENTS]], which skips the initial mob selection and reuses the
character already chosen by [[PICK_RANDOM_CHAR]].

<<zero page defines>>=
CHAR_INDEX              EQU     $F6     ; selected character/player index
FACTION_MASK            EQU     $F7     ; faction match value for FIND_MOB_BY_FACTION
@ %def CHAR_INDEX FACTION_MASK

<<event faction scene>>=
    ORG     $6619
EVENT_FACTION_SCENE:
    SUBROUTINE EVENT_FACTION_SCENE_CONT
    ; Random event: pick a random mob, check for matching faction
    ; in the mob list; if found, run SCENE_SETUP for that mob.
    JSR     PICK_RANDOM_MOB
EVENT_FACTION_SCENE_CONT:               ; alternate entry from RANDOM_EVENTS burst
    LDA     CHAR_PTR
    BANE    #$09,.has_char      ; $FA still at base ($4009)?
    RTS                         ; no character selected -> skip
.has_char:
    LDY     #$05
    LDA     (CHAR_PTR),Y        ; char record byte 5
    AND     #$60                ; bits 6-5 = faction mask
    STA     FACTION_MASK        ; save for FIND_MOB_BY_FACTION
    STOW    $4000,CHAR_PTR ;  reset $FA/$FB to $4000 (record base)
    JSR     FIND_MOB_BY_FACTION ; search mob list for matching faction
    BANE    #$00,.found
    JMP     EVENT_SPAWN_MOB     ; not found -> try spawning instead
.found:
    STOB    #$00,SOURCE_CHAR ; clear source char
    MOVB    CHAR_INDEX,ACTIVE_CHAR ; set active char to found index
    JSR     SCENE_SETUP
    JSR     CHECK_LOCATION_MATCH
    RTS
@ %def EVENT_FACTION_SCENE EVENT_FACTION_SCENE_CONT
@ [[EVENT_SPAWN_MOB]] attempts to activate a dormant character.  It picks
a random character and checks byte~8: if nonzero, the character is already
active, so it tries once more.  If both picks are active, it gives up.  For
an inactive character, the routine extracts its faction mask, searches for a
matching mob, and if found, calls [[REORDER_CHAR]] to bring the character
into the mob's group, followed by [[CLAMP_CHAR_FIELD]] to normalize its
stats.  This is the primary mechanism by which new entities enter the game
world during play.

<<event spawn mob>>=
    ORG     $664E
EVENT_SPAWN_MOB:
    SUBROUTINE EVENT_SPAWN_MOB
    ; Random event: pick a random character; if its byte 8 is nonzero
    ; (active), try again once.  If inactive, use its faction to find
    ; a matching mob and reorder it into the group.
    JSR     PICK_RANDOM_CHAR
    LDY     #$08
    LDA     (CHAR_PTR),Y     ; char record byte 8
    BEQ     .inactive        ; zero = slot available
    JSR     PICK_RANDOM_CHAR ; try once more
    LDY     #$08
    LDA     (CHAR_PTR),Y
    BEQ     .inactive
    RTS                      ; both active -> give up
.inactive:
    LDY     #$05
    LDA     (CHAR_PTR),Y     ; char record byte 5
    AND     #$60             ; faction mask
    STA     FACTION_MASK
    JSR     FIND_MOB_BY_FACTION
    BANE    #$00,.found
    RTS                      ; no matching mob -> skip
.found:
    MOVB    CHAR_INDEX,SOURCE_CHAR
    STOB    #$00,ACTIVE_CHAR
    MOVW    MOB_PTR,TARGET_REC ;  TARGET_REC/TARGET_REC+1 = mob data pointer
    JSR     REORDER_CHAR
    JMP     CLAMP_CHAR_FIELD
@ %def EVENT_SPAWN_MOB
[[PICK_RANDOM_MOB]] selects a random mob group using weighted sampling.  It
generates a random number in the range [[0..TOTAL_MOB_COUNT-1]], then
iterates through the character records, subtracting each character's group
count (byte~8) from the running total.  When the total reaches zero or goes
negative, that character's record is selected.  This weighting means
characters with larger groups are proportionally more likely to be chosen.

If [[TOTAL_MOB_COUNT]] is zero (no mobs in the world), the routine falls
through directly to [[PICK_RANDOM_CHAR]].  The shared tail
[[COPY_BE_TO_FA]] copies the result from [[DATA_PTR]] to [[CHAR_PTR]].

<<pick random mob>>=
    ORG     $6689
PICK_RANDOM_MOB:
    SUBROUTINE PICK_RANDOM_MOB
    ; Pick a random mob group by weighted selection.
    ; Uses TOTAL_MOB_COUNT as the range, then iterates char records
    ; subtracting group counts (byte 8) until the target is reached.
    ; Result: $FA/$FB points to the selected char record.
    LDA     TOTAL_MOB_COUNT
    BEQ     PICK_RANDOM_CHAR     ; no mobs -> fall through to pick char
    JSR     RANDOM_IN_RANGE      ; random 0..TOTAL_MOB_COUNT-1
    BAEQ    #$00,PICK_RANDOM_MOB ; zero = retry
    STA     MOB_PTR              ; remaining count
    STOB    #$01,CHAR_INDEX ; player index counter
.next_char:
    LDA     CHAR_INDEX
    JSR     GET_CHAR_RECORD
    LDY     #$08
    LDA     MOB_PTR              ; remaining
    SEC
    SBC     (DATA_PTR),Y         ; subtract group count (byte 8)
    STA     MOB_PTR
    BEQ     .found               ; exact match
    BMI     .found               ; overshot -> this is the one
    INC     CHAR_INDEX
    BNE     .next_char           ; always branches
.found:
COPY_BE_TO_FA:
    MOVW    DATA_PTR,CHAR_PTR ;  $FA/$FB = DATA_PTR/DATA_PTR+1 (selected record)
    RTS
@ %def PICK_RANDOM_MOB COPY_BE_TO_FA
@ [[PICK_RANDOM_CHAR]] selects uniformly from the active player range:
players~2 through [[CURRENT_PLAYER]]$-$1.  It computes the range, calls
[[RANDOM_IN_RANGE]], adds the offset to player~2, and loads the selected
character's record via [[GET_CHAR_RECORD]].

<<pick random char>>=
    ORG     $66BA
PICK_RANDOM_CHAR:
    SUBROUTINE PICK_RANDOM_CHAR
    ; Pick a random character from players 2..CURRENT_PLAYER-1.
    ; Result: $FA/$FB points to the selected char record, CHAR_INDEX = index.
    LDA     CURRENT_PLAYER
    SEC
    SBC     #$03            ; range = CURRENT_PLAYER - 3
    JSR     RANDOM_IN_RANGE ; random 0..range-1
    CLC
    ADC     #$02            ; offset to player 2
    STA     CHAR_INDEX      ; save selected index
    JSR     GET_CHAR_RECORD ; load record for player A
    JMP     COPY_BE_TO_FA   ; copy DATA_PTR/DATA_PTR+1 -> $FA/$FB
@ %def PICK_RANDOM_CHAR

\section{Character event processing}

@ [[PROCESS_CHAR_EVENTS]] walks a character's event list---a sequence of
3-byte entries pointed to by bytes~6--7 of the character record.  For each
entry whose second byte falls in the range [[$40--$7F]], the routine subtracts
[[$40]] (normalizing to a 0-based index), stores the result back, and triggers
the event via [[CHECK_LOCATION_MATCH]].  Entries with byte~1 outside this
range are skipped, and [[$FF]] in byte~0 marks the end of the list.

<<process char events>>=
    ORG     $66CE
PROCESS_CHAR_EVENTS:
    SUBROUTINE PROCESS_CHAR_EVENTS
    ; Walk the 3-byte event list pointed to by char record bytes 6-7.
    ; For entries with byte 1 in range $40-$7F, subtract $40 from the
    ; value and trigger the event via CHECK_LOCATION_MATCH.
    LDWIY    CHAR_PTR,#$06,EVENT_PTR ; char record byte 6 = event list low
.scan:
    LDY     #$00
    LDA     (EVENT_PTR),Y ; event byte 0
    BANE    #$FF,.check   ; $FF = end of list
    RTS
.check:
    INY
    LDA     (EVENT_PTR),Y ; event byte 1
    BMI     .advance      ; bit 7 set -> skip
    BAMI    #$40,.advance ; < $40?
    SEC
    SBC     #$40          ; normalize to 0-based
    STA     (EVENT_PTR),Y ; write back
    MOVB    CHAR_INDEX,ACTIVE_CHAR ; save triggering player index
    JMP     CHECK_LOCATION_MATCH
.advance:
    CLC
    LDA     EVENT_PTR
    ADC     #$03          ; next 3-byte entry
    STA     EVENT_PTR
    BCC     .no_carry
    INC     EVENT_PTR+1
.no_carry:
    JMP     .scan
@ %def PROCESS_CHAR_EVENTS
@ [[FIND_MOB_BY_FACTION]] searches the mob linked list starting from the
current character (via [[CHAR_PTR]] byte~2) for a mob whose byte [[$0F]] has
bit~7 set and whose bits~6--4 match [[FACTION_MASK]].  It returns [[A]]=1 if
a match is found (with [[MOB_PTR]] pointing to it), or [[A]]=0 if the end of
the list is reached without a match.

<<find mob by faction>>=
    ORG     $6706
FIND_MOB_BY_FACTION:
    SUBROUTINE FIND_MOB_BY_FACTION
    ; Walk the mob linked list from ($FA) byte 2, looking for a mob
    ; whose byte $0F has bit 7 set and bits 6-4 match FACTION_MASK (faction).
    ; Returns A=1 if found (with MOB_PTR/MOB_PTR+1 pointing to it), A=0 if not.
    LDY     #$02
    LDA     (CHAR_PTR),Y       ; char record byte 2 = first link
.check_link:
    BNE     .resolve
    RTS                        ; zero link -> return A=0
.resolve:
    JSR     GET_MOB_DATA       ; resolve link -> MOB_DATA_PTR/MOB_DATA_PTR+1
    MOVW    MOB_DATA_PTR,MOB_PTR ;  MOB_PTR/MOB_PTR+1 = mob data pointer
    LDY     #$0F
    LDA     (MOB_PTR),Y        ; mob data byte $0F
    BPL     .next              ; bit 7 clear -> skip
    AND     #$70               ; bits 6-4
    BANE    FACTION_MASK,.next ; match faction?
    LDA     #$01               ; found -> return 1
    RTS
.next:
    LDY     #$02
    LDA     (MOB_PTR),Y        ; next link
    JMP     .check_link
@ %def FIND_MOB_BY_FACTION

\section{Scene event dispatch}

[[CHECK_SCENE_EVENTS]] is the scene event dispatcher called from the main
loop for players~1 and~3.  It orchestrates the encounter system by scanning
the mob list for hostile groups, then dispatching to [[SCENE_LOOP]] with
different mode numbers depending on the situation:

\begin{itemize}
\item Mode~4: player~1 non-hostile scene
\item Mode~5: other player scene
\item Mode~6: hostile encounter introduction
\item Mode~7: post-encounter resolution
\item Mode~8: combat resolution
\end{itemize}

Several flag bytes in the [[$4230]] region track which phases have already
been processed this round, preventing duplicate dispatches.

@ [[SCENE_FOUND_FLAG]] and [[SCENE_HOSTILE_FLAG]] record the results
of [[SCAN_FOR_HOSTILE]].  [[SCENE_GROUP_IDX]] is the starting group index
for the scan.  [[SCENE_P1_DONE]], [[SCENE_P3_DONE]],
[[SCENE_HOSTILE_DONE]], and [[SCENE_EVENT_RESULT]] are one-shot flags in
the [[$4230]] region that [[CHECK_SCENE_EVENTS]] tests and sets to prevent
the same phase from firing twice in one round.

<<defines>>=
SCENE_FOUND_FLAG        EQU     $5A89   ; scan result: 1 = matching group found
SCENE_HOSTILE_FLAG      EQU     $5A8A   ; scan result: nonzero = hostile encountered
SCENE_GROUP_IDX         EQU     $5A8B   ; current group index for scanning
SCENE_P3_DONE           EQU     $423B   ; nonzero = player 3 scene processed
SCENE_P1_DONE           EQU     $423C   ; nonzero = player 1 scene processed
SCENE_HOSTILE_DONE      EQU     $423D   ; nonzero = hostile encounter processed
SCENE_EVENT_RESULT      EQU     $423E   ; nonzero = event fully handled
@ %def SCENE_FOUND_FLAG SCENE_HOSTILE_FLAG SCENE_GROUP_IDX SCENE_P3_DONE SCENE_P1_DONE SCENE_HOSTILE_DONE SCENE_EVENT_RESULT

<<check scene events>>=
    ORG     $6DFA
CHECK_SCENE_EVENTS:
    SUBROUTINE CHECK_SCENE_EVENTS
    ; Scene event dispatcher for players 1 & 3.  Checks encounter
    ; state and dispatches to SCENE_LOOP with mode 4-8 based on
    ; game state flags.  Called from MAIN_ENTRY's character loop.
    LDA     #$00
    BANE    SCENE_HOSTILE_DONE,.done     ; yes -> skip
    STOB    #$40,SCENE_GROUP_IDX ; start scanning from group $40
    JSR     SCAN_FOR_HOSTILE             ; scan for hostile encounter
    LDA     #$01
    BANE    SCENE_FOUND_FLAG,.done       ; no -> skip
    BANE    CURRENT_PLAYER,.other_player ; is this player 1?
    BANE    SCENE_HOSTILE_FLAG,.hostile  ; hostile encounter found?
    BAEQ    SCENE_P1_DONE,.done          ; yes -> skip
    STA     SCENE_P1_DONE                ; mark as done
    LDA     #$04
    JMP     SCENE_LOOP                   ; mode 4: player 1 non-hostile scene
.done:
    RTS
.other_player:
    BAEQ    SCENE_P3_DONE,.done          ; yes -> skip
    STA     SCENE_P3_DONE                ; mark as done
    JSR     SET_CURSOR_ROW21
    LDA     #$05
    JMP     SCENE_LOOP                   ; mode 5: other player scene
.hostile:
    STA     SCENE_HOSTILE_DONE           ; mark hostile as processed
    LDA     #$06
    JSR     SCENE_LOOP                   ; mode 6: hostile encounter intro
    JSR     PROCESS_SCENE_GROUPS         ; process mob groups
    LDA     SCENE_EVENT_RESULT
    BNE     .done                        ; nonzero = event handled, stop
    LDA     #$07
    JSR     SCENE_LOOP                   ; mode 7: post-encounter
    LDA     SCENE_COMBAT_FLAG
    BEQ     .done                        ; no combat -> done
    JSR     SCROLL_STATUS_LINE
    LDA     #$08
    JMP     SCENE_LOOP                   ; mode 8: combat resolution
@ %def CHECK_SCENE_EVENTS

@ [[CHECK_LOCATION_MATCH]] loads the character record for [[ACTIVE_CHAR]]
and compares its position with [[LOCATION_POS]].  If they match, it clears
[[LOCATION_POS]] to force a map redraw on the next [[ENTER_LOCATION]] call.
This ensures the display updates when an event changes the scene.

<<check location match>>=
    ORG     $672E
CHECK_LOCATION_MATCH:
    SUBROUTINE CHECK_LOCATION_MATCH
    ; Load char record for ACTIVE_CHAR ($5A29), check if DATA_PTR matches
    ; LOCATION_POS.  If so, clear LOCATION_POS to force a redraw.
    LDA     ACTIVE_CHAR
    JSR     GET_CHAR_RECORD
    LDA     DATA_PTR
    BAEQ    LOCATION_POS,.match
    RTS
.match:
    STOB    #$00,LOCATION_POS ; clear to trigger redraw
    RTS
@ %def CHECK_LOCATION_MATCH
@ [[SCAN_FOR_HOSTILE]] walks the mob group chain starting from
[[SCENE_GROUP_IDX]], checking each group for hostility via
[[CHECK_HOSTILE]].  It sets [[SCENE_FOUND_FLAG]] to~1 when the target group
is encountered in the chain, and [[SCENE_HOSTILE_FLAG]] to nonzero if any
hostile group is found.  The scan continues through the entire chain even
after finding a match, so it catches all hostiles.

<<scan for hostile>>=
    ORG     $6E5A
SCAN_FOR_HOSTILE:
    SUBROUTINE SCAN_FOR_HOSTILE
    ; Scan mob groups starting from SCENE_GROUP_IDX for hostile encounters.
    ; Sets SCENE_FOUND_FLAG=1 if the group matches, SCENE_HOSTILE_FLAG
    ; nonzero if a hostile is found.
    STOB    #$00,SCENE_FOUND_FLAG
    STA     SCENE_HOSTILE_FLAG
    LDA     SCENE_GROUP_IDX
    JSR     GET_MOB_DATA                   ; resolve group -> MOB_DATA_PTR/MOB_DATA_PTR+1
    MOVW    MOB_DATA_PTR,MOB_PTR ;  MOB_PTR/MOB_PTR+1 = mob data pointer
    MOVW    CHAR_PTR,MOB_DATA_PTR ;  save $FA/$FB into MOB_DATA_PTR/MOB_DATA_PTR+1
.walk:
    LDY     #$02
    LDA     (MOB_DATA_PTR),Y               ; mob data byte 2 = next link
    BNE     .has_link
    RTS                                    ; end of chain
.has_link:
    BANE    SCENE_GROUP_IDX,.check_hostile ; matches the target group?
    LDX     #$01
    STX     SCENE_FOUND_FLAG               ; mark as found
.check_hostile:
    JSR     GET_MOB_DATA                   ; resolve link -> MOB_DATA_PTR/MOB_DATA_PTR+1
    MOVW    MOB_DATA_PTR,TARGET_REC ;  TARGET_REC/TARGET_REC+1 = resolved mob data
    JSR     CHECK_HOSTILE                  ; check if hostile
    BEQ     .walk                          ; not hostile -> continue
    STA     SCENE_HOSTILE_FLAG             ; hostile found
    BNE     .walk                          ; always branches, continue scan
@ %def SCAN_FOR_HOSTILE
@ [[PROCESS_SCENE_GROUPS]] handles the hostile encounter phase by processing
mob groups [[$3F]], [[$41]], and [[$42]] with [[SCAN_AND_REORDER]].  Group
[[$40]] is skipped because it is the player's own group.  The routine
bookends the processing with [[LOAD_CHAR_TO_FA]] calls to save and restore
the player~3 record pointer.

<<process scene groups>>=
    ORG     $6E9E
PROCESS_SCENE_GROUPS:
    SUBROUTINE PROCESS_SCENE_GROUPS
    ; Process mob groups $3F, $41, $42 with SCAN_AND_REORDER,
    ; bookended by LOAD_CHAR_TO_FA for save/restore.
    STOB    #$03,SOURCE_CHAR
    JSR     LOAD_CHAR_TO_FA  ; save player 3's record to $FA/$FB
    STOB    #$00,ACTIVE_CHAR
    STOB    #$3F,SCENE_GROUP_IDX
    JSR     SCAN_AND_REORDER ; group $3F
    INC     SCENE_GROUP_IDX  ; $40 (skip -- that's the player's group)
    INC     SCENE_GROUP_IDX  ; $41
    JSR     SCAN_AND_REORDER ; group $41
    INC     SCENE_GROUP_IDX  ; $42
    JSR     SCAN_AND_REORDER ; group $42
    LDA     CURRENT_PLAYER
    JSR     LOAD_CHAR_TO_FA  ; restore current player's record
    RTS
@ %def PROCESS_SCENE_GROUPS
@ [[SCAN_AND_REORDER]] combines a hostile scan with a group reorder.  It
calls [[SCAN_FOR_HOSTILE]] and, if the target group is found, copies the mob
pointer into [[TARGET_REC]] and calls [[REORDER_CHAR]] to move the character
into the matching group.

<<scan and reorder>>=
    ORG     $6ED5
SCAN_AND_REORDER:
    SUBROUTINE SCAN_AND_REORDER
    ; Call SCAN_FOR_HOSTILE for current SCENE_GROUP_IDX.
    ; If a match is found, copy MOB_PTR/MOB_PTR+1 -> TARGET_REC/TARGET_REC+1 and reorder.
    JSR     SCAN_FOR_HOSTILE
    LDA     SCENE_FOUND_FLAG
    BNE     .found
    RTS                  ; nothing found
.found:
    MOVW    MOB_PTR,TARGET_REC ;  TARGET_REC/TARGET_REC+1 = mob data pointer
    JMP     REORDER_CHAR
@ %def SCAN_AND_REORDER

@ \subsection{Flush pending XP (\$6EE9--\$6F16)}

[[FLUSH_PENDING_XP]] extracts the pending XP field from byte~8 of the
entity record at [[ENTITY_PTR]] and adds it to the level in byte~11.
Byte~8 is a packed field:
\begin{itemize}
\item bits 6--4: pending XP (0--7)
\item bit~7: status flag (preserved)
\item bits 3--0: group count (cleared by this routine)
\end{itemize}
The routine clears the lower 7~bits of byte~8 (keeping only bit~7),
extracts bits~6--4 as a 3-bit value (0--7), and adds it to byte~11
(the level field).  If there was XP to flush, it displays message~\$2B.
If the lower 7~bits were zero (no pending XP and no group members), it
displays message~\$37 and returns to [[MOVE_LOOP]].

<<flush pending xp>>=
    ORG     $6EE9
FLUSH_PENDING_XP:
    SUBROUTINE FLUSH_PENDING_XP
    LDY     #$08
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y     ; byte 8: status|pending_xp|group_count
    TAX                        ; save original
    AND     #$80               ; keep only status flag (bit 7)
    STA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y     ; clear pending XP and group count
    TXA
    AND     #$7F               ; strip status flag
    BEQ     .no_xp             ; bits 6-0 all zero -> nothing to flush
    ROR                        ; \ extract bits 6-4 (pending XP)
    ROR                        ;  | shift right 4 positions
    ROR                        ;  |
    ROR                        ; /
    AND     #$07               ; mask to 3 bits (0-7)
    CLC
    LDY     #$0B
    ADC     (ENTITY_PTR),Y     ; add pending XP to level
    STA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y     ; store updated level
    JSR     SET_CURSOR_ROW21
    LDA     #MSG_XP_GAINED               ; XP gained message
    JMP     DISPLAY_MESSAGE

.no_xp:
    JSR     SET_CURSOR_ROW21
    LDA     #MSG_NO_XP               ; no XP message
    JSR     DISPLAY_MESSAGE
    JMP     MOVE_LOOP
@ %def FLUSH_PENDING_XP

@ \subsection{Drop gold system (\$6F17--\$704C)}

The drop gold system uses a binary search algorithm to let the player
choose how much gold to drop.  Four variables track the state:
\begin{itemize}
\item [[DROP_AMOUNT\_LO]]/[[DROP_AMOUNT\_HI]]: the current drop amount
\item [[DROP_STEP\_LO]]/[[DROP_STEP\_HI]]: the current binary search step
\end{itemize}

[[INIT_DROP_GOLD]] initializes the binary search.  It calls
[[FIND_MSB]] on the entity's gold (bytes~\$0D/\$0E) to find the
highest set bit, sets the drop amount to that power of~2, copies it
to the step, halves the step, and enters the drop gold menu.
If the entity has no gold, it displays message~\$2E and returns to
the other options menu.

<<defines>>=
DROP_AMOUNT_LO      EQU     $5A7A   ; drop gold amount (low byte)
DROP_AMOUNT_HI      EQU     $5A7B   ; drop gold amount (high byte)
DROP_STEP_LO        EQU     $5A7C   ; binary search step (low byte)
DROP_STEP_HI        EQU     $5A7D   ; binary search step (high byte)
DROP_DISPLAY_BUF    EQU     $7CEB   ; 5-byte decimal display buffer
@ %def DROP_AMOUNT_LO DROP_AMOUNT_HI DROP_STEP_LO DROP_STEP_HI DROP_DISPLAY_BUF

<<init drop gold>>=
    ORG     $6F17
INIT_DROP_GOLD:
    SUBROUTINE INIT_DROP_GOLD
    LDA     #$00
    STA     DROP_AMOUNT_LO
    LDY     #$0E
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y     ; gold high byte
    JSR     FIND_MSB           ; X = highest set bit mask
    STX     DROP_AMOUNT_HI
    CPX     #$00
    BNE     .has_gold
    DEY                        ; Y = $0D
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y     ; gold low byte
    JSR     FIND_MSB
    STX     DROP_AMOUNT_LO
    BNE     .has_gold
    JSR     SET_CURSOR_ROW21
    LDA     #MSG_NO_GOLD               ; "no gold" message
    JSR     DISPLAY_MESSAGE
    JMP     MENU_OTHER_OPTIONS

.has_gold:
    LDA     DROP_AMOUNT_LO     ; \ copy amount to step
    STA     DROP_STEP_LO       ;  |
    LDA     DROP_AMOUNT_HI     ;  |
    STA     DROP_STEP_HI       ; /
    JSR     HALVE_STEP         ; step = amount / 2
    JMP     MENU_DROP_GOLD     ; enter drop gold menu
@ %def INIT_DROP_GOLD

@ [[INIT_DROP_DISPLAY]] is the initialization callback for the drop gold
menu.  It clears the 5-byte display buffer at [[DROP_DISPLAY_BUF]] and
converts [[DROP_AMOUNT\_LO]]/[[DROP_AMOUNT\_HI]] to a decimal string
via [[NUM_TO_DECIMAL]].

<<init drop display>>=
    ORG     $6F52
INIT_DROP_DISPLAY:
    SUBROUTINE INIT_DROP_DISPLAY
    LDX     #$04
    LDA     #$20               ; space
.clear:
    STA     DROP_DISPLAY_BUF,X
    DEX
    BPL     .clear
    LDA     DROP_AMOUNT_LO
    STA     $BC
    LDA     DROP_AMOUNT_HI
    STA     $BD
    LDA     #<DROP_DISPLAY_BUF
    STA     $BA
    LDA     #>DROP_DISPLAY_BUF
    STA     $BB
    JSR     NUM_TO_DECIMAL
    RTS
@ %def INIT_DROP_DISPLAY

@ [[ADJ_DROP_INC]] and [[ADJ_DROP_DEC]] are the handlers for the \# and
@ keys in the drop gold menu.  They implement a binary search:
\begin{itemize}
\item \#~(X=3): subtract the step from the drop amount, then halve
  the step.
\item @~(X=4): add the step to the drop amount, halve the step, then
  check if the amount exceeds the entity's actual gold.  If so, undo
  by double-subtracting the step and switch to decrement mode.
\end{itemize}
If the step reaches zero, the search reinitializes via
[[INIT_DROP_GOLD]].

<<adj drop amount>>=
    ORG     $6F72
ADJ_DROP_INC:
    LDX     #$03               ; # pressed
    BNE     .entry

ADJ_DROP_DEC:
    LDX     #$04               ; @ pressed

.entry:
    LDA     #$00
    CMP     DROP_STEP_LO
    BNE     .nonzero
    CMP     DROP_STEP_HI
    BEQ     INIT_DROP_GOLD     ; step = 0 -> reinitialize

.nonzero:
    TXA
    CMP     #$03
    BEQ     .dec_amount        ; X=3 (#) -> subtract step

    ; X=4 (@): add step, halve, check bounds
    JSR     ADD_DROP
    JSR     HALVE_STEP
    LDY     #$0E
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y     ; actual gold hi
    CMP     DROP_AMOUNT_HI
    BCC     .over_limit        ; drop > gold -> too much
    BNE     .done              ; drop < gold -> ok
    DEY
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y     ; actual gold lo
    CMP     DROP_AMOUNT_LO
    BCS     .done              ; drop <= gold -> ok

.over_limit:
    JSR     SUB_DROP           ; undo: amount -= step
    JSR     SUB_DROP           ; undo again (net: amount -= step)
    LDX     #$04               ; switch to @ mode
    BNE     .entry             ; retry with reduced step

.dec_amount:
    JSR     SUB_DROP           ; amount -= step
    JSR     HALVE_STEP         ; step /= 2

.done:
    JMP     MENU_DROP_GOLD     ; re-enter drop gold menu
@ %def ADJ_DROP_INC ADJ_DROP_DEC

@ [[DROP_GOLD_EXEC]] is the handler for the ``DROP GOLD'' option in the
drop gold menu.  It subtracts the drop amount from the entity's gold
via [[MODIFY_CURRENT_STATS]], then generates a random multiplier
(1--25) and subtracts it from the amount.  If gold remains, it
displays message~\$2D and creates a gold drop event at the entity's
position via [[UPDATE_EVENT_LIST]].  If the amount is zero or negative,
it displays message~\$2C (gold lost/stolen) instead.

<<drop gold exec>>=
    ORG     $6FB5
DROP_GOLD_EXEC:
    SUBROUTINE DROP_GOLD_EXEC
    LDA     DROP_AMOUNT_LO
    STA     $BC
    LDA     DROP_AMOUNT_HI
    STA     $BD
    LDY     #$00
    STY     DROP_STEP_HI
    JSR     MODIFY_CURRENT_STATS ; subtract gold from entity
    LDA     #$19
    JSR     RANDOM_IN_RANGE    ; random 0-24
    STA     DROP_STEP_LO
    INC     DROP_STEP_LO       ; step = 1-25
    JSR     SET_CURSOR_ROW21
    JSR     SUB_DROP           ; amount -= random step (gold lost)
    LDA     DROP_AMOUNT_HI
    BMI     .lost              ; negative -> all lost
    BNE     .has_gold
    LDA     DROP_AMOUNT_LO
    BEQ     .lost              ; zero -> all lost

.has_gold:
    LDA     #MSG_GOLD_DROPPED               ; gold dropped message
    JSR     DISPLAY_MESSAGE
    LDA     DROP_AMOUNT_LO
    STA     $BC
    LDA     DROP_AMOUNT_HI
    STA     $BD
    LDY     #$03
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y     ; entity position
    JSR     UPDATE_EVENT_LIST  ; create gold event on map
    JMP     MOVE_LOOP

.lost:
    LDA     #MSG_GOLD_LOST               ; gold lost message
    JSR     DISPLAY_MESSAGE
    JMP     MOVE_LOOP
@ %def DROP_GOLD_EXEC

@ \subsection{Arithmetic helpers (\$7005--\$704C)}

[[FIND_MSB]] returns in~X the mask of the most significant set bit
in~A.  It starts with X=\$80 (bit~7) and shifts A left through carry;
if the carry is set, the current bit position is the MSB.  Otherwise
it shifts X right and continues.

[[ADD_DROP]] and [[SUB_DROP]] perform 16-bit addition and subtraction
on the drop amount ([[DROP_AMOUNT\_LO]]/[[DROP_AMOUNT\_HI]]) using
the step ([[DROP_STEP\_LO]]/[[DROP_STEP\_HI]]).

[[HALVE_STEP]] divides the step by~2 via a 16-bit right shift.

<<arithmetic helpers>>=
    ORG     $7005
FIND_MSB:
    SUBROUTINE FIND_MSB
    SEC
    LDX     #$80               ; start with bit 7 mask
.test:
    ROL                        ; shift A left through carry
    BCC     .next              ; bit was 0 -> try next
    RTS                        ; bit was 1 -> X = mask
.next:
    PHA
    TXA
    LSR                        ; shift mask right
    TAX
    PLA
    CLC
    JMP     .test

ADD_DROP:
    CLC
    LDA     DROP_AMOUNT_LO
    ADC     DROP_STEP_LO
    STA     DROP_AMOUNT_LO
    LDA     DROP_AMOUNT_HI
    ADC     DROP_STEP_HI
    STA     DROP_AMOUNT_HI
    RTS

SUB_DROP:
    SEC
    LDA     DROP_AMOUNT_LO
    SBC     DROP_STEP_LO
    STA     DROP_AMOUNT_LO
    LDA     DROP_AMOUNT_HI
    SBC     DROP_STEP_HI
    STA     DROP_AMOUNT_HI
    RTS

HALVE_STEP:
    CLC
    LDA     DROP_STEP_HI
    ROR
    STA     DROP_STEP_HI
    LDA     DROP_STEP_LO
    ROR
    STA     DROP_STEP_LO
    RTS
@ %def FIND_MSB ADD_DROP SUB_DROP HALVE_STEP

\section{Turn events}

@ [[TRIGGER_SCENE_EVENT]] handles events in the [[$D2--$D4]] range of the
encounter dispatch table.  It clears the character state, then enters the
scene loop with a mode derived from the event type, triggering a scripted
scene transition.

<<trigger scene event>>=
    ORG     $1D04
TRIGGER_SCENE_EVENT:
    SUBROUTINE TRIGGER_SCENE_EVENT

    LDA     #$00
    JSR     SET_CHAR_STATE          ; set char field 15 state to 0
    MOVW    EVENT_PTR,$5A5B ; save event pointer low
    JSR     COMMIT_MOVE             ; commit move
    MOVW    $5A5B,EVENT_PTR ; restore event pointer
    LDY     #$02
    LDA     (EVENT_PTR),Y           ; event byte 2 = scene index
    JSR     SCENE_LOOP              ; trigger scene
    LDY     #$01
    LDA     (EVENT_PTR),Y           ; event byte 1 = type
    BAPL    #$D3,.d3_or_above
    RTS                             ; $D2: trigger scene only
.d3_or_above:
    BNE     .d4
    LDA     #$FE                    ; $D3: mark event as empty
    DEY
    STA     (EVENT_PTR),Y
    RTS
.d4:
    LDA     #$FE                    ; $D4: mark event as empty
    DEY
    STA     (EVENT_PTR),Y
    LDA     #$0F
    JSR     SCENE_LOOP              ; trigger bonus scene $0F
    LDA     #$03
    JSR     RANDOM_IN_RANGE         ; random(3)
    CLC
    ADC     #$01                    ; 1-3
    JMP     APPLY_DAMAGE_TO_CURRENT ; apply effect to char
@ %def TRIGGER_SCENE_EVENT
@ When a character steps onto a treasure event, [[PICKUP_TREASURE]] handles the
interaction.  The routine first clears the character's state, copies the event
pointer to [[MOB_PTR]], and commits the movement.  It then reads byte~1 of the
event entry to determine the treasure type.  Values below~\$C9 are normal
treasure: the routine subtracts~\$C0 to get a treasure table index, reads the
quantity from byte~2, calls [[MODIFY_CURRENT_STATS]] to look up the item data,
and---if the character's inventory is not full---adds the item and formats a
pickup message with [[NUM_TO_DECIMAL]] and [[CLEAR_AND_DISPLAY]].  Values at
\$C9 or above indicate trapped chests.  A random roll selects one of four trap
types: lose 1--5~HP, lose 2--9~HP, decrement a counter in field~11, or zero
out all gold.  Each trap triggers a distinct scene (scenes~\$36--\$39).  If the
character is in a different room from the current room, the event entry's type
byte is stepped back by~9, turning the chest into a different kind of treasure
for re-encounter.  The special type~\$D1 triggers scene~\$0B, increments two
stat counters, and has a 1-in-3 chance of producing a bonus scene~\$0C---a
lucky find.

<<defines>>=
TRAP_TYPE           EQU     $5A58   ; treasure trap: random trap type (0-3)
@ %def TRAP_TYPE

<<pickup treasure>>=
    ORG     $646B
PICKUP_TREASURE:
    SUBROUTINE PICKUP_TREASURE

    LDA     #$00
    JSR     SET_CHAR_STATE          ; set char field 15 state to 0
    MOVW    EVENT_PTR,MOB_PTR ; copy event ptr -> MOB_PTR/MOB_PTR+1
    JSR     COMMIT_MOVE             ; commit move
    LDY     #$01
    LDA     (MOB_PTR),Y             ; event byte 1 = treasure type
    BAPL    #$C9,.trapped ; >= $C9 -> trapped chest or special
    SEC
    SBC     #$C0                    ; $C0-$C8: treasure index 0-8
    STA     NUM_VALUE+1
.rejoin:
    LDY     #$02
    LDA     (MOB_PTR),Y             ; event byte 2 = quantity
    STA     NUM_VALUE
    LDY     #$01
    JSR     MODIFY_CURRENT_STATS    ; look up treasure data
    LDY     #$04
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y          ; char field 4
    BAGE    #$15,.mark_used ; inventory full -> skip pickup
    JSR     CLEAR_STATUS_SLOTS      ; add item to inventory
    STOW    $7BAB,$BA
    JSR     NUM_TO_DECIMAL          ; format quantity
    LDWIY    ENTITY_PTR,#$0D,NUM_VALUE ; char field 13 (gold low)
    STOW    $7BCC,$BA
    JSR     NUM_TO_DECIMAL          ; format gold amount
    JSR     SET_CURSOR_ROW21
    STOW    $7B84,NUM_VALUE
    JSR     CLEAR_AND_DISPLAY       ; display pickup message
.mark_used:
    LDY     #$00
    LDA     #$FE                    ; mark event slot as empty
    STA     (MOB_PTR),Y
    RTS

    ; --- trapped chest (type >= $C9) ---
.trapped:
    BANE    #$D1,.not_d1
    JMP     .handle_d1              ; $D1: special chest
.not_d1:
    LDA     #$06
    JSR     RANDOM_IN_RANGE         ; random(6)
    AND     #$03                    ; trap type 0-3
    STA     TRAP_TYPE
    LDY     #$04
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y          ; char field 4
    BMI     .apply_trap
    BAPL    #$15,.apply_trap
    JSR     SET_CURSOR_ROW21
    LDA     #$36
    CLC
    ADC     TRAP_TYPE               ; scene $36 + trap type
    JSR     SCENE_LOOP              ; show trap scene
.apply_trap:
    LDA     TRAP_TYPE
    BAMI    #$01,.trap0 ; trap 0: lose 1-5 HP
    BEQ     .trap1                  ; trap 1: lose 2-9 HP
    BAEQ    #$02,.trap2             ; trap 2: decrement counter
    BNE     .trap3                  ; trap 3: zero gold
.trap0:
    LDA     #$05
    JSR     RANDOM_IN_RANGE
    CLC
    ADC     #$01                    ; 1-5 damage
    JSR     APPLY_DAMAGE_TO_CURRENT
    JMP     .after_trap
.trap1:
    LDA     #$08
    JSR     RANDOM_IN_RANGE
    CLC
    ADC     #$02                    ; 2-9 damage
    JSR     APPLY_DAMAGE_TO_CURRENT
    JMP     .after_trap
.trap2:
    LDY     #$0B
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y          ; char field 11
    AND     #$1F
    BEQ     .after_trap             ; already zero
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y
    SEC
    SBC     #$01                    ; decrement
    STA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y
    JMP     .after_trap
.trap3:
    LDY     #$0D
    LDA     #$00
    STA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y          ; zero gold low
    INY
    STA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y          ; zero gold high
.after_trap:
    LDY     #$02
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y          ; char field 2 = room
    BAEQ    CURRENT_ROOM,.same_room ; current room?
    DEY
    LDA     (MOB_PTR),Y             ; event byte 1
    SEC
    SBC     #$09                    ; step back 9 in treasure table
    STA     (MOB_PTR),Y
    RTS
.same_room:
    DEY
    LDA     (MOB_PTR),Y             ; event byte 1
    SEC
    SBC     #$C9                    ; convert to treasure index
    STA     NUM_VALUE+1
    JMP     .rejoin                 ; loop: process next treasure

    ; --- special chest $D1 ---
.handle_d1:
    LDA     #$0B
    JSR     SCENE_LOOP              ; show scene $0B
    JSR     INC_FIELD5_COUNTER
    JSR     INC_FIELD_COUNTER
    LDA     #$03
    JSR     RANDOM_IN_RANGE         ; random(3)
    BAEQ    #$00,.lucky
    RTS                             ; 2/3 chance: nothing
.lucky:
    LDA     #$0C
    JSR     SCENE_LOOP              ; show bonus scene $0C
    JMP     .mark_used              ; mark event used
@ %def PICKUP_TREASURE
@ [[INC_FIELD5_COUNTER]] and [[INC_FIELD_COUNTER]] increment a 5-bit counter
packed into the low bits of a character record field.  The first entry point
targets field~5 (the defense/experience counter); the second targets field~11
(the level counter).  Both share a common body that masks out the low five
bits, checks whether the value has already reached the maximum of~31, and if
not, adds~1 to the full byte---which works correctly because the upper bits
are preserved by the addition as long as the low field does not overflow past
31.

<<inc field5 counter>>=
    ORG     $657B
INC_FIELD5_COUNTER:
    SUBROUTINE INC_FIELD5_COUNTER
    ; Increment char field 5 low 5 bits (capped at $1F)
    LDY     #$05
    JMP     .body
INC_FIELD_COUNTER:
    ; Increment char field Y low 5 bits (capped at $1F)
    LDY     #$0B
.body:
    LDA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y
    TAX
    AND     #$1F
    BANE    #$1F,.inc
    RTS
.inc:
    CLC
    TXA
    ADC     #$01
    STA     (ENTITY_PTR),Y
    RTS
@ %def INC_FIELD5_COUNTER INC_FIELD_COUNTER
@ [[CLEAR_STATUS_SLOTS]] fills two 5-byte regions of the display buffer
(\$7BAB--\$7BAF and \$7BCC--\$7BD0) with spaces.  These regions hold the
formatted quantity and gold amount strings used by [[PICKUP_TREASURE]]'s
display message, and clearing them ensures no stale digits remain from a
previous interaction.

<<clear status slots>>=
    ORG     $6593
CLEAR_STATUS_SLOTS:
    SUBROUTINE CLEAR_AND_DISPLAY
    ; Clear 5 bytes at $7BAB-$7BAF and $7BCC-$7BD0 (spaces)
    LDA     #$20
    LDX     #$04
.loop:
    STA     $7BAB,X
    STA     $7BCC,X
    DEX
    BPL     .loop
    RTS
@ %def CLEAR_STATUS_SLOTS
@ [[CLEAR_AND_DISPLAY]] zeroes the flag at~\$5A57 and tail-calls
[[DISPLAY_MESSAGE_LOOP]].  Clearing the flag ensures the message loop starts
from scratch rather than continuing a previous multi-part display sequence.

<<clear and display>>=
    ORG     $65A1
CLEAR_AND_DISPLAY:
    SUBROUTINE MODIFY_CURRENT_STATS
    ; Clear $5A57 and JMP $764A (display message)
    STOB    #$00,$5A57
    JMP     DISPLAY_MESSAGE_LOOP
@ %def CLEAR_AND_DISPLAY
@ [[UPDATE_EVENT_LIST]] maintains the character's event list when treasure is
dropped or an event is spawned at a map position.  It takes a position in~A
and a value in [[NUM_VALUE]]/[[NUM_VALUE+1]]; if the value is zero, it returns
immediately.  The routine walks the 3-byte event entries starting from the
pointer at bytes~6--7 of the character record.  When it finds an empty slot
(\$FE), it inserts a new entry: byte~0 gets the position, byte~1 gets the
value high bits (masked to 3~bits) OR'd with~\$C0 to mark it as activated, and
byte~2 gets the value low byte.  If the routine finds an existing entry at the
same position with a type in the \$C0--\$D0 range, it adds the new value to
that entry instead of creating a duplicate.  If the list terminator~(\$FF) is
reached with no room, it displays message~\$2A (``event list full'').

<<update event list>>=
    ORG     $1260
UPDATE_EVENT_LIST:
    SUBROUTINE UPDATE_EVENT_LIST
    ; Update event list for position A with value NUM_VALUE/NUM_VALUE+1.
    ; If NUM_VALUE/NUM_VALUE+1 = 0, return immediately.
    ; Scans 3-byte event entries at ($FA)[6..7]:
    ;   $FF = end of list -> display message $2A
    ;   $FE = empty slot -> insert new entry
    ;   matching pos + type $C0-$D0 -> add to existing entry
    ;   else -> advance to next entry
    STA     $BA             ; save position
    LDA     #$00
    BANE    NUM_VALUE,.has_value
    BANE    NUM_VALUE+1,.has_value
    RTS
.has_value:
    LDWIY    CHAR_PTR,#$06,EVENT_PTR ; event list pointer low
.scan:
    LDY     #$00
    LDA     (EVENT_PTR),Y   ; entry byte 0 = position
    BANE    #$FF,.not_end
    JSR     SET_CURSOR_ROW21
    LDA     #MSG_ARMOR_WORTHLESS
    JMP     DISPLAY_MESSAGE ; "event list full" message
.not_end:
    BANE    #$FE,.check_match
    ; Empty slot: insert new entry
    LDA     $BA
    STA     (EVENT_PTR),Y   ; byte 0 = position
    INY
    LDA     NUM_VALUE+1
    AND     #$07
    ORA     #$C0            ; byte 1 = type + high bits
    STA     (EVENT_PTR),Y
    INY
    LDA     NUM_VALUE
    STA     (EVENT_PTR),Y   ; byte 2 = value low
    RTS
.check_match:
    BANE    $BA,.next       ; same position?
    INY
    LDA     (EVENT_PTR),Y   ; byte 1 = type
    BPL     .next           ; not activated
    BAMI    #$C0,.next ; below $C0
    BAPL    #$D1,.next ; above $D0
    ; Add to existing entry
    CLC
    LDA     NUM_VALUE
    INY
    ADC     (EVENT_PTR),Y   ; byte 2 += value low
    STA     (EVENT_PTR),Y
    DEY
    LDA     NUM_VALUE+1
    AND     #$07
    ADC     (EVENT_PTR),Y   ; byte 1 += value high (with carry)
    STA     (EVENT_PTR),Y
    RTS
.next:
    CLC
    LDA     EVENT_PTR
    ADC     #$03            ; next 3-byte entry
    STA     EVENT_PTR
    BCC     .no_carry
    INC     EVENT_PTR+1
.no_carry:
    JMP     .scan
@ %def UPDATE_EVENT_LIST
@ [[CHECK_CAN_LEAVE]] uses the PRNG to determine whether a character can
leave an area.  It steps the PRNG and compares the output against a threshold
of~\$40: if the random value is at or above the threshold (roughly 75\%
chance), the check passes and message~\$1C is displayed; otherwise it fails
with message~\$1D.  The result is returned in~A (1~for success, 0~for
failure).  Both paths print the mob's name before the message for context.

<<check can leave>>=
    ORG     $1231
CHECK_CAN_LEAVE:
    SUBROUTINE CHECK_CAN_LEAVE
    ; Check hostility threshold: if PRNG_OUTPUT >= $40, show message $1C
    ; and return 1; else show message $1D and return 0.
    JSR     STEP_PRNG
    LDA     PRNG_OUTPUT
    BAPL    #$40,.pass
    JMP     .fail
.pass:
    JSR     SET_CURSOR_ROW21
    JSR     PRINT_MOB_NAME
    JSR     SCROLL_STATUS_LINE
    LDA     #MSG_ESCAPE_FAIL
    JSR     DISPLAY_MESSAGE
    LDA     #$01
    RTS
.fail:
    JSR     SET_CURSOR_ROW21
    JSR     PRINT_MOB_NAME
    JSR     SCROLL_STATUS_LINE
    LDA     #MSG_TACKLE_FAIL
    JSR     DISPLAY_MESSAGE
    LDA     #$00
    RTS
@ %def CHECK_CAN_LEAVE

\section{Tune player}

\label{sec:tune_player}

The tune player runs short bytecode programs that play sound effects and
sound effects and music.  It is called with a tune index in X.

@ [[ATTRACT_FLAG]] is set to 1 when [[TUNE_PLAYER]] is invoked with
tune index 6 (the attract/demo mode) and cleared to 0 for all other
indices.  Downstream code checks this flag to alter behavior during the
title screen sequence.

<<defines>>=
ATTRACT_FLAG        EQU     $5AA7   ; 1 = attract/demo mode, 0 = normal
@ %def ATTRACT_FLAG
@ The script base addresses are stored in the table below.
The X~register passed to [[TUNE_PLAYER]] is a byte offset into
this table (X~=~0 for script~0, X~=~2 for script~1, etc.).

The table contains 12~entries (scripts 0--11).  The X~register passed
to [[TUNE_PLAYER]] is a byte offset (X~=~0 for script~0, X~=~2 for
script~1, etc.).

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{cclll}
\hline
\textbf{X} & \textbf{Tune} & \textbf{Address} & \textbf{Purpose} & \textbf{Callers} \\
\hline
\$00 & 0  & \$80C6 & (empty --- single END byte) & --- \\
\$02 & 1  & \$80C7 & combat hit effect & attack routines \\
\$04 & 2  & \$80D7 & combat damage effect & damage handler \\
\$06 & 3  & \$A300 & attract/opening & attract screen, scene loop, game init \\
\$08 & 4  & \$A3C3 & mob death effect & death handler (field~4 $<$ \$15) \\
\$0A & 5  & \$A3CE & NPC death effect & death handler (field~4 $\geq$ \$15) \\
\$0C & 6  & \$A3DE & combat avoided effect & hit handler, avoid handler \\
\$0E & 7  & \$A409 & entity interaction effect & movement, entity scripts \\
\$10 & 8  & \$A432 & AI turn effect & [[SETUP_SCENE_DISPLAY]] \\
\$12 & 9  & \$A437 & menu selection effect & [[INPUT_LOOP]] \\
\$14 & 10 & \$A3FC & encounter effect & encounter handler \\
\$16 & 11 & \$A43C & movement effect & [[COMMIT_MOVE]] \\
\hline
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

<<tune pointer table>>=
    ORG     $80AE
TUNE_TABLE:
    DC.W    $80C6 ; tune 0  (X=$00): empty (single END byte)
    DC.W    $80C7 ; tune 1  (X=$02): combat hit effect
    DC.W    $80D7 ; tune 2  (X=$04): combat damage effect
    DC.W    $A300 ; tune 3  (X=$06): attract/opening
    DC.W    $A3C3 ; tune 4  (X=$08): mob death effect
    DC.W    $A3CE ; tune 5  (X=$0A): NPC death effect
    DC.W    $A3DE ; tune 6  (X=$0C): combat avoided effect
    DC.W    $A409 ; tune 7  (X=$0E): entity interaction effect
    DC.W    $A432 ; tune 8  (X=$10): AI turn effect
    DC.W    $A437 ; tune 9  (X=$12): menu selection effect
    DC.W    $A3FC ; script 10 (X=$14): encounter effect
    DC.W    $A43C ; script 11 (X=$16): movement effect
@ %def TUNE_TABLE

<<tune player>>=
    ORG     $795B
TUNE_PLAYER:
    SUBROUTINE TUNE_PLAYER

    STA     $C010             ; clear keyboard strobe
    STOB    #$00,ATTRACT_FLAG ; attract_flag = 0
    BXNE    #$06,.not_attract ; tune index 6 = attract
    INC     ATTRACT_FLAG      ; attract_flag = 1
.not_attract:

    BXEQ    #$02,.setup_2     ; special setup for index 2
    BXEQ    #$04,.setup_4     ; special setup for index 4
    JMP     .load_ptr

.setup_2:
    DEY
    STY     $80D5             ; patch byte in script 1 data
    JMP     .load_ptr
.setup_4:
    DEY
    STY     $80E3             ; patch byte in script 2 data
@
@ [[TUNE_PC]] is the 2-byte script instruction pointer at [[$E4/$E5]].
The script base address is loaded from the table at [[$80AE]] into
[[TUNE_PC]], and the interpreter reads successive bytes through this
pointer, advancing it after each instruction.

<<zero page defines>>=
TUNE_PC               EQU     $E4     ; script instruction pointer (2 bytes, $E4/$E5)
@ %def TUNE_PC

<<tune player>>=

.load_ptr:
    LDA     TUNE_TABLE,X   ; low byte
    STA     TUNE_PC
    LDA     TUNE_TABLE+1,X ; high byte
    STA     TUNE_PC+1      ; TUNE_PC/TUNE_PC+1 = script start address
@

\subsubsection{Script 0 --- empty}

A single END byte.  Used as a no-op placeholder (script index~0 is
never called).

<<tune bytecode>>=
    ORG     $80C6
TUNE_0:
    DC.B    $24               ; END
@ %def TUNE_0

