@ \section{Relocated block: game support routines}

The following routines reside in the relocated block (\$9600--\$A8FF,
originally staged at \$2000--\$32FF).  They provide keyboard input,
scene data loading, disk checkpointing, and integrity checking.

\subsection{Tune stubs and keyboard dispatch (\$A440--\$A44B)}

[[TUNE_STUB_BIT]] is a short entry point that tests bit~\$A2 (a ZP
flag), loads A=\$0A, and jumps to the tune player at [[$A4BE]].
[[DISK_READ_JUMP]] jumps to [[DISK_READ]] (\$6C12).
[[DISK_RTS]] is a single RTS used as a no-op call target.

<<tune stubs>>=
    ORG     $A440
TUNE_END_MARKER:
    DC.B    $24               ; tune END byte (shared with TUNE_11)

LOAD_SCENE_DISK_ENTRY:
    LDX     #$0D               ; track $0D
    LDA     #$0A               ; sector $0A
    JMP     SETUP_AND_READ_DISK

DISK_READ_JUMP:
    JMP     DISK_READ

DISK_RTS:
    RTS
@ %def TUNE_END_MARKER LOAD_SCENE_DISK_ENTRY DISK_READ_JUMP DISK_RTS

@ \subsection{Read keyboard (\$A44C--\$A477)}

[[READ_KEYBOARD]] clears the keyboard strobe, calls [[COLROW_TO_POS]]
(\$0D30) to update the map position, then enters a polling loop.
It checks [[PRNG_OUTPUT]] (\$5A18) masked with \$7E; if zero, it
calls the integrity check routine at [[$A4E6]].  Then it steps the
PRNG, calls an animation delay at [[$755E]], and loops until a
keypress is detected (BPL on \$C000).  On keypress it clears the
strobe and returns the key in~A.

<<read keyboard routine>>=
    ORG     $A44C
READ_KEYBOARD:
    SUBROUTINE READ_KEYBOARD
    LDA     #$FF
    STA     $C010              ; clear keyboard strobe
    JSR     $0D30              ; update map position
    LDA     PRNG_OUTPUT
    AND     #$7E
    BNE     .display
    JSR     VERIFY_INTEGRITY

.display:
    JSR     $0D1E              ; display update
.poll:
    JSR     STEP_PRNG
    JSR     $755E              ; animation delay
    BPL     .got_key           ; key available
    JSR     $0D5E              ; idle processing
    JMP     .poll

.got_key:
    STA     $C010              ; clear keyboard strobe
    PHA
    JSR     $0D36              ; post-input processing
    PLA
    RTS
@ %def READ_KEYBOARD

@ \subsection{Load scene data from disk (\$A478--\$A4BD)}

[[$A478]] loads scene data from the game disk.  It sets up the RWTS
IOB for a buffer at [[SCENE_TEXT_DATA]] (\$5C00), calculates the
track and sector from [[GAME_SIG_TRACK]] and [[SCENE_NUMBER]]
(sector = (sig\_sector + scene) mod~13, incrementing track on
overflow), then reads the sector via [[DISK_READ]].  On failure
after 2~retries it returns carry set; on success carry clear.

<<load scene from disk>>=
    ORG     $A478
LOAD_SCENE_FROM_DISK:
    SUBROUTINE LOAD_SCENE_FROM_DISK
    JSR     DISK_RTS           ; no-op (placeholder)
    LDA     #$00
    LDY     #$08
    STA     (RWTS_IOB_PTR),Y   ; IOB+8 = buffer lo ($00)
    INY
    LDA     #$5C
    STA     (RWTS_IOB_PTR),Y   ; IOB+9 = buffer hi ($5C -> $5C00)
    LDA     GAME_SIG_TRACK     ; base track
    STA     $BE
    LDA     GAME_SIG_SECTOR    ; base sector
    CLC
    ADC     SCENE_NUMBER       ; + current scene
.mod13:
    CMP     #$0D               ; >= 13 sectors per track?
    BCC     .set_iob           ; no -> done
    INC     $BE                ; next track
    SEC
    SBC     #$0D               ; subtract 13
    JMP     .mod13

.set_iob:
    LDY     #$05
    STA     (RWTS_IOB_PTR),Y   ; IOB+5 = sector
    DEY
    LDA     $BE
    STA     (RWTS_IOB_PTR),Y   ; IOB+4 = track
    LDA     #$02               ; retry counter
    STA     $BE
.retry:
    JSR     DISK_READ_JUMP     ; read from disk
    BCS     .error
    JSR     DISK_RTS           ; no-op
    CLC                        ; success
    RTS
.error:
    DEC     $BE
    BNE     .retry
    JSR     DISK_RTS           ; no-op
    SEC                        ; all retries failed
    RTS
@ %def LOAD_SCENE_FROM_DISK

@ \subsection{Tune player dispatch (\$A4BE--\$A4E1)}

[[$A4BE]] sets up the RWTS IOB with the given track (X) and sector (A),
buffer at \$A400, then reads from disk with retries.  On persistent
failure it jumps to the [[COLD_RESTART]] error handler.

<<tune player dispatch>>=
    ORG     $A4BE
SETUP_AND_READ_DISK:
    SUBROUTINE SETUP_AND_READ_DISK
    LDY     #$05
    STA     (RWTS_IOB_PTR),Y   ; IOB+5 = sector (A)
    DEY
    TXA
    STA     (RWTS_IOB_PTR),Y   ; IOB+4 = track (X)
    LDA     #$00
    LDY     #$08
    STA     (RWTS_IOB_PTR),Y   ; IOB+8 = buffer lo ($00)
    INY
    LDA     #$A4
    STA     (RWTS_IOB_PTR),Y   ; IOB+9 = buffer hi ($A4 -> $A400)
    LDA     #$02               ; retry counter
    STA     $BE
.retry:
    JSR     DISK_READ_JUMP
    BCS     .error
    RTS                        ; success
.error:
    DEC     $BE
    BNE     .retry
    JMP     COLD_RESTART       ; fatal: disk read failure
@ %def SETUP_AND_READ_DISK

@ \subsection{Integrity verification (\$A4E2--\$A56E)}

[[INTEGRITY_DATA]] holds two pairs of expected checksum values
(4~bytes total) at \$A4E2--\$A4E5, stored as self-modifying
operands.

[[VERIFY_INTEGRITY]] computes a checksum over \$B300--\$B443 (the
disk I/O routines) using [[COMPUTE_CHECKSUM]], and compares the
result with the first expected pair at [[INTEGRITY_DATA]].  If they
mismatch, it jumps to [[GAME_INIT]] (\$6DED) to reinitialize.

[[VERIFY_DISK_IO]] computes a checksum over \$6DD8--\$6DFA (the
scene loader) and compares with the second expected pair.

[[COMPUTE_CHECKSUM]] accumulates a running XOR/ADD checksum over the
byte range \$BA/\$BB through \$BE/\$BF.  It returns the 16-bit
result in A (low) and Y (high).

<<integrity verification>>=
    ORG     $A4E2
INTEGRITY_DATA:
    HEX     AE 7A 4F 87        ; expected checksums (2 pairs)

VERIFY_INTEGRITY:
    SUBROUTINE VERIFY_INTEGRITY
    LDA     #$00               ; \ range: $B300-$B443
    STA     $BA                ;  |
    LDA     #$B3               ;  |
    STA     $BB                ;  |
    LDA     #$43               ;  |
    STA     $BE                ;  |
    LDA     #$B4               ;  |
    STA     $BF                ; /
    JSR     COMPUTE_CHECKSUM
    CMP     INTEGRITY_DATA     ; compare low byte
    BNE     .fail
    TYA
    CMP     INTEGRITY_DATA+1   ; compare high byte
    BNE     .fail
    RTS                        ; checksums match
.fail:
    JMP     $6DED              ; GAME_INIT: reinitialize

VERIFY_DISK_IO:
    LDA     #$D8               ; \ range: $6DD8-$6DFA
    STA     $BA                ;  |
    LDA     #$6D               ;  |
    STA     $BB                ;  |
    LDA     #$FA               ;  |
    STA     $BE                ;  |
    LDA     #$6D               ;  |
    STA     $BF                ; /
    JSR     COMPUTE_CHECKSUM
    CMP     INTEGRITY_DATA+2   ; compare low byte
    BNE     .fail
    TYA
    CMP     INTEGRITY_DATA+3   ; compare high byte
    BNE     .fail
    RTS
    ; unreachable padding (overwritten at runtime as checksum accumulators)
    HEX     B1 A0

COMPUTE_CHECKSUM:
    SUBROUTINE COMPUTE_CHECKSUM
    CLC
    LDY     #$00
    STY     $A527              ; checksum low = 0 (self-modifying)
    STY     $A528              ; checksum high = 0
.loop:
    LDA     ($BA),Y
    ADC     $A527
    STA     $A527
    JSR     .advance           ; advance pointer
    BCS     .done              ; reached end -> return
    LDA     ($BA),Y
    ADC     $A528
    STA     $A528
    EOR     $A527
    STA     $A527
    JSR     .advance
    BCC     .loop              ; not done -> continue

.done:
    LDA     $A527              ; return checksum low in A
    LDY     $A528              ; return checksum high in Y
    RTS

.advance:
    INC     $BA
    BNE     .no_carry
    INC     $BB
.no_carry:
    LDA     $BA
    CMP     $BE
    BNE     .not_end
    LDA     $BB
    CMP     $BF
    BNE     .not_end
    SEC                        ; reached end of range
    RTS
.not_end:
    CLC
    RTS
@ %def INTEGRITY_DATA VERIFY_INTEGRITY VERIFY_DISK_IO COMPUTE_CHECKSUM

@ \subsection{Cold restart error handler (\$A56F--\$A58F)}

[[COLD_RESTART]] is the fatal error handler.  It clears memory from
\$0800 to \$A46F (the entire program area), then jumps to \$C600
(the Disk~II boot ROM) to restart the system from disk.

<<cold restart>>=
    ORG     $A56F
COLD_RESTART:
    SUBROUTINE COLD_RESTART
    LDA     #$00
    STA     $BE
    LDA     #$08
    STA     $BF
    LDY     #$00
.clear:
    STA     ($BE),Y
    DEY
    BNE     .clear
    INC     $BF
    LDA     $BF
    CMP     #$A5               ; stop at page $A5
    BNE     .clear
    LDY     #$6F
.clear_tail:
    STA     ($BE),Y            ; clear $A500-$A56F
    DEY
    BNE     .clear_tail
    JMP     $C600              ; reboot from Disk II
@ %def COLD_RESTART

@ \subsection{Pointer advance helpers (\$A590--\$A5BB)}

These are small utility routines for advancing pointers and comparing
against end-of-range boundaries.  They duplicate logic from
[[COMPUTE_CHECKSUM]] but use different ZP addresses.

<<pointer helpers>>=
    ORG     $A590
LOAD_END_OFFSET:
    LDY     $A563              ; load end boundary (self-modifying operand)
    RTS

ADVANCE_BA:
    INC     $BA
    BNE     .no_carry
    INC     $BB
.no_carry:
    LDA     $BA
    CMP     $BE
    BNE     .not_end
    LDA     $BB
    CMP     $BF
    BNE     .not_end
    SEC
    RTS
.not_end:
    CLC
    RTS

ADVANCE_1A:
    INC     $1B
    LDA     $1A
    CMP     $1E
    BNE     .not_end2
    LDA     $1B
    CMP     $1F
    BNE     .not_end2
    SEC
    RTS
.not_end2:
    CLC
    RTS
@ %def ADVANCE_BA ADVANCE_1A

@ [[TUNE_LOOP_CTR]] counts iterations of the script's built-in loop
construct.  [[TUNE_PRNG_MASK]] controls action randomization: the
interpreter ANDs the PRNG output with this mask before dispatching.
Both are initialized to 0 and 1 respectively at the start of each
script invocation.

<<defines>>=
TUNE_LOOP_CTR     EQU     $5A8D   ; tune loop iteration counter
TUNE_PRNG_MASK    EQU     $5A92   ; PRNG mask for action randomization
@ %def TUNE_LOOP_CTR TUNE_PRNG_MASK

After setup, the interpreter initializes its loop counter and PRNG mask:

<<tune player>>=

    STOB    #$00,TUNE_LOOP_CTR ; loop counter = 0
    STOB    #$01,TUNE_PRNG_MASK ; PRNG mask = 1
TUNE_PLAYER_FETCH:
.fetch:
    LDY     #$00
    LDA     (TUNE_PC),Y    ; read script byte
    BALT    #$27,.control ; < $27 -> control command
    JMP     .action          ; >= $27 -> action dispatch
@
\subsubsection{Opcode reference}

Each script byte is interpreted as follows:

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{cll}
\hline
\textbf{Byte} & \textbf{Mnemonic} & \textbf{Effect} \\
\hline
\$00--\$1E & LOOP $n$ & If loop counter $<$ $n$, increment counter and jump to MARK2 address; else reset counter and advance \\
\$1F & MARK2 & Save next address as loop target \\
\$20 & MARK1 & Save next address as gosub target \\
\$21 & GOTO1 & Set PC to MARK1 address (gosub/restart) \\
\$22 & LOW & Set action vector to [[PLAY_LOW_TONE]] \\
\$23 & HIGH & Set action vector to [[PLAY_HIGH_TONE]] \\
\$24 & END & Return from tune \\
\$25 & HIRAND & Set PRNG mask to \$0F (high randomness) \\
\$26 & NORAND & Set PRNG mask to \$00 (exact notes) \\
\$27--\$FF & NOTE $f$,$d$ & Play note: frequency byte $f$ (XORed with masked PRNG), followed by duration byte $d$ \\
\hline
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

NOTE dispatches through [[TUNE_ACTION_VEC]], which is set by the LOW/HIGH
commands to point at [[PLAY_HIGH_TONE]].  The PRNG mask (set by NORAND/HIRAND)
controls how much the frequency byte is randomized before playback.

\subsubsection{Control commands (< \$27)}

@ [[TUNE_LOOP_ADDR]] is a 2-byte address saved by the ``set loop
address'' command (\$1F).  When the loop counter has not yet reached the
target byte value, the interpreter copies [[TUNE_LOOP_ADDR]] back into
[[TUNE_PC]] to restart the loop body.

<<defines>>=
TUNE_LOOP_ADDR    EQU     $5A8E   ; tune loop address (2 bytes)
@ %def TUNE_LOOP_ADDR

<<tune player>>=

.control:
    BAEQ    #$25,.cmd_25              ; set PRNG mask = $0F
    BCS     .cmd_26                   ; $26: PRNG mask = $00

    BAEQ    #$23,.cmd_23              ; $23: HIGH (PLAY_HIGH_TONE)
    BCS     .cmd_24                   ; $24: END (return)

    BAEQ    #$21,.cmd_21              ; $21: gosub
    BCS     .cmd_22                   ; $22: LOW (PLAY_LOW_TONE)

    BAEQ    #$1F,.cmd_1F              ; set loop address
    BCS     .cmd_20                   ; set gosub address

    ; --- Loop/end-loop (byte < $1F) ---
    BAEQ    TUNE_LOOP_CTR,.end_loop ; compare with loop counter
    BCC     .end_loop

    INC     TUNE_LOOP_CTR           ; counter++
    MOVW    TUNE_LOOP_ADDR,TUNE_PC ;  TUNE_PC/TUNE_PC+1 = loop address
    JMP     .fetch

.end_loop:
    STOB    #$00,TUNE_LOOP_CTR ; reset loop counter
    JMP     TUNE_ADVANCE
@
When the byte value equals or exceeds the loop counter, the loop
terminates and the counter resets.  Otherwise, the counter increments
and execution jumps back to the saved loop address.

\subsubsection{Command implementations}

@ [[TUNE_GOSUB_ADDR]] saves the return address for the script's gosub
command (\$21): after the subroutine finishes, [[TUNE_PC]] is restored
from this 2-byte value.  [[TUNE_ACTION_VEC]] is a 2-byte vector set by
commands \$22 and \$23 to select between the low and high tone handlers.

<<defines>>=
TUNE_GOSUB_ADDR   EQU     $5A90   ; tune gosub return address (2 bytes)
TUNE_ACTION_VEC   EQU     $5A93   ; action handler vector (2 bytes)
@ %def TUNE_GOSUB_ADDR TUNE_ACTION_VEC

<<tune player>>=

.cmd_25:                            ; PRNG mask = $0F
    STOB    #$0F,TUNE_PRNG_MASK
    JMP     TUNE_ADVANCE

.cmd_26:                            ; PRNG mask = $00
    STOB    #$00,TUNE_PRNG_MASK
    JMP     TUNE_ADVANCE

.cmd_23:                            ; HIGH ($23): action vector -> PLAY_HIGH_TONE
    STOW    PLAY_HIGH_TONE,TUNE_ACTION_VEC
    JMP     TUNE_ADVANCE

.cmd_22:                            ; LOW ($22): action vector -> PLAY_LOW_TONE
    STOW    PLAY_LOW_TONE,TUNE_ACTION_VEC
    JMP     TUNE_ADVANCE

.cmd_24:                            ; END ($24): return from tune
    RTS

.cmd_21:                            ; GOTO1 ($21): jump to saved address
    MOVW    TUNE_GOSUB_ADDR,TUNE_PC
    JMP     .fetch

.cmd_1F:                            ; set loop address = current+1
    JSR     TUNE_INC_PC
    MOVW    TUNE_PC,TUNE_LOOP_ADDR
    JMP     .fetch

.cmd_20:                            ; set gosub address = current+1
    JSR     TUNE_INC_PC
    MOVW    TUNE_PC,TUNE_GOSUB_ADDR
    JMP     .fetch
@
\subsubsection{Action dispatch ($\geq$ \$27)}

When the script byte is [[$27]] or higher, the PRNG output is masked and
XORed with the action byte, introducing randomness.  The action vector
at [[\DISPATCH_VEC]] is set by the handlers at [[TUNE_ACTION_VEC]].

<<tune player>>=

.action:
    STA     SOUND_DURATION         ; save action byte
    JSR     STEP_PRNG
    LDA     PRNG_OUTPUT            ; PRNG output
    AND     TUNE_PRNG_MASK       ; apply mask
    EOR     SOUND_DURATION         ; XOR with action byte
    STA     SOUND_FREQ             ; modified action
    JSR     TUNE_INC_PC          ; advance tune pointer
    LDY     #$00
    LDA     (TUNE_PC),Y          ; read parameter byte
    STA     SOUND_DURATION
    JSR     TUNE_ACTION_INDIRECT ; -> JMP (TUNE_ACTION_VEC)
    JMP     (DISPATCH_VEC)         ; dispatch via action vector
@ %def TUNE_PLAYER
The ``advance'' routine is the target of all [[JMP TUNE_ADVANCE]] in
the control commands.  It increments the tune pointer, checks for user
input (during attract mode), and loops back to [[.fetch]].

During the attract screen ([[ATTRACT_FLAG]] = 1), [[TUNE_ADVANCE]] checks
for keyboard or joystick input.  If detected, it returns immediately via RTS,
which exits the entire [[TUNE_PLAYER]] call.

<<tune advance>>=
    ORG     $7A4F
TUNE_ADVANCE:
    SUBROUTINE TUNE_ADVANCE

    JSR     TUNE_INC_PC       ; advance tune pointer
    LDA     ATTRACT_FLAG        ; attract_flag
    BEQ     .continue           ; not attract mode -> skip input check

    ; Attract mode: check keyboard
    LDA     $C000               ; keyboard register
    BPL     .check_joy          ; no key -> check joystick
    RTS                         ; key pressed -> exit

.check_joy:
    LDA     INPUT_MODE          ; joystick flag
    BEQ     .continue           ; no joystick -> continue script
    LDX     #$00
    LDA     $C061,X             ; button 0
    BPL     .btn1               ; not pressed
    RTS                         ; pressed -> exit
.btn1:
    INX
    LDA     $C061,X             ; button 1
    BPL     .continue           ; not pressed -> continue
    RTS                         ; pressed -> exit

.continue:
    LSR     WAIT_LOOP_COUNT     ; shift timing flag
    JMP     TUNE_PLAYER_FETCH ; loop back to interpreter
@ %def TUNE_ADVANCE
<<tune action indirect>>=
    ORG     $7A4C
TUNE_ACTION_INDIRECT:
    JMP     (TUNE_ACTION_VEC)
@ %def TUNE_ACTION_INDIRECT
@ [[TUNE_INC_PC]] increments the 16-bit script program counter at
[[TUNE_PC]]/[[TUNE_PC+1]], handling the carry from low to high byte.

<<tune helpers>>=
    ORG     $7A77
TUNE_INC_PC:
    SUBROUTINE TUNE_INC_PC

    INC     TUNE_PC
    BEQ     .carry
    RTS
.carry:
    INC     TUNE_PC+1
    RTS
@ %def TUNE_INC_PC

\chapter{The Attract Screen}

The soft-switch reads at [[$C050]]--[[$C057]] configure the Apple II display:
[[GR]], full-screen (no split text), page 1, hi-res. This puts the display
into HGR mode showing the framebuffer at [[$2000]]--[[$3FFF]].

\subsection{Sound and settings routines (\$0984--\$09F3)}

[[TOGGLE_SOUND]] (\$0984) is the handler for the ``SOUND IS ON'' menu
option.  It checks whether [[PLAY_HIGH_TONE]] starts with \$60 (RTS,
meaning sound is off) or \$A0 (LDY, meaning sound is on).  To disable
sound, it writes RTS (\$60) to both [[PLAY_HIGH_TONE]] and
[[PLAY_LOW_TONE]], making them return immediately.  To enable sound,
it restores the original LDY~\#\$0A opcode (\$A0).  It also patches
the ``SOUND IS ON'' label string: ``ON~'' (\$CE/\$A0) becomes ``OFF''
(\$C6/\$C6).

[[SETTINGS_DISPLAY_INIT]] (\$09AC) initializes the game settings
display by writing spaces into the ``DANGER'' label, formatting
[[EVENT_THRESHOLD]] via [[NUM_TO_DECIMAL]], and jumping to the
settings menu.

[[DEC_EVENT_THRESHOLD]] and [[INC_EVENT_THRESHOLD]] adjust the
random event probability (clamped to 0--99).

[[RETIRE_CHARACTER]] (\$09E7) clears [[ACTIVE_CHAR]], calls
[[REORDER_CURRENT_CHAR]], and re-enters [[SCENE_LOOP]] with scene~\$23.

<<sound and settings>>=
    ORG     $0984
TOGGLE_SOUND:
    SUBROUTINE TOGGLE_SOUND
    ; Check current state: PLAY_HIGH_TONE byte = $60 (RTS) means off
    LDA     #$60              ; RTS opcode
    CMP     PLAY_HIGH_TONE    ; is sound disabled?
    BNE     .turn_off
    ; --- Enable sound ---
    LDA     #$CE              ; 'N' (high-bit ASCII)
    STA     $7B0F             ; patch "OFF" -> "ON "
    LDA     #$A0              ; ' ' (space) / LDY opcode
    STA     $7B10             ; trailing space
    LDA     #$A0              ; LDY #$xx opcode (restores original)
.patch_tones:
    STA     PLAY_HIGH_TONE    ; patch PLAY_HIGH_TONE entry byte
    STA     PLAY_LOW_TONE     ; patch PLAY_LOW_TONE entry byte
    JMP     MENU_GAME_SETTINGS ; re-enter settings menu
.turn_off:
    ; --- Disable sound ---
    LDA     #$C6              ; 'F' (high-bit ASCII)
    STA     $7B0F             ; patch "ON " -> "OFF"
    STA     $7B10             ;
    LDA     #$60              ; RTS opcode
    BNE     .patch_tones      ; -> STA PLAY_HIGH_TONE / PLAY_LOW_TONE

    ; --- Initialize settings display ---
SETTINGS_DISPLAY_INIT:
    LDA     #$20              ; \ clear danger digit area
    STA     $7B24             ;  |
    STA     $7B25             ;  |
    STA     $7B26             ; /
    LDA     #$00
    STA     NUM_VALUE+1       ; high byte = 0
    LDA     EVENT_THRESHOLD   ; current threshold value
    STA     NUM_VALUE         ; -> NUM_VALUE
    LDA     #$22              ; \ DECIMAL_OUT_PTR = $7B22
    STA     DECIMAL_OUT_PTR   ;  | (danger display area)
    LDA     #$7B              ;  |
    STA     DECIMAL_OUT_PTR+1 ; /
    JMP     NUM_TO_DECIMAL    ; format and return

    ; --- Decrement event threshold (wrapper for menu) ---
DEC_THRESHOLD_WRAP:
    JSR     DEC_EVENT_THRESHOLD
    RTS

    ; --- Increment event threshold (wrapper for menu) ---
INC_THRESHOLD_WRAP:
    JSR     INC_EVENT_THRESHOLD
    RTS

    ; --- Decrement EVENT_THRESHOLD (clamp to 0) ---
DEC_EVENT_THRESHOLD:
    DEC     EVENT_THRESHOLD
    BPL     .dec_done         ; >= 0 -> ok
    INC     EVENT_THRESHOLD   ; clamp: -1 -> 0
.dec_done:
    RTS

    ; --- Increment EVENT_THRESHOLD (clamp to 99) ---
INC_EVENT_THRESHOLD:
    LDA     EVENT_THRESHOLD
    CMP     #$63              ; 99 decimal
    BCS     .inc_done         ; already at max
    INC     EVENT_THRESHOLD
.inc_done:
    RTS

    ; --- Retire current character ---
RETIRE_CHARACTER:
    LDA     #$00
    STA     ACTIVE_CHAR       ; clear active character
    JSR     REORDER_CURRENT_CHAR
    LDA     #$23              ; scene $23
    JMP     SCENE_LOOP
@ %def TOGGLE_SOUND SETTINGS_DISPLAY_INIT DEC_THRESHOLD_WRAP INC_THRESHOLD_WRAP DEC_EVENT_THRESHOLD INC_EVENT_THRESHOLD RETIRE_CHARACTER

\label{sec:attract_screen}

<<attract screen>>=
    ORG     $09F4
ATTRACT_SCREEN:
    SUBROUTINE ATTRACT_SCREEN

    STOB    #$01,ACTIVE_CHAR ; scene/character index = 1
    STA     SCENE_EVENT_RESULT ; mark event as handled
    JSR     GET_MOB_DATA  ; scene 1 pointer -> MOB_DATA_PTR/MOB_DATA_PTR+1
    MOVW    MOB_DATA_PTR,MOB_PTR ;  MOB_PTR/MOB_PTR+1 = MOB_DATA_PTR/MOB_DATA_PTR+1 (save pointer)
    JSR     SCENE_SETUP
    STOB    #$00,LOCATION_POS ; clear location-change flag
    JSR     SET_CURSOR_ROW21
    LDA     #$26               ; scene number $26 (38 decimal)
    JMP     SCENE_LOOP         ; tail-call
@ %def ATTRACT_SCREEN
The entry point for the resident interpreter.  Each iteration swaps
context (zero-page state) and dispatches one bytecode instruction.

<<attract loop>>=
    ORG     $0569
ATTRACT_LOOP:
    SUBROUTINE ATTRACT_LOOP

    JSR     CONTEXT_SWAP
    JSR     RESIDENT_DISPATCH
    JMP     ATTRACT_LOOP
@ %def ATTRACT_LOOP

\chapter{Resident Routines}

\label{sec:resident_interp}

EALDR copies 768 bytes from [[$A300]]--[[$A5FF]] to [[$0500]]--[[$07FF]]
before entering the main program.  This region contains a second bytecode
interpreter, separate from the EALDR VM, that runs during gameplay and
the attract screen.  It uses the same XOR encryption scheme as the EALDR
VM (low byte XOR [[$03]], high byte XOR [[$D9]]).

\paragraph{Disk origin.}
The source data at [[$A300]]--[[$A5FF]] is part of the EALDR image that
BOOT1 loads from tracks~1--2 into [[$A000]]--[[$BFFF]].  Within
track~1, the three pages map to physical sectors via the custom loader
interleave:

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{cccc}
\toprule
\thead{Page} & \thead{Physical sector} & \thead{DOS sector} & \thead{File offset} \\
\midrule
\$A3 & 6  & 12 & \$1C00 \\
\$A4 & 8  & 11 & \$1B00 \\
\$A5 & 10 & 10 & \$1A00 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

After [[GAME_INIT]], the relocation
[[$2000--$32FF]]~$\to$~[[$9600--$A8FF]] overwrites the original
[[$A300]]--[[$A5FF]] with HRCG/font data.  From that point on, only the
copy at [[$0500]]--[[$07FF]] survives.  The tune pointer table
(\S\ref{sec:tune_player}) references the original [[$A300]]-based
addresses, which is safe because tunes~3--7 run only during attract
mode, before [[GAME_INIT]].

The reset vector points here.  Simply jumps to [[ATTRACT_LOOP]].

<<stub entry>>=
    ORG     $0500
STUB_ENTRY:
    JMP     ATTRACT_LOOP
@ %def STUB_ENTRY

@ [[READ_DATA_FIELD]] reads a disk data field from the drive.  It
searches for the D5~AA~AD prologue, reads 342~(\$156) bytes of
encoded data (checking each against \$AF), then reads 256~(\$100)
bytes, and finally verifies the DE~AA epilogue.  Returns with carry
clear on success, carry set on error.  The entry at [[READ_DATA_FIELD_AD]]
(\$051E) skips the D5~AA search and checks only for the AD~byte.

During reading, [[BIT \$C000]] polls the keyboard---if a key is
pressed, the read is aborted and the nibble is stored at [[$07F6]].

<<read data field>>=
    ORG     $0503
READ_DATA_FIELD:
    SUBROUTINE READ_DATA_FIELD

    ; --- Search for D5 AA AD prologue ---
    LDY     #$20              ; retry counter
.search_d5:
    DEY
    BEQ     .error            ; timeout -> error
    LDA     DISK_DATA_REG     ; \ wait for disk byte
    BPL     *-3               ; /
.recheck:
    EOR     #$D5              ; D5?
    BNE     .search_d5        ; no -> restart search
    LDA     DISK_DATA_REG     ; \ wait for next byte
    BPL     *-3               ; /
    CMP     #$AA              ; AA?
    BNE     .recheck          ; no -> re-check as D5
READ_DATA_FIELD_AD:
    LDA     DISK_DATA_REG     ; \ wait for next byte
    BPL     *-3               ; /
    CMP     #$AD              ; AD?
    BNE     .recheck          ; no -> re-check as D5

    ; --- Read 342 bytes of encoded data ---
    PHA                       ; timing padding
    PLA
    LDY     #$56              ; 342 bytes ($156 wraps via DEY from $56)
.read_342:
    LDA     DISK_DATA_REG     ; \ wait for disk byte
    BPL     *-3               ; /
    BIT     $C000             ; check keyboard
    CMP     #$AF              ; valid nibble? (must be >= $AF)
    BNE     .abort            ; invalid -> abort
    DEY
    BNE     .read_342         ; loop for $56 bytes (86 dec)

    ; --- Read 256 bytes of data ---
    LDY     #$00              ; 256 bytes
.read_256:
    LDA     DISK_DATA_REG     ; \ wait for disk byte
    BPL     *-3               ; /
    BIT     $C000             ; check keyboard
    CMP     #$AF              ; valid nibble?
    BNE     .abort            ; invalid -> abort
    DEY
    BNE     .read_256         ; loop for 256 bytes

    ; --- Verify DE AA epilogue ---
    LDY     DISK_DATA_REG     ; \ wait for epilogue byte 1
    BPL     *-3               ; / (value discarded)
    PHA                       ; timing padding
    PLA
    LDA     DISK_DATA_REG     ; \ wait for epilogue byte 2
    BPL     *-3               ; /
    CMP     #$DE              ; DE?
    BNE     .error            ; no -> error
    LDA     DISK_DATA_REG     ; \ wait for epilogue byte 3
    BPL     *-3               ; /
    CMP     #$AA              ; AA?
    BEQ     .ok               ; yes -> success

.error:
    SEC                       ; carry set = error
    RTS
.ok:
    CLC                       ; carry clear = success
    RTS
.abort:
    STA     $07F6             ; save nibble that caused abort
    SEC                       ; carry set = error
    RTS
@ %def READ_DATA_FIELD READ_DATA_FIELD_AD

This 321-byte region between [[ATTRACT_LOOP]] and [[CONTEXT_SWAP]]
contains EALDR VM bytecodes interleaved with native 6502 routines.
The bytecodes drive the attract-screen display and the
copy-protection verifier that runs before the game starts.

Embedded within the bytecodes are several native routines called via
VM [[CALL0]] opcodes:
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{SEARCH\_ADDR\_FIELD} (\$05FD--\$0649): searches for a
      disk address field (D5~AA~96 prologue) and decodes 4\&4 nibble
      data.  Self-modifying code at \$064C stores the retry count.
\item \textbf{DELAY\_LOOP} (\$0681--\$068B): nested countdown delay
      for motor spin-up timing.
\item \textbf{READ\_AND\_VERIFY} (\$064B--\$0667): calls
      [[SEARCH_ADDR_FIELD]], then reads and checksums a data area
      while toggling drive phases for half-track seeks.
\end{itemize}

Three short native utility routines at the end (\$06A6--\$06B2)
provide VM-to-native exit points and bytecode decryption:
\begin{itemize}
\item \$06A6: swap context and return carry clear (OK).
\item \$06AB: swap context and return carry set (error).
\item \$06B0: decrypt high byte (EOR~\#\$D9).
\end{itemize}

The address at \$0678 doubles as RWTS scratch storage during disk
operations.

<<resident data and bytecodes>>=
    ORG     $0572
RESIDENT_BYTECODES:
    SUBROUTINE RESIDENT_BYTECODES
    ; --- Copy-protection verifier bytecodes ($0572-$05FD) ---
    ; Checks integrity of three disk addresses, then reads sectors
    ; with half-track seeks.  On failure, falls through to error display.
    ;
    ; Phase 1: verify three addresses match expected values
    VMLD    $0560             ; check addr byte 1
    VMSUBI  $38
    VMBEQ   VM_RES_ERROR      ; mismatch -> error
    VMLD    $0561             ; check addr byte 2
    VMSUBI  $60
    VMBEQ   VM_RES_ERROR
    VMLD    $0567             ; check addr byte 3
    VMSUBI  $38
    VMBEQ   VM_RES_ERROR
    ;
    ; Phase 2: two half-track read attempts
    VMCALL  .vm_read_tracks
    VMBEQ   .vm_pass1_ok
    VMGOTO  .vm_done          ; read failed -> exit ok (cracked)
.vm_pass1_ok:
    VMCALL  .vm_read_tracks
    VMBEQ   .vm_pass2_ok
    VMGOTO  .vm_done
.vm_pass2_ok:
    VMSUBI  $02               ; check error count
    VMBEQ   VM_RES_ERROR      ; too many errors -> fail
    VMGOTO  $0572             ; retry from start
.vm_done:
    VMCALL0 $06A6             ; exit via VM_EXIT_OK

    ; --- VM subroutine: read tracks with half-track seeks ---
.vm_read_tracks:
    VMLD    $C0E9             ; motor on
    VMLDI   $FF               ; \ delay for motor spin-up
    VMCALL1 $FCA8             ;  | (ROM WAIT routine)
    VMLDI   $FF               ;  |
    VMCALL1 $FCA8             ; /
    VMLD    $C0EE             ; set drive to read mode
    VMLDI   $00
    VMST    $07E2             ; clear error counter
    VMCALL  .vm_read_one      ; \ read 4 sectors at
    VMCALL  .vm_read_one      ;  | different half-track
    VMCALL  .vm_read_one      ;  | positions
    VMCALL  .vm_read_one      ; /
    VMLD    $C0E8             ; motor off
    VMLD    $07E3             ; return error status
    VMRET

    ; --- VM subroutine: read one sector + seek half track ---
.vm_read_one:
    VMLDI   $03
    VMST    RES_RETRY_COUNT ; 3 retries
    VMCALL1 READ_AND_VERIFY_RES ; read sector
    VMLD    $C0E7             ; \ seek: toggle phases
    VMCALL1 READ_AND_VERIFY_RES ;  | for half-track
    VMCALL1 READ_AND_VERIFY_RES ; /
    VMLD    $C0E1             ; phase 0 on
    VMCALL  .vm_seek_delay
    VMLDI   $03
    VMST    RES_RETRY_COUNT
    VMCALL1 READ_AND_VERIFY_RES
    VMLD    $C0E7             ; \ more phase toggling
    VMCALL1 READ_AND_VERIFY_RES ;  |
    VMCALL1 READ_AND_VERIFY_RES ; /
    VMLD    $C0E5             ; phase 2 on
    VMCALL  .vm_seek_delay
    VMRET

    ; --- Native: search for D5 AA 96 address field ---
SEARCH_ADDR_FIELD_RES:
    LDY     #$FF              ; outer retry counter
.search_d5:
    LDX     RES_RETRY_COUNT ; inner retry counter
.wait_d5:
    LDA     DISK_DATA_REG     ; \ wait for disk byte
    BPL     .wait_d5          ; /
    CMP     #$D5              ; D5 prologue?
    BEQ     .found_d5
    DEY
    BNE     .wait_d5
    DEX
    BNE     .wait_d5
    RTS                       ; timeout (carry undefined)
.found_d5:
    LDA     DISK_DATA_REG     ; \ wait for next byte
    BPL     *-3               ; /
    CMP     #$AA              ; AA?
    BEQ     .found_aa
    DEY
    BNE     .wait_d5          ; retry
    SEC
    RTS                       ; timeout
.found_aa:
    LDA     DISK_DATA_REG     ; \ wait for next byte
    BPL     *-3               ; /
    CMP     #$96              ; 96? (address field marker)
    BEQ     .found_96
    DEY
    BNE     .wait_d5          ; retry
    SEC
    RTS
.found_96:
    ; --- Decode 4&4 nibble data (2 pairs -> $50) ---
    LDY     #$02              ; 2 pairs to decode
.decode_pair:
    LDA     DISK_DATA_REG     ; \ wait for even nibble
    BPL     *-3               ; /
    ROL                       ; shift into position
    STA     $50               ; save
    LDA     DISK_DATA_REG     ; \ wait for odd nibble
    BPL     *-3               ; /
    AND     $50               ; combine
    STA     $50               ; decoded byte
    DEY
    STX     RES_RETRY_COUNT ; save retry count
    BPL     .decode_pair      ; next pair
    CLC                       ; success
    LDX     #$01
    RTS
RES_RETRY_COUNT:
    DC.B    $03               ; retry count (self-modified)

    ; --- Native: read and verify one sector ---
READ_AND_VERIFY_RES:
    JSR     SEARCH_ADDR_FIELD_RES
    BCS     .read_done
    JSR     READ_DATA_FIELD   ; read data field
.read_done:
    LDA     #$00
    ADC     $07E2             ; accumulate errors
    STA     $07E2
    LDA     $C0E0             ; \ reset drive phases
    LDA     $C0E2             ;  |
    LDA     $C0E4             ;  |
    LDA     $C0E6             ; /
    RTS

    ; --- VM bytecodes: seek delay subroutine ---
.vm_seek_delay:
    VMLDI   $70               ; delay count
    VMCALL1 DELAY_RES         ; delay
    VMLD    $C0E0             ; \ toggle phases for
    VMLD    $C0E2             ;  | half-track positioning
    VMLD    $C0E4             ;  |
    VMLD    $C0E6             ; /
    VMLDI   $28               ; shorter delay
    VMCALL1 DELAY_RES
    VMRET

    ; --- Native: delay loop ---
DELAY_RES:
    LDX     #$20              ; outer counter
.delay_inner:
    DEX
    BNE     .delay_inner      ; inner loop
    SEC
    SBC     #$01              ; decrement A
    BNE     DELAY_RES         ; outer loop
    RTS

    ; --- VM bytecodes: error display loop ---
VM_RES_ERROR:
    VMST    $0400             ; write char to screen
    VMLDX   $068E             ; load from table (self-ref)
    VMBEQ   VM_RES_ERROR      ; zero -> loop
    VMLD    $068F             ; load addr
    VMCALL1 $06B0             ; decrypt high byte
    VMSUBI  $FF               ; adjust
    VMCALL1 $06B0             ; decrypt again
    VMST    $068F             ; store back
    VMGOTO  VM_RES_ERROR      ; infinite error loop
;
; $06A6-$06B2: Native utility routines
VM_EXIT_OK:
    JSR     CONTEXT_SWAP                 ; swap back to main ZP
    CLC                                  ; carry clear = success
    RTS
VM_EXIT_ERR:
    JSR     CONTEXT_SWAP                 ; swap back to main ZP
    SEC                                  ; carry set = error
    RTS
DECRYPT_HIGH_BYTE:
    EOR     #$D9                         ; decrypt high byte of address
    RTS
@ %def RESIDENT_BYTECODES VM_EXIT_OK VM_EXIT_ERR DECRYPT_HIGH_BYTE
Swaps 16 bytes between zero page [[$50]]--[[$5F]] and [[$07E5]]--[[$07F4]].
This gives the resident interpreter its own private set of zero-page
temporaries that don't interfere with the main program.

<<context swap>>=
    ORG     $06E0
CONTEXT_SWAP:
    SUBROUTINE CONTEXT_SWAP

    LDX     #$0F
.loop:
    LDA     $50,X  ; load ZP byte
    PHA            ; save on stack
    LDA     $7E5,X ; load shadow byte
    STA     $50,X  ; -> ZP
    PLA            ; recover old ZP byte
    STA     $7E5,X ; -> shadow
    DEX
    BPL     .loop
    RTS
@ %def CONTEXT_SWAP
The 14 bytes between [[CONTEXT_SWAP]] and [[RESIDENT_DECODE_DISPATCH]]
([[$06F2--$06FF]]) are unreferenced and decode as the high-bit ASCII
fragment ``\texttt{DON'T BREAK TH}''\,---likely a truncated development
message.

<<context swap padding>>=
    ORG     $06F2
RESIDUAL_DONT_BREAK:
; Residual string: "DON'T BREAK TH" (high-bit ASCII, truncated)
    HEX     c4cfcea7d4a0c2d2c5c1cba0d4c8
@ %def RESIDUAL_DONT_BREAK
The 18-byte table maps opcode indices to handler addresses in page [[$07]]:

<<resident dispatch table>>=
    ORG     $06D3
RESIDENT_DISPATCH_TABLE:
    HEX     00 27 55 5F 6D 8A AD B9
    HEX     4F A2 CE 26 79
; last 5 bytes overlap with CONTEXT_SWAP code at $06E0
@ %def RESIDENT_DISPATCH_TABLE
Dispatches one bytecode instruction using a stack trick.  X and Y hold
the bytecode pointer from the previous iteration.  They are pushed onto
the stack at entry, then [[PULL_TWO_RET_ADDRS]] rearranges the stack
so the saved X/Y values end up in [[$52/$53]] as the new bytecode pointer.

<<resident dispatch>>=
    ORG     $06B3
RESIDENT_DISPATCH:
    SUBROUTINE RESIDENT_DISPATCH

    TXA                              ; \
    PHA                              ;  | save X, Y on stack
    TYA                              ;  | (these ARE the bytecode pointer)
    PHA                              ; /
    JSR     PULL_TWO_RET_ADDRS       ; rearrange stack, jump to .resume

    ; Control returns here via JMP ($54):
.resume:
    PULB    $52 ; recover saved Y
    PULB    $53 ;  recover saved X

    LDY     #$04                     ; skip 4 bytes
RESIDENT_DISPATCH_FETCH:
.fetch:
    LDA     ($52),Y                  ; read opcode
    INY
    BNE     .no_carry
    INC     $53
.no_carry:
    TAX                              ; opcode -> X (also saves position)
    LDA     RESIDENT_DISPATCH_TABLE,X
    STA     $07E0              ; patch JMP low byte at $07DF in handler page
    JMP     $07DF              ; jump to handler page dispatch
@ %def RESIDENT_DISPATCH
Opcode \$00 handler---the resident interpreter's GOTO instruction.
Decodes an address and redirects execution there.

<<resident decode dispatch>>=
    ORG     $0700
RESIDENT_DECODE_DISPATCH:
    SUBROUTINE RESIDENT_DECODE_DISPATCH

    JSR     DECODE_ENCRYPTED_ADDR   ; -> $54/$55
    MOVW    $54,$52 ;  $52/$53 = decoded address
    LDY     #$00
    JMP     RESIDENT_DISPATCH_FETCH ; fetch from new location
@ %def RESIDENT_DECODE_DISPATCH
@

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{ccl}
\toprule
\thead{Opcode} & \thead{Table byte} & \thead{Handler address} \\
\midrule
\$00 & \$00 & \$0700 (RESIDENT\_DECODE\_DISPATCH) \\
\$01 & \$27 & \$0727 \\
\$02 & \$55 & \$0755 \\
\$03 & \$5F & \$075F \\
\$04 & \$6D & \$076D \\
\$05 & \$8A & \$078A \\
\$06 & \$AD & \$07AD \\
\$07 & \$B9 & \$07B9 \\
\$08 & \$4F & \$074F \\
\$09 & \$A2 & \$07A2 \\
\$0A & \$CE & \$07CE \\
\$0B & \$26 & \$0726 \\
\$0C & \$79 & \$0779 \\
\$0D & \$A2 & \$07A2 \\
\$0E & \$0F & \$070F \\
\$0F & \$B5 & \$07B5 \\
\$10 & \$50 & \$0750 \\
\$11 & \$48 & \$0748 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

Opcodes \$09 and \$0D share the same handler (\$07A2).

Decodes a 2-byte encrypted address from the bytecode stream.
Uses the same XOR scheme as the EALDR VM.  The decoded address is
left in [[$54/$55]].

<<decode encrypted addr>>=
    ORG     $0710
DECODE_ENCRYPTED_ADDR:
    SUBROUTINE DECODE_ENCRYPTED_ADDR

    LDA     ($52),Y ; read low byte
    EOR     #$03    ; decrypt
    INY
    BNE     .no_carry1
    INC     $53
.no_carry1:
    STA     $54     ; decoded low
    LDA     ($52),Y ; read high byte
    INY
    BNE     .no_carry2
    INC     $53
.no_carry2:
    EOR     #$D9    ; decrypt
    STA     $55     ; decoded high
    RTS
@ %def DECODE_ENCRYPTED_ADDR

@ The resident EALDR VM opcode handlers.  Each reads its arguments via
[[DECODE_ENCRYPTED_ADDR]] and returns to the dispatch loop at~\$06C2.
VM state: [[$52/$53]]=IP, [[$54/$55]]=decoded address, [[$56]]=accumulator.

Note: the VMBEQ handler at \$075A contains a [[BNE +0]] (no-op branch)---
this is one of the Passport crack patches that disables copy-protection
branching.

@ Opcode \$0B (VMASL) reuses the RTS at \$0726, which is the last byte
of [[DECODE_ENCRYPTED_ADDR]].  The VMASL handler is simply RTS (a
no-op that returns without modifying the accumulator).

<<resident vm handlers>>=
    ORG     $0727
    ; --- $01: VMCALL1 (call native, result -> acc) ---
RES_VM_CALL1:
    SUBROUTINE RES_VM_CALL1
    JSR     DECODE_ENCRYPTED_ADDR
    TYA                       ; \ save bytecode position
    PHA                       ; /
    LDA     $56               ; A = VM accumulator
    JSR     RES_VM_CALL1_IND  ; call via ($54)
    STA     $56               ; result -> VM acc
    PLA                       ; \ restore Y
    TAY                       ; /
    JMP     $06C2             ; dispatch next

    ; --- PULL_TWO_RET_ADDRS ($0738) ---
    ; Rearranges stack for RESIDENT_DISPATCH: pulls own and caller's
    ; return addresses, increments each (RTS pushes addr-1), and
    ; jumps through ($54).
PULL_TWO_RET_ADDRS:
    PULB    $54               ; own return addr (low)
    PULB    $55               ; own return addr (high)
    PULB    $52               ; caller's return addr (low)
    PULB    $53               ; caller's return addr (high)
    INC     $52
    INC     $54
    BNE     .no_inc
    INC     $55
.no_inc:
    JMP     ($0054)           ; jump through decoded addr

    ; --- $08: VMCALL0 (terminal jump to native code) ---
RES_VM_CALL0:
    JSR     DECODE_ENCRYPTED_ADDR
RES_VM_CALL1_IND:
    JMP     ($0054)           ; indirect jump through $54/$55

    ; --- $02: VMBEQ (branch if acc == 0) ---
RES_VM_VMBEQ:
    JSR     DECODE_ENCRYPTED_ADDR
    LDA     $56               ; test VM accumulator
    BNE     *+2               ; PATCHED: BNE +0 = no-op (was branch to GOTO)
    JMP     $06C2             ; always: dispatch next (branch disabled)

    ; --- $03: VMLDI (load immediate -> acc) ---
RES_VM_VMLDI:
    LDA     ($52),Y           ; read immediate byte
    INY
    BNE     .no_carry1
    INC     $53
.no_carry1:
    EOR     #$4C              ; decrypt
    STA     $56               ; -> VM acc
    JMP     $06C2

    ; --- $04: VMLD (load from memory -> acc) ---
RES_VM_VMLD:
    JSR     DECODE_ENCRYPTED_ADDR
    LDX     #$00
    LDA     ($54,X)           ; acc = *(addr)
    STA     $56
    JMP     $06C2

    ; --- $0C: VMADD (acc += *(addr)) ---
RES_VM_VMADD:
    JSR     DECODE_ENCRYPTED_ADDR
    LDA     $56               ; acc
    CLC
    ADC     $54               ; + decoded low byte
    STA     $54
    BCC     .no_carry2
    INC     $55
.no_carry2:
    JMP     RES_VM_VMLD+3     ; -> LDX #$00 / LDA ($54,X) / ...

    ; --- $05: VMCALL (VM subroutine call) ---
RES_VM_VMCALL:
    JSR     DECODE_ENCRYPTED_ADDR
    TYA                       ; \ compute return address:
    CLC                       ;  | IP + Y offset
    ADC     $52               ;  |
    STA     $52               ;  |
    BCC     .no_carry3        ;  |
    INC     $53               ; /
.no_carry3:
    LDA     $52               ; \ push return IP
    PHA                       ;  |
    LDA     $53               ;  |
    PHA                       ; /
    LDY     #$00              ; reset Y
    JMP     $0703             ; set IP = $54/$55, dispatch

    ; --- $09: VMRET (return from VM subroutine) ---
RES_VM_VMRET:
    PLA                       ; \ pop return IP
    STA     $53               ;  | (high byte first)
    PLA                       ;  |
    STA     $52               ; /
    LDY     #$00
    JMP     $06C2             ; dispatch next

    ; --- $06: VMST (store acc to memory) ---
RES_VM_VMST:
    JSR     DECODE_ENCRYPTED_ADDR
    LDA     $56               ; VM acc
    LDX     #$00
    STA     ($54,X)           ; *(addr) = acc
    JMP     $06C2

    ; --- $07: VMSUBI (acc -= immediate) ---
RES_VM_VMSUBI:
    LDA     ($52),Y           ; read immediate byte
    INY
    BNE     .no_carry4
    INC     $53
.no_carry4:
    EOR     #$4C              ; decrypt
    STA     $54               ; temp
    LDA     $56               ; acc
    SEC
    SBC     $54               ; acc - immediate
    STA     $56
    JMP     $06C2

    ; --- $0A: VMINC (*(addr)++, result -> acc) ---
RES_VM_VMINC:
    JSR     DECODE_ENCRYPTED_ADDR
    LDX     #$00
    LDA     ($54,X)           ; load byte
    CLC
    ADC     #$01              ; increment
    STA     ($54,X)           ; store back
    STA     $56               ; -> VM acc
    JMP     $06C2
@ %def RES_VM_VMASL RES_VM_CALL1 RES_VM_CALL0 RES_VM_CALL1_IND RES_VM_VMBEQ RES_VM_VMLDI RES_VM_VMLD RES_VM_VMADD RES_VM_VMCALL RES_VM_VMRET RES_VM_VMST RES_VM_VMSUBI RES_VM_VMINC

[[PULL_TWO_RET_ADDRS]] pulls both return addresses from the stack
(its own and the caller's), increments each by 1 (since RTS pushes
addr\textminus{}1), and jumps through [[$54/$55]] back to the code
after the [[JSR]] in [[RESIDENT_DISPATCH]].

@ [[PULL_TWO_RET_ADDRS]] is now part of [[<<resident vm handlers>>]]
at~\$0738, since it shares the same address range as the VM opcode
handlers.
A 3-byte relay in the handler page.  Jumps to
[[RESIDENT_DECODE_DISPATCH]] at [[$0700]].

<<decode dispatch relay>>=
    ORG     $07DF
DECODE_DISPATCH_RELAY:
    JMP     RESIDENT_DECODE_DISPATCH
@ %def DECODE_DISPATCH_RELAY
The remaining 30 bytes of the handler page ([[$07E2--$07FF]]) are
unreferenced residual data left over from the EALDR copy
([[$A300--$A5FF]]~$\to$~[[$0500--$07FF]]).  Decoded as Apple~II
text the tail reads ``\texttt{SSSSSSSSSS}'' (ten high-bit~S) followed by
the low-ASCII fragment ``\texttt{e checker}''.

<<resident page tail>>=
    ORG     $07E2
RESIDUAL_PAGE_TAIL:
; Unused residual data at end of resident handler page
    HEX     0000000e968c41964120
    HEX     d3d3d3d3d3d3d3d3d3d3
    HEX     006520636865636b6572  ; "e checker" (low ASCII)
@ %def RESIDUAL_PAGE_TAIL

\chapter{Disk I/O}

The disk I/O routines occupy [[$B300--$BFFF]] at runtime.  They are not
loaded directly to their final addresses by the EALDR\@.  Instead, the
EALDR loads them into the hi-res page staging area [[$3300--$3FFF]]
(tracks~[[$0F]] and [[$10]]).  During [[GAME_INIT]],
[[RELOCATE_HIRES_STAGING]] copies [[$3300--$3FFF]] to [[$B300--$BFFF]].

These routines handle all disk access for the main game, including
scene loading and save/restore operations.

The area splits into two distinct regions:
\begin{itemize}
\item [[$B300--$B5FF]]: Custom game disk code---a VM-driven sector
  reader with its own data field verifier, context-swap mechanism,
  and embedded bytecode program.
\item [[$B600--$BFFF]]: Standard Apple~II DOS~3.3 RWTS (Read/Write
  Track/Sector), byte-identical to the system master after relocation,
  with only three patched bytes:
  \begin{itemize}
  \item [[$B748--$B749]]: JMP target changed from [[$9B03]] (DOS
    file manager) to [[$9D84]] (game's handler).
  \item [[$B7E1]]: max-drives configuration byte changed from
    [[$02]] to [[$00]].
  \end{itemize}
  The standard RWTS is fully documented in \emph{Beneath Apple DOS}
  (Worth \& Lechner, 1984) and will not be re-disassembled here.
\end{itemize}

The main program calls two entry points in this area:

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{lll}
\toprule
\thead{Address} & \thead{Label} & \thead{Called from} \\
\midrule
[[$B300]] & [[DISK_READ_FIELD]] & [[LOAD_SCENE_DATA]] (\$6DD8) \\
[[$B7B5]] & [[RWTS_ENTRY]] & [[RWTS_DISPATCH]] (\$6C18) \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

The RWTS (Read/Write Track/Sector) at~[[$B600--$BFFF]] is a copy of
the standard Apple~II DOS~3.3 RWTS from the system master, with the
standard~[[$80]] page relocation applied (disk pages [[$36--$3F]]
relocated to~[[$B6--$BF]]).  Byte-for-byte comparison with the DOS~3.3
System Master (680-0051-00) confirms that all code is identical after
relocation, except for the three patched bytes noted above.  The
remaining differences are runtime state in the IOB parameter block
at~[[$B7E8]] and the contents of the nibble buffers
at~[[$BB00--$BC55]].

The RWTS is fully documented in \emph{Beneath Apple DOS} (Worth \&
Lechner, 1984), chapter~4, and is not disassembled here.  The binary
data is included verbatim from [[dos.asm]].

@ [[RWTS_CORE]] at [[$BD00]] is the main dispatcher inside the standard
DOS 3.3 RWTS.  [[RWTS_ENTRY]] calls it after saving the processor status
and disabling interrupts.

<<defines>>=
RWTS_CORE               EQU     $BD00   ; RWTS core dispatcher
@ %def RWTS_CORE
@ The chunk below includes the standard RWTS binary verbatim, accessed through [[RWTS_ENTRY]] and [[RWTS_CORE]].

<<dos33 rwts>>=
    ORG     $B600
DOS33_RWTS:
    INCLUDE "dos.asm"
@ %def DOS33_RWTS
[[DISK_READ_FIELD]] is the entry point called by [[LOAD_SCENE_DATA]]
to read sector data from disk.  It is a trampoline into the disk~VM
interpreter loop at~[[$B36A]], which uses an embedded bytecode program
to control the multi-sector read process.  The carry flag is clear on
entry (set by the caller) to indicate a read operation.

<<disk read field>>=
    ORG     $B300
DISK_READ_FIELD:
    JMP     DISK_VM_LOOP ; enter VM interpreter
    NOP                  ; pad
@ %def DISK_READ_FIELD
Searches for the standard data field prologue ([[D5 AA AD]]) on
the disk, then reads all 342 nibbles (86~secondary + 256~primary) and
verifies each byte equals~[[$AF]].  Finally checks the data epilogue
([[DE AA]]).  Returns carry clear on success, carry set on error.

[[VERIFY_DATA_FIELD]] is called internally by the disk~VM (via [[JSR $B304]]).

@ [[DISK_DATA_REG]] at [[$C0EC]] is the Disk~II controller's data
register for the active slot.  [[VERIFY_DATA_FIELD]] reads nibble bytes
from this register in a tight loop while searching for the D5~AA~AD
prologue and verifying the data field contents.

<<defines>>=
DISK_DATA_REG           EQU     $C0EC   ; disk controller data register (active slot)
@ %def DISK_DATA_REG

<<verify data field>>=
    ORG     $B304
VERIFY_DATA_FIELD:
    SUBROUTINE VERIFY_DATA_FIELD

; --- Search for D5 AA AD data field prologue ---
    LDY     #$20             ; timeout counter = 32
.search_d5:
    DEY
    BEQ     .error           ; timeout
    LDA     DISK_DATA_REG    ; read disk nibble
    BPL     *-3              ; wait for data ready
.check_d5:
    EOR     #$D5             ; check for D5
    BNE     .search_d5       ; not D5, retry
    LDA     DISK_DATA_REG    ; read next nibble
    BPL     *-3
    BANE    #$AA,.check_d5   ; not AA, re-check as D5
    LDA     DISK_DATA_REG    ; read third nibble
    BPL     *-3
    BANE    #$AD,.check_d5   ; not AD, re-check as D5

; --- Found D5 AA AD: read and verify data nibbles ---
    PHA                      ; \ waste cycles (timing)
    PLA                      ; /
    LDY     #$56             ; 86 nibbles (secondary buffer)
.read_secondary:
    LDA     DISK_DATA_REG    ; read nibble
    BPL     *-3
    BIT     $C000            ; timing sync
    BANE    #$AF,.bad_nibble ; mismatch -> error
    DEY
    BNE     .read_secondary

    LDY     #$00             ; 256 nibbles (primary buffer)
.read_primary:
    LDA     DISK_DATA_REG    ; read nibble
    BPL     *-3
    BIT     $C000            ; timing sync
    BANE    #$AF,.bad_nibble ; mismatch -> error
    DEY
    BNE     .read_primary

; --- Verify DE AA data field epilogue ---
    LDY     DISK_DATA_REG    ; read (discard) checksum nibble
    BPL     *-3
    PHA                      ; \ waste cycles
    PLA                      ; /
    LDA     DISK_DATA_REG    ; read epilogue byte 1
    BPL     *-3
    BANE    #$DE,.error      ; bad epilogue
    LDA     DISK_DATA_REG    ; read epilogue byte 2
    BPL     *-3
    BAEQ    #$AA,.ok         ; good epilogue

.error:
    SEC                      ; carry set = error
    RTS

.ok:
    CLC                      ; carry clear = success
    RTS

.bad_nibble:
    STA     $B5F6            ; save mismatched nibble for diagnostics
    SEC                      ; carry set = error
    RTS
@ %def VERIFY_DATA_FIELD
The disk~VM interpreter loop.  Each iteration swaps the VM context
(zero-page [[$50--$5F]] $\leftrightarrow$ saved state at [[$B5E5]])
and then dispatches the next VM opcode.  The VM bytecode program
follows immediately after the [[JMP]] at~[[$B370]] and controls the
multi-sector disk read sequence.  The loop has no explicit exit; the
VM program returns to the caller by manipulating the stack.

<<disk vm loop>>=
    ORG     $B36A
DISK_VM_LOOP:
    JSR     DISK_VM_SWAP     ; swap ZP $50-$5F with saved state
    JSR     DISK_VM_DISPATCH ; execute next VM opcode
    JMP     DISK_VM_LOOP     ; repeat
; VM bytecode program follows at $B373
@ %def DISK_VM_LOOP
The VM bytecode program follows immediately after the VM loop.  All
address operands are encrypted (low byte XOR~[[$9C]], high byte
XOR~[[$AD]]); immediate operands are XOR'd with~[[$7A]].  The program
implements a disk copy-protection verifier: it checks code integrity,
turns on the drive motor, reads data from multiple half-track positions,
and exits with carry indicating success or failure.

Decoded program flow:

\begin{enumerate}
\item Three integrity checks: verifies bytes at [[$B361]], [[$B362]],
  and [[$B368]] (the [[SEC]], [[RTS]], and [[SEC]] opcodes in
  [[VERIFY_DATA_FIELD]]).  Exits with error if any byte was patched.
\item Calls the disk-read subroutine at [[$B3A8]] (embedded below).
  On failure, retries once; on second failure, allows up to~2 errors
  before restarting.
\item The subroutine turns on the motor, waits for spin-up, sets read
  mode, calls the half-track verifier ([[READ_AND_VERIFY]]) from
  multiple head positions, then turns off the motor.
\item On success, exits via [[DISK_VM_EXIT_OK]] (carry clear).
\end{enumerate}

<<disk vm bytecode>>=
    ORG     $B373
DISK_VM_BYTECODE:
; --- Integrity checks ---
; LDA_ABS $B361; SUB_IMM #$38; BNZ $B48D  (verify SEC at .error)
    HEX     04 fd 1e 07 42 02 11 19
; LDA_ABS $B362; SUB_IMM #$60; BNZ $B48D  (verify RTS at .error+1)
    HEX     04 fe 1e 07 1a 02 11 19
; LDA_ABS $B368; SUB_IMM #$38; BNZ $B48D  (verify SEC at .bad_nibble+3)
    HEX     04 f4 1e 07 42 02 11 19
; --- First attempt ---
; CALL $B3A8 (disk read sub); BNZ $B394 (retry on error)
    HEX     05 34 1e
; GOTO $B3A5 (exit OK path, skipping retry)
    HEX     02 08 1e ;BNZ $B394 (if error -> retry)
    HEX     0c 39 1e ;GOTO $B3A5 (success -> exit)
; --- Retry (second attempt, at $B394) ---
; CALL $B3A8; BNZ $B39D (error handler)
    HEX     05 34 1e
    HEX     02 01 1e ;BNZ $B39D (if error -> handler)
; GOTO $B3A5 (exit OK)
    HEX     0c 39 1e
; --- Error handler at $B39D ---
; SUB_IMM #$02; BNZ $B48D (fatal if >2 errors); GOTO $B373 (restart)
    HEX     07 78 02 11 19 0c ef 1e
; --- Success exit at $B3A5 ---
; CALL0 $B492 (DISK_VM_EXIT_OK)
    HEX     09 0e 19
; --- Disk read subroutine at $B3A8 ---
; LDA_ABS $C0E9 (motor on)
    HEX     04 75 6d
; LDA_IMM #$FF; CALL1 $FCA8 (ROM WAIT)  x2  (motor spin-up delay)
    HEX     03 85 01 34 51
    HEX     03 85 01 34 51
; LDA_ABS $C0EE (Q7L = read mode)
    HEX     04 72 6d
; LDA_IMM #$00; STA_ABS $B5E2 (clear error accumulator)
    HEX     03 7a 06 7e 18
; CALL $B3D0 x4 (half-track verification passes)
    HEX     05 4c 1e
    HEX     05 4c 1e
    HEX     05 4c 1e
    HEX     05 4c 1e
; LDA_ABS $C0E8 (motor off)
    HEX     04 74 6d
; LDA_ABS $B5E2 (load error count); RET
    HEX     04 7e 18 08
; --- Half-track verifier subroutine at $B3D0 ---
; LDA_IMM #$03; STA_ABS $B44D (set retry counter)
    HEX     03 79 06 d1 19
; CALL1 $B44E (READ_AND_VERIFY)
    HEX     01 d2 19
; LDA_ABS $C0E7 (phase 3 on -- half-track step)
    HEX     04 7b 6d
; CALL1 $B44E x2
    HEX     01 d2 19 01 d2 19
; LDA_ABS $C0E1 (phase 0 on -- half-track step)
    HEX     04 7d 6d
; CALL $B46B (PARK_STEPPER sub)
    HEX     05 f7 19
; LDA_IMM #$03; STA_ABS $B44D (reset retry counter)
    HEX     03 79 06 d1 19
; CALL1 $B44E (READ_AND_VERIFY)
    HEX     01 d2 19
; LDA_ABS $C0E7 (phase 3 on)
    HEX     04 7b 6d
; CALL1 $B44E x2
    HEX     01 d2 19 01 d2 19
; LDA_ABS $C0E5 (phase 2 on -- half-track step)
    HEX     04 79 6d
; CALL $B46B (PARK_STEPPER); RET
    HEX     05 f7 19 08
; $B3FF: next byte ($A0) is the LDY opcode of SEARCH_ADDR_FIELD
@ %def DISK_VM_BYTECODE
Searches for the D5~AA~96 address field prologue on disk.  The entry
point at [[$B3FF]] sets~Y to~[[$FF]] (256~inner retries), then falls
through to the search loop.  The outer retry count is loaded from and
saved back to the data byte at~[[$B44D]].  On success, returns with
carry clear, X~=~1, and the last decoded address-field nibble
(sector number) in~[[$50]].  On failure, returns with carry set.

The 4-and-4 decoding loop reads three field pairs
(volume, track, sector), each encoded as two disk nibbles whose
even/odd bits must be combined via [[ROL]]/[[AND]].

<<search addr field>>=
    ORG     $B3FF
SEARCH_ADDR_FIELD:
    LDY     #$FF               ; 256 inner retries
; $B400: FF is the immediate operand (part of the LDY instruction)
.search:
    LDX     DISK_RETRY_COUNT ; outer retry count
.next_nibble:
    LDA     DISK_DATA_REG      ; read nibble
    BPL     *-3                ; wait for ready
    BAEQ    #$D5,.got_d5       ; first prologue byte?
    DEY                        ; inner countdown
    BNE     .next_nibble
    DEX                        ; outer countdown
    BNE     .next_nibble
    RTS                        ; timeout (carry unchanged)

.got_d5:
    LDA     DISK_DATA_REG
    BPL     *-3
    BAEQ    #$AA,.got_aa       ; second prologue byte?
    DEY
    BNE     .next_nibble
    SEC
    RTS                        ; timeout

.got_aa:
    LDA     DISK_DATA_REG
    BPL     *-3
    BAEQ    #$96,.got_96       ; third prologue byte (addr mark)?
    DEY
    BNE     .next_nibble
    SEC
    RTS                        ; timeout

.got_96:
; --- Decode 3 address field pairs (4-and-4 encoding) ---
    LDY     #$02               ; 3 pairs: volume, track, sector
.decode_pair:
    LDA     DISK_DATA_REG      ; read odd-bits nibble
    BPL     *-3
    ROL                        ; shift data, odd bits in even positions
    STA     $50                ; save partial
    LDA     DISK_DATA_REG      ; read even-bits nibble
    BPL     *-3
    AND     $50                ; combine: result = decoded byte
    STA     $50                ; last decoded value (sector on final iter)
    DEY
    STX     DISK_RETRY_COUNT ; save remaining retry count
    BPL     .decode_pair       ; Y: 2->1->0->FF (3 iterations)

    CLC                        ; success
    LDX     #$01
    RTS

DISK_RETRY_COUNT:
    DC.B    3                  ; $B44D: outer retry counter (default 3)
@ %def SEARCH_ADDR_FIELD DISK_RETRY_COUNT
Three bytes between the dispatch trampoline and the saved state.
[[$B5E2]] is the error accumulator used by [[READ_AND_VERIFY]]
to count failed sector reads across multiple attempts.

<<disk vm error accum>>=
    ORG     $B5E2
DISK_VM_ERROR_ACCUM:
    DC.B    0   ; error count (updated by READ_AND_VERIFY)
    DC.B    0,0 ; scratch
@ %def DISK_VM_ERROR_ACCUM
Native routine called by the VM via CALL1.  Searches for an address
field ([[JSR $B3FF]]), then verifies the data field
([[JSR VERIFY_DATA_FIELD]]).  Accumulates errors in
[[DISK_VM_ERROR_ACCUM]] at~[[$B5E2]].  Afterward, turns off all
four stepper motor phases (preventing motor heating).

<<read and verify>>=
    ORG     $B44E
READ_AND_VERIFY:
    JSR     SEARCH_ADDR_FIELD   ; find D5 AA 96 address prologue
    BCS     .skip_verify        ; no address field -> skip data verify
    JSR     VERIFY_DATA_FIELD   ; verify D5 AA AD data field
.skip_verify:
    LDA     #$00
    ADC     DISK_VM_ERROR_ACCUM ; carry -> error count
    STA     DISK_VM_ERROR_ACCUM
; --- Turn off all stepper motor phases ---
    LDA     $C0E0               ; phase 0 off
    LDA     $C0E2               ; phase 1 off
    LDA     $C0E4               ; phase 2 off
    LDA     $C0E6               ; phase 3 off
    RTS
@ %def READ_AND_VERIFY
VM bytecode subroutine that delays and turns off all stepper motor
phases.  Called via VM opcode~5 (CALL) from the half-track verifier.
The delays allow the stepper motor to settle between half-track
movements.

<<disk vm sub park stepper>>=
    ORG     $B46B
DISK_VM_SUB_PARK_STEPPER:
; LDA_IMM #$70; CALL1 $B482 (DELAY_LOOP)  -- long delay
    HEX     03 0a 01 1e 19
; LDA_ABS $C0E0 (phase 0 off)
    HEX     04 7c 6d
; LDA_ABS $C0E2 (phase 1 off)
    HEX     04 7e 6d
; LDA_ABS $C0E4 (phase 2 off)
    HEX     04 78 6d
; LDA_ABS $C0E6 (phase 3 off)
    HEX     04 7a 6d
; LDA_IMM #$28; CALL1 $B482 (DELAY_LOOP)  -- short delay
    HEX     03 52 01 1e 19
; RET
    HEX     08
@ %def DISK_VM_SUB_PARK_STEPPER
Native delay routine.  Takes the delay count in~[[A]] (passed from
VM accumulator via CALL1).  Inner loop: [[DEX]] from [[$20]] to~0
(32~iterations).  Outer loop: [[SBC~\#$01]] until A~reaches~0.
Total delay $\approx$ 160~×~A cycles.

<<delay loop>>=
    ORG     $B482
DELAY_LOOP:
    SUBROUTINE DELAY_LOOP
    LDX     #$20
.inner:
    DEX
    BNE     .inner
    SEC
    SBC     #$01
    BNE     DELAY_LOOP
    RTS
@ %def DELAY_LOOP
Short VM bytecode fragment that loads [[$20]] into the accumulator
and jumps to [[DISK_VM_EXIT_ERR]], which swaps context and returns
to the caller with carry set.  Reached by the integrity-check and
error-handler [[BNZ]] branches in the main bytecode program.

<<disk vm sub exit err>>=
    ORG     $B48D
DISK_VM_SUB_EXIT_ERR:
; LDA_IMM #$20; CALL0 $B497 (DISK_VM_EXIT_ERR)
    HEX     03 5a 09 0b 19
@ %def DISK_VM_SUB_EXIT_ERR
These native routines exit the disk~VM\@.  Each calls
[[DISK_VM_SWAP]] to restore the caller's zero-page state, then
returns with carry flag indicating success or failure.

<<disk vm exit ok>>=
    ORG     $B492
DISK_VM_EXIT_OK:
    JSR     DISK_VM_SWAP ; restore caller's ZP
    CLC                  ; carry clear = success
    RTS
@ %def DISK_VM_EXIT_OK
@ [[DISK_VM_EXIT_ERR]] is the error counterpart: it swaps context back and
returns with carry set, signalling failure to the caller.

<<disk vm exit err>>=
    ORG     $B497
DISK_VM_EXIT_ERR:
    JSR     DISK_VM_SWAP ; restore caller's ZP
    SEC                  ; carry set = error
    RTS
@ %def DISK_VM_EXIT_ERR
@ [[DISK_VM_MISC_B49C]] is a two-byte helper that XORs~A with~\$AD and
returns.  It is used by the VM opcode decoder to decrypt the high byte of
address operands (the encryption key for high bytes is~\$AD).

<<disk vm misc b49c>>=
    ORG     $B49C
DISK_VM_MISC_B49C:
    EOR     #$AD
    RTS
@ %def DISK_VM_MISC_B49C
Swaps 16~bytes between zero-page locations [[$50--$5F]] and the
saved VM state at [[$B5E5--$B5F4]].  This preserves the caller's
zero-page state while the VM executes, and restores it afterward.

<<disk vm swap>>=
    ORG     $B4CC
DISK_VM_SWAP:
    SUBROUTINE DISK_VM_SWAP

    LDX     #$0F    ; 16 bytes ($50-$5F)
.loop:
    LDA     $50,X   ; \ swap ZP with saved state
    PHA             ;  |
    LDA     $B5E5,X ;  |
    STA     $50,X   ;  |
    PLA             ;  |
    STA     $B5E5,X ; /
    DEX
    BPL     .loop
    RTS
@ %def DISK_VM_SWAP
Scratch/data area between [[DISK_VM_SWAP]] and the opcode handlers.
Contains mostly zeros with bytes~[[$4A $4C $4E]] at~[[$B4EE--$B4F0]],
mirroring the initial saved-state values for ZP~[[$5B--$5D]].

<<disk vm data b4de>>=
    ORG     $B4DE
DISK_VM_DATA_B4DE:
    HEX     00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00
    HEX     4a 4c 4e
    HEX     00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00
@ %def DISK_VM_DATA_B4DE
Executes one VM opcode.  Pulls the return address from the stack to
locate the current instruction pointer, reads the next opcode byte,
looks up the handler address (low byte) in the table at~[[$B4BF]],
and self-modifies a [[JMP]] at~[[$B5DF]] to dispatch to the
handler in page~[[$B5]].

<<disk vm dispatch>>=
    ORG     $B49F
DISK_VM_DISPATCH:
    SUBROUTINE DISK_VM_DISPATCH

    TXA
    PHA                           ; save X
    TYA
    PHA                           ; save Y
    JSR     DISK_VM_PULL_IP       ; pull IP from stack -> $52/$53
    PULB    $52 ; restore as VM instruction pointer
    PULB    $53 ;  (values set by DISK_VM_PULL_IP
    LDY     #$04
DISK_VM_RESUME:
    LDA     ($52),Y               ; read opcode from VM program
    INY
    BNE     .no_page
    INC     $53
.no_page:
    TAX
    LDA     DISK_VM_HANDLER_TBL,X ; look up handler low byte
    STA     $B5E0                 ; self-modify JMP target at $B5DF
    JMP     DISK_VM_TRAMPOLINE    ; dispatch (JMP $B5xx)

; --- VM opcode handler table ---
; Each byte is the low address of a handler in page $B5.
; Opcode index -> handler address ($B5xx).
DISK_VM_HANDLER_TBL:
    HEX     79 27 55 5f 6d 8a ad b9 a2 4f ce 26 00
@ %def DISK_VM_DISPATCH DISK_VM_RESUME DISK_VM_HANDLER_TBL
@ [[DISK_VM_PULL_IP]] is an RTS-trick bootstrap used during VM startup.  It
pulls two return addresses from the 6502 stack: the inner one (from the JSR
that called it) and the outer one (from the JSR that entered
[[DISK_VM_DISPATCH]]).  The outer address becomes the VM instruction pointer
([[$52/$53]]), and both are incremented by~1 to compensate for the 6502's
convention of pushing address$-$1 during JSR.  Execution then resumes at the
inner return address via an indirect jump, allowing the dispatcher to
``capture'' its caller's position as the starting bytecode address.

<<disk vm pull ip>>=
    ORG     $B538
DISK_VM_PULL_IP:
    SUBROUTINE DISK_VM_PULL_IP

; Pulls two return addresses from the stack.
; The outer return address (from JSR DISK_VM_DISPATCH) becomes the
; VM instruction pointer.  Resumes execution at the inner return
; address + 1 (i.e., returns to the code after JSR DISK_VM_PULL_IP).
    PULB    $54 ; inner return address
    PULB    $55
    PULB    $52 ; outer return address
    PULB    $53 ; = VM instruction pointer
    INC     $52       ; adjust IP (6502 pushes addr-1)
    INC     $54       ; \ adjust inner return address
    BNE     .no_carry ;  |
    INC     $55       ; /
.no_carry:
    JMP     ($54)     ; resume at inner return + 1
@ %def DISK_VM_PULL_IP
Shared subroutine used by most VM opcode handlers.  Reads two
encrypted bytes from the bytecode stream at~[[$52/$53 + Y]], decrypts
the address operand (low byte XOR~[[$9C]], high byte XOR~[[$AD]]),
stores the result in~[[$54/$55]], and advances~Y past both bytes.

<<disk vm read addr>>=
    ORG     $B510
DISK_VM_READ_ADDR:
    LDA     ($52),Y ; read encrypted low byte
    EOR     #$9C    ; decrypt
    INY
    BNE     .no_page1
    INC     $53
.no_page1:
    STA     $54     ; operand low
    LDA     ($52),Y ; read encrypted high byte
    INY
    BNE     .no_page2
    INC     $53
.no_page2:
    EOR     #$AD    ; decrypt
    STA     $55     ; operand high
    RTS
@ %def DISK_VM_READ_ADDR
The disk~VM has 13~opcodes (indices 0--12).  Each handler's low
address is stored in the table at~[[$B4BF]]; dispatch jumps to
[[$B5xx]].  Handlers return to the dispatch loop by jumping to
[[DISK_VM_RESUME]] at~[[$B4AE]], which reads the next opcode and
dispatches again.

\begin{center}
\begin{tabular}{rllp{5cm}}
\toprule
\thead{Op} & \thead{Addr} & \thead{Mnemonic} & \thead{Description} \\
\midrule
 0 & \$B579 & LDA\_IDX  & ACC $\leftarrow$ *(addr + ACC) \\
 1 & \$B527 & CALL1     & Call native; A=ACC in, A$\to$ACC out \\
 2 & \$B555 & BNZ       & Branch if ACC $\ne$ 0 \\
 3 & \$B55F & LDA\_IMM  & ACC $\leftarrow$ immediate (XOR \$7A) \\
 4 & \$B56D & LDA\_ABS  & ACC $\leftarrow$ *(addr) \\
 5 & \$B58A & CALL      & VM subroutine call (push IP) \\
 6 & \$B5AD & STA\_ABS  & *(addr) $\leftarrow$ ACC \\
 7 & \$B5B9 & SUB\_IMM  & ACC $\leftarrow$ ACC $-$ immediate \\
 8 & \$B5A2 & RET       & VM subroutine return (pop IP) \\
 9 & \$B54F & CALL0     & Jump to native code (no return) \\
10 & \$B5CE & INC\_LOAD & *(addr) += 1; ACC $\leftarrow$ result \\
11 & \$B526 & HALT      & Exit VM (RTS) \\
12 & \$B500 & GOTO      & Unconditional branch \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{center}

Unconditional branch.  Reads a 2-byte encrypted address operand and
sets the VM instruction pointer to that address.

<<disk vm op goto>>=
    ORG     $B500
DISK_VM_OP_GOTO:
    JSR     DISK_VM_READ_ADDR ; read target -> $54/$55
DISK_VM_SET_IP:
    MOVW    $54,$52 ; set IP = operand
    LDY     #$00
    JMP     DISK_VM_RESUME    ; dispatch next opcode
@ %def DISK_VM_OP_GOTO DISK_VM_SET_IP
Exits the VM by executing [[RTS]], which returns to the caller of
[[DISK_VM_DISPATCH]].  This handler is just the [[RTS]] at the end
of [[DISK_VM_READ_ADDR]]---the dispatch table points to~[[$B526]]
which is that instruction.

(No separate chunk needed; [[DISK_VM_READ_ADDR]] provides the [[RTS]].)

Calls a native 6502 subroutine.  Passes the VM accumulator in~[[A]]
and captures the subroutine's return value from~[[A]] back into the
accumulator.  The~Y register (bytecode offset) is preserved across
the call.

<<disk vm op call1>>=
    ORG     $B527
DISK_VM_OP_CALL1:
    SUBROUTINE DISK_VM_OP_CALL1
    JSR     DISK_VM_READ_ADDR ; read native addr -> $54/$55
    TYA
    PHA                       ; save Y (bytecode offset)
    LDA     $56               ; A = VM accumulator
    JSR     DISK_VM_JMP_IND   ; call native routine via JMP ($54)
    STA     $56               ; capture return A -> accumulator
    PLA
    TAY                       ; restore Y
    JMP     DISK_VM_RESUME    ; dispatch next opcode
@ %def DISK_VM_OP_CALL1
Jumps to a native 6502 routine and does not return to the VM\@.
Used for operations like ``enter the main program'' or ``jump to
a disk routine'' that take over control flow.  The [[JMP ($54)]]
at~[[$B552]] also serves as a reusable trampoline for opcode~1.

<<disk vm op call0>>=
    ORG     $B54F
DISK_VM_OP_CALL0:
    JSR     DISK_VM_READ_ADDR ; read native addr -> $54/$55
DISK_VM_JMP_IND:
    JMP     ($54)             ; indirect jump (no return to VM)
@ %def DISK_VM_OP_CALL0 DISK_VM_JMP_IND
Branch if the VM accumulator is nonzero.  Reads a 2-byte encrypted
target address, then either branches (reuses [[DISK_VM_SET_IP]])
or falls through to the next opcode.

<<disk vm op bnz>>=
    ORG     $B555
DISK_VM_OP_BNZ:
    JSR     DISK_VM_READ_ADDR ; read branch target -> $54/$55
    LDA     $56               ; test accumulator
    BNE     DISK_VM_SET_IP    ; nonzero -> branch (reuse GOTO tail)
    JMP     DISK_VM_RESUME    ; zero -> continue
@ %def DISK_VM_OP_BNZ
Loads an immediate value into the VM accumulator.  The operand is a
single encrypted byte (XOR~[[$7A]]).

<<disk vm op lda imm>>=
    ORG     $B55F
DISK_VM_OP_LDA_IMM:
    LDA     ($52),Y ; read encrypted byte
    INY
    BNE     .no_page
    INC     $53
.no_page:
    EOR     #$7A    ; decrypt
    STA     $56     ; accumulator = value
    JMP     DISK_VM_RESUME
@ %def DISK_VM_OP_LDA_IMM
Loads a byte from an absolute address into the VM accumulator.

<<disk vm op lda abs>>=
    ORG     $B56D
DISK_VM_OP_LDA_ABS:
    JSR     DISK_VM_READ_ADDR ; read address -> $54/$55
DISK_VM_LOAD_IND:
    LDX     #$00
    LDA     ($54,X)           ; ACC = *(address)
    STA     $56
    JMP     DISK_VM_RESUME
@ %def DISK_VM_OP_LDA_ABS DISK_VM_LOAD_IND
Indexed load.  Reads a 2-byte base address, adds the VM accumulator
as an offset, then loads the byte at (base~+~ACC) into the
accumulator.  Useful for table lookups.  Falls into
[[DISK_VM_LOAD_IND]] to perform the actual load.

<<disk vm op lda idx>>=
    ORG     $B579
DISK_VM_OP_LDA_IDX:
    SUBROUTINE DISK_VM_OP_LDA_IDX
    JSR     DISK_VM_READ_ADDR ; read base addr -> $54/$55
    LDA     $56               ; index = old accumulator
    CLC
    ADC     $54               ; base_lo + index
    STA     $54
    BCC     .no_carry
    INC     $55               ; propagate carry
.no_carry:
    JMP     DISK_VM_LOAD_IND  ; load from ($54/$55) -> ACC
@ %def DISK_VM_OP_LDA_IDX
VM-level subroutine call.  Pushes the current absolute IP onto the
6502 hardware stack, then branches to the operand address.

<<disk vm op call>>=
    ORG     $B58A
DISK_VM_OP_CALL:
    SUBROUTINE DISK_VM_OP_CALL
    JSR     DISK_VM_READ_ADDR ; read target -> $54/$55
    TYA
    CLC
    ADC     $52               ; \ resolve absolute IP
    STA     $52               ;  | (base + Y offset)
    BCC     .no_carry
    INC     $53               ; /
.no_carry:
    PSHW    $52 ; push IP for RET
    LDY     #$00
    JMP     DISK_VM_SET_IP    ; GOTO target address
@ %def DISK_VM_OP_CALL
VM-level subroutine return.  Pops the IP previously pushed by
opcode~5 (CALL) and resumes execution there.

<<disk vm op ret>>=
    ORG     $B5A2
DISK_VM_OP_RET:
    PULW    $52 ; pop saved IP
    LDY     #$00
    JMP     DISK_VM_RESUME
@ %def DISK_VM_OP_RET
Stores the VM accumulator to an absolute address.

<<disk vm op sta abs>>=
    ORG     $B5AD
DISK_VM_OP_STA_ABS:
    JSR     DISK_VM_READ_ADDR ; read address -> $54/$55
    LDA     $56               ; A = accumulator
    LDX     #$00
    STA     ($54,X)           ; *(address) = ACC
    JMP     DISK_VM_RESUME
@ %def DISK_VM_OP_STA_ABS
Subtracts an encrypted immediate value from the VM accumulator.

<<disk vm op sub imm>>=
    ORG     $B5B9
DISK_VM_OP_SUB_IMM:
    LDA     ($52),Y ; read encrypted byte
    INY
    BNE     .no_page
    INC     $53
.no_page:
    EOR     #$7A    ; decrypt
    STA     $54     ; temp
    LDA     $56     ; A = accumulator
    SEC
    SBC     $54     ; ACC - immediate
    STA     $56     ; accumulator = result
    JMP     DISK_VM_RESUME
@ %def DISK_VM_OP_SUB_IMM
Increments the byte at an absolute address and loads the new value
into the VM accumulator.  Atomic read-modify-write.

<<disk vm op inc load>>=
    ORG     $B5CE
DISK_VM_OP_INC_LOAD:
    JSR     DISK_VM_READ_ADDR ; read address -> $54/$55
    LDX     #$00
    LDA     ($54,X)           ; read current value
    CLC
    ADC     #$01              ; increment
    STA     ($54,X)           ; write back
    STA     $56               ; accumulator = new value
    JMP     DISK_VM_RESUME
@ %def DISK_VM_OP_INC_LOAD
The self-modifying [[JMP]] instruction whose low byte is patched by
[[DISK_VM_DISPATCH]] before each handler call.  The byte at
[[$B5E0]] is overwritten with the handler's low address from the
opcode table.

<<disk vm trampoline>>=
    ORG     $B5DF
DISK_VM_TRAMPOLINE:
    JMP     DISK_VM_OP_GOTO         ; self-modified: low byte patched
@ %def DISK_VM_TRAMPOLINE
The 16-byte region at~[[$B5E5--$B5F4]] holds the saved copy of
zero-page [[$50--$5F]] when the VM is not executing.  The context
swap routine ([[DISK_VM_SWAP]]) exchanges these with the live
zero-page values on each VM entry and exit.  Bytes~11--13 (\$5B--\$5D)
hold initial values [[$4A $4C $4E]].

Bytes at~[[$B5F5--$B5FF]] are additional VM workspace:
[[$B5F6]] stores a mismatched nibble from [[VERIFY_DATA_FIELD]].

<<disk vm saved state>>=
    ORG     $B5E5
DISK_VM_SAVED_STATE:
;            $50                        $54                  $58
    HEX     00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 00 4a 4c 4e 00 00 00 00
;           saved ZP $50-$5F; bytes 9-11 ($59-$5B) = $4A,$4C,$4E
DISK_VM_SCRATCH:
    HEX     00          ; $B5F5
    HEX     00          ; $B5F6: bad nibble storage
    HEX     00 00 00    ; $B5F7-$B5F9
    HEX     a0 a0       ; $B5FA-$B5FB
    HEX     00 00 00 01 ; $B5FC-$B5FF
@ %def DISK_VM_SAVED_STATE DISK_VM_SCRATCH

